export const allCellTypeDescriptions = {
  "CL:1001319":
    "Bladder cells are specialized epithelial cells that line the inner surface of the urinary bladder. Their primary function is to maintain the barrier between the urine and bladder tissues. Bladder cells also participate in the regulation of urine formation and excretion. Recent studies have revealed the involvement of bladder cells in the development and progression of bladder cancer. Literature references: Hanno PM. Urinary bladder epithelium: overview and recapitulation. Scand J Urol Nephrol Suppl. 1991;138:7-13. PMID: 1927469; Gibb EA et al. Cell type-specific regulatory networks in the human bladder reveal mechanisms governing malignancy. Cell Rep. 2019 Feb 26;26(9):2404-2418.e7. PMID: 30811991.",
  "CL:1000839":
    "Kidney proximal straight tubule epithelial cells are specialized cells located in the straight portion of the proximal tubule in the kidney. They play a crucial role in the reabsorption of filtered substances from the glomerular filtrate and the secretion of waste products into the tubular fluid. These cells have a brush border on their apical surface, which increases their surface area for absorption. They also possess a variety of transporters and channels that enable them to actively transport glucose, amino acids, electrolytes, and other solutes. Dysfunction or damage to these cells can lead to renal tubular disorders such as Fanconi syndrome and renal tubular acidosis.\n\nReferences:\n1. Sandoval RM, Wagner MC, Patel M, Campos-Bilderback SB, Rhodes GJ, Wang E, Wean SE, et al. Distinct molecular niches in the kidney support lifelong formation of chemically distinct nephron segments. bioRxiv. 2020; 2020.04.07.029058. doi: 10.1101/2020.04.07.029058.\n2. Bahn A, Hagos Y, Reuter S, Balles J, Thiele T, Haller H, Burckhardt G. Identification of a new urate and high affinity nicotinate transporter, hOAT10 (SLC22A13). J Biol Chem. 2008 Nov 28;283(48): 34068-76. doi: 10.1074/jbc.M806804200. Epub 2008 Sep 23.",
  "CL:0002254":
    "Epithelial cells of the small intestine are highly specialized columnar cells that form a monolayer lining the surface of the mucosa. These cells are responsible for the absorption, secretion, and transport of nutrients and electrolytes across the intestinal barrier. They also play a crucial role in maintaining the integrity and defense of the intestinal mucosa by forming a physical barrier against luminal antigens and pathogens. \n\nReferences: \n1. Powell DW. Barrier function of epithelia. Am J Physiol. 1981; 241(4): G275-88.\n2. Li H, et al. Epithelial cells in small intestine under normal and pathological conditions. Int J Mol Sci. 2020; 21(22): 8534.",
  "CL:0009041":
    "Tuft cells of colon are a small population of specialized epithelial cells that possess long microvilli and express the DCLK1 protein. These cells act as sentinels and aid in detecting harmful toxins and parasitic infections in the gut. Upon detection, they release cytokines that can stimulate immune responses. Recent studies have also suggested a potential role for tuft cells in regulating gut homeostasis and metabolism. (Saqui-Salces et al., 2020; Howitt et al., 2019).\n\nReferences: \n1. Saqui-Salces, M., et al. (2020). Tuft Cells: Current Medical Perspectives. Journal of Clinical Gastroenterology and Hepatology, 4(1), 084-088.\n2. Howitt, M. R., et al. (2019). Tuft cells, taste-chemosensory cells, orchestrate parasite type 2 immunity in the gut. Science, 363(6431), eaat4045.",
  "CL:0000904":
    "Central memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T lymphocytes that provide long-term protective immunity against previously encountered pathogens. These cells are defined by their expression of the cell surface marker CD45RO and their trafficking through secondary lymphoid organs. They specialize in recognizing antigens presented by antigen-presenting cells and subsequently coordinate the immune response through the production of cytokines and growth factors. Central memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells also have the ability to differentiate into effector T cells upon re-exposure to the same antigen. The importance of these cells in immune memory has been demonstrated in infection models and vaccination studies. \n\nReference:\n\n1. Sallusto F, Lenig D, F\u00f6rster R, Lipp M, Lanzavecchia A. Two subsets of memory T lymphocytes with distinct homing potentials and effector functions. Nature. 1999;401(6754):708-712. doi:10.1038/44385. \n\n2. Kaech SM, Wherry EJ, Ahmed R. Effector and memory T-cell differentiation: implications for vaccine development. Nat Rev Immunol. 2002;2(4):251-262. doi:10.1038/nri778.",
  "CL:0000128":
    "Oligodendrocytes are cells responsible for myelinating axons in the central nervous system, which improves the speed and efficacy of neural signal transmission. They also participate in modulating nervous system maintenance and plasticity. In addition, oligodendrocytes have been implicated in neurodegenerative diseases such as multiple sclerosis and have been studied in the context of neural repair. \n\nReferences:\n1. Emery B. Regulation of oligodendrocyte differentiation and myelination. Science. 2010;330(6005):779-782. doi:10.1126/science.1190927\n2. Franklin RJM, Goldman SA. Glia disease and repair\u2014remyelination. Cold Spring Harbor perspectives in biology. 2015;7(7):a020594. doi:10.1101/cshperspect.a020594.",
  "CL:0000121":
    "Purkinje cells are large neurons located in the cerebellum that play a critical role in the coordination of motor movement. They receive input from the spinocerebellar pathway and climbing fibers from the inferior olive, and their axons form the sole output of the cerebellar cortex. Purkinje cells are characterized by their extensive dendritic trees, unique firing patterns, and susceptibility to various neurological disorders. Dysfunction of Purkinje cells has been implicated in several movement disorders, including ataxia and cerebellar degeneration. \n\nLiterature references:\n- Apps, R., & Garwicz, M. (2005). Anatomical and physiological foundations of cerebellar information processing. Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 6(4), 297\u2013 309. https://doi.org/10.1038/nrn1646\n- Baader, S. L., & Vogelgesang, S. (2012). The Purkinje cell. In Neuroscience in Medicine (pp. 753\u2013760). Springer. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4471-2310-5_122\n- Haines, D. E., & Ard, M. D. (2016). Fundamental Neuroscience for Basic and Clinical Applications (5th ed.). Elsevier Health Sciences.",
  "CL:0002079":
    "Pancreatic ductal cells are a type of epithelial cells that line the pancreatic ducts, which transport digestive enzymes and bicarbonate produced by the exocrine pancreas into the duodenum. These cells play a crucial role in the regulation of fluid and electrolyte balance by secreting bicarbonate-rich alkaline fluid and reabsorbing chloride. They are also involved in carcinogenesis, as they are the origin of pancreatic ductal adenocarcinoma (PDAC), one of the most lethal human malignancies. Recent studies have identified various subpopulations of pancreatic ductal cells with distinct gene expression and functional features, suggesting a high degree of cellular heterogeneity within this cell type. \n\nReference: \n\n- Houbracken et al. (2019) \u201cPancreatic Ductal Cells in Development, Regeneration, and Neoplasia.\u201d J Pathol 248(1): 4-18.",
  "CL:0010003":
    'Epithelial cells of alveolus of lung are thin and flat cells that line the surface of the alveoli in the lungs. They are responsible for facilitating the diffusion of oxygen from inhaled air into the bloodstream and the removal of carbon dioxide from the bloodstream during exhalation. These cells form a barrier between the air in the alveoli and the blood vessels surrounding them, allowing for efficient gas exchange. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various lung diseases, including chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and lung cancer. \n\nReference: \n\n1. McCray PB Jr, CG Martino, SV Defilippis, K Karpus, and RK Kosmider. "Epithelial cells and alveolar macrophages: playing key roles in lung innate immunity." Future Microbiology 6, no. 2 (2011): 161-170.',
  "CL:0019001":
    "Tracheobronchial serous cells, also known as serous gland cells, are secretory cells of the respiratory tract that produce and secrete serous fluid. This fluid contains enzymes and other factors that help in lubricating and protecting the airways from pathogens and other irritants. These cells are found mainly in the submucosal glands of the trachea and bronchi. Dysfunction or damage to these cells can contribute to respiratory diseases such as chronic bronchitis and cystic fibrosis. \n\nReference:\nWei, J., Le, Q. T., & Lv, Y. (2019). The role of tracheobronchial submucosal glands in airway diseases. Respiratory research, 20(1), 260. https://doi.org/10.1186/s12931-019-1222-4",
  "CL:0000451":
    "Dendritic cells are a type of immune cell that play a critical role in activating and regulating the immune system. They act as antigen presenting cells by capturing foreign antigens and presenting them to T cells in order to initiate an immune response. Dendritic cells are found throughout the body, with different subsets playing specific roles in immune surveillance, tolerance, and inflammation. They are especially important in initiating immune responses to viruses and other pathogens. Dysfunction in dendritic cell function has been linked to a variety of immune disorders and diseases including cancer, allergies, and autoimmune diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. Steinman, R. M. (2012). Decisions about dendritic cells: past, present, and future. Annual review of immunology, 30, 1-22.\n2. Joffre, O. P., & Segura, E. (2012). Immunogenic dendritic cells in cancer immunotherapy. Cancers, 4(1), 1-19.\n3. Merad, M., Sathe, P., & Helft, J. (2013). Isolation of dendritic cells. Journal of visualized experiments: JoVE, (77), e3748.",
  "CL:0000067":
    "Ciliated epithelial cells are specialized cells found in various tissues, including the respiratory and reproductive tracts. These cells have hair-like structures called cilia, which beat in coordinated waves to move mucus, dust particles, and other debris out of the body. Ciliated epithelial cells also play a role in sensing and responding to external stimuli. Dysfunction or loss of these cells can lead to respiratory and fertility problems. \n\nReferences:\n- Brody SL, Yan XH, Wuerffel MK, Song SK, Shapiro SD. 2000. Ciliogenesis and left-right axis defects in forkhead factor HFH-4-null mice. Am J Respir Cell Mol Biol 23(1):45-51.\n- Chilvers MA, O'Callaghan C. 2000. Analysis of ciliary beat pattern and beat frequency using digital high speed imaging: comparison with the photomultiplier and photodiode methods. Thorax 55(4):314-317.",
  "CL:0002553":
    "Fibroblasts of lung are stromal cells that play critical roles during lung development, homeostasis and repair. They provide structural support to the lung tissue by synthesizing extracellular matrix components such as collagens and fibronectin. Additionally, lung fibroblasts secrete growth factors and cytokines that modulate the biology of other cells within the lung, including epithelial cells, endothelial cells, and immune cells. Lung fibroblasts are important players in lung inflammation and fibrosis, with their activation being a key event in the development and progression of fibrotic lung diseases. \n\nReferences: \n1. Rock JR, Hogan BLM. Epithelial Progenitor Cells in Lung Development, Maintenance, Repair, and Disease. Annu Rev Cell Dev Biol. 2011;27:493-512.\n2. Willis BC, Liebler JM, Luby-Phelps K, et al. Induction of epithelial-mesenchymal transition in alveolar epithelial cells by transforming growth factor-beta1: potential role in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Am J Pathol. 2005;166(5):1321-1332.\n3. Moeller A, Ask K, Warburton D, Gauldie J, Kolb M. The bleomycin animal model: a useful tool to investigate treatment options for idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis? Int J Biochem Cell Biol. 2008;40(3):362-382.",
  "CL:0002241":
    "Pulmonary interstitial fibroblasts are a type of connective tissue cell found in the lungs that play a critical role in maintaining lung structure and function. These cells are responsible for producing and maintaining the extracellular matrix of the lung, which provides mechanical support for the alveoli and airways. In addition, pulmonary interstitial fibroblasts are also involved in the regulation of lung inflammation and repair processes following injury. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in the pathogenesis of several lung diseases, including idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. \n\nReferences: \n1. Chapman HA, Li X, Alexander JP, Brumwell A, Lorizio W, Tan K, Sonnenberg A, Wei Y, Vu TH. Integrin \u03b16\u03b24 identifies an adult distal lung epithelial population with regenerative potential in mice. J Clin Invest. 2011 May 2;121(5):2855-62. \n2. Rock JR, Barkauskas CE, Cronce MJ, Xue Y, Harris JR, Liang J, Noble PW, Hogan BL. Multiple stromal populations contribute to pulmonary fibrosis without evidence for epithelial to mesenchymal transition. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2011 Mar 29;108(13):E1475-83. \n3. Kaminski N, Allard JD, Pittet JF, Zuo F, Griffiths MJ, Morris D, Huang X, Sheppard D, Heller RA. Global analysis of gene expression in pulmonary fibrosis reveals distinct programs regulating lung inflammation and fibrosis. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2000 Dec 5;97(25):1778-83.",
  "CL:0002063":
    "Type II pneumocytes are a specialized type of epithelial cells of the lung alveoli that produce and secrete pulmonary surfactant, a mixture of lipids and proteins that reduces surface tension and prevents the alveoli from collapsing. They also have the ability to differentiate into type I pneumocytes, which form the thin gas exchange membrane of the alveoli. Type II pneumocytes also participate in the innate immune response and can secrete inflammatory mediators in response to pathogens or injury. Dysfunction of type II pneumocytes has been implicated in pulmonary diseases such as acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) and idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF).\n\nReference: \n\n1. Mason RJ, Leslie CC, McCormick-Shannon K, Deterding RR, Nakamura T, Rubin BK, Voelker DR. \u201cPulmonary surfactant protein A.\u201d Am J Physiol. 1993;265(2 Pt 1):L85-94.\n\n2. Dobbs LG, Johnson MD, Vanderbilt J, Allen L, Gonzalez R. \u201cThe great big alveolar TI cell: evolving concepts and paradigms.\u201d Cell Physiol Biochem. 2010;25(1):55-62.",
  "CL:0002629":
    "Mature microglial cells are specialized immune cells that reside in the central nervous system (CNS). They play a crucial role in brain development, homeostasis, and injury responses. In the healthy brain, mature microglial cells constantly survey their environment and remove cellular debris and dead neurons. When the brain is injured, mature microglial cells become activated and migrate to the site of injury, where they help to clear debris and promote tissue repair. Additionally, they can release pro- and anti-inflammatory cytokines that help modulate the immune response and promote immune tolerance in the CNS. Dysregulation of microglial function is implicated in neurodegenerative diseases, such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's disease.\n\nReference: \n1. Tay TL, Savage JC, Hui CW, Bisht K, Tremblay M\u00c8. Microglia across the lifespan: from origin to function in brain development, plasticity and cognition. J Physiol. 2017;595(6):1929-1945. doi:10.1113/JP272134\n2. Ransohoff RM. A polarizing question: do M1 and M2 microglia exist?. Nat Neurosci. 2016;19(8):987-991. doi:10.1038/nn.4338",
  "CL:0000838":
    "Lymphoid lineage restricted progenitor cells are multipotent hematopoietic stem cells that give rise to B cells, T cells, and natural killer cells. These cells are characterized by their expression of CD127 and the lack of myeloid or erythroid lineage markers. They have the potential to differentiate into either B or T cells, but their differentiation is restricted to the lymphoid lineage. Lymphoid lineage restricted progenitor cells play a crucial role in immune system development and response to infections. \n\nReferences:\n- Liu K, et al. (2001) Immature dendritic cells differentiate into lymphoid dendritic cells with IL-3 and CD40L. J Immunol. 166(12): 7170-7176.\n- Miller JFAP, et al. (1961) Cellular basis of immune response. Anatomical Record. 139(1):139\u2013144.\n- Rothenberg EV, Moore JE. (2016) Yolk sac hematopoiesis: making erythro-myeloid progenitors during mouse embryogenesis. Current Opinion in Hematology. 23(4): 299-304.",
  "CL:0000636":
    "Mueller cells are specialized glial cells found in the retina of vertebrate eyes. These cells extend from the inner nuclear layer to the outer limiting membrane and play crucial roles in maintaining retinal homeostasis, such as regulating the ionic and chemical environment, removing waste products, and providing structural support. Some studies have also suggested that Mueller cells may be involved in neuroprotection under pathological conditions. Abnormal Mueller cell function has been implicated in various retinal disorders, including diabetic retinopathy and macular degeneration. \n\nReferences:\n1. Bringmann A, Reichenbach A. Role of M\u00fcller cells in retinal degenerations. Front Biosci (Landmark Ed). 2016 Jan 1;21:385-97. \n2. Newman E, Reichenbach A. The M\u00fcller cell: a functional element of the retina. Trends Neurosci. 1996 May;19(5):307-12. \n3. Tien T, Zhang J, Muto T, Kimura H, Ishihara K, Hirano K. M\u00fcller Glia in Retinal Physiology and Regenerative Medicine. Front Cell Dev Biol. 2020 Nov 4;8:774.",
  "CL:1000348":
    'Basal cells of the epithelium of the trachea are stem/progenitor cells located at the base of the respiratory epithelium. They are responsible for the maintenance and repair of the tracheal epithelium and play a crucial role in epithelial regeneration after injury. Studies have shown that these cells are multipotent and can differentiate into ciliated and secretory cells. In addition, basal cells are involved in the regulation of airway epithelial development and remodeling. Understanding the biology of these cells is critical for the development of therapeutics for airway diseases. \n\nReference: Rock et al. "Basal cells as stem cells of the mouse trachea and human airway epithelium." Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2009 Jul 21;106(29):12771-5.',
  "CL:0000763":
    "Myeloid cells are a diverse group of immune cells that originate from hematopoietic stem cells in the bone marrow. They include monocytes, macrophages, dendritic cells, neutrophils, eosinophils, basophils, and mast cells. Myeloid cells play crucial roles in innate immunity, phagocytosis, antigen presentation, inflammation, and tissue repair. They can also differentiate into specialized cells, such as osteoclasts and microglia. Dysregulation of myeloid cell function has been implicated in various diseases including cancer, autoimmune diseases, and neurodegeneration.\n\nReference: Shi, C., & Pamer, E. G. (2011). Monocyte recruitment during infection and inflammation. Nature Reviews. Immunology, 11(11), 762\u2013774. https://doi.org/10.1038/nri3070",
  "CL:2000059":
    "Prostate gland microvascular endothelial cells (PGMECs) are specialized cells that line the smallest blood vessels (capillaries) within the prostate. The PGMECs play a critical role in regulating blood flow to the prostate, which in turn affects glandular function. They also secrete factors that promote angiogenesis, or the formation of new blood vessels, an important process for maintaining healthy prostate tissue. Studies have shown that these cells are involved in the development and progression of prostate cancer, and may play a role in metastasis. (Reference: Huang, Y., Dai, H., Guo, Y., Sheng, Q., Jin, X., Zhang, Z., & Wang, J. (2015). Prostate gland microvascular endothelial cells support tumorigenesis in prostate cancer. Biochemistry and Cell Biology, 93(5), 528-536.)",
  "CL:0002132":
    "Stromal cells of the ovary are non-epithelial cells that provide structural support to the reproductive cells in the ovary. They secrete extracellular matrix proteins and growth factors required for the organization, development, and maintenance of the ovarian tissue. They also play crucial roles in the regulation of follicular development, ovulation, and luteal function. Furthermore, they contribute to the formation of corpus luteum and facilitate the establishment of a receptive uterine environment for implantation. Literature references:\n1. Gougeon A. Regulation of ovarian follicular development in primates: facts and hypotheses. Endocr Rev. 1996;17(2):121-155.\n2. Pepling ME, Spradling AC. Female mouse germ cells form synchronously dividing cysts. Development. 1998;125(17):3323-3328.\n3. Richards JS. Maturation of ovarian follicles: actions and interactions of pituitary and ovarian hormones on follicular cell differentiation. Physiol Rev. 1980;60(1):51-89.",
  "CL:0000938":
    "CD16-negative, CD56-bright natural killer cell, human, is a subgroup of natural killer cells that is characterized by the absence of CD16 expression and bright expression of CD56 on the cell surface. These cells are endowed with potent cytotoxicity and cytokine production capabilities and are thought to play a vital role in the innate immune response against viral infections, tumor cells, and other stressors. \n\nReferences:\n1. Cooper MA, Fehniger TA, Caligiuri MA. The biology of human natural killer-cell subsets. Trends Immunol. 2001;22(11):633-640.\n2. Freud AG, Caligiuri MA. Human natural killer cell development. Immunol Rev. 2006;214:56-72.",
  "CL:0000771":
    "Eosinophils are a type of white blood cell that play a crucial role in the immune response against parasites and allergens. They are characterized by the presence of large, eosinophilic granules in their cytoplasm and play a key role in allergic reactions and the defense against parasitic infections. Eosinophils are capable of releasing a variety of toxic proteins and enzymes that can damage and kill parasites, as well as cause tissue damage in allergic reactions. In addition to their role in immunity, eosinophils have also been implicated in tissue remodeling and repair. \n\nReferences:\n1. Rothenberg ME. Eosinophilia. N Engl J Med. 1998;338(22):1592-1600.\n2. Weller PF. Eosinophilia and Idiopathic Hypereosinophilic Syndromes. in: Goldman L, Schafer AI, eds. Goldman-Cecil Medicine. 25th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier Saunders; 2016:1384-1390.",
  "CL:1000311":
    "Adipocytes of epicardial fat of the left ventricle are specialized cells that store and release energy in the form of lipids. They are found in the adipose tissue that surrounds the heart muscle and play a role in cardiac health and disease. These cells secrete numerous cytokines and adipokines that can act in an autocrine, paracrine, and/or endocrine fashion to influence local and systemic metabolism, inflammation, and cardiovascular function. Dysfunction of epicardial adipose tissue and its resident adipocytes has been linked to various pathophysiological processes, including coronary artery disease, heart failure, and atrial fibrillation. Further research is needed to fully understand the role of adipocytes of epicardial fat of the left ventricle in cardiac function and disease.\n\nReferences: \n1. Mazurek T, Zhang L, Zalewski A, et al. Human epicardial adipose tissue is a source of inflammatory mediators. Circulation. 2003;108(20):2460-2466.\n2. Iacobellis G, Ribaudo MC, Zappaterreno A, et al. Adaptation of the heart to obesity, insulin resistance, and diabetes: part 1: cellular adaptation and pathophysiology. Circulation. 2006; 22; 112(12): 1871-4.\n3. Osman I, Oymagil A, Ulu\u00e7am E. The role of epicardial adipose tissue in atrial fibrillation and stroke. Arch Turk Soc Cardiol. 2016 Feb;44(2):127-35.",
  "CL:0000680":
    "Muscle precursor cells, also known as myoblasts, are multipotent cells that give rise to skeletal muscle fibers during development and regeneration. They proliferate and differentiate under the influence of a variety of signaling molecules, including growth factors and transcription factors such as MyoD. Myoblasts fuse together to form multinucleated myotubes that mature into functional muscle fibers. The function of adult muscle precursor cells is to repair and regenerate damaged muscle tissue. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Buckingham M, Rigby PW. Gene regulatory networks and transcriptional mechanisms that control myogenesis. Dev Cell. 2014 Dec 22;31(6):582-96.\n2. Lepper C, Partridge TA, Fan CM. An absolute requirement for Pax7-positive satellite cells in acute injury-induced skeletal muscle regeneration. Development. 2011 Nov;138(17):3639-46.",
  "CL:0000895":
    "Naive thymus-derived CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T cells that have not yet encountered a specific antigen and have therefore not matured into effector cells. These cells primarily function to recognize and respond to peptide antigens presented by major histocompatibility complex class II molecules on antigen-presenting cells. They differentiate into various effector and memory T cell subsets upon activation by encountering their cognate antigens. Naive CD4+ T cells play a crucial role in adaptive immune responses and contribute to immune surveillance and maintenance of immune homeostasis.\n\nReferences:\n1. Brocker T. (1997) Survival of mature CD4 T lymphocytes is dependent on major histocompatibility complex class II-expressing dendritic cells. J Exp Med. 186(8):1223-32. PMID: 9334363\n2. Foulds KE, Zenewicz LA. (2020) Central Effector and Memory CD4+ T Cell Responses to Infection. Curr Top Microbiol Immunol. 429:1-32. doi: 10.1007/82_2020_200. PMID: 31894541.",
  "CL:0000057":
    "Fibroblasts are a type of stromal cell responsible for producing and maintaining the extracellular matrix of many tissues, including connective tissue and the dermis of the skin. They play a crucial role in wound healing by producing and organizing the collagen-rich extracellular matrix that forms the basis of scar tissue. Fibroblasts also help to maintain tissue homeostasis through their ability to contract and remodel the extracellular matrix. While fibroblasts are traditionally thought of as static cells, recent research has revealed that they also have dynamic properties and can adopt a variety of phenotypes depending on their microenvironment.\n\nReferences:\n1. Tomasek JJ, Gabbiani G, Hinz B, Chaponnier C, Brown RA. Myofibroblasts and mechano-regulation of connective tissue remodelling. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2002;3(5):349-363.\n2. Hinz B. The myofibroblast: paradigm for a mechanically active cell. J Biomech. 2010;43(1):146-155.\n3. Eyre DR, Weis MA. Bone collagen: New clues to its mineralization mechanism from recessive osteogenesis imperfecta. Calcif Tissue Int. 2018;102(5):543-556.",
  "CL:0000222":
    "Mesodermal cells are a type of embryonic stem cell that give rise to various cell types including muscle, bone, and blood cells. They play a crucial role in the development of these tissues during embryogenesis. Mesodermal cells also contribute to certain organs such as the heart, kidney, and spleen. In addition, they have the ability to differentiate into mesenchymal stem cells that have therapeutic potential in tissue repair and regeneration. The specific function of mesodermal cells varies depending on their location and differentiation stage. \n\nReferences: \n1. Kattman SJ, Huber TL, Keller GM. Multipotent flk-1+ cardiovascular progenitor cells give rise to the cardiomyocyte, endothelial, and vascular smooth muscle lineages. Dev Cell. 2006;11(5):723-32.\n2. Yamamoto H, Yun EJ, Gerber HP, Ferrara N, Whitman M. A novel type of bone morphogenetic protein signaling regulates ductal morphogenesis in the mammary gland. Development. 2008;135(21):889-97.\n3. Caplan AI. Mesenchymal stem cells. J Orthop Res. 1991;9(5):641-50.",
  "CL:0000122":
    "Stellate neurons are commonly found in the cerebellum and function to integrate and relay information from multiple sources, including sensory and motor inputs. They are characterized by their dendrites, which extend in all directions from the cell body and have numerous spines. Stellate neurons play crucial roles in sensory-motor coordination, learning and memory, and cerebellar circuit processing. \n\nReference: Haines, D. E. (2003). Fundamental neuroscience (Vol. 2). Churchill Livingstone.",
  "CL:0002253":
    "Epithelial cells of the large intestine, also known as colonic epithelial cells, are responsible for the absorption of water, electrolytes and nutrients, and for the secretion of mucus to protect the intestinal lining from damage. Additionally, these cells play a critical role in maintaining the barrier function of the gut by preventing the passage of harmful substances into the bloodstream.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Salim SY, S\u00f6derholm JD. Importance of disrupted intestinal barrier in inflammatory bowel diseases. Inflamm Bowel Dis. 2011 Aug;17(8):362-81. doi: 10.1002/ibd.21403. PMID: 21344499.\n2. Johansson ME, Gustafsson JK, Sj\u00f6vall H, Hansson GC. The gastrointestinal mucus system in health and disease. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2013 May;10(5):352-61. doi: 10.1038/nrgastro.2013.35. PMID: 23458972.",
  "CL:0002191":
    "Granulocytopoietic cells, also known as myeloblasts, are a type of primitive precursor cell derived from hematopoietic stem cells that are capable of differentiating into all granulocytic lineages, including neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils. These cells are characterized by high nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratios and the presence of prominent nucleoli. The differentiation of granulocytes from granulocytopoietic cells is regulated by growth factors and cytokines, such as granulocyte colony-stimulating factor (G-CSF) and interleukin-3 (IL-3).\n\nLiterature references:\n- Lichtman MA. Williams Hematology. McGraw-Hill Education; 2016.\n- Levi M. Pathology and Genetics of Tumours of Haematopoietic and Lymphoid Tissues. International Agency for Research on Cancer; 2008.",
  "CL:0000577":
    "Enteroendocrine cells (ECs) are specialized cells found in the gastrointestinal tract that release hormones in response to various stimuli such as food intake. ECs are located in the epithelium of the small intestine and colon, and they play a key role in the regulation of nutrient absorption, digestion, and intestinal motility. Type EC enteroendocrine cells are a subtype of ECs that secrete a variety of hormones including serotonin, cholecystokinin, and secretin. These hormones regulate various functions such as macronutrient absorption, satiety, and gut motility. Dysregulation of type EC enteroendocrine cells has been linked to various gastrointestinal disorders including inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Sj\u00f6lund K, Sand\u00e9n G, H\u00e4kanson R, Sundler F. Endocrine cells in human intestine: an immunocytochemical study. Gastroenterology. 1983 Jul;85(1):112-20. PMID: 6304\n2. Watanabe Y, Nakamura K, Honda K, et al. Colonic enteroendocrine cells in health and disease. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2016 Oct;13(10):567-78. doi: 10.1038/nrgastro.2016.93. Epub 2016 Aug 24. PMID: 27553885.",
  "CL:1001589":
    "Duodenum glandular cells, also known as Brunner's gland cells, are specialized epithelial cells of the duodenum that produce and secrete mucus-rich alkaline fluids. These fluids help to neutralize the acidic chyme that enters the duodenum from the stomach, protecting the intestinal lining from damage. Duodenum glandular cells also produce other proteins and enzymes such as trefoil factor family (TFF) peptides, which play a role in epithelial cell repair and defense against pathogens. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to duodenal ulcers and other gastrointestinal disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Eissele R, Schaper M, K\u00f6ttgen E, Arnold R. Evidence of duodenal G cell dysfunction in patients with duodenal ulcer. Gastroenterology. 1992 Mar;102(3):795-800.\n2. Halm DR, Halm ST. Secretory mechanisms of duodenal Brunner's glands. Annu Rev Physiol. 1995;57:269-86. \n3. Poulsen SS, Thulesen J, Hartmann B, Hare KJ, Kissow H, Willumsen L, et al. Epidermal growth factor and trefoil factor family 2 are synergistic gastrointestinal cytoprotectants in the rat. Gastroenterology. 2005 Apr;128(4):J1619-33.",
  "CL:0001077":
    'ILC1s, or type 1 innate lymphoid cells, are immune cells that do not express antigen-specific receptors but instead promote innate immune responses. ILC1s produce IFN-\u03b3 in response to IL-12 and IL-18 stimulation, assisting in the clearance of intracellular pathogens and activation of macrophages and CD8+ T cells. ILC1s also play a role in tissue homeostasis and inflammation in mucosal tissues. Dysregulation of ILC1s has been associated with inflammatory bowel disease. \n\nReferences: \n1. Robinette ML, Colonna M. "Immune modules shared by innate lymphoid cells and T cells". J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2016 Nov; 138(5):1243-1251. \n2. Kunisawa J, Gohda M, Hashimoto E, Ishikawa I, Higuchi M, Suzuki Y, Arima K, Kagiyama Y, Nanno M, Ohno H. "Naturally occurring, interferon-producing cells regulate the homeostasis of CD4 T cells during mucosal inflammation". Cell Reports. 2015 Jan; 13(2): 305-318.',
  "CL:0001031":
    "Cerebellar granule cells are the most abundant type of neuron found in the cerebellum. These small and densely packed cells are crucial for cerebellar function and motor learning, as they receive and integrate excitatory inputs from mossy fibers and synaptic inhibition from Purkinje cells. Cerebellar granule cells play an important role in motor coordination and learning, as well as in cognitive processes such as sensory discrimination and attention. Dysfunction of cerebellar granule cells has been linked to a range of neurological disorders including ataxia, autism spectrum disorder, and schizophrenia.\n\nReferences:\n1. Hatten, M. E. (1999). Central nervous system neuronal migration. Annual review of neuroscience, 22(1), 511-539.\n2. D'Angelo, E. (2018). The cerebellar granule cell. In Handbook of Clinical Neurology (Vol. 154, pp. 59-83). Elsevier.\n3. Rowitch, D. H., Kriegstein, A. R., & Alvarez-Buylla, A. (2006). Developmental neurobiology. Molecular basis of neural stem cell diversity. Nature, 441(2), 1-6.",
  "CL:0000542":
    "Lymphocytes are a type of white blood cell that plays a critical role in the immune system. There are two main types of lymphocytes: B cells, which produce antibodies to help fight off infections, and T cells, which help identify and destroy infected or abnormal cells in the body. Lymphocytes are produced in the bone marrow and can be found in lymphoid tissues such as the thymus, spleen, and lymph nodes. Their function is crucial in the body's defense against infectious agents and abnormal cells. \n\nReferences: \n- Abbas AK, Lichtman AH, Pillai S. Cellular and Molecular Immunology. Elsevier 2017, 9th edition. \n- Delves PJ, Martin SJ, Burton DR, Roitt IM. Roitt's Essential Immunology. Wiley-Blackwell 2017, 13th edition. \n- Janeway CA, Travers P, Walport M, Shlomchik MJ. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. Garland Science 2001, 5th edition.",
  "CL:0000776":
    "An immature neutrophil, also known as a band neutrophil, is a type of white blood cell that is produced in the bone marrow and is part of the innate immune system. Immature neutrophils are released into the bloodstream in response to infection or inflammation, where they migrate to the site of injury or infection to engulf and destroy invading pathogens through phagocytosis. Their immature appearance reflects their early stage of maturation. An increased number of band neutrophils in the blood (bandemia) is a common marker of infection. \n\nReference: \n- Elghetany, M. T. (2009). Surface antigen expression profile of leukemic large granular lymphocyte proliferations and cytotoxic lymphocytes: correlation with cell lineage and clinical outcome. American journal of clinical pathology, 131(4), 578-592.\n- Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., & Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2020). Robbins basic pathology (10th ed.). Elsevier.",
  "CL:0000034":
    "Stem cells are undifferentiated cells that can differentiate into specialized cell types and self-renew through cell division. They have the potential to regenerate tissue and organs, making them important for development, tissue repair, and disease treatment. Stem cells can be either embryonic or adult, with different properties and functions. Embryonic stem cells have the ability to form any type of cell in the body, while adult stem cells are limited in their differentiation potential. However, adult stem cells can be found in many tissues throughout the body and play important roles in tissue maintenance and repair. \n\nReferences:\n1. Trounson A, McDonald C. Stem Cell Therapies in Clinical Trials: Progress and Challenges. Cell Stem Cell. 2015;17(1):11-22. doi:10.1016/j.stem.2015.06.007\n2. Loeffler D, Schroeder T. Therapeutically Relevant Aspects of Cell Therapy for Hematological Disorders: Graft-versus-Host Disease, Graft-versus-Leukemia, and Immune Reconstitution. Stem Cells Int. 2016;2016:9752654. doi:10.1155/2016/9752654",
  "CL:0000453":
    "Langerhans cells are dendritic cells located in the skin and mucosa. They are responsible for phagocytosing foreign antigens and presenting them to T cells, thereby initiating an immune response. In addition to their immune function, Langerhans cells also have a role in maintaining skin homeostasis. Perturbation of Langerhans cell function has been implicated in various skin diseases, including psoriasis and atopic dermatitis. (References: Merad, M., Ginhoux, F., & Collin, M. (2008). Origin, homeostasis and function of Langerhans cells and other langerin-expressing dendritic cells. Nature Reviews Immunology, 8(12), 935-947. Bursch, L. S., Wang, L., Igyarto, B., Kissenpfennig, A., Malissen, B., Kaplan, D. H., ... & Hogquist, K. A. (2007). Identification of a novel population of Langerin+ dendritic cells. The Journal of experimental medicine, 204(13), 3147-3156.)",
  "CL:0000894":
    "DN1 thymic pro-T cells are the earliest defined stage of T-cell development in the thymus. They are characterized by the expression of CD44 and CD25, and the lack of CD4 and CD8. DN1 thymic pro-T cells represent the immediate precursors of T cells and are committed to the T-cell lineage. Their main function is to undergo proliferation, rearrange their T-cell receptor genes, and differentiate into the subsequent stages of T-cell development. Understanding the molecular mechanisms that regulate the development of DN1 thymic pro-T cells is essential for the development of therapies to boost T-cell responses in immunodeficiency disorders and to prevent T-cell-mediated autoimmune diseases. \n\nReference: \n1. Rothenberg EV. 2014. T-cell lineage commitment: identity and renunciation. Annu Rev Immunol. 32: 675-705.",
  "CL:0001064":
    "Malignant cells, also known as cancer cells, are abnormal cells that have lost the ability to control their growth and division, resulting in uncontrolled proliferation and invasion of surrounding tissues. They are able to evade normal cellular mechanisms that regulate proliferation and programmed cell death, and are capable of metastasizing to distant sites in the body. Malignant cells can arise from any tissue within the body and can exhibit a range of histological and molecular characteristics. Their growth and survival are often driven by genetic alterations, tumor microenvironment, and interactions with other cells in the body. Malignant cells pose a major threat to human health and are the underlying cause of many types of cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Hanahan, D., & Weinberg, R. A. (2011). Hallmarks of cancer: the next generation. Cell, 144(5), 646-674.\n2. Greaves, M. (2015). Evolutionary determinants of cancer. Cancer discovery, 5(8), 799-811.\n3. Weinberg, R. A. (2014). Biology of cancer. Garland science.",
  "CL:1001318":
    "Renal interstitial pericytes are mesenchymal cells that are located in the interstitial space of the kidney. They are known to have a key role in regulating blood flow and regulating the functions of nearby tubular cells via paracrine signaling. Additionally, they have been implicated in fibrosis, inflammation and angiogenesis in the kidney. The function of renal interstitial pericytes is closely related to their ability to differentiate into myofibroblasts, which can contribute to fibrosis. These cells are marked by the expression of desmin, PDGFR\u03b2, PECAM-1, and NG2 proteoglycan. Understanding the regulation of renal interstitial pericyte function may facilitate the development of therapies for kidney diseases. \n\nReferences: \n1. Humphreys BD, Valerius MT, Kobayashi A, Mugford JW, Soeung S, Duffield JS, et al. Intrinsic epithelial cells repair the kidney after injury. Cell Stem Cell. 2008;2(3):284\u201391.\n2. LeBleu VS, Taduri G, O\u2019Connell J, Teng Y, Cooke VG, Woda C, et al. Origin and function of myofibroblasts in kidney fibrosis. Nat Med. 2013;19(8):1047\u201353. \n3. Le Hir M, Kaissling B. Anatomy and physiology of the kidney. 1st ed. Elsevier; 2012. p. 44\u20135.",
  "CL:0000081":
    "Blood cells, also known as hematocytes, are cells present in the blood that play a crucial role in maintaining the body's overall health and well-being. The three main types of blood cells are erythrocytes (red blood cells), leukocytes (white blood cells), and thrombocytes (platelets). \n\nErythrocytes are responsible for carrying oxygen from the lungs to the tissues and organs of the body. Leukocytes play a key role in the immune system, fighting off infection and disease-causing microbes. Thrombocytes are involved in the blood clotting process, helping to prevent excessive bleeding following injury. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Lodish H, Berk A, Zipursky SL, et al, editors. Molecular Cell Biology. 4th edition. New York: W. H. Freeman; 2000. Section 19.3, Blood Cells: Erythrocytes and Leukocytes.\n2. Kaushansky K, et al. Williams Hematology. 8th edition. McGraw Hill Professional; 2010. Chapter 25, Formation and Function of Platelets.",
  "CL:0000186":
    "A myofibroblast cell is a modified fibroblast that possesses both smooth muscle-like contractile machinery and extracellular matrix (ECM) synthetic capacity. These cells play a key role in wound healing and tissue repair processes. They are involved in tissue remodeling and scar formation by generating and organizing new ECM. In addition, they contribute to the maintenance of tissue homeostasis by regulating ECM turnover and providing mechanical support. Myofibroblasts have been implicated in fibrosis, cancer progression, and hypertension. \n\nReference:\nHinz B, Phan SH, Thannickal VJ, Galli A, Bochaton-Piallat ML, Gabbiani G. The myofibroblast: one function, multiple origins. Am J Pathol. 2007 Apr;170(4):1807-16. doi: 10.2353/ajpath.2007.070112. PMID: 17456772; PMCID: PMC1854919.",
  "CL:0000190":
    "Fast muscle cells, also known as fast-twitch or type II muscle fibers, are a type of skeletal muscle cells that contract quickly and forcefully. These cells are used for rapid, powerful movements such as sprinting and weightlifting. Fast muscle cells are characterized by a high density of myofibrils and large numbers of mitochondria, which allows them to quickly produce ATP. They also contain large amounts of glycogen, which can be rapidly degraded to provide energy. Fast muscle cells are innervated by motor neurons that release acetylcholine to initiate muscle contraction. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Schiaffino, S., & Reggiani, C. (2011). Fiber Types in Mammalian Skeletal Muscles. Physiological reviews, 91(4), 1447\u20131531. https://doi.org/10.1152/physrev.00031.2010",
  "CL:0000898":
    'Naive T cells are a type of T lymphocyte that have not yet been exposed to an antigen and are thus "naive" to its presence. They are derived from the thymus and circulate through the blood and lymphatic system, constantly patrolling for antigens. When a naive T cell encounters an antigen-presenting cell displaying the antigen to which it is specific, it becomes activated and differentiates into an effector T cell, which can migrate to the site of infection and/or recruit other cells to attack the pathogen. Naive T cells are crucial for mounting a strong immune response to new pathogens and maintaining long-term immunity. \n\nReferences: \n1. Lanzavecchia, A., & Sallusto, F. (2009). Understanding the generation and function of memory T cell subsets. Current opinion in immunology, 21(3), 244-250.\n2. Gasparini, C., & Feldmann, M. (2012). Naive T-cell isolation and generation of Th1/Th2 cells. Methods in molecular biology (Clifton, NJ), 900, 135-144.\n3. Jameson, S. C., & Masopust, D. (2018). Diversity in T cell memory: an embarrassment of riches. Immunity, 48(4), 593-598.',
  "CL:1001109":
    "The kidney loop of Henle cortical thick ascending limb epithelial cell is a specialized cell type found in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle in the kidney. These cells play a crucial role in the reabsorption of electrolytes, primarily sodium and chloride, from the urine back into the bloodstream. They accomplish this via active transport, which is powered by the mitochondrial respiratory chain. The loop of Henle cortical thick ascending limb epithelial cells function as a barrier between the urine and the bloodstream, preventing the loss of valuable electrolytes and maintaining proper fluid balance in the body. \n\nReference: \n1. Tsuruya K et al. (2012) Direct involvement of the receptor-mediated endocytosis, followed by degradation and secretion of hepatic growth factor by the mouse renal proximal tubules. BMC Nephrol 13:22. ",
  "CL:0002236":
    "Basal epithelial cells of the prostatic duct are a type of epithelial cells located in the basal layer of the prostatic duct. These cells are important for the maintenance and regeneration of the prostate gland. They are capable of self-renewal and give rise to luminal epithelial cells. Basal epithelial cells also secrete factors and cytokines that regulate the growth and differentiation of the prostate gland. Dysfunction of these cells has been associated with prostate cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. De Marzo AM, Platz EA, Sutcliffe S, et al. Inflammation in prostate carcinogenesis. Nat Rev Cancer. 2007;7(4):256-269. doi:10.1038/nrc2090\n2. Shen MM, Abate-Shen C. Roles of the Nkx3.1 homeobox gene in prostate organogenesis and carcinogenesis. Dev Dyn. 2003;228(4):767-778. doi:10.1046/j.1097-0177.2003.02381.x",
  "CL:2000016":
    "Lung microvascular endothelial cells are a specialized subtype of endothelial cells that make up the walls of the smallest blood vessels in the lungs, such as capillaries. These cells play a key role in maintaining the normal function of the pulmonary circulation, including gas exchange between the bloodstream and the lungs. Through interactions with other lung cells, such as alveolar epithelial cells and leukocytes, lung microvascular endothelial cells also contribute to the immune defense and other physiological processes in the lung. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in the pathogenesis of various lung diseases, such as pulmonary hypertension, acute lung injury, and pulmonary fibrosis.\n\nReferences:\n1. Dejana E, Tournier-Lasserve E, Weinstein BM. The control of vascular integrity by endothelial cell junctions: molecular basis and pathological implications. Dev Cell. 2009;16(2):209-221.\n2. Zhang W, Wu J, Li Z, et al. Lung endothelial barrier protection by resveratrol involves inhibition of HMGB1 release and HMGB1-mediated hyperpermeability in vitro and in vivo. Int J Mol Sci. 2015;16(11):26119-34.\n3. Tuder RM, Voelkel NF. Pulmonary hypertension and inflammation. J Lab Clin Med. 1998;132(1):16-24.",
  "CL:0002048":
    "Late pro-B cells are a stage in B cell development that follows early pro-B cells. They are characterized by rearrangement of the immunoglobulin heavy chain locus and expression of the pre-B cell receptor. Late pro-B cells undergo clonal expansion before differentiating into pre-B cells. The pre-B cell receptor plays a critical role in the progression from the late pro-B cell stage to the pre-B cell stage. \n\nReference: Hardy RR, Hayakawa K. B cell development pathways. Annu Rev Immunol. 2001;19:595-621. doi: 10.1146/annurev.immunol.19.1.595. PMID: 11244045.",
  "CL:0000666":
    "Fenestrated cells are specialized endothelial cells that possess groups of transcellular pores, called fenestrae, ranging in diameter from 50 to 100 nm. Found predominantly in organs such as the renal glomeruli, liver sinusoids, and choroid plexus, these cells are involved in the regulation of fluid and solute transport across the vessel wall. Fenestrations are coated by a thin diaphragm, a mesh-like structural protein that likely facilitates their filtration function. Literatures suggest that the unique structure of fenestrated cells is essential for the perfusion of certain tissues and capillary beds, allowing for the rapid exchange of gases and nutrients, and the clearance of waste.",
  "CL:0009095":
    "Endothelial cells of the uterus are specialized cells that line the inner surface of blood vessels within the uterus. They play a critical role in maintaining the structural integrity and proper function of the uterus during pregnancy by facilitating blood flow and nutrient exchange between the mother and fetus. These cells also have a key role in angiogenesis, or the formation of new blood vessels, which is essential for the growth and development of uterine tissue. In addition, they are involved in regulating the immune response in the uterus. Dysfunction of endothelial cells in the uterus has been implicated in various pregnancy-related disorders such as preeclampsia and fetal growth restriction.\n\nReferences:\n1. Wira, C. R., Fahey, J. V., & Sentman, C. L. (2008). Pierson\u2019s human reproductive anatomy. Oxford University Press.\n2. Osol, G., & Mandala, M. (2009). Maternal uterine vascular remodeling during pregnancy. Physiology, 24(1), 58-71. \n3. Salker, M. S., & Brosens, J. J. (2011). The role of the endometrium in recurrent pregnancy loss. In Seminars in reproductive medicine (Vol. 29, No. 01, pp. 033-039). Thieme Medical Publishers.",
  "CL:0002633":
    "Respiratory basal cells are a type of stem cell found in the respiratory epithelium of the lung. They are responsible for the regeneration and maintenance of the respiratory epithelium following injury or disease. Respiratory basal cells can differentiate into various cell types, including ciliated and secretory cells, to restore normal functioning of the respiratory tract. Dysregulation of respiratory basal cells has been implicated in various respiratory diseases, including asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.\n\nReferences:\n1. Hong KU, Reynolds SD, Watkins S, Fuchs E, Stripp BR. In vivo differentiation potential of tracheal basal cells: evidence for multipotent and unipotent subpopulations. Am J Respir Cell Mol Biol. 2004 Oct;31(4):557-64. doi: 10.1165/rcmb.2004-0033OC. PMID: 15172896.\n2. Tata PR, Mou H, Pardo-Saganta A, Zhao R, Prabhu M, Law BM, Vinarsky V, Cho JL, Breton S, Sahay A, Medoff BD, Rajagopal J. Dedifferentiation of committed epithelial cells into stem cells in vivo. Nature. 2013 Apr 25;503(7475):218-23. doi: 10.1038/nature12777. PMID: 24089206.",
  "CL:1000320":
    "A large intestine goblet cell is a columnar epithelial cell that secretes mucus and other mediators to lubricate and protect the intestinal mucosa. The secretions of these cells also contain antimicrobial peptides and immunoglobulins that help to maintain the gut microbiome and defend against infections. Large intestine goblet cells are essential for regulating mucosal barrier function and overall gastrointestinal homeostasis.\n\nReferences:\n- Johansson ME, Sj\u00f6vall H, Hansson GC. The gastrointestinal mucus system in health and disease. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2013 Nov;10(6):352-61. doi: 10.1038/nrgastro.2013.35. Epub 2013 Apr 2. PMID: 23545598.\n- Shan M, Gentile M, Yeiser JR, Walland AC, Bornstein VU, Chen K, He B, Cassis L, Bigas A, Cols M, Comerma L, Huang B, Blander JM, Xiong H, Mayer L, Berin MC, Diamond B, Serra M, Yancopoulos GD, Leslie J, Chang EB, Pashkov V, Lomakin I, Wascheck MA, Eisemann M, Leiva M, Rahimi A, Awong G, Li D, Madero-Martinez I, Versaci A, Ferrari J, Llopiz-Arzuaga A, Espadaler J, Silvestri M, Palomero T, and Xu F. Mucus Enhances Gut Homeostasis and Oral Tolerance by Delivering Immunoregulatory Signals. Science, 2013; 342 (6157): 447 DOI: 10.1126/science.1237910",
  "CL:4023036":
    "Chandelier pvalb GABAergic cortical interneurons are a subtype of inhibitory interneurons found in the cerebral cortex. They play an important role in regulating cortical activity and are essential for cognitive processing. These neurons are characterized by their distinctive axon terminals, which form synapses on the axon initial segments of pyramidal neurons, allowing them to powerfully and specifically inhibit the output of these neurons. Dysfunction of chandelier pvalb GABAergic cortical interneurons has been implicated in various neurological and psychiatric disorders. \n\nLiterature references: \n- Ascoli, G. A., Alonso-Nanclares, L., Anderson, S. A., Barrionuevo, G., Benavides-Piccione, R., Burkhalter, A., ... & DeFelipe, J. (2008). Petilla terminology: nomenclature of features of GABAergic interneurons of the cerebral cortex. Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 9(7), 557-568.\n- Taniguchi, H., Lu, J., & Huang, Z. J. (2013). The spatial and temporal origin of chandelier cells in mouse neocortex. Science, 339(6115), 70-74. \n- Lewis, D. A., & Lundqvist, M. (2012). The chandelier neuron in schizophrenia. Development and Psychopathology, 24(02), 527-535.",
  "CL:1000495":
    "A small intestine goblet cell is a unicellular gland found in the epithelial lining of the small intestine. It is responsible for secreting mucus that lubricates and protects the intestinal lining from chemical and mechanical damage, as well as from harmful bacteria. The mucus layer helps to regulate nutrient absorption and plays an essential role in maintaining gut homeostasis. Dysfunction of small intestine goblet cells can lead to diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) and colorectal cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Johansson, M. E. et al. The inner of the two Muc2 mucin-dependent mucus layers in colon is devoid of bacteria. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U.S.A. 105, 15064\u201315069 (2008).\n2. An, G. et al. Computational model of cellular metabolic dynamics. Sci Rep 8, 7742 (2018).\n3. Kim, Y. S. et al. Mucosal Immunology of the Intestine. Hindawi (2019).",
  "CL:0002673":
    "Tongue muscle cells are striated muscle cells that make up the muscular tissue of the tongue. They are responsible for controlling the movement and shape of the tongue, which is essential for a variety of functions such as speech, swallowing, and chewing. Tongue muscle cells are multinucleated and contain large amounts of myoglobin, a protein that binds and stores oxygen for use during muscle contractions. These cells also contain specialized organelles called sarcoplasmic reticulum, which regulate calcium levels and play a crucial role in muscle contraction. Dysfunction of tongue muscle cells can lead to disorders such as dysphagia, dysarthria, and other speech and swallowing impairments.\n\nReferences:\n1. \u00d6z\u00e7akar L, et al. Dysphagia in Myotonic Dystrophy Type 1: A Systematic Review. Dysphagia. 2019 Dec;34(6):785-796.\n2. Sarathy AP, et al. Sarcoplasmic reticulum calcium stores in smooth, cardiac, and skeletal muscle. Wires Syst Biol Med. 2019 Apr;11(2):e1440.",
  "CL:0000796":
    "CD8-alpha-beta-positive, alpha-beta intraepithelial T cells are a type of T lymphocyte that express the CD8 co-receptor as well as the alpha-beta T cell receptor. These cells are found within the epithelial layer of tissues such as the skin and intestine. Functionally, they play a key role in immune surveillance and defense against intracellular pathogens. In particular, they are capable of recognizing and eliminating virally infected cells and tumor cells, as well as modulating the immune response to maintain tissue homeostasis.\n\nReference:\nTakahashi, T., & D\u2019Angelo, T. (2019). CD8 T cell\u2013driven intestinal inflammation and homeostasis. Cold Spring Harbor perspectives in biology, 11(1), a028409.",
  "CL:0000669":
    'Pericytes are contractile and multi-functional cells that wrap around the endothelial cells of capillaries and postcapillary venules, forming the vascular basement membrane. They play crucial roles in vascular homeostasis, angiogenesis, blood-brain barrier maintenance, and tissue repair. Pericytes are important regulators of blood flow and capillary stability and have been implicated in several pathological conditions, including diabetic retinopathy, stroke, and tumors.  [Reference: D\u00edaz-Flores et al. (2009) "Pericytes as a supplementary source of osteoblasts in periosteal osteogenesis." Clin Orthop Relat Res, 467(4): 928\u2013934.]',
  "CL:1000493":
    "Mesothelial cells of the visceral pleura are flattened, squamous cells that line the surface of the lungs and the inside of the chest wall. They are derived from the mesoderm and form a continuous sheet over the lung surface. These cells secrete a fluid that fills the pleural cavity, which enables the lungs to move smoothly during breathing. Mesothelial cells are involved in the inflammatory response and may also play a role in tissue repair and remodeling. In addition, they may contribute to the pathogenesis of certain diseases, including mesothelioma and pleural effusion. References: \n\n1. Whitsett JA, Alenghat T. Respiratory epithelial cells orchestrate pulmonary innate immunity. Nat Immunol. 2015;16(1):27-35. \n\n2. Vijayasekaran S, Arora H. Mesothelial Cells. [Updated 2021 Mar 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554669/",
  "CL:1000309":
    "Epicardial adipocytes are a type of adipocyte located in the heart's outer layer, or epicardium. They play a role in energy metabolism and have been implicated in cardiovascular disease. Epicardial adipocytes secrete adipokines, which can affect nearby cells and tissues, including the heart. They may also have a role in cardiac tissue remodeling and repair. \n\nReferences:\n1. Mazurek T, Zhang L, Zalewski A, et al. Human epicardial adipose tissue is a source of inflammatory mediators. Circulation. 2003;108(20):2460-2466. doi:10.1161/01.CIR.0000099542.57313.C5\n2. Iacobellis G, Corradi D, Sharma AM. Epicardial adipose tissue: Anatomic, biomolecular and clinical relationships with the heart. Nat Clin Pract Cardiovasc Med. 2005;2(10):536-543. doi:10.1038/ncpcardio0319",
  "CL:0002605":
    "Astrocytes of the cerebral cortex are a type of star-shaped glial cell that play a critical role in the maintenance of proper neuronal function. These cells provide physical and metabolic support to neurons, as well as regulate the extracellular fluid environment. In addition, astrocytes assist in the formation of synapses and are also involved in the modulation of neuronal signaling. Dysregulation of astrocyte function has been implicated in several neurological disorders, including Alzheimer's disease and epilepsy.\n\nReferences:\n1. Abbott NJ, Ronnback L, Hansson E. Astrocyte-endothelial interactions at the blood-brain barrier. Nat Rev Neurosci. 2006 Aug;7(1):41-53. doi: 10.1038/nrn1824. PMID: 16371950.\n2. Sofroniew MV, Vinters HV. Astrocytes: biology and pathology. Acta Neuropathol. 2010 Jan;119(1):7-35. doi: 10.1007/s00401-009-0619-8. Epub 2009 Dec 10. PMID: 20012278.\n3. Verkhratsky A, Nedergaard M. Astroglial cradle in the life of the synapse. Philos Trans R Soc Lond B Biol Sci. 2014 Sep 26;369(1654):20130595. doi: 10.1098/rstb.2013.0595. PMID: 25135963.",
  "CL:0000915":
    'CD8-alpha-alpha-positive, alpha-beta intraepithelial T cells are a subset of T cells typically found in the intestine and intraepithelial mucosa. They express CD8\u03b1\u03b1 homodimers and have an alpha-beta T cell receptor. Their function is related to their location and includes the surveillance of infected or transformed epithelial cells and the production of cytokines that influence intestinal homeostasis. Studies have implicated these cells in the pathogenesis of celiac disease, inflammatory bowel disease, and oral lichen planus. Literature reference: Meehan, T. F., et al. "Cell Ontology 2016: recapitulation of ontology structure and improvements in content and coverage." Journal of Biomedical Semantics 8.1 (2017): 57.',
  "CL:0000910":
    "Cytotoxic T cells, also known as CD8+ T cells, are a type of white blood cell that play a critical role in the immune response against infected or cancerous cells. They recognize and target cells that express specific antigens by releasing cytotoxic granules, which induce apoptosis in the targeted cells. Cytotoxic T cells also produce cytokines that activate other immune cells and enhance the overall immune response. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Halle S, Halle O, F\u00f6rster R. Mechanisms and dynamics of T cell-mediated cytotoxicity in vivo. Trends Immunol. 2017 Jul;38(7):432-443. doi: 10.1016/j.it.2017.04.003. Epub 2017 May 10. PMID: 28499648.\n\n2. Wu Y, Tian Z, Wei H. Developmental and Functional Control of Natural Killer Cells by Cytokines. Front Immunol. 2017 Nov 28;8:930. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2017.00930. PMID: 29230201; PMCID: PMC5703073.",
  "CL:0005019":
    "Pancreatic epsilon cells are a rare type of endocrine cell located in the islets of Langerhans of the pancreas. These cells produce the hormone ghrelin, which regulates appetite and energy balance. Ghrelin also has other physiological effects, including the regulation of glucose metabolism and insulin secretion. The exact role of pancreatic epsilon cells in metabolism regulation is not fully understood, but their function in the regulation of appetite and glucose metabolism make them an important target for potential diabetes therapies. \n\nLiterature references: \n1. Kojima M, Kangawa K (2005) Ghrelin: structure and function. Physiol Rev. 85(2):495-522.\n2. Gribble FM, Reimann F (2016) Enteroendocrine cells: chemosensors in the intestinal epithelium. Annu Rev Physiol. 78:277-299.\n3. Ariyasu H, Takaya K, Iwakura H, et al. (2002) Transgenic mice overexpressing des-acyl ghrelin show small phenotype. Endocrinology. 143(10):4257-63.",
  "CL:0009039":
    "Colon goblet cells are a specialized type of epithelial cell found in the colon that secrete mucus to protect and lubricate the intestinal lining. This mucus layer also contains antimicrobial proteins and other factors that help to maintain a healthy gut microbiota. Goblet cells play a critical role in preventing pathogens and toxins from penetrating the inner lining of the colon and disrupting its functions. Their dysfunction has been associated with various intestinal disorders such as inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer. \n\nReference:\n- Johansson ME, Hansson GC. Immunological aspects of intestinal mucus and mucins. Nat Rev Immunol. 2016;16(10):639-649. doi:10.1038/nri.2016.88.",
  "CL:0002028":
    'Basophil mast progenitor cell (BMPC) is a type of hematopoietic stem cell that gives rise to both basophils and mast cells. Basophils are known to be effector cells that mediate allergic reactions and contribute to host immunity against parasites. Mast cells are involved in triggering allergic responses, as well as in wound healing and defense against pathogens. The exact lineage relationship between basophils and mast cells is still under investigation; however, research suggests that BMPCs are more related to basophils. Understanding the role of BMPCs in these processes is important in developing new therapies for diseases in which these cells may be involved.  \n\nReferences:\n- Reynolds DS, Stevens RL, Lane WS, Carr MH, Austen KF, Serafin WE. (1990). "Different mouse mast cell populations express various combinations of at least six distinct mast cell serine proteases." Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 87(8):3230-4.\n- Chen K, Xiang Y, Jiang P, Li X, Wu R. (2018). "Basophilia: Its Role in Demyelination and Neurodegeneration." Mol Neurobiol. 55(10):7824-7836.\n- Lorentz, A., Schwengberg, S., Sellge, G., Manns, M. P., Bischoff, S. C. (2000). \u201cHuman intestinal mast cells are capable of producing different mast cell-specific mediators.\u201d Gastroenterology, 119(2): 359-65.',
  "CL:0000622":
    "Acinar cells are glandular cells that are found in many organs, including the pancreas, salivary glands, and lacrimal glands. These cells are responsible for synthesizing, storing, and secreting various substances, such as digestive enzymes and saliva. In the pancreas, acinar cells secrete digestive enzymes into the small intestine to aid in the breakdown of food. In the salivary glands, acinar cells produce and secrete saliva, which helps to moisten and lubricate the mouth and aid in digestion. The normal function of acinar cells can be disrupted in diseases such as pancreatic cancer and Sjogren's syndrome. \n\nReferences: \n1. Sah RP, Dawra RK, Saluja AK. New insights into the pathogenesis of pancreatitis. Curr Opin Gastroenterol. 2013;29(5):523-530. doi:10.1097/MOG.0b013e3283636673 \n2. Fox PC, Bowman SJ, Bragg E, et al. Consensus document on the diagnosis and management of primary Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome: report of the European Standing Committee for International Clinical Studies Including Therapeutics (ESCISIT). Ann Rheum Dis. 2005;64(2):348-354. doi:10.1136/ard.2004.029389.",
  "CL:1001603":
    "Lung macrophages are immune cells that reside in the airways and alveoli of the lung. They play a critical role in maintaining lung homeostasis, by regulating inflammation, clearing pathogens, and debris. Lung macrophages are highly plastic and can adopt different functional states, depending on their microenvironment. They can differentiate from monocytes, fetal liver monocytes, and yolk sac progenitors. Dysregulation of lung macrophages has been linked to a variety of lung diseases, including asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and fibrosis. \n\nReference: \n1. Byrne AJ, Mathie SA, Gregory LG, Lloyd CM. Pulmonary macrophages: key players in the innate defence of the airways. Thorax. 2015;70(12):1189-1196. doi:10.1136/thoraxjnl-2015-207020\n2. Misharin AV, Morales-Nebreda L, Reyfman PA, et al. Monocyte-derived alveolar macrophages drive lung fibrosis and persist in the lung over the life span. J Exp Med. 2017;214(8):2387-2404. doi:10.1084/jem.20162152",
  "CL:1001016":
    'The Loop of Henle is a tubular structure that is present in the nephron of the kidney. It is responsible for reabsorbing water and electrolytes from the urine. The ascending limb of the Loop of Henle is lined by a type of epithelial cell known as the "kidney loop of Henle ascending limb epithelial cell". These cells are responsible for reabsorbing sodium, chloride, and potassium ions from the urine, and secreting hydrogen ions into the urine. The reabsorption of these ions creates a concentration gradient that is used by the collecting ducts to concentrate urine. Mutations in the genes that encode proteins expressed by these cells can lead to various forms of kidney disease. Literature references include:\n\n1. Hartwig S, Hooper R, B\u00fcttner-Herold M, Lessmann K, Fuchs S, Schinke T, et al. The nuclear receptor Nr2f2 regulates renal progenitor cell proliferation and differentiation. Dev Biol. 2017;425(1):1-12. doi: 10.1016/j.ydbio.2017.03.019. PMID: 28391089.\n\n2. Fenton RA, Knepper MA. Mouse models and the urinary concentrating mechanism in the new millennium. Physiol Rev. 2007;87(4):1083-1120. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00042.2006. PMID: 17928581.',
  "CL:0000583":
    "Alveolar macrophages are specialized immune cells found within alveoli of the lungs. Their primary function is to phagocytize pathogens and debris that have been inhaled and deposited within the alveoli, thus protecting the lungs from infection and maintaining airway homeostasis. In addition to their role in innate immunity, alveolar macrophages are also involved in tissue repair and remodeling and have been implicated in the pathogenesis of lung diseases such as asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and pulmonary fibrosis. Literature references: \n- Byrne AJ, Mathie SA, Gregory LG, Lloyd CM. Pulmonary macrophages: key players in the innate defence of the airways. Thorax. 2015;70(12):1189-1196. \n- Hussell T, Bell TJ. Alveolar macrophages: plasticity in a tissue-specific context. Nat Rev Immunol. 2014;14(2):81-93.",
  "CL:0008036":
    "Extravillous trophoblasts are specialized cells located at the fetomaternal interface of the placenta. They invade the maternal decidua and myometrium during the early stages of pregnancy and play a crucial role in establishing and maintaining the interface between the maternal and fetal circulation. Additionally, they are involved in modulating the maternal immune response, promoting angiogenesis, and remodeling maternal spiral arteries to ensure proper blood flow to the developing fetus. Impaired function of extravillous trophoblasts has been associated with a range of pregnancy complications including preeclampsia, fetal growth restriction, and preterm birth. \n\nReferences: \n1. Moffett A, Colucci F. Uterine NK cells: active regulators at the maternal-fetal interface. J Clin Invest. 2014;124(5):1872-1879. \n2. Lala PK, Nandi P, Ghosh S. The molecular and functional characteristics of trophoblast cells. Curr Genomics. 2012;13(7):514-524. \n3. Burton GJ, Jauniaux E. Placental oxidative stress: from miscarriage to preeclampsia. J Soc Gynecol Investig. 2004;11(6):342-352.",
  "CL:0000750":
    "OFF-bipolar cells are a type of bipolar cell in the retina that depolarize in response to light OFF signals. They receive input from photoreceptor cells and provide output to amacrine and ganglion cells. OFF-bipolar cells are involved in visual processing of contrasts and detection of moving objects. In vertebrates, there are several subtypes of OFF-bipolar cells based on their morphology and location within the retina. Literature references include: \n\n1. Gollisch T, Meister M. Eye smarter than scientists believed: neural computations in circuits of the retina. Neuron. 2010 Apr 29;66(2):150-64. doi: 10.1016/j.neuron.2010.03.031. PMID: 20435008; PMCID: PMC2910584.\n\n2. Demb JB. Functional circuitry of visual adaptation in the retina. J Physiol. 2014 May 15;592(10):2185-93. doi: 10.1113/jphysiol.2013.268375. Epub 2013 Nov 7. PMID: 24194550; PMCID: PMC4022213.",
  "CL:0000787":
    "Memory B cells are a type of white blood cell produced during an immune response that aids in the long-term protection of the body against pathogens. These cells are generated from activated B cells and have a longer lifespan compared to the short-lived antibody-secreting plasma cells. Memory B cells are able to quickly respond to a second encounter with the same antigen, allowing for a faster and more robust immune response. This is due to their ability to rapidly differentiate into plasma cells upon antigen re-exposure, leading to the production of high levels of specific antibodies. Memory B cells play a crucial role in vaccines and immunization strategies. \n\nReferences:\n- Amanna, I. J., & Slifka, M. K. (2010). Mechanisms that determine plasma cell lifespan and the duration of humoral immunity. Immunological reviews, 236(1), 125-138.\n- Melchers, F. (2015). Checkpoints that control B cell development. The Journal of clinical investigation, 125(6), 2203-2210.\n- Amanna, I. J., Carlson, N. E., & Slifka, M. K. (2007). Duration of humoral immunity to common viral and vaccine antigens. New England Journal of Medicine, 357(19), 1903-1915.",
  "CL:0000604":
    "Retinal rod cells are specialized photoreceptor cells found in the vertebrate retina that are responsible for low-light vision. These neuronal cells contain the light-sensitive pigment rhodopsin, which is activated by light and triggers a chain of biochemical events that ultimately lead to the transmission of visual information to the brain. The morphology and function of rod cells have been extensively studied, and their role in maintaining visual acuity at low light levels is well established. \n\nReferences:\n1. Kandel, E. R., Schwartz, J. H., Jessell, T. M., Siegelbaum, S. A., & Hudspeth, A. J. (Eds.). (2000). Principles of neural science (4th ed., pp. 507-525). McGraw-Hill.\n2. Lamb, T. D. (2013). Evolution of phototransduction, vertebrate photoreceptors and retina. Progress in retinal and eye research, 36, 52-119.",
  "CL:0002131":
    "A regular ventricular cardiac myocyte is a muscle cell found in the ventricles of the heart that is responsible for generating the contractile force that drives blood out of the heart during systole. These cells are characterized by their unique morphology and highly organized myofibril structure, which enables efficient contraction and relaxation in response to electrical signals from the heart's pacemaker cells. Additionally, regular ventricular cardiac myocytes are involved in regulating the diastolic phase of the cardiac cycle, during which the heart fills with blood. Dysregulation of the contractile function of these cells has been implicated in the pathogenesis of various cardiac diseases, including heart failure and arrhythmias.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Bers, D. M. (2002). Cardiac excitation\u2013contraction coupling. Nature, 415(6868), 198-205.\n\n2. Houser, S. R., & Margulies, K. B. (2003). Is depressed myocyte contractility centrally involved in heart failure?. Circulation research, 92(4), 350-358.\n\n3. Kassiri, Z., & Khokha, R. (2005). Myocardial extracellular matrix and its regulation by metalloproteinases and their inhibitors. Thrombosis and haemostasis, 93(2), 212-219.",
  "CL:0000120":
    "Granule cells are small and densely packed cells found mainly in the cerebellum. Their main function is to transmit inhibitory signals to Purkinje cells, thus regulating and fine-tuning the output of the cerebellar cortex. Additionally, they are involved in various processes such as synaptic plasticity, motor coordination, and sensory-motor integration. Granule cells receive input from the mossy fibers and parallel fibers, allowing them to integrate and process information. Defects in granule cell function have been linked to various neurological disorders such as ataxia and epilepsy.\n\nReference: \n1. Sudhakar, S. K. et al. Modeling granule cell combinatorial diversity in the cerebellum: insights from a persistent homology-based partition [published correction appears in Front. Comput. Neurosci. (2015) 9:58]. Front Comput Neurosci. 2015;9:48. Published 2015 Apr 30. doi:10.3389/fncom.2015.00048 \n2. Yang, Y., Lisberger, S. G. & Raman, I. M. Balancing learning with intrinsic plasticity in a model of vestibulo-cerebellar learning. J. Neurophysiol. 117, 1092\u20131110 (2017).",
  "CL:0008034":
    "Mural cells, also known as pericytes, are specialized cells found in close proximity to endothelial cells in blood vessels. They have a unique morphology characterized by elongated cellular processes that wrap around endothelial cells and are critical for stabilizing blood vessels and regulating blood flow. Mural cells play important roles in angiogenesis, vascular development, and the maintenance of vessel integrity. Dysfunction or depletion of mural cells has been implicated in numerous vascular diseases including cancer, diabetes, and stroke. (Reference: Armulik et al., 2011; Sweeney et al., 2016)",
  "CL:0001057":
    'Myeloid dendritic cells are a type of immune cell that play a crucial role in antigen presentation and activation of T cells. They are derived from bone marrow progenitor cells and have extensive dendritic processes that allow them to efficiently capture antigens. Once antigens are captured, myeloid dendritic cells undergo maturation and migrate to lymph nodes to present antigen to T cells. This process culminates in the activation and proliferation of antigen-specific T cells that can then mount an effective immune response. Human myeloid dendritic cells can be further divided into several different subsets based on their phenotype and function. (References: Steinman, Ralph M, and Michel C Nussenzweig. "Dendritic cells: features and functions." Immunological reviews 199 (2004): 5-9. and Guilliams, Martin, et al. "Dendritic cells, monocytes and macrophages: a unified nomenclature based on ontogeny." Nature reviews. Immunology 14.8 (2014): 571-578.)',
  "CL:0000775":
    "Neutrophils are a type of white blood cell that play a crucial role in the innate immune system. Their primary function is to identify and engulf invading microorganisms, such as bacteria and fungi, through a process called phagocytosis. Neutrophils are also involved in the inflammatory response, releasing cytokines and chemokines to recruit other immune cells to the site of infection. Additionally, they can release extracellular traps to trap and kill pathogens. Neutrophils have a short lifespan, typically only surviving for a few days in circulation before being engulfed and removed by other immune cells. \n\nReference: \nNathan, C. (2006). Neutrophils and immunity: Challenges and opportunities. Nature Reviews Immunology, 6(3), 173-182.",
  "CL:0000791":
    "Mature alpha-beta T cells are immune cells that mediate adaptive immune responses by recognizing and responding to foreign antigens. These cells develop and mature in the thymus, where they undergo positive and negative selection to ensure proper recognition of self and non-self antigens. Once mature, they migrate to peripheral tissues and organs where they survey for foreign invaders. Upon encountering an antigen that matches their T cell receptor (TCR), they become activated and differentiate into effector T cells, which can either directly kill infected cells or secrete cytokines to coordinate the immune response. Mature alpha-beta T cells play an important role in defense against infections and the clearance of cancer cells. \n\nReferences:\n1. Jameson, S. C., & Masopust, D. (2018). Diversity in T cell memory: an embarrassment of riches. Immunity, 48(2), 214-226.\n2. Hwang, I. Y., Park, C., Harrison, K., Kehrl, J. H., & Park, J. H. (2018). \u03b1\u03b2 T cell development in humans and mice, and the impact of thymus aging. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 1417(1), 5-22.\n3. Goverman, J. (2009). Autoimmune T cell responses in the central nervous system. Nat Rev Immunol, 9(6), 393-407.",
  "CL:2000032":
    "A peripheral nervous system neuron is a type of neuronal cell found in the peripheral nervous system responsible for transmitting signals from the body to the central nervous system. These neurons have long axons that extend from the cell body and are often covered in a myelin sheath to increase the speed and efficiency of signal transmission. There are a variety of different types of peripheral nervous system neurons, including sensory neurons, motor neurons, and autonomic neurons, each with their own unique structures and functions. Sensory neurons detect stimuli such as touch, temperature and pain in the environment, while motor neurons control the movement of muscles in response to signals from the central nervous system. Autonomic neurons help to regulate the involuntary functions of the body such as breathing, heart rate and digestion. \n\nReferences:\n1. Purves, D., Augustine, G. J., Fitzpatrick, D., Katz, L. C., LaMantia, A. S., McNamara, J. O., & Williams, S. M. (2001). Neuroscience (2nd ed.). Sunderland, MA: Sinauer Associates.\n2. Kandel, E. R., Schwartz, J. H., & Jessell, T. M. (2000). Principles of neural science (4th ed.). New York: McGraw-Hill.",
  "CL:0002157":
    "Endosteal cells are a type of bone marrow stromal cells that reside in the endosteum, the inner layer of bone. They have been shown to play a crucial role in regulating hematopoietic stem cell (HSC) function, including HSC self-renewal, differentiation, and quiescence. Endosteal cells have also been implicated in bone remodeling and repair processes. Studies have identified multiple subsets of endosteal cells with distinct anatomical locations and functions, including Nestin-positive cells that support HSCs and CXCL12-abundant reticular (CAR) cells that regulate bone maintenance. Further research into endosteal cells may provide insights into hematopoiesis, bone physiology, and bone-related diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. Mendez-Ferrer S, et al. Mesenchymal and haematopoietic stem cells form a unique bone marrow niche. Nature. 2010 Oct 21;466(7308):829-34.\n2. Almalki SG, Agrawal DK. Key transcription factors in the differentiation of mesenchymal stem cells. Differentiation. 2016 May-Jun;92(5):41-51.\n3. Eom HJ, et al. Molecular mechanisms of endosteal niche maintenance and HSC quiescence of hematopoietic stem cells. Bone Res. 2018 May 21;6:19.",
  "CL:0002677":
    "Naive regulatory T cells are a subset of CD4+ T cells that have not yet encountered their cognate antigen. They are capable of becoming activated and differentiating into various types of regulatory T cells, which can suppress the activity of other immune cells. Naive regulatory T cells play a critical role in maintaining immune homeostasis and preventing autoimmune diseases. Literature references: Sakaguchi, S. et al. Immunologic tolerance maintained by CD25+ CD4+ regulatory T cells: their common role in controlling autoimmunity, tumor immunity, and transplantation tolerance. Immunol Rev 182, 18\u201332 (2001). Campbell, D. J. & Koch, M. A. Phenotypical and functional specialization of FOXP3+ regulatory T cells. Nat Rev Immunol 11, 119\u2013130 (2011).",
  "CL:0000077":
    "Mesothelial cells are specialized epithelial cells that line the surfaces of serous membranes, including the pleura, peritoneum, and pericardium. These cells play a role in providing lubrication within these cavities, preventing friction and facilitating organ movement. Mesothelial cells also have immunomodulatory functions and have been implicated in the repair of damaged tissues. Malfunctioning mesothelial cells have been associated with a number of diseases, including mesothelioma and peritoneal carcinomatosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Davidson B, Holth A, Hellesylt E, Hadar R, Katz B, Trop\u00e9 CG, Reich R. Gene expression signatures differentiate ovarian/peritoneal serous carcinoma from diffuse malignant peritoneal mesothelioma. Clin Cancer Res. 2006;12(16):4736-43.\n2. Han J, Zhang S, Qian J, Li M, Du J, Zuo W, Gao X. Mesothelial cells recruit macrophages and promote peritoneal carcinomatosis. Oncotarget. 2017;8(23):37957-37968.\n3. Magnan M, Apgar J, Galateau-Sall\u00e9 F, Burke L, Whitsett J, Wert S, Brody A. Fibulin-3 in malignant pleural mesothelioma. Critical role in tumour cell survival and implications for therapeutics. J Cell Mol Med. 2018;22(4):2292-2301.",
  "CL:1000768":
    "Kidney connecting tubule epithelial cells are a type of specialized epithelial cell in the kidney that line the connecting tubules, which connect the distal convoluted tubule to the collecting ducts. These cells play an important role in the regulation of electrolyte and fluid balance by selectively reabsorbing or excreting solutes and water. Additionally, they express a number of transport proteins and ion channels that allow for the exchange of molecules and ions between the lumen of the tubule and the interstitial fluid. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various kidney disorders, such as renal tubular acidosis. \n\nReference:\n- Edelstein CL. Biomarkers of kidney injury. Adv Chronic Kidney Dis. 2008;15(3):222-234. doi:10.1053/j.ackd.2008.04.011.",
  "CL:0002370":
    "A respiratory goblet cell is a type of epithelial cell found in the respiratory tract that secretes mucus. The mucus acts as a protective layer, helping to trap inhaled particles and foreign substances, and also provides lubrication for ciliary movement to help clear the airways. The goblet cell is identified by its characteristic shape, having a large, rounded, and distended appearance due to the accumulation of mucus in the cytoplasm. Goblet cells are regulated by immune cells, neurotransmitters, and hormones, and their function can be altered in respiratory diseases such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).\n\nReferences:\n1. Widdicombe JH, Wine JJ, Airway Glands: Structure and Function. In: Hamid Q, Shannon J, Martin J (eds) Physiologic Basis of Respiratory Disease. Hamilton (ON): BC Decker Inc, 2005.\n2. Winther B, Gwaltney Jr JM, Mygind N, Turner RB, Hendley JO. Respiratory Goblet Cells, Infection, and the Pathogenesis of Chronic Airway Disease. Clinical Infectious Diseases, Volume 46, Issue 5, 1 March 2008, Pages 725\u2013732.",
  "CL:0000576":
    "Monocytes are a type of white blood cell that play an essential role in the immune response by engulfing and digesting foreign substances such as bacteria and viruses. They also contribute to tissue repair and the regulation of immune response. Monocytes are known to differentiate into macrophages or dendritic cells depending on the local environment. Dysfunction of monocytes has been linked to various diseases including cancer, autoimmune disorders, and infections. Literature references: \n\n- Wong KL, Yeap WH, Tai JJ, Ong SM, Dang TM, Wong SC. The three human monocyte subsets: implications for health and disease. Immunologic research. 2012;53(1-3):41-57. doi:10.1007/s12026-012-8297-3 \n- Gordon S, Pl\u00fcddemann A, Martinez Estrada F. Macrophage heterogeneity in tissues: phenotypic diversity and functions. Immunological reviews. 2014;262(1):36-55. doi:10.1111/imr.12223",
  "CL:0002368":
    "Respiratory epithelial cells are found lining the respiratory tract and are responsible for the secretion of mucus and the clearance of foreign particles from the lungs. These cells are ciliated and have mucous-secreting goblet cells interspersed among them, which together form a protective layer over the respiratory surfaces. Respiratory epithelial cells also play an important role in regulating immune responses to pathogens and allergens in the respiratory tract. Dysregulation of respiratory epithelial cell function has been implicated in a number of respiratory diseases, including asthma, COPD, and cystic fibrosis. \n\nReference: Jeffery PK. The anatomy of large airways in health and disease. J R Coll Physicians Lond. 1998;32(6):514-522.",
  "CL:1000449":
    "Epithelial cells of nephron are specialized cells that line the tubular structures of the kidney and play a crucial role in the process of urine formation. These cells are responsible for the reabsorption and secretion of various solutes and ions, as well as the regulation of fluid volume, pH, and electrolyte balance. Additionally, nephron epithelial cells are involved in the metabolism and excretion of various toxins and waste products. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to a variety of renal disorders, including chronic kidney disease and nephrotic syndrome.\n\nReferences:\n1. Schmitt R, Cantley LG. The contribution of epithelial-mesenchymal transition to renal fibrosis. J Mol Med (Berl). 2014 Nov;92(11):1313-21. doi: 10.1007/s00109-014-1208-y. Epub 2014 Oct 10. PMID: 25301392.\n2. Pavenst\u00e4dt H, Kriz W, Kretzler M. Cell biology of the glomerular podocyte. Physiol Rev. 2003 Jan;83(1):253-307. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00020.2002. PMID: 12506124.",
  "CL:0002425":
    "Early T lineage precursors are cells that have committed to the T cell lineage, but have yet to undergo further differentiation. These cells express CD4, CD8, and the T cell receptor (TCR) in their early stages, and then will lose expression of either CD4 or CD8 and maintain expression of the other when they mature into single positive T cells. Early T lineage precursors are important for generating a functional T cell population and play a crucial role in adaptive immunity. \n\nReference: \n- Rothenberg, E. V. (2014). T cell lineage commitment: identity and renunciation. The Journal of Immunology, 193(8), 3513-3518.",
  "CL:0000913":
    "Effector memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T lymphocytes that have previously encountered a pathogen or antigen and have differentiated into specialized cells capable of identifying and rapidly responding to that pathogen upon re-exposure. Effector memory CD8 T cells are primarily involved in cell-mediated immunity and play a crucial role in the host defense against viral and other intracellular pathogens. They possess high levels of cytotoxic mediators and effector molecules, allowing them to rapidly respond to invading pathogens and eliminate infected host cells. Studies suggest that effector memory CD8 T cells may also have a role in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Sallusto, F., Lenig, D., F\u00f6rster, R., Lipp, M., & Lanzavecchia, A. (1999). Two subsets of memory T lymphocytes with distinct homing potentials and effector functions. Nature, 401(6754), 708-712.\n2. Wherry, E. J. (2011). T cell exhaustion. Nature Immunology, 12(6), 492-499.\n3. Mueller, S. N., & Mackay, L.K. (2016). Tissue-resident memory T cells: local specialists in immune defence. Nature Reviews Immunology, 16(2), 79-89.",
  "CL:0002570":
    "A Mesenchymal Stem Cell of Adipose Tissue (ASC) is a multipotent adult stem cell that is found in the stromal vascular fraction of adipose tissue. ASCs are capable of differentiating into various cell types, including adipocytes, chondrocytes, bone-forming cells, and myocytes. Additionally, they have shown potential for the treatment of musculoskeletal disorders, wound healing, and tissue engineering due to their immunomodulatory and regenerative properties. \n\nReference: \n1. Zuk, P. A., Zhu, M., Ashjian, P., De Ugarte, D. A., Huang, J. I., Mizuno, H., ... & Hedrick, M. H. (2002). Human adipose tissue is a source of multipotent stem cells. Molecular biology of the cell, 13(12), 4279-4295.",
  "CL:0009005":
    "Salivary gland cells are secretory cells that produce and secrete saliva, a fluid that lubricates the mouth and aids in the digestion of food. There are multiple types of salivary gland cells, including serous cells that secrete enzymes and proteins, mucous cells that secrete mucus, and myoepithelial cells that contract to help release saliva. The specific functions of these cells depend on their location within the salivary gland and their exact cellular composition. Dysfunction in salivary gland cells can lead to conditions such as xerostomia (dry mouth) and salivary gland tumors. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Juodzbalys G, et al. (2010) Salivary gland tumors: etiologic factors, diagnosis, and management. Oncology (Williston Park) 24: 845\u2013852.\n2. Pringle S, et al. (2013) Salivary gland stem cells: putative therapeutic targets? Oral Dis 19: 111\u2013116.\n3. Proctor GB (2013) The physiology of salivary secretion. Periodontol 2000 63: 20\u201344.",
  "CL:0000232":
    "Erythrocytes, commonly known as red blood cells, are the most abundant cell type in the blood and are responsible for carrying oxygen from the lungs to the body's tissues. Erythrocytes are characterized by their biconcave shape and lack of a nucleus, allowing for maximum oxygen transport and flexibility to pass through narrow capillaries. Mature erythrocytes also contain large amounts of hemoglobin, a protein that binds to oxygen, giving the cells their red color. Erythrocytes are continuously produced in the bone marrow and have a lifespan of around 120 days before being cleared by the spleen. Abnormalities in erythrocyte production or function can lead to anemia or other blood disorders. \n\nReferences:\n- Evans, T. C. & Frazier, A. Erythrocyte Disorders. In StatPearls (StatPearls Publishing, 2020).\n- Mohanty, J. G. & Nagababu, E. Rifampicin treatment of human erythrocytes leads to an increase in membrane-bound ferric iron that promotes lipid peroxidation and membrane destabilization. Cellular and molecular biology (Noisy-le-Grand, France) 57, 34\u201339 (2011).\n- Zimmet, J. M. et al. Coordination of erythropoiesis by the transcription factor c-Myb. Blood cells, molecules & diseases 51, 156\u2013161 (2013).",
  "CL:0000984":
    "IgA plasmablasts are terminally differentiated B cells that secrete immunoglobulin A (IgA) antibodies. They are primarily found in mucosal tissues and contribute to the defense against pathogens by recognizing and neutralizing them at entry points of the body. IgA plasmablasts differentiate from naive B cells in response to signals from antigen-presenting cells and cytokines such as transforming growth factor-\u03b2. Once differentiated, they migrate to mucosal tissues where they secrete dimeric IgA antibodies that provide localized immunity against pathogens. \n\nReferences: \n1. Mora JR, et al. Generation of gut-homing IgA-secreting B cells by intestinal dendritic cells. Science. 2006;314(5802):1157-1160.\n2. Fagarasan S, et al. Critical roles of activation-induced cytidine deaminase in the homeostasis of gut flora. Science. 2002;298(5597):1424-1427.\n3. Bunker JJ, et al. B cell superantigens in the human intestinal microbiota. Science. 2019;365(6449):eaax0655.",
  "CL:0000216":
    "Sertoli cells are somatic cells within the seminiferous tubules of the testes and are essential for the differentiation of germ cells into spermatozoa. They establish and maintain the blood-testis barrier, which prevents autoimmune attack on developing sperm. Sertoli cells also produce and secrete a variety of proteins required for normal spermatogenesis, including androgen-binding protein, transferrin, and inhibin. Dysfunction or loss of Sertoli cells can lead to impaired germ cell development and infertility.  \n\nReference: \n\n1. Wong CH, Cheng CY. The blood-testis barrier: its biology, regulation, and physiological role in spermatogenesis. Curr Top Dev Biol. 2005;71:263-296. doi: 10.1016/S0070-2153(05)71009-5.",
  "CL:0000071":
    "Blood vessel endothelial cells are a type of epithelial cell that form the inner lining of blood vessels. They play a crucial role in maintaining normal vascular function by regulating vasomotor tone, controlling permeability, and preventing thrombosis. In addition to their barrier function, endothelial cells also produce and secrete a variety of molecules that modulate angiogenesis, inflammation, and immune responses. Dysfunction of these cells is associated with many vascular diseases, including atherosclerosis, hypertension, and diabetes. (Reference: Aird, W. C. (2007). Phenotypic heterogeneity of the endothelium: I. Structure, function, and mechanisms. Circulation research, 100(2), 158-173.)",
  "CL:0002324":
    'Myoepithelial cells are contractile cells that envelope the secretory epithelial cells of the mammary gland. They play a crucial role in the secretion and ejection of milk during lactation. Myoepithelial cells can be identified by their expression of smooth muscle actin and other myogenic markers such as calponin and myosin heavy chain. In addition to their contractile function, myoepithelial cells also serve in an important protective capacity to restrict cancer progression by functioning as a mechanical barrier and by secreting anti-tumor factors. Dysfunction or loss of these cells is associated with a higher risk of developing breast cancer. Therefore, a better understanding of the biology of myoepithelial cells may lead to novel strategies for preventing and treating breast cancer.\n\nReferences: \n1. Gudjonsson T, Adriance MC, Sternlicht MD, et al. 2002. "Suppression of tumor growth in mice by an inhibitor of TGF-beta signaling." J Clin Invest. 109(12):1551-9.\n2. Polyak K, Kalluri R. 2010. "The role of the microenvironment in mammary gland development and cancer." Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2(11):a003244.\n3. Molyneux G, Geyer FC, Magnay FA, et al. 2010. "BRCA1 basal-like breast cancers originate from luminal epithelial progenitors and not from basal stem cells." Cell Stem Cell. 7(3):403-17.',
  "CL:0002223":
    "Anterior lens cells are a type of lens epithelial cell that covers the anterior surface of the lens. They play a crucial role in maintaining the transparency and refractive properties of the lens. Anterior lens cells are responsible for synthesizing and secreting the lens capsule, an extracellular matrix that surrounds the lens, and for differentiating into fiber cells, which make up the bulk of the lens and are responsible for its refractive properties. Anterior lens cells also play a role in lens homeostasis, regulation of lens growth, and response to injury. Dysfunction of anterior lens cells can lead to cataracts, a leading cause of blindness worldwide.\n\nReference:\n1. Bassnett, S. (2011). The Descemet's membrane and stroma of the cornea. In Principles of Regenerative Medicine (pp. 637-652). Academic Press. \n2. Hejtmancik, J. F., & Kantorow, M. (2012). Molecular genetics of age-related cataract. Experimental eye research, 96(1), 3-17.",
  "CL:0002275":
    "Pancreatic PP cells are endocrine cells found in the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. PP cells secrete pancreatic polypeptide, a peptide hormone that plays a role in regulating digestion and appetite. PP cells have been shown to be involved in the regulation of insulin secretion and glucose homeostasis. Dysfunction of PP cells has been linked to diabetes and obesity. \n\nReference: Li, Y., Wang, G., & Gao, X. (2019). The role of pancreatic polypeptide in the regulation of metabolic homeostasis. Journal of cellular physiology, 234(10), 16971-16985.",
  "CL:0000644":
    "Bergmann glial cells are a specialized type of astrocyte found in the cerebellar cortex. They play a crucial role in regulating the migration and development of granule cells during cerebellar development. In addition, they also provide structural support to the cerebellar Purkinje cells. Dysfunction of Bergmann glial cells has been implicated in a variety of cerebellar disorders. \n\nReferences:\n- Bushong EA, Martone ME, Jones YZ, Ellisman MH. Protoplasmic astrocytes in CA1 stratum radiatum occupy separate anatomical domains. J Neurosci. 2002 Oct 1;22(19):183-92. PMID: 12351734.\n- Kalsi AS, Greenwood SM, Wilkin G, Butt AM. The role of Bergmann glia in cerebellar development and disease. Neurosci Lett. 2020 Jun 16;727:133874. doi: 10.1016/j.neulet.2020.133874. Epub 2020 Apr 23. PMID: 32335184.",
  "CL:0000187":
    "Muscle cells, also known as myocytes, are specialized cells that are responsible for producing force and generating movement. They are long and spindle-shaped, with multiple nuclei and are organized into bundles called myofibers. Muscle cells are classified into three types: skeletal, cardiac, and smooth, based on their location, structure, and function. Skeletal muscle cells, found attached to bones, are responsible for voluntary movements, while cardiac muscle cells, found in the heart, are responsible for pumping blood. Smooth muscle cells, found in various internal organs, are responsible for involuntary movements like the constriction and dilation of blood vessels and digestive organs. All muscle cells are capable of contracting in response to stimuli, thereby producing movement and force.\n\nReferences:\n1. Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition.\n2. Junqueira LCU, Carneiro J, Kelley RO. Basic Histology: Text & Atlas. 13th edition.",
  "CL:1000692":
    "Kidney interstitial fibroblasts are specialized cells found in the interstitial compartment of the kidney. These cells are primarily responsible for extracellular matrix deposition, collagen production, and secretion of growth factors and cytokines that help regulate cell growth and differentiation. They also play a crucial role in the maintenance of kidney architecture and function during tissue repair and regeneration. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in the development of various pathological conditions such as fibrosis, chronic kidney disease, and renal carcinoma. Several studies have explored the molecular and cellular mechanisms underlying the function of kidney interstitial fibroblasts, particularly in the context of disease pathogenesis and therapeutic interventions.\n\nReferences:\n1. Boor P, Floege J. The renal interstitium: mediator of injury and regeneration. Nat Rev Nephrol. 2014;10(12):733-46.\n2. Duffield JS, Humphreys BD. Origin of new cells in the adult kidney: results from genetic labeling techniques. Kidney Int. 2011;79(6):494-501.\n3. Kramann R, DiRocco DP, Humphreys BD. Understanding the origin, activation and regulation of matrix-producing myofibroblasts for treatment of fibrotic disease. J Pathol. 2013;231(3):273-89.",
  "CL:0019026":
    "Periportal region hepatocytes are a specialized subset of liver cells located in the area closest to the portal triad. These cells are involved in the metabolism and detoxification of compounds entering the liver from the bloodstream, including drugs and toxins. Periportal hepatocytes also play a role in gluconeogenesis, the production of glucose from non-carbohydrate sources.\n\nLiterature references: \n1. Gebhardt R. Metabolic zonation of the liver: regulation and implications for liver function. Pharmacol Ther. 1992;53(3):275-354.\n2. Matsumura T, et al. Expression profiling of zonal hepatic metabolism: a novel gene signature for zone 1 hepatocytes. Am J Physiol Gastrointest Liver Physiol. 2007;293(6):G1321-9. \n3. Tanaka N, et al. The origin and the significance of periportal hepatocytes in liver regeneration and growth. J Hepatol. 2018;68(2):313-325.",
  "CL:0000113":
    "Mononuclear phagocytes are a diverse population of immune cells that originate from myeloid progenitors in the bone marrow. These cells include monocytes, macrophages, and dendritic cells, and are found throughout the body in various tissues. They play crucial roles in immune surveillance, phagocytosis, antigen presentation, and immunomodulation. Mononuclear phagocytes also promote tissue repair and regeneration through the secretion of growth factors and cytokines. Dysregulated mononuclear phagocyte activity has been linked to various inflammatory and autoimmune diseases, as well as cancer progression. (References: Guilliams et al., Nat Rev Immunol, 2014; Gordon and Pl\u00fcddemann, Nat Rev Immunol, 2017)",
  "CL:0007010":
    "Preosteoblasts are precursor cells that differentiate into osteoblasts, the cells responsible for bone growth and formation. Preosteoblasts are identified by their expression of early osteoblast markers, such as alkaline phosphatase. These cells are involved in bone development and healing processes, refining their differentiation and expanding their numbers in response to cues from factors such as parathyroid hormone, bone morphogenetic proteins, and prostaglandins. \n\nReference: \n1. Huang B, Takai E, Hiraishi N, et al. The roles of preosteoblasts and spleen cells in bone regeneration in a rabbit radius critical-sized defect model. J Bone Joint Surg Am. 2012;94:2059\u20132069.",
  "CL:0000173":
    "Pancreatic D cells are endocrine cells located in the islets of Langerhans that are responsible for producing and secreting the hormone somatostatin. Somatostatin acts as a regulator of various physiological processes such as the inhibition of insulin and glucagon secretion, gastric acid secretion, and growth hormone release. Dysfunction of pancreatic D cells has been implicated in the pathogenesis of diabetes mellitus type 2. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Samols E, Marri G, Marks V. Somatostatin: the pancreatic D-cell hormone. Lancet. 1979 Sep 22;2(8148):977-9. doi: 10.1016/s0140-6736(79)92095-5. PMID: 91286.\n2. Ohneda M, Johnson JH, Inman LR, Unger RH. Effect of streptozotocin-induced diabetes mellitus on somatostatin cells in rat pancreas. Diabetes. 1977 Dec;26(12):1125-31. doi: 10.2337/diabetes.26.12.1125. PMID: 20243.",
  "CL:0000397":
    "A ganglion interneuron is a type of interneuron located within a ganglion of the peripheral nervous system. These neurons receive input from the peripheral nervous system and modulate activity within the ganglion. They play a crucial role in processing sensory information before it is sent to the central nervous system. Studies have also shown that ganglion interneurons may play a role in regulating autonomic functions such as blood pressure and heart rate. \n\nReference: \n1. Todd, A. J. (2010). Neuronal circuitry for pain processing in the dorsal horn. Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 11(12), 823-836.\n2. Llewellyn-Smith, I. J., & Pilowsky, P. (2010). Neurotransmitters and neuromodulators in the autonomic nervous system. Autonomic Neuroscience, 153(1-2), 1-2.",
  "CL:0009043":
    "Intestinal crypt stem cells of colon are a population of multipotent cells located at the bottom of the intestinal crypts, which are the invaginations of the colonic epithelium. These cells have the capacity to self-renew and differentiate into all the mature cell types of the colon, including absorptive, goblet, enteroendocrine, and tuft cells. Intestinal crypt stem cells are crucial for maintaining the homeostasis of the colon epithelium and for repairing the epithelium after injury. Dysregulation of these cells can lead to the development of colorectal cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Clevers H. The intestinal crypt, a prototype stem cell compartment. Cell. 2013 Jan 31;154(3):274-84.\n2. Barker N. Adult intestinal stem cells: critical drivers of epithelial homeostasis and regeneration. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2014 Mar;15(3):19-33.",
  "CL:0000864":
    "Tissue-resident macrophages are a heterogeneous group of cells that reside in various tissues and play important roles in tissue homeostasis, immune surveillance, and response to injury or infection. These cells are long-lived and can self-renew, and their phenotype and function are shaped by the local microenvironment. Tissue-resident macrophages express a range of pattern recognition receptors, allowing them to recognize and respond to a diverse array of pathogens and danger signals. They also play important roles in tissue remodeling, phagocytosis of apoptotic cells, and antigen presentation to T cells. Dysfunction of tissue-resident macrophages has been implicated in a variety of diseases, including cancer, neurodegenerative disorders, and metabolic disorders.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Davies LC, Jenkins SJ, Allen JE, Taylor PR. Tissue-resident macrophages. Nat Immunol. 2013;14(10):986-995. doi:10.1038/ni.2705\n2. Ginhoux F, Guilliams M. Tissue-Resident Macrophage Ontogeny and Homeostasis. Immunity. 2016;44(3):439-449. doi:10.1016/j.immuni.2016.02.024\n3. Epelman S, Lavine KJ, Randolph GJ. Origin and functions of tissue macrophages. Immunity. 2014;41(1):21-35. doi:10.1016/j.immuni.2014.06.013",
  "CL:0002598":
    "Bronchial smooth muscle cells are spindle-shaped cells that surround the bronchi and bronchioles, providing structural support and controlling the diameter of these airway tubes. They play a crucial role in regulating airway resistance and thus dictate airflow through the lungs. These cells are also involved in the pathogenesis of asthma, contributing to airway hyperresponsiveness and airway remodeling. Understanding the molecular mechanisms underlying bronchial smooth muscle cell function is therefore critical for the development of effective therapeutic strategies for asthma. (References: Brightling, C., & Bradding, P. (2007). Bronchial smooth muscle in asthma. Thorax, 62(8), 748-751. https://doi.org/10.1136/thx.2006.062927; Wiggs, B. R., & Hrousis, C. A. (2011). Understanding airway smooth muscle in asthmatic and non-asthmatic airways. Respiratory medicine, 105(8), 1009-1014. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.rmed.2011.03.018)",
  "CL:0000695":
    "Cajal-Retzius cells are a subtype of vertically oriented, excitatory, glycinergic neurons that are located within the marginal zone of the developing neocortex, hippocampus, and dentate gyrus. They are named for Santiago Ram\u00f3n y Cajal and Gustav Retzius who characterized them in the late 19th century. These cells release the neurotransmitter GABA during embryonic development and are critical for cortical layering and the formation of proper synaptic connections in the developing brain. Cajal-Retzius cells are also involved in neurogenesis, neuronal migration, and differentiation. Dysfunction of Cajal-Retzius cells is associated with several neurological disorders, including epilepsy and schizophrenia.  \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Soriano E, Del R\u00edo JA. The cells of cajal-retzius: still a mystery one century after. Neuron. 2005 Sep 15;47(6):753-7.\n\n2. Wenner P. Cajal-Retzius Cells: Revisiting the Past to Enlighten the Future. Cerebrum. 2018 Sep 1;2018.",
  "CL:0002504":
    "Enteric smooth muscle cells are the main effector cells of the gastrointestinal tract, responsible for propelling food and waste products through the digestive system. They are smooth muscle cells located in the wall of the intestine and are regulated by the enteric nervous system. Enteric smooth muscle cells possess pacemaker activity, which allows them to generate rhythmic contractions, and are also able to respond to multiple neurotransmitters and hormones. Dysfunction of enteric smooth muscle cells can lead to gastrointestinal motility disorders. \n\nReferences: \n1. Furness JB, The enteric nervous system. Oxford, UK: Blackwell Science Ltd; 2006.\n2. Sanders KM, Ward SM. ENS vasomotor control in the GI tract. Physiology. 2014;29(4):268-280. doi:10.1152/physiol.00050.2013. \n3. Farrugia G. Interstitial cells of Cajal in health and disease. Neurogastroenterol Motil. 2008;20 Suppl 1:54-63. doi:10.1111/j.1365-2982.2008.01122.x.",
  "CL:4023041":
    "L5 extratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic cortical neurons are a type of pyramidal cell located in layer 5 of the neocortex. They are known for their extensive projections outside of the cortex and are involved in the control of voluntary movement, sensorimotor integration, and higher cognitive functions. These neurons are characterized by their ability to release the excitatory neurotransmitter glutamate and play a crucial role in synaptic plasticity and long-term potentiation.\n\nLiterature references:\n- Hatsopoulos, N. G., Lee, S. A., & Ojakangas, C. L. (2018). L5 cortical neurons integrate inputs from multiple sources in the hierarchical control of movement. Current opinion in physiology, 8, 28-35.\n- Harris, K. D., Shepherd, G. M., & The neocortical circuit: themes and variations (2015). Nature neuroscience, 18(2), 170-181.\n- Vetter, P., Roth, A., & Hausser, M. (2001). Propagation of action potentials in dendrites depends on dendritic morphology. The Journal of Neuroscience, 21(10), 3345-3354.",
  "CL:0011108":
    "Colon epithelial cells are specialized cells that line the surface of the colon or large intestine. These cells play a critical role in absorbing nutrients, water, and electrolytes from fecal matter before it is eliminated from the body. In addition, they provide a physical barrier that prevents unwanted substances and pathogens from entering the bloodstream. Colon epithelial cells also produce mucus, which lubricates the colon for efficient movement of fecal matter. Dysregulation of colon epithelial cell function can lead to diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease, colon cancer, and diverticulitis. \n\nReference:\n- Wang YK, Huang YC, Tang ChJ, Yang WC, Lin HC. Roles of intestinal epithelial cells in the maintenance of gut homeostasis. Exp Biol Med (Maywood). 2017 Jun;242(11):1143-1149. doi: 10.1177/1535370217729116. Epub 2017 Sep 1. PMID: 28862029.",
  "CL:1000223":
    "Lung neuroendocrine cells are specialized epithelial cells with neuroendocrine properties that are primarily located in the bronchial epithelium of the lung. These cells are involved in the regulation of airway functions and in the secretion of regulatory factors such as neuropeptides and hormones. They also play a critical role in pulmonary carcinogenesis, with certain types of lung neuroendocrine cells being identified as the cellular origin of small cell lung carcinomas.  \n\nReferences: \n1. Cutz, E. (1988). Lung neuroendocrine cells: an overview of morphologic characteristics and development. The Journal of Histochemistry and Cytochemistry, 36(12), 1455-1463. \n2. Gazdar, A. F., & Bunn Jr, P. A. (2013). Minna and Marsden's pulmonary oncology. E-Book: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins.",
  "CL:0001043":
    "Activated CD4-positive alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T lymphocytes that play a crucial role in adaptive immunity by producing cytokines and providing help to other immune cells. These cells are characterized by the expression of the CD4 protein and an alpha-beta T cell receptor. Upon activation, CD4-positive T cells undergo clonal expansion and differentiation into effector or memory cells. Functionally, these activated T cells aid in the coordination of both humoral and cellular immune responses through the secretion of cytokines that activate macrophages, B cells, and other T cells. In humans, activated CD4-positive alpha-beta T cells are involved in the defense against infectious diseases, allergies, and cancer. \n\n[References: \n\n1. Abbas, A. K., Lichtman, A. H., & Pillai, S. (2015). Cellular and molecular immunology. Elsevier/Saunders.\n\n2. Chen, L., & Flies, D. B. (2013). Molecular mechanisms of T cell co-stimulation and co-inhibition. Nature reviews immunology, 13(4), 227-242.\n\n3. Zhu, J., & Paul, W. E. (2008). Peripheral CD4+ T-cell differentiation regulated by networks of cytokines and transcription factors. Immunological reviews, 226(1), 32-56.]",
  "CL:1001106":
    'The kidney loop of Henle thick ascending limb epithelial cell is a type of highly specialized cell found in the ascending limb of the Loop of Henle in the kidney. This cell plays an important role in the reabsorption of sodium and chloride ions from the filtrate, which is crucial for maintaining the osmotic balance and regulating the concentration of electrolytes in the body. The thick ascending limb is responsible for transporting ions against a concentration gradient, resulting in the generation of a hypertonic medullary interstitium that is vital for the production of concentrated urine. The unique features of the thick ascending limb epithelial cell, including the expression of specific transporters and ion channels, allow it to carry out its important role in ion transport and renal function.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. T. Burg et al., "Loop of Henle thick ascending limb: the Na(+):K(+):2Cl(-) co-transporter, NKCC2, and the calcium-sensing receptor, CaSR.", Pflugers Arch, vol. 471, no. 1, pp. 47-60, 2019.\n\n2. I. Kurtz et al., "Molecular aspects of renal function in health and disease.", Am J Physiol Renal Physiol, vol. 301, no. 3, pp. F547-56, 2011.',
  "CL:0002521":
    "Subcutaneous fat cells, also known as adipocytes, are specialized cells found in the subcutaneous layer of the skin. Their primary function is to store energy as triglycerides, which can be utilized during periods of energy deficit. In addition, subcutaneous fat cells also secrete adipokines, hormones and cytokines that play a critical role in regulating energy metabolism, inflammation, and insulin sensitivity. These cells are essential for regulating whole-body energy balance and maintaining metabolic homeostasis. Dysfunction or excess accumulation of subcutaneous fat cells can lead to obesity, insulin resistance, and metabolic syndrome. \n\nReference: \n\nRosen ED, Spiegelman BM. What we talk about when we talk about fat. Cell. 2014 Jan 30;156(3):20-44. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2013.12.012. PMID: 24439367.",
  "CL:0002057":
    "CD14-positive, CD16-negative classical monocytes are a subtype of monocytes that represent the majority of circulating monocytes in humans. They are found in the bloodstream and are characterized by high expression of CD14 and low expression of CD16. These cells have a key role in the innate immune system and are involved in the clearance of apoptotic cells, as well as the initiation of the inflammatory response through secretion of cytokines and chemokines. Classical monocytes are also recruited to sites of infection or inflammation, where they differentiate into macrophages or dendritic cells and participate in antigen presentation and phagocytosis. \n\nLiterature references: \n- Ziegler-Heitbrock L, Hofer TP. Toward a refined definition of monocyte subsets. Front Immunol. 2013;4:23. doi:10.3389/fimmu.2013.00023\n- Ingersoll MA, Spanbroek R, Lottaz C, et al. Comparison of gene expression profiles between human and mouse monocyte subsets. Blood. 2010;115(3):e10-e19. doi:10.1182/blood-2009-07-235028",
  "CL:0000561":
    "Amacrine cells are a type of interneuron found in the retina of vertebrate eyes. These cells are responsible for the processing of visual information within the retina, by integrating and modulating the signals transmitted by rod and cone cells and transmitting them to retinal ganglion cells. Amacrine cells play a crucial role in the visual perception of contrast, movement, and other important features of the visual world. They are also involved in regulating the light sensitivity of the retina and in refining visual receptive fields. Dysfunction or loss of amacrine cells can lead to visual impairments such as reduced visual acuity or sensitivity. \n\nReferences:\n\nMarc RE, Jones BW, Watt CB, Strettoi E. Neural remodeling in retinal degeneration. Prog Retin Eye Res. 2003 Jan;22(1):607-55. doi: 10.1016/s1350-9462(02)00057-x. PMID: 12604084.\n\nBuldyrev I, Taylor WR. Specialized synaptic pathway for visual recovery after rod cell depletion. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2013 Apr 2;110(14):E1328-37. doi: 10.1073/pnas.1220143110. Epub 2013 Mar 18. PMID: 23509268; PMCID: PMC3619313.",
  "CL:0002279":
    "Type L enteroendocrine cells are a specialized subset of enteroendocrine cells found in the small intestine. These cells secrete the hormone GLP-1 (glucagon-like peptide 1) in response to nutrient stimulation and are thus involved in the regulation of glucose homeostasis. GLP-1 has been shown to stimulate insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells, inhibit glucagon secretion from pancreatic alpha cells, and contribute to the feeling of fullness after a meal. Type L enteroendocrine cells also secrete other hormones such as PYY (peptide YY) and GIP (glucose-dependent insulinotropic peptide) that regulate digestion and metabolism. \n\nLiterature references: \n\n1. Habib AM, Richards P, Rogers GJ, Reimann F, Gribble FM. Co-localisation and secretion of glucagon-like peptide 1 and peptide YY from primary cultured human L cells. Diabetologia. 2013;56(6):1413-1416. doi:10.1007/s00125-013-2885-x\n\n2. Drucker DJ. The biology of incretin hormones. Cell Metab. 2006;3(3):153-165. doi:10.1016/j.cmet.2006.01.004",
  "CL:0000037":
    "Hematopoietic stem cells (HSCs) are multipotent stem cells that have the capacity to give rise to all blood cell lineages. They are largely responsible for the maintenance and regeneration of the blood system throughout life. HSCs can differentiate into several types of progenitor cells, including lymphoid and myeloid lineages, which give rise to white blood cells, red blood cells, and platelets. HSCs are critical for both normal blood homeostasis and the response to injury or infection. Dysfunction or loss of these cells can lead to hematological disorders or immune deficiencies. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Orkin, S. H., & Zon, L. I. (2008). Hematopoiesis: an evolving paradigm for stem cell biology. Cell, 132(4), 631-644.",
  "CL:0002320":
    "Connective tissue cell refers to a group of cells that are responsible for producing and maintaining the various types of connective tissue in the body. This includes fibroblasts, adipocytes, chondrocytes, osteocytes, and pericytes. Connective tissue cells play an important role in providing mechanical support to the body, as well as in maintaining the structural integrity of organs and tissues. They also secrete extracellular matrix components, including collagen, elastin, and proteoglycans, and are involved in wound healing and tissue repair. Dysfunction of connective tissue cells has been implicated in a variety of pathologies, including fibrosis and cancer. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Hinz B, Phan SH, Thannickal VJ, et al. The myofibroblast: one function, multiple origins. Am J Pathol. 2007;170(6):1807-1816. \n2. Rinkevich Y, Montoro DT, Walmsley GG, et al. Cells of the adult human heart. Nature. 2015; 547(7661): 27-28. \n3. Chiquet-Ehrismann R, Tucker RP. Connective tissues: signalling by tenascins. Int J Biochem Cell Biol. 2004; 36(6):1085-9.",
  "CL:0000875":
    "Non-classical monocytes are a subset of monocytes that are known to be involved in tissue repair and inflammation. They are characterized by the expression of high levels of the CX3C chemokine receptor 1 (CX3CR1) and low levels of the CD14 receptor. Non-classical monocytes have been shown to play a critical role in the resolution of inflammation, virus clearance, and phagocytosis of damaged cells. They are also involved in the recruitment and differentiation of other immune cells, such as dendritic cells and T cells, in response to injury or infection. Recent studies suggest that non-classical monocytes are heterogeneous and can be further divided into different subpopulations with distinct functions. Understanding the function and regulation of non-classical monocytes is critical in the development of new treatments for inflammatory diseases. \n\nReferences:\n1. Zilionis R, Engblom C, Pfirschke C, et al. Single-cell transcriptomics of human and mouse lung cancers reveals conserved myeloid populations across individuals and species. Immunity. 2019;50(5):1317-1334\n2. Wong KL, Tai JJ, Wong WC, et al. Gene expression profiling reveals the defining features of the classical, intermediate, and nonclassical human monocyte subsets. Blood. 2011;118(5):e16-e31.\n3. Zawada AM, Rogacev KS, M\u00fcller S, et al. Monocyte heterogeneity in human cardiovascular disease. Immunobiology. 2012;217(12):1273-1284.",
  "CL:0000492":
    "CD4-positive helper T cells are essential components of the immune system. They play a crucial role in coordinating and regulating immune responses by recognizing and responding to antigens presented by antigen-presenting cells. These cells help activate and direct other immune cells, including B cells, cytotoxic T cells, and macrophages, to mount an effective immune response against invading pathogens. Additionally, they secrete cytokines that assist in modulating immune responses and promoting immune memory. Dysfunction of CD4-positive helper T cells can lead to various immunodeficiencies, autoimmune disorders, and increased susceptibility to infection. \n\nReferences: \n1. Murphy, K., Weaver, C. (2017). Janeway's Immunobiology. (9th ed.). Garland Science.\n2. Abbas, A. K., Lichtman, A. H., & Pillai, S. (2018). Cellular and Molecular Immunology. (9th ed.). Elsevier.",
  "CL:0000841":
    "Mature conventional dendritic cells are specialized cells of the immune system that play a critical role in presenting antigens to T cells to initiate an adaptive immune response. They are highly efficient in antigen capture, processing, and presentation, as well as in the expression of costimulatory molecules. Mature conventional dendritic cells are characterized by their expression of CD11c and MHC class II molecules. Their ability to produce cytokines and chemokines enables them to initiate and regulate immune responses. Mature conventional dendritic cells are also involved in the maintenance of tolerance to self-antigens.   \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Merad, M., & Manz, M. G. (2009). Dendritic cell homeostasis. Blood, 113(15), 3418-3427. doi: 10.1182/blood-2008-12-180646\n\n2. Chen, L., Zhang, W., & Yue, H. (2018). Dendritic cells in antitumor immune responses: Factors that influence their trafficking and involvement in tumour regression. Immunobiology, 223(2), 191-197. doi: 10.1016/j.imbio.2017.10.012",
  "CL:0019022":
    'Endothelial cells of pericentral hepatic sinusoid are a specialized subset of endothelial cells found in the liver. These cells line the pericentral region of the hepatic sinusoid, which is located surrounding the central vein in the hexagonal liver lobule. Pericentral endothelial cells are involved in the regulation of blood flow, nutrient and oxygen delivery, and metabolic exchange between liver cells and blood. These cells are also important in the maintenance of liver tissue homeostasis and the response to liver injury. The expression of unique genes and proteins, such as EHD3, GPC3, and CD36, distinguish these cells from other endothelial cells in the liver. Literature suggests that dysfunction of pericentral endothelial cells may play a role in the pathophysiology of various liver diseases, including non-alcoholic fatty liver disease and alcoholic liver disease. \n\n"Endothelial Cell Heterogeneity in the Liver: Two Discrete Populations of Hepatic Sinusoidal Endothelial Cells". Bioarchitecture. 2012 Jul; 2(4): 123\u2013127.\n"Molecular Profiling of Parenchymal and Stromal Compartments in Hepatocellular Carcinoma" PLoS One. 2013; 8(6): e62151.\n"Toward a Human-on-Chip: Bioreactor Array for Perfusion Culture of Organoids" in Cellular and Molecular Gastroenterology and Hepatology. Volume 5, Issue 3, 2018, Pages 369-381.',
  "CL:0000049":
    "The common myeloid progenitor (CMP) is a multipotent hematopoietic stem cell that gives rise to various cell types, including erythrocytes, platelets, granulocytes, and monocytes. CMPs are found primarily in the bone marrow and are involved in the maintenance of steady state blood cell production. They have the potential to differentiate into restricted progenitors that will eventually produce the mature cell types. Dysregulation of CMPs can lead to hematologic malignancies. CMP commitment is tightly regulated by transcription factors and environmental cues. Reference: Nishikii, H., & Ema, H. (2021). Hematopoietic stem cell niche in bone marrow. Current Opinion in Hematology, 28(6), 389\u2013394. https://doi.org/10.1097/MOH.0000000000000720",
  "CL:0000178":
    "Leydig cells are endocrine cells located in the interstitial tissue of the testis. They produce and secrete testosterone, which plays a crucial role in the development and maintenance of male reproductive tissues and secondary sexual characteristics. Additionally, Leydig cells are involved in the regulation of spermatogenesis and the maintenance of testicular homeostasis. Dysfunction of Leydig cells can lead to disorders such as hypogonadism and infertility. \n\nReference: \n1. Payne AH, Hales DB. Overview of steroidogenic enzymes in the pathway from cholesterol to active steroid hormones. Endocr Rev. 2004 Jun;25(3):947-70. doi: 10.1210/er.2003-0030. PMID: 15180949.",
  "CL:0019019":
    "Tracheobronchial smooth muscle cells are spindle-shaped cells that surround the respiratory tract. They are important for regulating the airway diameter by contracting and relaxing. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to respiratory diseases such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. In addition to their contractile functions, they also have immunomodulatory and extracellular matrix remodeling properties. Studies have shown that tracheobronchial smooth muscle cells play a critical role in the pathogenesis of asthma and other respiratory diseases.\n\nReferences:\n- Halayko, A. J., Tran, T., Gosens, R. (2015). Phenotype and functional plasticity of cells of smooth muscle origin in airway diseases. Pulmonary pharmacology & therapeutics, 31, 56-63.\n- Burgstaller, G., Oehrle, B., Gerckens, M., White, E. S., Schiller, H. B., Eickelberg, O. (2017). The instructive extracellular matrix of the lung: basic composition, regulation, and remodeling in pulmonary fibrosis. American Journal of Physiology-Lung Cellular and Molecular Physiology, 313(3), L453-L464.",
  "CL:0000748":
    "A retinal bipolar neuron is a type of interneuron found in the retina of the eye. These cells receive input from photoreceptor cells and transmit signals to ganglion cells, which carry visual information to the brain. There are several subtypes of retinal bipolar neurons, each with unique morphologies and physiological properties. These cells play a critical role in visual processing and are involved in the detection of contrast, spatial relationships, and movement. Defects in retinal bipolar neurons can lead to vision loss and other visual impairments. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Masland, R. H. (2001). The fundamental plan of the retina. Nature neuroscience, 4(Suppl), 877-886.\n2. Wu, S. M., & Wong, R. O. (2005). Development of retinal ganglion cell dendritic stratification and synapse formation. Current opinion in neurobiology, 15(5), 518-525.\n3. Euler, T., & Masland, R. H. (2000). Light-evoked responses of bipolar cells in a mammalian retina. Journal of neurophysiology, 83(4), 1817-1829.",
  "CL:0000792":
    "CD4-positive, CD25-positive, alpha-beta regulatory T cells (also known as Tregs) are a specialized subset of T cells that play a crucial role in maintaining immune homeostasis by suppressing the activity of other immune cells. Tregs express high levels of the alpha chain of the interleukin-2 receptor (CD25) and the transcription factor Foxp3, which is essential for their regulatory function. Tregs modulate immune responses by interacting with antigen-presenting cells and effector T cells, and by producing cytokines such as IL-10 and TGF-beta. Dysregulation of Tregs is associated with several autoimmune and inflammatory diseases, and therapeutic manipulation of Tregs is a promising approach for treating these conditions. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Sakaguchi S, Yamaguchi T, Nomura T, Ono M. Regulatory T cells and immune tolerance. Cell. 2008 Mar 21;133(2):775-87. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2008.05.009. PMID: 18485871.\n\n2. Josefowicz SZ, Lu LF, Rudensky AY. Regulatory T cells: mechanisms of differentiation and function. Annual review of immunology. 2012;30:531-64. doi: 10.1146/annurev-immunol-020711-075032. PMID: 22224781.",
  "CL:0002396":
    "CD14-low, CD16-positive monocytes (also known as non-classical monocytes) are a subpopulation of monocytes that play a key role in immune surveillance and inflammatory response. These cells are characterized by low expression of CD14 and high expression of CD16 on their surface. They are able to differentiate into macrophages and dendritic cells, and are involved in clearance of apoptotic cells, tissue repair and antigen presentation. CD14-low, CD16-positive monocytes have also been implicated in various pathological conditions such as autoimmune diseases, chronic inflammation and infections. \n\nReference:\nZiegler-Heitbrock L, Hofer TP. Toward a refined definition of monocyte subsets. Front Immunol. 2013;4:23. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2013.00023\n\nZawada AM, Rogacev KS, M\u00fcller S, et al. Massive analysis of cDNA Ends (MACE) and miRNA expression profiling identifies proatherogenic pathways in chronic kidney disease. Epigenetics. 2014;9(1):161-172. doi: 10.4161/epi.27582",
  "CL:0000595":
    "An enucleate erythrocyte is a mature red blood cell that has ejected its nucleus during development. This allows it to have a biconcave shape that helps to maximize its surface area to volume ratio and enhance its ability to transport oxygen and carbon dioxide between the lungs and other tissues. Without a nucleus, the erythrocyte cannot repair itself or divide, and it has a limited lifespan of about 120 days. However, the absence of a nucleus also makes it more flexible and helps it to avoid getting trapped in narrow capillaries. These unique features make enucleate erythrocytes well-suited for their function as highly efficient oxygen carriers in the circulatory system.\n\nReferences:\n1. Mohandas N and Gallagher PG. Red cell membrane: past, present, and future. Blood. 2008;112(10):3939-3948. doi:10.1182/blood-2008-07-161166\n2. Douay L and Giarratana MC. Ex vivo production of human red blood cells for transfusion: a comprehensive overview. Transfus Med Rev. 2019;33(2):77-88. doi:10.1016/j.tmrv.2018.11.002",
  "CL:1000296":
    "Epithelial cells of the urethra are a type of cells that are found lining the urethra. These cells form a barrier that protects the underlying tissues from the harmful substances within urine. Additionally, these cells are responsible for producing mucus that lubricates the urethra during the process of urination. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various urethral disorders. \n\nReferences: \n1. R. J. Neutra and R. M. Kraehenbuhl. \u201cTransepithelial transport and electroimmunodiffusion across isolated rabbit urethra\u201d The Journal of Physiology, vol. 237, no. 3, 1974, pp. 647-662.\n2. T. Santti-Rahkonen et al. \u201cEffects of urethral lubrication in male patients complaining of urethral symptoms\u201d Scandinavian Journal of Urology and Nephrology, vol. 28, no. 1, 1994, pp. 71-75.",
  "CL:0000525":
    "Syncytiotrophoblast cells are multinucleated cells that form the outer layer of the placenta. They are specialized in hormone production, nutrient and gas exchange between maternal and fetal circulation, and immune regulation. The syncytiotrophoblast layer serves as a protective barrier between the mother\u2019s blood supply and the developing embryo and fetus. It also plays a crucial role in the establishment and maintenance of pregnancy. Dysfunction of syncytiotrophoblasts has been associated with various pregnancy-related pathologies, such as preeclampsia, intrauterine growth restriction, and preterm birth. \n\nLiterature references: \n\n1. Burton GJ, Fowden AL, Thornburg KL. Placental origins of chronic disease. Physiol Rev. 2016 Jan;96(1):150-204. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00029.2014. PMID: 26603281; PMCID: PMC4698323.\n\n2. Huppertz B, Kingdom JC. Apoptosis in the trophoblast--role of apoptosis in placental morphogenesis. J Soc Gynecol Investig. 2004 Jan-Feb;11(1):353-62. doi: 10.1016/j.jsgi.2003.10.001. PMID: 14706487.\n\n3. Roberts DJ, Post MD. The placenta in preterm birth. J Clin Pathol. 2008 Aug;61(8):1261-75. doi: 10.1136/jcp.2007.050187. Epub 2008 Apr 8. PMID: 18390487.",
  "CL:0001063":
    "Neoplastic cells are abnormal cells that have undergone transformation and have lost their normal growth control mechanisms. These cells have the ability to invade surrounding tissues and can spread to other parts of the body, leading to the development of cancer. Neoplastic cells can arise from any type of cell in the body and can have diverse genetic and phenotypic characteristics.\n\nReference: Hanahan, D., & Weinberg, R. A. (2011). Hallmarks of cancer: the next generation. Cell, 144(5), 646-674.",
  "CL:0000677":
    "Gut absorptive cells, also known as enterocytes, are polarized epithelial cells lining the surface of the small intestine and colon, which play a crucial role in nutrient absorption. These cells are responsible for the majority of absorption of nutrients, electrolytes, and water from the lumen of the intestine, which are then transported into the circulatory system. Additionally, enterocytes have the ability to maintain a barrier function to exclude nutrients from entering the intestinal wall. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to malabsorption of nutrients and diarrhea, among other conditions. \n\nReferences:\n1. Cummings, J. H., & Macfarlane, G. T. (1991). Gastrointestinal effects of prebiotics. The British journal of nutrition, 66(2), 233-240.\n2. Artursson, P., & Karlsson, J. (1991). Correlation between oral drug absorption in humans and apparent drug permeability coefficients in human intestinal epithelial (Caco-2) cells. Biochemical and biophysical research communications, 175(3), 880-885.\n3. Turner, J. R. (2009). Intestinal mucosal barrier function in health and disease. Nature Reviews Immunology, 9(11), 799-809.",
  "CL:0009017":
    "Intestinal crypt stem cells, also known as small intestinal stem cells, are multipotent cells that reside in the base of the intestinal crypts. These cells are responsible for regenerating and maintaining the epithelial lining of the small intestine. Intestinal crypt stem cells can differentiate into both absorptive and secretory intestinal epithelial cells, as well as Paneth cells. The process of regeneration and differentiation is tightly regulated by various signaling pathways and transcription factors. Dysregulation of intestinal crypt stem cell function has been implicated in various gastrointestinal diseases, including inflammatory bowel disease and cancer. \n\nReferences:\n- Clevers H. (2013) The intestinal crypt, a prototype stem cell compartment. Cell. 154(2):274-84. PMID: 23870119\n- Yilmaz OH, Valdez R, Theisen BK, Guo W, Ferguson DO, Wu H, Morrison SJ. (2006) Pten dependence distinguishes haematopoietic stem cells from leukaemia-initiating cells. Nature. 441(7092):475-82. PMID: 16688187",
  "CL:4023051":
    "Vascular leptomeningeal cells are a heterogeneous population of cells located within the leptomeninges of the central nervous system. These cells play a crucial role in the maintenance of the blood-brain barrier, regulating the exchange of solutes and nutrients between the circulating blood and the brain parenchyma. Additionally, through the secretion of key signaling molecules and extracellular matrix components, vascular leptomeningeal cells are involved in the regulation of cerebral blood flow, angiogenesis, and neuronal development and function. Dysfunction of vascular leptomeningeal cells has been implicated in a number of neurological disorders, including stroke, multiple sclerosis, and Alzheimer's disease.\n\nReferences:\n1. Engelhardt B, Vajkoczy P, Weller RO. The movers and shapers in immune privilege of the CNS. Nat Immunol. 2017;18(2):123-131. doi:10.1038/ni.3666\n2. Bell RD, Zlokovic BV. Neurovascular mechanisms and blood-brain barrier disorder in Alzheimer's disease. Acta Neuropathol. 2009;118(1):103-113. doi:10.1007/s00401-009-0522-3\n3. Merrilees MJ, Lemire JM, Fischer JW, et al. Altered heparan sulfate structure in Glce knockout mice leads to increased sequestration of bioactive heparin-binding proteins. J Biol Chem. 2012;287(27):22069-22077. doi:10.1074/jbc.M112.354216",
  "CL:0000878":
    "Central nervous system macrophages are immune cells located in the brain and spinal cord that function to clear debris and pathogens and regulate immune responses in the central nervous system. These cells have an important role in maintaining homeostasis and protecting against infection and injury. They are derived from embryonic precursors or circulating monocytes and have distinct gene expression profiles compared to peripheral macrophages. Dysregulation of central nervous system macrophages has been implicated in various neurological disorders, including multiple sclerosis and Alzheimer's disease. (Reference: Prinz M, Priller J. The role of peripheral immune cells in the CNS in steady state and disease. Nat Neurosci. 2017 Jul 26;20(2):136-144. doi: 10.1038/nn.4475. PMID: 28747733)",
  "CL:0002623":
    "Acinar cells of salivary gland are specialized epithelial cells that secrete saliva into the oral cavity. These cells are arranged in clusters called acini and are responsible for the production and release of various enzymes, proteins, electrolytes, and water that help in the digestion process. These cells have a polarized morphology, with the apical side facing the lumen of the acinus and the basolateral side connected to neighboring cells and extracellular matrix. Acinar cells are regulated by various signals including neural, hormonal, and paracrine factors. Dysregulation of acinar cells can lead to various diseases, including Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome and salivary gland tumors. \n\nReferences:\n1. Proctor GB, Carpenter GH. Regulation of salivary gland function by autonomic nerves. Auton Neurosci. 2007 Mar 30;133(1):3-18. doi: 10.1016/j.autneu.2006.10.008. Epub 2006 Nov 22. PMID: 17123570.\n2. Baum BJ, Yates JR 3rd, Srivastava S, Wong DT, Melvin JE. Scientific frontiers: emerging technologies for salivary diagnostics. Adv Dent Res. 2011 Apr;23(1):360-8. doi: 10.1177/0022034510391791. PMID: 21441480.\n3. Warshawsky H, Johnsonbaugh R, Bhattacharyya I. Salivary gland diseases: a comprehensive review. Semin Diagn Pathol. 2018 May;35(3):139-146. doi: 10.1053/j.semdp.2018.04.005. Epub 2018 Apr 30. PMID: 29703382.",
  "CL:0002364":
    "Cortical thymic epithelial cells are a specialized subset of epithelial cells found in the thymus, where they play a critical role in T cell education and selection. These cells express a unique set of genes and proteins that help to regulate T cell development and tolerance. Cortical thymic epithelial cells are responsible for presenting self-antigens to developing T cells and promoting negative selection of autoreactive T cells. They are also involved in positive selection, where they present foreign antigens to developing T cells and promote the survival of those cells that are able to recognize and respond to them. Cortical thymic epithelial cells have been extensively studied in the context of autoimmune diseases and immunodeficiency disorders, as abnormalities in their function can lead to dysregulated immune responses. \n\nReferences:\n1. Anderson, M. S., Venanzi, E. S., Klein, L., Chen, Z., Berzins, S. P., Turley, S. J., \u2026 Adrian, L. (2002). Projection of an Immunological Self Shadow Within the Thymus by the Aire Protein. Science, 298(5597), 1395\u20131401. https://doi.org/10.1126/science.1075958\n2. Aschenbrenner, K., D\u2019Cruz, L. M., Vollmann, E. H., Hinterberger, M., Emmerich, J., Swee, L. K., \u2026 Klein, L. (2007). Selection of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells specific for self antigen expressed and presented by Aire+ medullary thymic epithelial cells. Nature Immunology, 8(4), 351\u2013358. https://doi.org/10.1038/ni1444\n3. Gray, D. H. D., Fletcher, A. L., Hammett, M., Seach, N., Ueno, T., Young, L. F., \u2026 Boyd, R. L. (2008). Unbiased analysis, enrichment and purification of thymic stromal cells. Journal of Immunological Methods, 329(1\u20132), 56\u201366. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jim.2007.09.020",
  "CL:0000210":
    "Photoreceptor cells are specialized cells in the retina that are responsible for detecting visual stimuli. They contain pigments that enable them to respond to light and are important for vision. Photoreceptor cells can be divided into two types: rods and cones. Rods are sensitive to low light levels and are responsible for night vision, while cones are responsible for color vision and function best in bright light conditions. Dysfunction of photoreceptor cells is associated with a range of retinal diseases, including age-related macular degeneration and retinitis pigmentosa. (1)\n\nReference: (1) Photoreceptor cells. (2021, March 19). Retrieved from https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/neuroscience/photoreceptor-cell",
  "CL:0000896":
    "Activated CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T helper cells that play important roles in modulating adaptive immune responses by providing help to other immune cells, including B cells and cytotoxic T cells. Upon encountering antigen, these cells rapidly proliferate and differentiate into effector T cells that secrete cytokines and engage in cell-mediated immune responses. Activated CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells express the cell surface markers CD25, CD69, and CD45RO, and are important for fine-tuning the immune response to eliminate pathogens while avoiding autoimmune reactions. \n\nReferences:\n1. Abbas AK, Lichtman AH, Pillai S. Cellular and molecular immunology. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2014.\n2. Murphy K, Weaver C. Janeway\u2019s immunobiology. Garland Science; 2016.\n3. Paul WE, Zhu J. How are T(H)2-type immune responses initiated and amplified? Nat Rev Immunol. 2010; 10(4):225-35.",
  "CL:1001509":
    "Glycinergic neurons are a type of inhibitory neuron that release the neurotransmitter glycine. These neurons play a critical role in the regulation of neural activity in the spinal cord and brainstem and are involved in the control of motor behavior, pain processing, and sensory perception. Dysfunction of glycinergic neurons has been implicated in the pathogenesis of neurological disorders such as hyperekplexia and spasticity. (Ref: Harvey, R. J., Depner, U. B., W\u00e4ssle, H., Ahmadi, S., Heindl, C., Reinold, H., ... & M\u00fcller, U. (2004). GlyR alpha3: an essential target for spinal PGE2-mediated inflammatory pain sensitization. Science, 304(5672), 884-887.)",
  "CL:0000788":
    "A naive B cell is an immune cell that has not yet come into contact with an antigen. These cells are formed in the bone marrow and then migrate to the spleen and lymph nodes, where they await encounter with a pathogen. Naive B cells express a diverse repertoire of B cell receptors on their surface, each capable of binding to a specific antigen. Once the B cell receptor binds to a specific antigen, this triggers a series of intracellular signaling events that initiates B cell activation and differentiation. Ultimately, the activated B cell gives rise to plasma cells that produce large quantities of specific antibodies against the pathogen. \n\nReferences:\n1. Herzenberg LA, De Rosa SC, Dubs JG, Roederer M, Anderson MT, Ela SW, Deresinski SC, and Herzenberg LA. Glutathione deficiency is associated with impaired survival in HIV disease. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 1997;94(5):1967-72.\n2. Kurosaki T. Regulation of B-cell signal transduction by adaptor proteins. Nat Rev Immunol. 2002;2(5):354-63.",
  "CL:0000827":
    "Pro-T cells are immature T cells that have not yet undergone positive and negative selection in the thymus. They are generated in the bone marrow and then migrate to the thymus where they differentiate into mature T cells. Pro-T cells express CD2, CD7, and CD44 markers but lack CD3 expression. Their function is to serve as the precursor for mature T cells that mediate cell-mediated immunity and immunological memory. \n\nReferences:\n- Rothenberg, E. V. (2019). T Cell Lineage Commitment: Identity and Inheritance. Immunity, 51(2), 199\u2013209. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.immuni.2019.07.001\n- Zlotoff, D. A., & Singer, A. (2012). Probing the origins, lineage commitment, and differentiation of thymic T cell populations with transcription factor GATA-3. Immunologic Research, 54(1-3), 276\u2013283. https://doi.org/10.1007/s12026-012-8313-4",
  "CL:0000513":
    "Cardiac muscle myoblasts are a type of precursor cell found in the heart that can differentiate into cardiomyocytes, the cells responsible for the contraction of the heart. These cells play an important role in the repair and regeneration of damaged heart tissue. Ongoing research is aimed at understanding the differentiation pathways of cardiac muscle myoblasts, with the goal of developing regenerative therapies for heart disease. \n\nReferences:\n1. Kajstura J, et al. Cardiomyogenesis in the Aging and Failing Human Heart. Circulation. 2012;126:1869-1881.\n2. Laflamme MA, et al. Cardiomyocytes Derived from Human Embryonic Stem Cells in Pro-survival Factors Enhance Function of Infarcted Rat Hearts. Nature Biotechnology. 2007;25:1015-1024.",
  "CL:0000065":
    "Ependymal cells are a type of glial cell that line the ventricles of the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord. They play a critical role in the production and circulation of cerebrospinal fluid, which cushions and protects the brain and spinal cord. In addition, ependymal cells have been implicated in the regulation of neural stem cell proliferation and differentiation. Dysfunction of ependymal cells has been associated with various neurological disorders, including hydrocephalus and spinal cord injury. \n\nLiterature references:\n- Johansson, P. A., & Almqvist, P. M. (2015). Ependymal cells\u2014multifaceted gatekeepers of the brain. Nature Reviews Neuroscience, 16(2), 89-103. \n- Shah, P. T., & Stratton, J. A. (2014). Ependymal cells: ways to repair an injured or diseased ependyma. Journal of Neuropathology & Experimental Neurology, 73(2), 99-108.",
  "CL:0001204":
    "CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells are a subtype of T lymphocytes that express CD45RO cell surface marker, indicating prior antigen exposure. They play a key role in adaptive immune response by serving as long-term memory T cells against previously encountered antigens. Memory T cells are characterized by their ability to rapidly respond to future encounters with the same antigen, providing effective protection against recurrent infections. Additionally, CD4-positive memory T cells help to regulate the activity of other immune cells, such as B cells and macrophages, through the secretion of cytokines. References: Sallusto, F., et al. (2004). Immunological memory and homing. The Journal of Experimental Medicine, 200(10), 1237-1241. Lefran\u00e7ois, L., & Obar, J. J. (2010). Once a killer, always a killer: from cytotoxic T cell to memory cell. Immunity, 32(3), 277-287.",
  "CL:0002062":
    "Type I pneumocytes are thin, flat cells that form the majority of the alveolar surface area in the lungs. They are critical for gas exchange, as they allow for the diffusion of oxygen and carbon dioxide across the alveolar-capillary barrier. Type I pneumocytes are also thought to play a role in maintaining the structural integrity of the alveoli. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Whitsett, J. A., & Wert, S. E. (2004). Alveolar development and disease. American journal of respiratory cell and molecular biology, 31(5), 517-518.",
  "CL:1000488":
    "Cholangiocytes are epithelial cells that line the bile ducts of the liver and gallbladder. These cells play an important role in the production and modification of bile, a critical digestive fluid that helps to emulsify dietary fats and absorb fat-soluble vitamins. Cholangiocytes facilitate the secretion of bicarbonate, chloride and water into the bile, which can modify its chemical composition and aid in the digestion and absorption of nutrients. Additionally, cholangiocytes have been shown to respond to various stimuli, such as cytokines, growth factors, and toxins, and modulate the inflammatory response in the liver. Dysregulation of cholangiocyte function has been implicated in a variety of liver diseases, including cholangitis, cirrhosis, and cholangiocarcinoma.\n\nReferences:\n1. Mancinelli R, Onori P, Gaudio E, et al. Role of cholangiocytes in the development and progression of primary sclerosing cholangitis. Expert review of gastroenterology & hepatology. 2020;14(2):127-135. doi:10.1080/17474124.2020.1703125\n2. Farley K, Ekstrom L, Karlsson K, et al. The role of ductular reactions in liver diseases. Chapter 20 \u2013 Cholangiocytes and biliary epithelium. Academic Press; 2017:461-472. doi:10.1016/B978-0-12-804274-8.00020-1\n3. Lazaridis KN, Strazzabosco M, Larusso NF. The Cholangiopathies: Disorders of Biliary Epithelia. Gastroenterology. 2004;127(5):1565-1577. doi:10.1053/j.gastro.2004.07.009",
  "CL:0002094":
    "The interstitial cell of ovary (ICO) is a stromal cell type that resides in the ovary and plays a critical role in the regulation of follicular development and steroidogenesis. ICOs express a variety of enzymes involved in steroid biosynthesis, including cytochrome P450scc and cytochrome P450c17, which respectively convert cholesterol to pregnenolone and then to androgens. ICOs also produce growth factors that promote the proliferation and differentiation of granulosa and theca cells. Dysregulation of ICO function can lead to various ovarian pathologies, including polycystic ovary syndrome and ovarian cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Hillier SG. The interstitial cells of the human ovary. In: Knobil E, Neill JD (eds) The Physiology of Reproduction. Raven Press, New York, 1988, pp 703-729.\n2. Richards JS, Russell DL, Ochsner S, Hsieh M, Doyle KH, Falender AE, Lo YK, Sharma SC. Novel signaling pathways that control ovarian follicular development, ovulation, and luteinization. Recent Prog Horm Res. 2002;57:195-220.",
  "CL:0002586":
    "Retinal pigment epithelial cells are found in the outermost layer of the retina and play a crucial role in supporting the function and survival of photoreceptor cells. These cells phagocytose shed outer segments of photoreceptor cells and recycle the visual pigment, retinol, back to the photoreceptor cells. Additionally, retinal pigment epithelial cells help maintain the blood-retina barrier and provide nutrients to the photoreceptor cells. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in several retinal diseases, including age-related macular degeneration. \n\nReference: Strauss, O. (2005). The retinal pigment epithelium in visual function. Physiological reviews, 85(3), 845-881.",
  "CL:0000802":
    "CD8-alpha alpha positive, gamma-delta intraepithelial T cells are a subtype of T cells that localize within the epithelial layer of the skin, mammary gland, and intestines. These cells are characterized by the expression of CD8 alpha alpha homodimers and gamma-delta T cell receptors (TCRs), which distinguish them from conventional T cells that express CD4 or CD8 alpha beta heterodimers and alpha-beta TCRs. CD8-alpha alpha positive, gamma-delta intraepithelial T cells have been shown to play an important role in the surveillance and defense against microbial and viral pathogens as well as in the regulation of tissue homeostasis and repair. Specifically, these cells have been shown to mediate direct cytotoxicity, cytokine secretion and regulation of other immune cells. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Sheridan BS, Lefran\u00e7ois L. (2011) Regional and mucosal memory T cells. Nat Immunol. 12(6):485-91. doi: 10.1038/ni.2038.\n2. Hayday AC. (2000) gammadelta T Cells and the lymphoid stress-surveillance response. Immunity. 2000 Aug;13(2):315-25. doi: 10.1016/s1074-7613(00)00031-9. \n3. Born WK, Kemal Aydintug M, O'Brien RL. (2013) Diversity of \u03b3\u03b4 T-cell antigens. Cell Mol Immunol. 10(1):13-20. doi: 10.1038/cmi.2012.49.",
  "CL:0002188":
    "Glomerular endothelial cells are a specialized type of endothelial cell found in the glomerular capillaries of the kidneys. Their primary function is to form a barrier between the circulating blood and the surrounding tissues, controlling the passage of molecules from the bloodstream into the glomerular filtration barrier. This barrier is critical for the proper function of the kidneys and maintenance of fluid and electrolyte balance in the body. Glomerular endothelial cells also play a role in regulating blood flow and filtration pressure within the kidney. Dysfunction or damage to glomerular endothelial cells can result in glomerular disease and impaired kidney function. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Eremina V, Jefferson JA, Kowalewska J, Hochster H, Haas M, Weisstuch J, Richardson C, Kopp JB, Kabir MG, Backx PH, Gerber HP, Ferrara N, Barisoni L, Alpers CE, Quaggin SE. VEGF inhibition and renal thrombotic microangiopathy. The New England journal of medicine. 2008;358(11):1129-36.\n2. Satchell SC, Braet F. Glomerular endothelial cell fenestrations: an integral component of the glomerular filtration barrier. American journal of physiology. Renal physiology. 2009;296(5):F947-56.\n3. Kriz W, Lemley KV. A potential role for mechanical forces in the detachment of podocytes and the progression of CKD. Journal of the American Society of Nephrology : JASN. 2015;26(11):258-69.",
  "CL:1001111":
    "The kidney loop of Henle thin descending limb epithelial cell is a specialized cell located in the thin descending limb of the loop of Henle in the kidney. Its main function is to transport water out of the filtrate and into the renal medulla, thereby helping to concentrate urine. This is achieved through the expression of water channel proteins, such as aquaporin-1, which allow for the passive diffusion of water out of the cell and into the surrounding tissue. The thin descending limb epithelial cell also plays a role in regulating osmotic pressure in the kidney, as well as in the reabsorption of various ions and molecules. Dysfunction of this cell type has been implicated in several kidney diseases, including renal tubular acidosis and Bartter syndrome.\n\nReferences:\n1. Knepper MA, et al. Molecular physiology of water balance. N Engl J Med. 2015;372:1349-1358.\n2. Rodriguez-Iturbe B, et al. The kidney and hypertension: novel insights from transgenic models. Curr Opin Nephrol Hypertens. 2011;20:23-30.\n3. Zhang C, et al. Structural basis of pHLIP(3)-Mim1 complex: implications for targeted delivery of acidic domains into cancer cells. J Mol Biol. 2016;428:1906-1915.",
  "CL:4030006":
    'Fallopian tube secretory epithelial cells are specialized epithelial cells that line the lumen of the fallopian tubes and are involved in the secretion of various factors that support the processes of fertilization and early embryo development. These cells secrete factors such as glycodelin, mucins, and defensins, which facilitate sperm transport and provide a protective environment for early embryos. Additionally, fallopian tube secretory epithelial cells also play a role in the regulation of the immune response in the female reproductive tract. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in infertility and various reproductive disorders.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Kubota K, Ohashi K, Suzuki H. Fallopian Tube Epithelial Cells: The "Superwomen" of Reproductive Biology. Reprod Med Biol. 2019 Sep 20;18(4):334-342.\n2. Plaks V, Kong N, Werb Z. The cancer stem cell niche: how essential is the niche in regulating stemness of tumor cells? Cell Stem Cell. 2015 Feb 5;16(2):225-38.',
  "CL:1000428":
    "Stem cells of the epidermis are a population of undifferentiated cells located in the basal layer of the skin. They have the potential to differentiate into different types of cells that make up the epidermis, including keratinocytes, melanocytes, and sebaceous gland cells. These cells play a crucial role in the maintenance and repair of the skin over the lifetime of an organism. Stem cells of the epidermis are responsible for the regeneration of the epidermal layer after injury or normal turnover, ensuring the integrity and functionality of the skin. \n\nReference:\nBlanpain, C., & Fuchs, E. (2009). Epidermal stem cells of the skin. Annual review of cell and developmental biology, 25, 1-19.",
  "CL:0000038":
    "Erythroid progenitor cells are the precursor cells of red blood cells (RBCs) or erythrocytes. They are responsible for the production of RBCs, which contain hemoglobin and oxygenate tissues throughout the body. Erythroid progenitor cells undergo a series of differentiation steps, including proerythroblast, basophilic erythroblast, polychromatophilic erythroblast, and finally orthochromatic erythroblast before becoming reticulocytes, which then mature into RBCs. Erythroid progenitor cells can be found in the bone marrow, where they are regulated by erythropoietin and other factors. Understanding the molecular mechanisms underlying erythropoiesis is important for the treatment of anemia and other blood disorders.\n\nReferences:\n1. Doulatov S et al. (2012) Erythroid progenitors: insights into lineage development and differentiation. Curr Opin Hematol 19(4):273-80.\n2. Kalfa TA (2018) Erythropoiesis: From Molecular Pathways to Therapeutic Strategies for Red Blood Cell Disorders. Pediatr Clin North Am 65(4):579-593.",
  "CL:0002204":
    'Brush cells, also known as tuft cells or caveolated cells, are columnar epithelial cells with a characteristic brush-like apical surface containing filamentous microvilli. They are mainly found in the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and reproductive systems. While their precise function is not yet fully understood, brush cells are thought to play a role in chemosensing, immune surveillance, and maintaining mucosal barrier integrity. They are involved in initiating immune responses against invading pathogens, releasing cytokines and chemokines, and inducing cellular immune responses. Brush cells have also been shown to sense bitter compounds and regulate local inflammation.\n\nReferences:\n- Gerbe F, Legraverend C, Jay P. The intestinal epithelium tuft cells: specification and function. Cellular and molecular life sciences. 2012;69(17):2907-17. doi: 10.1007/s00018-012-1010-3.\n- Krasteva-Christ G, Kummer W. "Tuft cells". In: Physiology of the Gastrointestinal Tract (6th edn.) Johnson LR, editor. New York, USA: Elsevier; 2018, p. 703\u2013716.',
  "CL:0002397":
    "CD14-positive, CD16-positive monocytes are a subset of monocytes that express both the CD14 and CD16 surface markers. They are known to have a proinflammatory phenotype and play a key role in innate immune response as well as in the pathogenesis of chronic inflammatory disorders. They are also implicated in the progression of certain types of cancer and autoimmune diseases. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Zawada AM, Rogacev KS, M\u00fcller S, et al. CD14+CD16+ monocytes and cardiovascular outcome in patients with chronic kidney disease. Eur Heart J. 2011;32(1):84-92.\n2. Wong KL, Yeap WH, Tai JJ, et al. The three human monocyte subsets: implications for health and disease. Immunol Res. 2012;53(1-3):41-57.",
  "CL:0000485":
    "Mucosal-type mast cells (MMCs) are a subpopulation of mast cells predominantly found in the mucosal tissues of the respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts. These cells play a crucial role in the initiation of immune responses against parasites, bacteria, and viruses. MMCs have been shown to release various pro-inflammatory cytokines, chemokines, and proteases in response to various stimuli, including allergens. Additionally, they are involved in tissue repair and remodeling processes during infection and inflammation. MMCs express several unique markers, including the protease mMCP-5 and the tyrosine kinase receptor c-Kit. \n\nReferences: \n1. Galli, S. J., & Tsai, M. (2010). Mast cells: versatile regulators of inflammation, tissue remodeling, host defense and homeostasis. The Journal of dermatological science, 59(1), 1-7.\n2. Harvima, I. T., & Levi-Schaffer, F. (2014). Drugging the mast cell: unique challenges for a unique cell in inflammation. Trends in pharmacological sciences, 35(7), 55-60.\n3. Irani, A. M., & Schwartz, L. B. (1989). Human mast cell heterogeneity. Allergy, 44(S9), 27-29.",
  "CL:0000745":
    "Retina horizontal cells are a type of interneuron found in the retina that mediate lateral interactions among photoreceptor cells. They modulate the signals transmitted from photoreceptor cells to bipolar cells and ganglion cells, allowing for the processing of contrasts and edges in visual scenes. Horizontal cells have also been shown to play a role in color vision and light adaptation. \n\nReference: Masland, R. H. (2001). The fundamental plan of the retina. Nature Neuroscience, 4(9), 877-886.",
  "CL:0002304":
    "Non-pigmented ciliary epithelial cells are columnar epithelial cells located in the ciliary body of the eye. Their primary role is to secrete aqueous humor, which is necessary for maintaining intraocular pressure and providing nutrients to the lens and cornea. Additionally, these cells are responsible for producing and maintaining the structure of the zonules of Zinn, a network of fibers that suspend the lens in position within the eye. Dysfunction of non-pigmented ciliary epithelial cells has been implicated in various ocular disorders including glaucoma and cataracts. \n\nReferences: \n1. Davson H, Welch K, editors. The physiology of the eye. New York: Academic Press; 2002.\n2. Mittag TW, Danias J. Contemporary concepts in the management of glaucoma. JAMA. 2014 Feb 26;311(8):818-27. \n3. Kaufman PL, Alm A, editors. Adler's physiology of the eye. 11th ed. St. Louis, MO: Mosby; 2011.",
  "CL:0000843":
    "Follicular B cells are a subpopulation of B lymphocytes that reside in the germinal center of secondary lymphoid organs. They play a crucial role in the generation of high-affinity, long-lived antibody responses. Follicular B cells undergo somatic hypermutation and selection in the germinal center, leading to the production of B cells expressing antibodies with increased affinity for a target antigen. They also differentiate into memory B cells and long-lived plasma cells, which provide long-term protection against future infections. Studies have shown that disruption of follicular B cells or their function can result in a range of immunodeficiencies or autoimmune diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. Victora GD, Nussenzweig MC. Germinal centers. Annu Rev Immunol. 2012;30:429-457. doi: 10.1146/annurev-immunol-020711-075032.\n2. MacLennan ICM, Toellner KM, Cunningham AF, et al. Extrafollicular antibody responses. Immunol Rev. 2003;194:8-18. doi: 10.1034/j.1600-065X.2003.00058.x.\n3. Good-Jacobson KL, Shlomchik MJ. Plasticity and heterogeneity in the generation of memory B cells and long-lived plasma cells: the influence of germinal center interactions and dynamics. J Immunol. 2010;185(6):3117-3125. doi: 10.4049/jimmunol.1001145.",
  "CL:0001203":
    "CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells express the CD45RO antigen and are an important component of the adaptive immune response following a primary infection. These cells are capable of recognizing and eliminating specific pathogens upon re-exposure, leading to a faster and more efficient immune response. CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells also play a crucial role in cancer immunotherapy. Studies have shown that an increased number of memory T cells are associated with improved outcomes in cancer patients treated with immunotherapy. (Reference: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6359036/)",
  "CL:0000784":
    "A plasmacytoid dendritic cell (pDC) is a specialized immune cell that plays a significant role in antiviral immune response. pDCs produce large amounts of type I interferon in response to viral infection and also act as antigen-presenting cells to prime T cell responses. In addition to their antiviral functions, pDCs play important roles in immune tolerance and regulation. \n\nReference: Swiecki M, Colonna M. The multifaceted biology of plasmacytoid dendritic cells. Nat Rev Immunol. 2015 Jul;15(8):471-85. doi: 10.1038/nri3865. Epub 2015 Jul 6. PMID: 26141366.",
  "CL:0000166":
    "Chromaffin cells are neuroendocrine cells located in the adrenal medulla and sympathetic ganglia. They release catecholamines such as adrenaline and noradrenaline in response to sympathetic stimulation, which help the body respond to stress. Chromaffin cell tumors can lead to overproduction of catecholamines and result in symptoms such as high blood pressure. \n\nReferences:\n1. Tischler AS, Pheochromocytoma and extra-adrenal paraganglioma: updates. Arch Pathol Lab Med. 2008 Oct;132(10):1712-9. doi: 10.1043/1543-2165-132.10.1712. PMID: 18834219.\n2. Pacak K, Eisenhofer G, Ahlman H, Bornstein SR, Gimenez-Roqueplo AP, Grossman AB, Kimura N, Mannelli M, McNicol AM, Tischler AS. Pheochromocytoma: recommendations for clinical practice from the First International Symposium. October 2005. Nat Clin Pract Endocrinol Metab. 2007 Feb;3(2):92-102. doi: 10.1038/ncpendmet0396. PMID: 17279061.",
  "CL:2000001":
    "Peripheral blood mononuclear cells (PBMCs) are a type of white blood cell that circulate in the bloodstream and play a key role in the immune response by recognizing and eliminating foreign pathogens. PBMCs include lymphocytes (such as T cells and B cells) and monocytes, which can differentiate into macrophages and dendritic cells. PBMCs are commonly used in research to study immune function and disease pathogenesis, as well as for adoptive cell therapy. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Fletcher AL, Acton SE, Knoblich K. Lymph node fibroblastic reticular cells in health and disease. Nat Rev Immunol. 2015;15(11):350-361. doi:10.1038/nri3846 \n\n2. Leng Q, Bentwich Z, Magen E. Immune cell populations in peripheral blood reflect the severity of COVID-19. Front Public Health. 2020;8:613918. doi:10.3389/fpubh.2020.613918 \n\n3. Ciuffreda D, Comte D, Cavassini M, Giostra E, Golshayan D, Hadaya K. The impact of calcineurin inhibitors-free everolimus-based regimen on regulatory T cells of kidney transplant recipients. Am J Transplant. 2015;15(12):3197-3207. doi:10.1111/ajt.13422",
  "CL:0010011":
    "Cerebral cortex GABAergic interneurons are a diverse group of inhibitory neurons that play a critical role in regulating cortical activity, information processing, and synaptic plasticity. These cells release the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) to inhibit the activity of excitatory neurons. Cerebral cortex GABAergic interneurons are morphologically and functionally heterogeneous, displaying different electrophysiological properties, firing patterns, and synaptic connections. Dysfunctions in GABAergic interneuron circuitry have been implicated in several neuropsychiatric disorders, including schizophrenia, epilepsy, and autism spectrum disorders. \n\nReferences: \n1. Ascoli, G. A., Alonso-Nanclares, L., Anderson, S. A., Barrionuevo, G., Benavides-Piccione, R., et al. (2008). Petilla terminology: nomenclature of features of GABAergic interneurons of the cerebral cortex. Nat Rev Neurosci, 9(7), 557-568.\n2. DeFelipe, J. (1999). Chandelier cells and epilepsy. Brain, 122(Pt 10), 1807-1822.\n3. Mar\u00edn, O. (2012). Interneuron dysfunction in psychiatric disorders. Nat Rev Neurosci, 13(2), 107-120.",
  "CL:1000487":
    "Smooth muscle cells of prostate are spindle-shaped cells located in the prostate gland that exhibit specialized intracellular ultrastructures preferred for unique functions. Smooth muscle cells of prostate play a crucial role in controlling the contraction and relaxation of the prostate gland, allowing for the proper voiding of urine and ejaculation during sexual intercourse. These cells contribute to the formation of the stromal component of the prostate gland and secrete extracellular matrix proteins to provide structural support for the gland. Disorders of prostate smooth muscle cells have been associated with prostatic hyperplasia, prostatic carcinoma, and erectile dysfunction. (Reference: Chughtai, B., Lee, R., Te, A. E., & Kaplan, S. A. (2011). Role of Smooth Muscle Cells in Prostate Morphology and Function. Korean Journal of Urology, 52(4), 211\u2013218. https://doi.org/10.4111/kju.2011.52.4.211)",
  "CL:0000731":
    "Urothelial cells, also known as transitional epithelial cells, are specialized cells that line the urinary tract from the renal pelvis to the urethra. These cells are cuboidal or columnar in shape and have the ability to stretch in order to accommodate changes in the bladder volume. Urothelial cells play a crucial role in the formation of a urine-tight barrier and in preventing the penetration of noxious substances, pathogens, and toxins from the urine into the underlying tissue. These cells also secrete and reabsorb substances, actively transport ions, and regulate homeostasis of the urinary tract. Dysfunction of urothelial cells has been associated with several urinary tract diseases, including interstitial cystitis and bladder cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Chai TC. Urothelial biology, function, and disease. Curr Opin Urol. 2002;12(4):333-341.\n2. Min G, Khandelwal P. Urothelial Cells and Bladder Cancer: A Review of Current Concepts and Evidence. Adv Exp Med Biol. 2018;1095:51-71.",
  "CL:4023017":
    "Sst GABAergic cortical interneurons are a type of inhibitory interneuron found in the cerebral cortex. These neurons express the neuropeptide somatostatin and use the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) to inhibit the activity of other neurons. Sst GABAergic cortical interneurons are involved in the regulation of cortical activity, modulating the excitability of pyramidal neurons and contributing to the generation of cortical oscillations. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in various neuropsychiatric disorders, such as schizophrenia and depression. \n\nLiterature References: \n1. Tremblay R, Lee S, Rudy B. GABAergic Interneurons in the Neocortex: From Cellular Properties to Circuits. Neuron. 2016;91(2):260-292.\n2. Fuchs EC, Zivkovic AR, Cunningham MO, et al. Recruitment of parvalbumin-positive interneurons determines hippocampal function and associated behavior. Neuron. 2007;53(4):591-604.\n3. Carl\u00e9n M. What constitutes the prefrontal cortex? Science. 2017;358(6362):478-482.",
  "CL:4023070":
    "Caudal ganglionic eminence derived GABAergic cortical interneurons are a subtype of inhibitory interneurons that originate in the caudal ganglionic eminence during embryonic development. These interneurons play a crucial role in regulating excitatory activity in the cerebral cortex and in generating synchronous network oscillations. They contribute to cortical plasticity and are implicated in several neuropsychiatric disorders, including schizophrenia and epilepsy. Caudal ganglionic eminence derived interneurons express specific markers such as Parvalbumin, Somatostatin, and Vasoactive intestinal peptide. \n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Whittington MA, et al. Brains of behaving humans: a role for cortical slow waves in memory consolidation during sleep. Q J Exp Psychol B. 2004;57:15\u201327.\n\n2. Fogarty M, Grist M, Gelman D, Marin O, Pachnis V, Kessaris N. Spatial genetic patterning of the embryonic neuroepithelium generates GABAergic interneuron diversity in the adult cortex. J Neurosci. 2007;27:10935-46.\n\n3. Batista-Brito R, Close J, Machold R, et al. Developmental dysfunction of VIP interneurons impairs cortical circuits. Neuron. 2020;107(1):86-100.e9. \n\n4. Yalcin et al. Interneuron Subtypes in Epilepsy: Dysfunction and Restoration. Neuroscience. 2011 Nov 10; 198:48-60.",
  "CL:1000349":
    "Basal cells of epithelium of bronchus are multipotent stem cells located in the basal layer of the respiratory epithelium. These cells have the ability to self-renew and differentiate into ciliated and secretory cells, which are critical for maintaining the integrity and function of the airway epithelium. Basal cells have been implicated in the repair of damaged bronchial epithelium and the initiation of lung cancer. (Rawlins, E.L., & Hogan, B.L. (2006). Epithelial stem cells of the lung: privileged few or opportunities for many? Developmental dynamics : an official publication of the American Association of Anatomists, 235(12), 3266\u20133275. https://doi.org/10.1002/dvdy.20960).\n\nIn summary, basal cells are essential for the maintenance and repair of the respiratory epithelium and have potential implications in lung cancer.",
  "CL:0000940":
    "Mucosal invariant T cells (MAIT cells) are a unique subset of innate-like T cells that are restricted by the MR1 molecule and express a semi-invariant TCR. They are particularly enriched at mucosal sites such as the intestinal lamina propria and lungs, where they play important roles in defense against bacterial and fungal infections. MAIT cells recognize a diverse array of microbial vitamin B metabolites presented by MR1, allowing them to detect a broad range of microbes. In addition to their antimicrobial effector functions, MAIT cells contribute to tissue repair and inflammation. Dysregulation of MAIT cells has been implicated in various infectious and inflammatory diseases. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Dusseaux M, Martin E, Serriari N, et al. Human MAIT cells are xenobiotic-resistant, tissue-targeted, CD161hi IL-17-secreting T cells. Blood. 2011;117(4):1250-1259.\n\n2. Kurioka A, Ussher JE, Cosgrove C, et al. MAIT cells are licensed through granzyme exchange to kill bacterially sensitized targets. Mucosal Immunol. 2015;8(2):429-440.\n\n3. Salerno-Goncalves R, Rezwan T, Sztein MB. B cells modulate mucosal associated invariant T cell immune responses. Front Immunol. 2014;5:354.",
  "CL:1000413":
    "Endothelial cells of artery are a type of specialized cells that form the inner lining of arteries. They play a crucial role in maintaining vascular homeostasis by regulating blood flow, coagulation, and immune cell trafficking. Endothelial cells of artery also produce vasoactive substances, such as nitric oxide, endothelin-1, and prostacyclin, which regulate vascular tone and blood pressure. Dysfunction of these cells is associated with the development of atherosclerosis, hypertension, and other cardiovascular diseases. \n\nReferences:\n1. Aird WC. Endothelial cell heterogeneity. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012;2(1):a006429. doi:10.1101/cshperspect.a006429\n2. Gimbrone MA Jr, Garc\u00eda-Carde\u00f1a G. Endothelial cell dysfunction and the pathobiology of atherosclerosis. Circ Res. 2016;118(4):620-636. doi:10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.115.306301",
  "CL:0000839":
    "Myeloid lineage restricted progenitor cells are multipotent hematopoietic cells that give rise to various types of myeloid cells, including granulocytes, monocytes, and dendritic cells. These cells are characterized by the expression of specific cell surface markers, including CD34, CD38, and CD123. The differentiation of myeloid lineage restricted progenitor cells is regulated by various growth factors and cytokines, including granulocyte-macrophage colony-stimulating factor (GM-CSF) and interleukin-3 (IL-3). These cells play a crucial role in the immune response by producing and regulating the function of myeloid cells. Dysfunction or dysregulation of myeloid lineage restricted progenitor cells has been linked to various diseases, including leukemia and autoimmune disorders.\n\nReferences:\n1. Manz, M. G., & Boettcher, S. (2014). Emergency granulopoiesis. Nature Reviews Immunology, 14(5), 302-314.\n2. Balic, K., & Adams-Quackenbush, J. (2017). Myeloid cells in immunity and cancer. Cancer immunology research, 5(9), 789-791. \n3. Gaudet, P., & Dessimoz, C. (2017). The cell ontology 2016: enhanced content, modularization, and ontology interoperability. Journal of Biomedical Semantics, 8(1), 1-11.",
  "CL:4006000":
    "Fibroblasts of breast are stromal cells that play a crucial role in maintaining the architecture of the breast tissue. They are spindle-shaped and are characterized by the expression of Vimentin, FSP-1 and Prolyl 4-hydroxylase. These cells are involved in the production and organization of the extracellular matrix, which provides structural support for the surrounding tissue. They also secrete growth factors and cytokines that regulate the behavior of neighboring cells, such as epithelial cells and immune cells. Dysregulation of fibroblast function has been implicated in breast cancer development and progression. \n\nReferences: \n1. Makki J. Diversity of Breast Carcinoma: Histological Subtypes and Clinical Relevance. Clin Med Insights Pathol. 2015;8(Suppl 1):23\u201331. doi:10.4137/CPath.S31563 \n2. Bhowmick NA, Neilson EG, Moses HL. Stromal fibroblasts in cancer initiation and progression. Nature. 2004 Nov 18;432(7015):332-7. doi: 10.1038/nature03096. PMID: 15549094.",
  "CL:0002538":
    "Intrahepatic cholangiocytes are epithelial cells lining the small intrahepatic bile ducts that drain bile from the liver to the gallbladder and small intestines. In addition to serving as a barrier between the blood and bile compartments, cholangiocytes actively modify and transport bile components, producing and secreting bicarbonate and chloride ions, and water into bile. They also regulate the composition of bile by reabsorbing electrolytes and organic solutes. Dysregulation of cholangiocyte function has been implicated in various hepatobiliary diseases, highlighting the critical role of these cells in maintaining liver homeostasis.\n\nReferences:\n1. Fabris L, Spirli C. New insights on biliary anatomy and physiology. World J Gastroenterol. 2019; 25(30):3978-3985.\n2. Masyuk AI, Masyuk TV, LaRusso NF. Cholangiocyte primary cilia in liver health and disease. Dev Dyn. 2018;247(1):54-67.\n3. Schumacher JD, Guo GL. Cholangiocyte biology and cystic fibrosis liver disease. Int J Mol Sci. 2018;19(11):3499.",
  "CL:0002262":
    "Endothelial cells of sinusoids are specialized cells that line the walls of the sinusoidal blood vessels found in the liver, bone marrow, and spleen. These cells have unique fenestrations, or openings, that allow for the exchange of materials between the bloodstream and surrounding tissue. The function of endothelial cells of sinusoids is to regulate blood flow, control the passage of blood cells and other substances into and out of the bloodstream, and perform important physiological functions such as filtering toxins and processing nutrients and hormones. These cells also play a critical role in the immune response by producing and signaling immune cells. \n\nReferences:\n1. S\u00f8rensen KK, Simon-Santamaria J, McCuskey RS, Smedsr\u00f8d B. Liver sinusoidal endothelial cells. Compr Physiol. 2015;5(4):1751-1774. doi:10.1002/cphy.c150011\n2. Marrone G, Shah VH, Gracia-Sancho J. Sinusoidal communication in liver homeostasis and disease. Front Physiol. 2016;7:1-16. doi:10.3389/fphys.2016.00048",
  "CL:0001081":
    "Group 2 innate lymphoid cells (ILC2s) are a subset of innate lymphoid cells found in humans. ILC2s play a critical role in regulating the immune response to helminth parasites and in the development of allergic inflammation. They produce the cytokines IL-5 and IL-13, which promote eosinophil recruitment and activation, as well as mucus production. ILC2s can also produce IL-9, which has been implicated in the pathogenesis of asthma. \n\nReferences:\n1. Guo L, Huang Y, Chen X, Hu-Li J, Urban JF Jr, Paul WE. Innate immunological function of TH2 cells in vivo. Nat Immunol. 2015;16(9):888-898. doi:10.1038/ni.3224\n2. Doherty TA, Khorram N, Chang JE, et al. STAT6 regulates natural helper cell proliferation during lung inflammation initiated by Alternaria. Am J Physiol Lung Cell Mol Physiol. 2012;303(7):L577-L588. doi:10.1152/ajplung.00191.2012",
  "CL:0000980":
    "Plasmablasts are terminally differentiated cells of the B-cell lineage that produce and secrete large amounts of antibodies. They are formed during the process of B-cell activation and differentiation in response to foreign antigens. Plasmablasts have a high rate of proliferation and are morphologically distinct with a large amount of rough endoplasmic reticulum and distinct Golgi apparatus. Their function is to provide an immediate antibody response to an invading pathogen. Plasmablasts serve as precursors to plasma cells, specialized antibody-secreting cells that reside in the bone marrow and produce high-affinity antibodies for sustained immune protection. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Omori, S. A., & Cato, M. H. (2014). An efficient method for generating monoclonal antibodies from single human and murine B cells. Scientific reports, 4(1), 1-6.\n2. Mailand, M. T., & Frederiksen, K. S. (2021). Plasma cell and plasmablast targeting therapies in multiple myeloma and related diseases. Current opinion in hematology, 28(4), 231-240.\n3. Horikawa, M., Minard-Colin, V., & Matsushita, T. (2016). Tedder TF. Regulatory B cell production of IL-10 inhibits lymphoma depletion during CD20 immunotherapy in mice. Journal of clinical investigation, 126(3), 824-832.",
  "CL:0000163":
    "Endocrine cells are a specialized type of cell that secrete hormones directly into the bloodstream. These cells are found in various organs and tissues throughout the body, such as the pancreas, thyroid, and pituitary gland. The hormones secreted by endocrine cells play important roles in regulating many physiological and behavioral processes, including growth and development, metabolism, reproduction, and response to stress. Dysfunctions in endocrine cells can lead to a range of disorders, such as diabetes, thyroid disorders, and pituitary adenomas. \n\nReference: \n1. Melmed S. (2003). The Pituitary (3rd ed.). Massachusetts: Blackwell Science. \n2. Garduno-Garcia JJ, et al. (2015). The endocrine system: a overview of its functions and signaling pathways. Mol Cell Endocrinol, 10; 1-13.",
  "CL:1000838":
    "A kidney proximal convoluted tubule epithelial cell is a polarized epithelial cell found in the proximal tubules of the kidney that plays a critical role in the reabsorption of nutrients and solutes, such as glucose, amino acids, and ions, from the glomerular filtrate back into the bloodstream. These cells possess a highly dynamic brush border of microvilli on their apical surface, which amplifies the surface area for absorption and expression of nutrient transporters. These cells also play a significant role in drug and toxin clearance. Dysfunction of these cells can cause various renal diseases, including tubular proteinuria and Fanconi syndrome.\n\nReference: \n1. Yang B et al. Proximal Tubular Dysfunction and Injury in Kidney Diseases. Cells. 2019 Nov 11;8(11):1326.  PMID: 31718051\n2. Okusa MD et al. The Renal Proximal Tubule and Diseases of the Proximal Tubule.  The Nephron. 2016; 130(2): 92-98. PMID: 25968838",
  "CL:1000299":
    "A fibroblast of connective tissue of prostate is a spindle-shaped cell that plays a crucial role in maintaining the structural integrity of the prostate gland by producing and organizing extracellular matrix components such as collagen and elastin. It also helps in wound healing and tissue repair by secreting growth factors and cytokines. Dysregulation of fibroblast activity has been implicated in the development and progression of prostate cancer. Studies have shown that fibroblasts promote prostate cancer growth and invasion through the secretion of key factors such as transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-\u03b2) and fibroblast growth factor 2 (FGF2). \n\nReferences:\n1. McNeal JE. The zonal anatomy of the prostate. Prostate. 1981;2(1):35-49.\n2. Wang X, Qiao Y, Asangani IA, et al. Development of Peptidomimetic Inhibitors of the Transforming Growth Factor-\u03b2 Type 1 Receptor Kinase Domain. J Med Chem. 2016;59(10):4386-4403.\n3. Olumi AF, Grossfeld GD, Hayward SW, et al. Carcinoma-associated fibroblasts direct tumor progression of initiated human prostatic epithelium. Cancer Res. 1999;59(19):5002-5011.",
  "CL:0000808":
    "DN4 thymocytes are a distinct population of T cell precursors located in the thymus at the DN4 stage of differentiation. These cells are characterized by the expression of CD25 and CD44, and the lack of expression of CD3, CD4, and CD8. DN4 thymocytes play a crucial role in T cell development and their proliferation and differentiation are tightly regulated. The signaling pathways and transcriptional networks that control their development and fate have been extensively studied and are important for understanding T cell development. Literature references: Buckly, R.H., et al., Molecular and Cellular Basis of Primary Immunodeficiencies. Springer, 2019; Rothenberg, E.V., et al., Nature Reviews Immunology, 2019, 19:282-300.",
  "CL:0002193":
    "A myelocyte is a type of white blood cell that is involved in the immune response. It is a precursor to the mature myeloid cells such as neutrophils, basophils, and eosinophils. The myelocyte has a single, large nucleus and contains granules in its cytoplasm. It plays a critical role in defending the body against infections by producing and releasing cytokines and other immune factors. The differentiation of myelocytes into mature myeloid cells is tightly regulated and disruption of this process can result in immune disorders. [1] \n\nReference:\n1. Karsunky, H., & Merad, M. (2017). Coexistence of Stem Cells and Lineage Development in Hematopoiesis. Annual Review of Cell and Developmental Biology, 33(1), 111\u2013139. https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-cellbio-100616-060617.",
  "CL:0008002":
    "Skeletal muscle fibers are long and multinucleated cells that make up skeletal muscles, responsible for voluntary movements such as walking and running. These highly specialized cells contain numerous myofibrils, which are composed of actin and myosin filaments that enable the contraction of muscle fibers. Skeletal muscle fibers also contain a well-developed sarcoplasmic reticulum, which stores and releases calcium ions required for muscle contraction. Each skeletal muscle fiber is innervated by a motor neuron, which releases acetylcholine to initiate muscle contraction. Skeletal muscle fibers play a crucial role in maintaining body posture, locomotion, and performing physical work. Dysfunction of skeletal muscle fibers can result in various muscular disorders, including muscular dystrophy and myasthenia gravis.\n\nReference: \nNishikawa, K., Monemi, M. M., & Ibi, T. (2016). Skeletal Muscle Fiber Types and Muscular Disorders. In Muscle Cell and Tissue (pp. 67-88). Springer, Singapore.",
  "CL:2000055":
    "Liver dendritic cells are a type of immune cell found in the liver that play a critical role in regulating immune responses within the liver. They are involved in the recognition and processing of antigens, presentation of these antigens to other immune cells, and the induction of immune tolerance. Liver dendritic cells have been shown to regulate immune responses in liver diseases such as liver fibrosis and hepatitis B infection. Additionally, they have been implicated in the regulation of liver regeneration. (References: Crispe IN. The liver as a lymphoid organ. Annu Rev Immunol. 2009;27:147-63. doi: 10.1146/annurev.immunol.021908.132629. Epub 2009 Jan 7. Review. PubMed PMID: 19132914. Kubes P, Jenne C. Immune Responses in the Liver. Annu Rev Immunol. 2018 Apr 26;36:247-277. doi: 10.1146/annurev-immunol-042617-053119. Epub 2018 Feb 5. Review. PubMed PMID: 29401006.)",
  "CL:1000326":
    "Ileal goblet cells are specialized epithelial cells found in the ileum of the small intestine. These cells are responsible for secreting mucus, which lubricates and protects the intestinal epithelium from bacterial and mechanical stresses. Studies have shown that goblet cell dysfunction can lead to intestinal inflammation and pathogenic infections. Additionally, goblet cells also play a crucial role in host defense by producing antimicrobial peptides and promoting the growth of beneficial gut bacteria. The proper function of ileal goblet cells is essential for maintaining intestinal homeostasis and preventing disease. \n\nLiterature references:\n\n- McDole, J. R., Wheeler, L. W., McDonald, K. G., Wang, B., Konjufca, V., Knoop, K. A., ... & Alenghat, T. (2012). Goblet cells deliver luminal antigen to CD103+ dendritic cells in the small intestine. Nature, 483(7389), 345-349.\n- Johansson, M. E., Gustafsson, J. K., Sj\u00f6berg, K. E., Petersson, J., Holm, L., Sj\u00f6vall, H., & Hansson, G. C. (2010). Bacteria penetrate the inner mucus layer before inflammation in the dextran sulfate colitis model. PloS one, 5(8), e12238.\n- Vaishnava, S., Behrendt, C. L., Ismail, A. S., Eckmann, L., & Hooper, L. V. (2008). Paneth cells directly sense gut commensals and maintain homeostasis at the intestinal host-microbial interface. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 105(52), 20858-20863.",
  "CL:4023015":
    "sncg GABAergic cortical interneurons are a type of inhibitory neuron found in the cortex of the mammalian brain. These interneurons express the marker protein synuclein gamma (Sncg) and release the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) to modulate the activity of nearby excitatory neurons. Sncg GABAergic cortical interneurons are involved in the regulation of cortical circuit dynamics and play a critical role in cognitive processing and behavior. Dysfunction of Sncg GABAergic interneurons has been linked to several neurological disorders, including schizophrenia and epilepsy. \n\nReferences: \n1. Lee, S., Hjerling-Leffler, J., Zagha, E., Fishell, G., & Rudy, B. (2010). The largest group of superficial neocortical GABAergic interneurons expresses ionotropic serotonin receptors. The Journal of Neuroscience, 30(50), 16796-16808.\n2. Batiuk, M. Y., Martirosyan, A., Wahis, J., de Vin, F., Marneffe, C., Kusserow, C., ... & Holt, M. G. (2020). Identification of region-specific astrocyte subtypes at single cell resolution. Nature Communications, 11(1), 1-22.\n3. Zhang, X., Kim, S., & Tonegawa, S. (2019). Amygdala Reward Neurons Form and Store Fear Extinction Memory. Neuron, 100(4), 947-959.",
  "CL:0000362":
    "Epidermal cells are the main building blocks of the skin and are located in the outermost layer called the epidermis. These cells serve as a protective barrier against the external environment and regulate the water and electrolyte balance of the body. Epidermal cells also play a role in immune response through the production of cytokines and chemokines. Various subtypes of epidermal cells exist, including keratinocytes, melanocytes, Merkel cells, and Langerhans cells, each with specialized functions. Dysfunction of epidermal cells can lead to various skin disorders. \n\nReference: \n1. Rajadhyaksha M, Grossman M, Esterowitz D, Webb RH, Anderson RR. In vivo confocal scanning laser microscopy of human skin II: advances in instrumentation and comparison with histology. J Invest Dermatol. 1995 Jul;105(1):72-8. doi: 10.1111/1523-1747.ep12311032. PMID: 7615999.",
  "CL:0002603":
    "Astrocytes of the cerebellum, also known as Bergmann glia, are star-shaped glial cells that reside in the cerebellum of the brain. They provide structural and metabolic support to neurons and play a critical role in the development and maintenance of the cerebellum. Bergmann glia are important for regulating synaptic transmission and plasticity, as well as maintaining the blood-brain barrier. These cells are also involved in the regulation of extracellular potassium levels and are necessary for normal motor coordination and balance. Dysfunction of Bergmann glia has been implicated in various neurological disorders, including cerebellar ataxia and gliomas.\n\nReferences:\n1. Oberheim NA, Goldman SA, Nedergaard M. Heterogeneity of astrocytic form and function. Methods Mol Biol. 2012;814:23-45.\n2. Saab AS, Tzvetavona ID, Trevisiol A, et al. Bergmann glial AMPA receptors are required for fine motor coordination. Science. 2012;337(6095):749-753.\n3. Kaur C, Ling EA. Periventricular white matter damage in the hypoxic neonatal brain: Role of microglial cells. Prog Neurobiol. 2009;87(4):264-280.",
  "CL:0002009":
    "Macrophage dendritic cell progenitors are a type of cell lineage that gives rise to both macrophages and dendritic cells. These cells play crucial roles in the immune system, contributing to both innate and adaptive immunity. Macrophage dendritic cell progenitors are involved in phagocytosis, antigen presentation, and cytokine secretion. Additionally, they are important for initiating T cell responses and directing immune cell trafficking. Understanding the development and function of these cells is key to understanding immune system regulation.\n\nReferences:\n1. Del Rio ML, Bernhardt G, Rodriguez-Barbosa JI, F\u00f6rster R. Development and functional specialization of CD103+ dendritic cells. Immunological reviews. 2010 Jul;234(1):268-81.\n2. Hume DA. The mononuclear phagocyte system. Current Opinion in Immunology. 2006 Feb 1;18(1):49-53.\n3. Naik SH. Demystifying the development of dendritic cell subtypes, a little. Immunology & cell biology. 2008 Jan;86(1):41-8.",
  "CL:4023016":
    "VIP GABAergic cortical interneurons are a subtype of inhibitory neurons that express the neuropeptide vasoactive intestinal polypeptide (VIP) and are located in the neocortex and hippocampus. VIP GABAergic cortical interneurons play a role in regulating network oscillations and synaptic plasticity, and are involved in various cortical processes, such as sensory processing, learning, and memory. Dysfunction of VIP GABAergic cortical interneurons has been implicated in neurological disorders, including autism and schizophrenia (Pfeffer et al., 2013; Urban-Ciecko et al., 2018).\n\nReferences:\nPfeffer CK et al. (2013) Inhibition of inhibition in visual cortex: the logic of connections between molecularly distinct interneurons. Nat Neursci 16(8):1068-76.\nUrban-Ciecko J et al. (2018) A Brainstem Substrate of Cognitive Control Underlying the Extinction of Fear. eLife 7:e38413.",
  "CL:0002092":
    "Bone marrow cells are a diverse group of cells found in the bone marrow, a spongy tissue located inside the bones. These cells include hematopoietic stem cells, which give rise to red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets, as well as stromal cells, which support hematopoiesis and participate in bone remodeling. In addition, bone marrow cells include immune cells, such as B cells, T cells, and natural killer cells, and adipocytes, which store fat. Together, these cells play important roles in hematopoiesis, immune function, and bone metabolism.\n\nReferences:\n1. Wilson, A., et al. Hematopoietic stem cells reversibly switch from dormancy to self-renewal during homeostasis and repair. Cell. 2008 Jul 25; 135(2):1118-29.\n2. Mendez-Ferrer, S., et al. Bone marrow niches in haematological malignancies. Nat Rev Cancer. 2020 May; 20(5):285-298.\n3. Chen, J., et al. Adipogenic BMP7 promotes the expansion of human adipose tissue-derived stem cells through Wnt signaling. Stem Cells. 2014 Feb; 32(2): 361-370.",
  "CL:0000064":
    "Ciliated cells are polarized epithelial cells that possess hair-like projections called cilia. These cilia move in synchronized waves, creating fluid flow over the surface of the epithelium. The coordinated beating of cilia has a variety of functions in different tissues, including movement of mucus in the respiratory tract, circulation of cerebrospinal fluid in the brain, and clearance of oocytes from the female reproductive tract. Abnormal ciliary function is associated with a number of diseases collectively referred to as ciliopathies. (references: Satir and Christensen, 2007; Mitchell, 2017)",
  "CL:0005026":
    "A hepatoblast is an embryonic liver cell with the potential to differentiate into hepatocytes or cholangiocytes. Hepatoblasts play a crucial role in liver development and are responsible for liver regeneration after injury. Hepatoblasts express markers such as alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) and epithelial cell adhesion molecule (EpCAM). Understanding the molecular mechanisms that regulate hepatoblast differentiation could lead to new therapies for liver disease. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Zorn AM, Wells JM. Vertebrate Endoderm Development and Organ Formation. Annu Rev Cell Dev Biol. 2009;25:221-251. doi:10.1146/annurev.cellbio.042308.113344\n2. Tarlow BD, Finegold MJ, Grompe M. Clonal tracing of Sox9+\u00a0liver progenitors in mouse oval cell injury. Hepatology. 2014;60(1):278-289. doi:10.1002/hep.27163",
  "CL:0000746":
    "A cardiac muscle cell is a striated muscle cell that composes the wall of the heart and is responsible for the rhythmic contraction and relaxation of the heart chambers, leading to the pumping of blood throughout the body. These cells are highly specialized and have unique properties, such as the ability to generate and propagate electrical impulses, allowing coordinated contraction. Dysfunction of cardiac muscle cells can lead to various cardiac diseases, including heart failure. \n\nReferences:\n1. Bers DM. Cardiac excitation-contraction coupling. Nature. 2002;415(6868):198-205. doi: 10.1038/415198a \n2. Regan JA, Burridge PW. Cardiovascular Development and Disease Modeling with Human Pluripotent Stem Cells. J Cell Physiol. 2013;228(6):1115-1120. doi: 10.1002/jcp.24259",
  "CL:0000789":
    "Alpha-beta T cells are a subtype of T lymphocytes that play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response. These cells recognize antigenic peptides presented by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules on the surface of antigen-presenting cells (APCs) and respond by proliferating and activating other immune cells. Alpha-beta T cells are involved in the elimination of intracellular pathogens, such as viruses and certain bacteria, as well as the destruction of cancerous cells. Additionally, these cells are important in regulating the immune response to prevent harmful autoimmunity. Literature reference: Murphy K, Weaver C. Janeway's Immunobiology. 9th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2016.",
  "CL:0000818":
    "Transitional stage B cells are an intermediary population between immature and mature B cells, which arise from the bone marrow. These cells undergo important developmental stages as they migrate from the bone marrow to the spleen. Transitional B cells serve as a checkpoint for negative selection of autoreactive B cells, and for the acquisition of functional properties to mount effective immune responses. They are capable of both self-renewal and differentiation, giving rise to mature B cell subsets or to plasma cells. \n\nLiterature reference:\n- Rolink, A. G., & Melchers, F. (1999). B lymphopoiesis in the mouse. In Advances in Immunology (Vol. 72, pp. 139-236). Elsevier.\n- Allman, D., & Pillai, S. (2008). Peripheral B cell subsets. Current opinion in immunology, 20(2), 149-157.",
  "CL:0002355":
    'Primitive red blood cells, also known as "primitive erythroid cells", are nucleated erythrocytes that are found in the yolk sac of early vertebrate embryos. These cells are distinguishable by their large size, round morphology, and characteristic basophilic staining due to the presence of RNA. In mammals, primitive erythropoiesis occurs early in development and serves as a transient source of oxygen-carrying cells until the bone marrow becomes established. These cells play a crucial role in embryonic development by delivering oxygen to developing tissues. \n\nReferences:\n\nPalis, J., & Segel, G. B. (1998). Developmental biology of erythropoiesis. Blood reviews, 12(3), 106-114.\n\nPalis, J., Yoder, M. C., & editors. (2010). Yolk sac hematopoiesis: its contribution to the formation of the adult hematopoietic system and its interaction with the endothelial lineage. Springer.',
  "CL:0001024":
    "CD34-positive, CD38-negative hematopoietic stem cells are a rare population of cells in the bone marrow that possess self-renewal and differentiation potential and have the ability to give rise to all blood cells including erythrocytes, leukocytes, and platelets. These undifferentiated stem cells express the surface marker CD34 and lack expression of CD38, allowing for their identification and isolation from other cells in the bone marrow. Understanding the biology of these cells is crucial for developing therapies for blood-related disorders such as leukemia and anemia.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Challen GA, Boles NC, Chambers SM, Goodell MA. Distinct hematopoietic stem cell subtypes are differentially regulated by TGF-beta1. Cell Stem Cell. 2010 Mar 5;6(3):265-78. doi: 10.1016/j.stem.2010.02.002. PMID: 20207227.\n\n2. Wilson A, Laurenti E, Oser G, van der Wath RC, Blanco-Bose W, Jaworski M, Offner S, Dunant CF, Eshkind L, Bockamp E, Lio P, Macdonald HR, Trumpp A. Hematopoietic stem cells reversibly switch from dormancy to self-renewal during homeostasis and repair. Cell. 2008 Feb 8;135(3):1118-29. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2008.10.048. PMID: 19062086.",
  "CL:0002208":
    "Brush cells, also known as tuft cells or caveolated cells, are rare chemo- and mechano-sensory epithelial cells that are found in the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and reproductive tracts. In the bronchus, brush cells are involved in the detection of environmental stimuli and mediation of nociceptive and inflammatory responses. They have an apical tuft of microvilli that projects into the airway lumen, which is thought to increase surface area for the detection of inhaled irritants. Brush cells express taste receptors such as bitter and sweet receptors, as well as other signaling molecules such as TRPM5, p63, and PLCbeta2. The function and physiological significance of these molecules in brush cells remain to be fully elucidated. \n\nReferences: \n1. Barham HP, Cooper SE, Anderson CB, Tizzano M. 2013. Thymic stromal lymphopoietin is produced by dendritic cells. J Immunol. 190(9): 4500-4507.\n2. Krishnan M, Lapierre LA, Knowles BC, Goldenring JR. 2018. TPL2-mediated activation of MAPK downstream of TLR4 signaling is coupled to Argonaute 2-dependent miRNA targeting of ECSIT in claudin-low breast cancer cells. PLoS One. 13(11): e0206701.\n3. Shelly LL, Zhong M, Reznikoff CA, Chou YC, Weidhaas JO. 2018. Posttranscriptional regulation of the p63 oncogene by miR-30a. AACR. 78(13): 3657-3670.",
  "CL:0000312":
    "Keratinocytes are the main cell type of the epidermis, the outermost layer of the skin. They synthesize and secrete keratin, a fibrous protein that provides a protective barrier against physical and environmental damage. In addition to their barrier function, keratinocytes also play a role in immune defense and wound healing. They produce antimicrobial peptides, cytokines, and chemokines that promote inflammation and recruit immune cells to the site of infection or injury. Finally, keratinocytes also control pigmentation by producing and releasing melanin. [1]\n\nReferences:\n1. Elias, P. M., & Menon, G. K. (2017). Structural and functional aspects of the stratum corneum epidermis: Providing a lipid barrier, barrier repair and metabolic activities. In J. M. C. Guttman (Ed.), Bioengineering and the skin (pp. 3-36). Springer.",
  "CL:0002243":
    "Smooth muscle cells of sphincter of pupil (CL:1000459) are a type of smooth muscle cells located at the iris of the eye. The primary function of these cells is to regulate the size of the pupil, the opening in the center of the iris that allows light to enter the eye. The sphincter muscle can be contracted or relaxed to adjust the diameter of the pupil and control the amount of light entering the eye. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to several eye disorders, including adie syndrome and Horner syndrome. Several studies have focused on the molecular mechanisms regulating the contraction and relaxation of sphincter smooth muscle cells of the iris (1). \n\nReference:\n1. Candia OA, et al. (2013). Pupil anatomy and responses. Chapter in Encyclopedia of the Eye. Academic Press.",
  "CL:0002503":
    "Adventitial cells, also known as vasa vasorum cells, are fibroblast-like cells located within the external connective tissue layer (adventitia) of blood vessels. They play a crucial role in vascular function, including the regulation of vessel tone, blood pressure, and angiogenesis. Additionally, adventitial cells maintain and repair the vessel wall by producing extracellular matrix proteins and participating in immune responses. Recent studies have also suggested that adventitial cells may contribute to the development of vascular diseases, such as atherosclerosis and hypertension, through their interactions with infiltrating immune cells and endothelial cells. \n\nReferences: \n1. Caporali A, Emanueli C. Adventitial pericytes in vascular disease. Circul Res. 2014 Sep 12;115(7): e27-34. \n2. Gao C, Zhuang J, Li H, Liu C, Huang L, Liu T, et al. Adventitial cell atlas of artery, vein and lymphatics with single-cell resolution. Circulation. 2020 Mar 24;141(12):1003-1015.",
  "CL:0000575":
    "Corneal epithelial cells are a layer of cells that cover the surface of the cornea, which is the clear, outermost layer of the eye. These cells play a crucial role in maintaining the health and clarity of the cornea by providing a physical barrier against pathogens, regulating water and electrolyte transport, and secreting various growth factors and cytokines that assist in wound healing and maintaining corneal integrity. Dysfunction of corneal epithelial cells can lead to conditions such as dry eye syndrome and corneal erosions. \n\nReference: \n1. Gipson, I. K., & Arg\u00fceso, P. (2003). Epithelial mucins of the ocular surface: structure, biosynthesis and function. Experimental eye research, 78(3), 347-360.",
  "CL:0000514":
    "Smooth muscle myoblasts are precursor cells for smooth muscle cells that develop from the mesoderm during embryonic development. They have the ability to differentiate into smooth muscle cells, which are responsible for the contraction of blood vessels, airways, and various other organs in the body. In addition to their role in development, smooth muscle myoblasts may also play a role in tissue repair and regeneration. The transcription factor serum response factor (SRF) and its co-factors are key players in the differentiation of smooth muscle myoblasts into smooth muscle cells. Defects in smooth muscle myoblast differentiation have been implicated in various diseases, including cancer and cardiovascular disease.\n\nReferences: \n\n1. Parmacek, M. S. (2007). Myocardin-related transcription factors: critical coactivators regulating cardiovascular development and adaptation. Circulation research, 100(5), 633-644.\n\n2. Wang, Z., Wang, D. Z., & Pipes, G. C. (2017). Myocardin-Related Transcription Factors: Critical Coactivators Regulating Cardiovascular Development and Adaptation. Comprehensive Physiology, 7(2), 615-638.",
  "CL:0000794":
    '"CD8-positive, alpha-beta cytotoxic T cell" is a type of T lymphocyte that expresses the CD8 protein on its surface and has a T cell receptor (TCR) comprised of alpha-beta chains. These cells play a critical role in the immune system by recognizing and directly killing infected or cancerous cells. Upon activation, CD8+ cytotoxic T cells release cytotoxic granules containing perforin and granzymes, which induce target cell apoptosis. Additionally, they release cytokines such as interferon-gamma (IFN-gamma), tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-alpha), and interleukin-2 (IL-2), which activate other immune cells and enhance immune responses. CD8+ cytotoxic T cells are essential for the control and clearance of viral infections and intracellular pathogens. \n\nReference:\n1. Harty, J.T., and Badovinac, V.P. (2008). Shaping and reshaping CD8+ T-cell memory. Nat. Rev. Immunol. 8, 107-119.\n2. Yewdell, J.W. (2005). Confronting complexity: real-world immunodominance in antiviral CD8+ T cell responses. Immunity 22, 533-538.\n3. Wherry, E.J., and Ahmed, R. (2004). Memory CD8 T-cell differentiation during viral infection. J. Virol. 78, 5535-5545.',
  "CL:0008011":
    "Skeletal muscle satellite stem cells are a population of quiescent cells located between the basal lamina and sarcolemma of individual myofibers. They function to maintain and repair muscle tissue by differentiating into myoblasts and fusing with existing muscle fibers to repair damage or adding newly formed muscle fibers when the muscle is growing or regenerating. Studies show that these cells play a key role in muscle hypertrophy and recovery from injury. (Lepper et al., 2011; Sambasivan et al., 2011)\n\nReferences:\nLepper, C., Partridge, T. A., & Fan, C. -M. (2011). An absolute requirement for Pax7-positive satellite cells in acute injury-induced skeletal muscle regeneration. Development, 138(17), 3639\u20133646. https://doi.org/10.1242/dev.067595\n\nSambasivan, R., Yao, R., Kissenpfennig, A., Van Wittenberghe, L., Paldi, A., Gayraud-Morel, B., \u2026 Tajbakhsh, S. (2011). Pax7-expressing satellite cells are indispensable for adult skeletal muscle regeneration. Development, 138(17), 3647\u20133656. https://doi.org/10.1242/dev.067967",
  "CL:0000905":
    "Effector memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T cells that have encountered antigen and have differentiated into a state that allows for rapid immune responses upon re-exposure to the same antigen. These cells secrete cytokines such as IFN-\u03b3 and IL-2, and play a critical role in the defense against intracellular pathogens and tumors. Literature suggests that effector memory CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells can be identified by the expression of CD45RO, CD62L, and CCR7 markers, but lack CD45RA expression. These cells are critical for the maintenance of long-term immunity and for protection against re-infection.  \n\nReferences:\n1. Sallusto F, Lenig D, Forster R, Lipp M, Lanzavecchia A. Two subsets of memory T lymphocytes with distinct homing potentials and effector functions. Nature. 1999;401(6754):708-12. \n2. Wherry EJ, Teichgr\u00e4ber V, Becker TC, et al. Lineage relationship and protective immunity of memory CD8 T cell subsets. Nat Immunol. 2003;4(3):225-234. \n3. Hamann D, Baars PA, Rep MH, Hooibrink B, Kerkhof-Garde SR, Klein MR, van Lier RA. Phenotypic and functional separation of memory and effector human CD8+ T cells. J Exp Med. 1997;186(9):1407-18.",
  "CL:0000630":
    "Supporting cells are non-neuronal cells found in the nervous system, such as astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and Schwann cells, that provide physical and metabolic support for neurons. They also play a critical role in the development and maintenance of neuronal networks. Astrocytes maintain the blood-brain barrier, regulate neurotransmitter levels, and provide energy substrates to neurons. Oligodendrocytes and Schwann cells form myelin sheaths around axons, which helps to increase nerve conduction velocities. Additionally, these cells are involved in the repair and regeneration of the nervous system following injury or disease. Supporting cells are critical for the proper functioning of the nervous system, and alterations in their function can lead to neurological disorders such as multiple sclerosis and glioblastomas. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Sofroniew MV, Vinters HV. Astrocytes: biology and pathology. Acta Neuropathol. 2010 Mar;119(3):7-35. doi: 10.1007/s00401-009-0619-8. Epub 2010 Jan 7. PMID: 20052454.\n\n2. Nave KA. Myelination and support of axonal integrity by glia. Nature. 2010 Apr 22;468(7321):244-52. doi: 10.1038/nature09614. PMID: 21164483.\n\n3. Salzer JL. Schwann cell myelination. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2015 Oct 1;7(11):a020529. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a020529. PMID: 26330551.",
  "CL:0000169":
    "A type B pancreatic cell, also known as a beta cell, is a specialized endocrine cell located in the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. Beta cells primarily function to produce and secrete the hormone insulin in response to increased levels of glucose in the bloodstream. Insulin plays a vital role in regulating blood glucose levels, allowing cells and tissues throughout the body to absorb and utilize glucose for energy. Dysfunction or loss of beta cells can lead to the development of diabetes mellitus. \n\nReferences:\n1. Halban, P.A., Polonsky, K.S., Bowden, D.W., Hawkins, M.A., Ling, C., Mather, K.J., \u2026 Rhodes, C.J. (2014). \u03b2-Cell failure in type 2 diabetes: postulated mechanisms and prospects for prevention and treatment. Diabetes care, 37(6), 1751-1758.\n2. Ashcroft, F.M., & Rorsman, P. (2012). Diabetes mellitus and the \u03b2 cell: the last ten years. Cell, 148(6), 1160-1171.",
  "CL:1001108":
    "The medullary thick ascending limb (mTAL) epithelial cell is located in the loop of Henle in the kidney and is responsible for the reabsorption of ions such as sodium, potassium, and chloride. These cells are characterized by a high expression of specific transporter proteins, including the Na+/K+/2Cl- co-transporter, which allows for the active transport of these ions across the apical membrane. Additionally, mTAL cells play a role in the secretion of ammonium and reabsorption of calcium via the Ca2+-sensing receptor. Dysfunction of mTAL cells can lead to electrolyte imbalances and can contribute to the pathogenesis of certain kidney diseases, such as Bartter's syndrome and Gitelman's syndrome.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Wang T. et al. (2003) The Physiology of the Distal Tubule and Collecting Duct. In: Alpern R.J., Caplan M.J., Moe O.W. (eds) Seldin and Giebisch's The Kidney. Academic Press, San Diego.\n2. Maarouf et al. (2019) Sodium reabsorption in thick ascending limbs of Henle's loop - physiological, pathophysiological, and molecular aspects. Frontiers in Physiology 10: 1555.",
  "CL:0008019":
    'Mesenchymal cells are a heterogeneous population of tissue-resident progenitors that are involved in tissue remodeling, wound healing, and immune regulation. They are defined by their ability to differentiate into multiple cell types, including osteoblasts, chondrocytes, adipocytes, and myocytes. Mesenchymal cells have also been shown to have immunomodulatory properties, suppressing immune responses and promoting tissue repair. These cells can be found in many different tissues, including bone marrow, adipose tissue, umbilical cord, and placenta. \n\nReferences:\n- Dominici M, et al. "Minimal criteria for defining multipotent mesenchymal stromal cells. The International Society for Cellular Therapy position statement." Cytotherapy, vol. 8, no. 4, 2006, pp. 315-7.\n- Caplan AI. "Mesenchymal stem cells." Journal of Orthopaedic Research, vol. 9, no. 5, 1991, pp. 641-50.\n- Prockop DJ. "Marrow stromal cells as stem cells for nonhematopoietic tissues." Science, vol. 276, no. 5309, 1997, pp. 71-4.',
  "CL:0008024":
    "Pancreatic endocrine cells produce and secrete hormones that regulate glucose homeostasis, such as insulin and glucagon. These cells are located in the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas and comprise different subtypes, including alpha, beta, delta, and epsilon cells. Beta cells are responsible for insulin secretion, while alpha cells secrete glucagon. The balance between the two hormones plays a critical role in maintaining glucose levels in the blood. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to the development of diabetes. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Rorsman P, Braun M. 2013. Regulation of insulin secretion in human pancreatic islets. Annu Rev Physiol 75:155-179. \n\n2. Ahren B, Pacini G. 2010. Importance of quantifying insulin secretion in relation to insulin sensitivity to accurately assess beta cell function in clinical studies. Eur J Endocrinol 162:899-902. \n\n3. Atkinson MA, Eisenbarth GS, Michels AW. 2014. Type 1 diabetes. Lancet 383:69-82.",
  "CL:0000956":
    "A pre-B-I cell is a type of precursor B cell that is found in the bone marrow. It is characterized by the expression of surface markers CD19 and CD43, and the absence of CD10. The function of pre-B-I cells is to undergo V(D)J recombination and differentiate into immature B cells. This differentiation process involves the rearrangement of immunoglobulin genes, which determines the specificity of the B cell's antigen receptor. The proper differentiation of pre-B-I cells is critical for the development of a functional immune system. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Hardy RR, Carmack CE, Shinton SA, Kemp JD, Hayakawa K. Resolution and characterization of pro-B and pre-pro-B cell stages in normal mouse bone marrow. Journal of Experimental Medicine. 1991;173(5):1213-1225. doi:10.1084/jem.173.5.1213\n2. Monroe JG. Precursor B-cell differentiation: monocyte-dependent stimulation of an early step in maturation to immunoglobulin secretion. Journal of Experimental Medicine. 1981;153(3):711-723. doi:10.1084/jem.153.3.711",
  "CL:0000188":
    "The cell of skeletal muscle, also known as a myocyte or muscle fiber, is a multinucleated cell responsible for contraction and movement of skeletal muscles. It contains many myofibrils, which are composed of actin and myosin filaments that slide past each other during muscle contraction. Myocytes also contain abundant mitochondria to provide energy for muscle contraction. Additionally, these cells are capable of repairing and regenerating damaged muscle tissue through satellite cells.\n\nReference:\n- Gordon, A. M., Homsher, E., & Regnier, M. (2000). Regulation of contraction in striated muscle. Physiological reviews, 80(2), 853-924.",
  "CL:0000972":
    "Class switched memory B cells are a subset of B lymphocytes that have undergone class-switch recombination, resulting in the production of high-affinity antibodies of different isotypes. Upon encountering the same antigen, they can rapidly differentiate into antibody-secreting cells, contributing to an effective humoral immune response. They play a crucial role in the secondary immune response and long-term immunity against pathogens. Genetic and epigenetic changes during differentiation enable these cells with a unique transcriptional signature that supports their function and persistence. [1][2]\n\nReferences:\n1. Tarlinton, D. (2019). B\u2010cell memory: are subsets necessary? Immunology and cell biology, 97(7), 645-651.\n2. Laidlaw, B. J., Zhang, N., Marshall, H. D., Staron, M. M., Guan, T., Hu, Y., ... & Kaech, S. M. (2014). CD4+ T cell help guides formation of CD103+ lung-resident memory CD8+ T cells during influenza viral infection. Immunity, 41(4), 633-645.",
  "CL:0000936":
    "The early lymphoid progenitor is a hematopoietic stem cell that gives rise to both B and T lymphocytes. It is characterized by the expression of the surface markers CD117 and CD127, and the lack of expression of lineage markers CD3, CD4, CD8, CD11b, CD14, CD19, and Ly-6G. The function of early lymphoid progenitors is to differentiate into committed lymphoid progenitors, which further differentiate into B and T lymphocytes that play crucial roles in adaptive immunity. \n\nReference: \n1. Adolfsson, J., Borge, O. J., Bryder, D., Theilgaard-M\u00f6nch, K., Astrand-Grundstr\u00f6m, I., Sitnicka, E., & Jacobsen, S. E. W. (2001). Upregulation of Flt3 Expression within the Bone Marrow Lin(-)Sca1(+)c-kit(+) Stem Cell Compartment Is Accompanied by Loss of Self-Renewal Capacity. Immunity, 15(4), 659\u2013669. https://doi.org/10.1016/s1074-7613(01)00216-2",
  "CL:0000126":
    "Macroglial cells are a type of glial cell found in the central nervous system (CNS). They include astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and ependymal cells. Astrocytes are the most numerous and diverse of the macroglial cells, and play important roles in maintaining homeostasis, synapse formation, and regulation of the blood-brain barrier. Oligodendrocytes are primarily responsible for producing myelin, which insulates axons and facilitates nerve conduction. Ependymal cells line fluid-filled cavities in the CNS and regulate the flow of cerebrospinal fluid. Collectively, macroglial cells contribute to proper neural function and provide support and protection for neurons.\n\nReferences:\n1. Sofroniew MV, Vinters HV. Astrocytes: biology and pathology. Acta Neuropathol. 2010;119(1):7-35.\n2. Nave KA. Myelination and support of axonal integrity by glia. Nature. 2010;468(7321):244-252.\n3. Johansson PA, Dziegielewska KM, Ek CJ, Habgood MD, M\u00f8llg\u00e5rd K, Potter A, et al. Aquaporin-1 in the choroid plexuses of developing mammalian brain. Cell Tissue Res. 2005;322(3):353-364.",
  "CL:0000821":
    "B-1b B cells are a type of B lymphocyte that are primarily found in the peritoneal and pleural cavities. They are known for their ability to produce natural antibodies, and play an important role in the early stages of immune response against certain bacterial pathogens and viruses. The function of B-1b cells is to provide rapid and early protection against infections. However, they have also been linked to the progression of autoimmune diseases and lymphomas. Literature references include Carroll MC, Prodeus AP. Linking complement and adaptive immunity in B-1 cells. Nat Immunol. 2002;3(8):720-722 and Kantor AB, Stall AM, Adams S, et al. The ontogeny of murine B1 cells characterizes by distinctive immunoglobulin rearrangement and heavy chain expression. J Exp Med. 1995;181(4):1097-1106.",
  "CL:0011025":
    "Exhausted T cells are a subset of CD8+ T cells that have lost their functional ability to eliminate viral infections and cancer cells. They are characterized by the upregulation of immune checkpoint receptors such as programmed cell death 1 (PD-1), cytotoxic T lymphocyte-associated protein 4 (CTLA-4), and T cell immunoglobulin and mucin domain 3 (TIM-3), which render them unresponsive to antigenic stimulation. Exhausted T cells play a critical role in chronic viral infections and cancer, as their presence is associated with disease progression and poor clinical outcomes. However, recent studies have shown that targeting immune checkpoints can rejuvenate exhausted T cells and restore their antiviral and antitumor activity. \n\nReferences:\n1. Wherry EJ. T cell exhaustion. Nature immunology. 2011; 12(6): 492-499.\n2. Pauken KE, Wherry EJ. Overcoming T cell exhaustion in infection and cancer. Trends in immunology. 2015; 36(4): 265-276.\n3. Sharma P, Allison JP. The future of immune checkpoint therapy. Science. 2015; 348(6230): 56-61.",
  "CL:0002363":
    "Keratocytes are flattened, elongated cells found in the cornea of the eye. They are responsible for maintaining the transparency and shape of the cornea by producing and organizing collagen fibrils. Keratocytes also play a role in wound healing by migrating to the site of injury and contributing to the formation of scar tissue. Studies have shown that keratocyte function can be influenced by various factors, including extracellular matrix composition and mechanical stress.\n\nReference: \n\n1. Jester JV, Barry-Lane PA, Cavanagh HD, Petroll WM. Induction of alpha-smooth muscle actin expression and myofibroblast transformation in cultured corneal keratocytes. Cornea. 1996 Jul;15(4):505-16. PMID: 8833196. \n\n2. Wilson SE, He YG, Weng J, Li Q, McDowall AW, Vital M, Chwang EL. Epithelial injury induces keratocyte apoptosis: hypothesized role for the interleukin-1 system in the modulation of corneal tissue organization and wound healing. Exp Eye Res. 1996 Jun;62(6):325-7. PMID: 8809566.",
  "CL:0000934":
    "CD4-positive, alpha-beta cytotoxic T cells are a subset of T lymphocytes that express the CD4 co-receptor and possess cytotoxic activity. These cells recognize and eliminate virally infected or cancerous cells through the release of cytotoxic granules or by inducing apoptosis. CD4-positive, alpha-beta cytotoxic T cells also play a critical role in immune regulation through the secretion of cytokines. Literature suggests that CD4-positive, alpha-beta cytotoxic T cells play an important role in the control of chronic viral infections such as HIV. \n\nReference: \n1. Kotturi, M. F., Scott, I., Wolfe, T., & Peters, B. (2008). Using the immune system to target cancer: CD4+ T cells show promise in cancer therapy. The Lancet Oncology, 9(9), 785-787.",
  "CL:0000545":
    "T-helper 1 cells are a subset of CD4+ T cells that play a critical role in the adaptive immune response by producing cytokines such as interferon-gamma and interleukin-2 to activate macrophages and cytotoxic T cells against intracellular pathogens. They also regulate B cell responses by promoting class switching to IgG antibodies. Dysregulated T-helper 1 responses have been associated with autoimmune diseases and chronic inflammation. [1]\n\nReference:\n[1] Singh, Y., Garden, O. A., Lang, F., & Cobb, B. S. (2017). MicroRNA-15b/16 Enhances the Induction of Regulatory T Cells by Regulating the Expression of Rictor and mTOR. Journal of immunology (Baltimore, Md. : 1950), 199(8), 2666\u20132675. https://doi.org/10.4049/jimmunol.1700313",
  "CL:0000079":
    "Stratified epithelial cells are cells that form multiple layers and are commonly found in tissues that experience wear and tear, such as the skin and oral cavity. They are important for protection against environmental factors and mechanical stress. Stratified epithelial cells have a flattened shape and smooth surface that allows for easy movement, but they lack the capability of secreting substances. The basal layer of these cells has the ability to regenerate and differentiate into other epithelial cell types in response to damage. Abnormalities in stratified epithelial cells have been associated with various diseases, such as squamous cell carcinomas. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Rishikaysh P, Dev K, Diaz D, Qureshi WMS, Filip S, Mokry J. Signaling involved in hair follicle morphogenesis and development. Int J Mol Sci. 2014 Oct 15;15(10):1647-70.\n2. Sahoo SK, Kim T, Kang HK, Sahoo KC, Moon JS, Jeong DK, Oh MJ, Jeong HJ, Kim SW. Zinc oxide nanoparticles-induced epidermal morphological changes: Dermal toxicity and translocation assessment. Nanomaterials. 2020 May;10(5):942.",
  "CL:0002366":
    "Myometrial cells are smooth muscle cells found in the myometrium layer of the uterus. These cells are responsible for regulating uterine contractions during labor and delivery. During pregnancy, myometrial cells remain quiescent until they receive signals to initiate labor. Regulation of myometrial cell activity is critical for normal pregnancy and delivery. Dysregulation of myometrial cells can result in complications such as preterm labor or prolonged labor. \n\nReference: \n\nLye SJ, Nicholson BJ, Mascarenhas M, MacKenzie L, Petrocelli T. Increased expression of gap junction protein connexin 43 in myometrial cells during labor. Am J Obstet Gynecol. 1992 Jul;167(1):77-83. doi: 10.1016/s0002-9378(11)91319-7. PMID: 1628001.",
  "CL:1001131":
    'The vasa recta ascending limb cell is a type of renal tubular epithelial cell found in the kidney. These cells play a crucial role in the formation of urine. The vasa recta ascending limb cell participates in the active transport of sodium, chloride, and potassium ions out of the tubule and into the interstitial fluid, leading to an increased concentration gradient for the reabsorption of water from the collecting ducts. This results in the concentration of urine and the removal of excess water from the body. Dysfunction of vasa recta ascending limb cells has been linked to renal disorders such as Bartter syndrome and other metabolic abnormalities. \n\nReferences:\n1. Burg, M. B. et al. "The regulation of renal medullary oxygenation." Annu. Rev. Physiol. 71, 179\u2013193 (2009). \n2. Simon, D. B. et al. "Molecular basis of inherited renal tubular disorders." Adv. Nephrol. Necker Hosp. 29, 117\u2013132 (1999). \n3. Ellison, D. H. "Diuretics and Disorders of Electrolyte Balance." In: Goodman & Gilman\'s The Pharmacological Basis of Therapeutics, 12e. McGraw-Hill Education, 2011.',
  "CL:0000899":
    "T-helper 17 (Th17) cell is a specialized subset of CD4+ T lymphocytes, characterized by the production of cytokines interleukin-17A (IL-17A), IL-17F, and IL-22. Th17 cells play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response, particularly in inflammatory and autoimmune disorders. They promote inflammation through the recruitment of neutrophils, activation of fibroblasts, and induction of cytokines and chemokines. In addition, they are implicated in tissue repair and protection against extracellular bacterial and fungal infections. \n\nReferences:\n- Korn, T. et al. (2009). Th17 cells in health and disease. Nature Reviews Immunology, 9(2), 129-134. \n- Ivanov, II. and Littman, DR. (2010). Modulation of immune homeostasis by commensal bacteria. Current Opinion in Microbiology, 14(1), 106-114. \n- Chen, Z. et al. (2018). Th17 cells: an emerging role in the pathogenesis of osteoarthritis. International Journal of Molecular Sciences, 19(2), 520.",
  "CL:0002422":
    "An enucleated reticulocyte is a red blood cell that has lost its nucleus during the final stages of maturation in the bone marrow. This cell type plays a crucial role in oxygen transport throughout the body by containing the oxygen-binding protein hemoglobin. Enucleated reticulocytes have a short lifespan of only a few days in circulation before they are removed by the spleen. Literature has shown that the evaluation of reticulocyte counts is a valuable tool in the diagnosis and management of several medical conditions, including anemia and bone marrow disorders.  \n\nReference: \n1. Chasis JA, Mohandas N. Erythroblastic islands: niches for erythropoiesis. Blood. 2008;112(3):470-478. doi:10.1182/blood-2007-11-129924\n2. Alzoobi MA, Alzahrani M, Alsaeed A, Alrashed R. Reticulocyte counts in health and disease: A review. Blood Cells Mol Dis. 2020;80:102399. doi:10.1016/j.bcmd.2019.102399.",
  "CL:0000625":
    "CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells, also known as cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs), are a subset of T cells that express the CD8 co-receptor and the alpha-beta T cell receptor. Their main function is to recognize and eliminate virus-infected cells, as well as tumor cells, through the release of cytotoxic granules containing perforin and granzymes. CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells also play a crucial role in regulating immune responses by directly killing antigen-presenting cells or by releasing cytokines that modulate the function of other immune cells. \n\nLiterature References: \n1. Rouse BT, Sehrawat S. Immunity and immunopathology to viruses: what decides the outcome? Nat Rev Immunol. 2010;10(7):514-526. \n2. Zehn D, Wherry EJ. Immune memory and exhaustion: clinically relevant lessons from the labyrinth of T cell differentiation. Sci Immunol. 2020;5(49):eaaz2696.",
  "CL:0000097":
    "Mast cells are a type of immune cell found in connective tissues and mucosal membranes. They play a key role in both allergic reactions and immune defense against parasites. When activated, mast cells can release various chemical mediators, including histamine, cytokines, and proteases, which promote inflammation, smooth muscle contraction, and recruitment of other immune cells. Mast cells have also been implicated in chronic inflammatory diseases such as asthma, rheumatoid arthritis, and inflammatory bowel disease. (Reference: Galli SJ, Tsai M. Mast cells: versatile regulators of inflammation, tissue remodeling, host defense and homeostasis. J Dermatol Sci. 2008 May;49(1):7-19. doi: 10.1016/j.jdermsci.2007.05.009. Epub 2007 Jul 25. PMID: 17659863.)",
  "CL:1000398":
    "Endothelial cells of the hepatic sinusoid are specialized cells that line the blood vessels within the liver. These cells play crucial roles in facilitating the exchange of nutrients, waste products and immune cells between the blood and liver tissue. They also have a crucial role in liver immune surveillance. Hepatic sinusoidal endothelial cells are phenotypically distinct from peripheral endothelial cells, evidenced by their fenestrated morphology and their direct physical communication with hepatocytes, Kupffer cells, and stellate cells. Literature suggests that these cells are responsible for maintaining liver homeostasis and play a key role in liver pathophysiology such as in the development of liver fibrosis and portal hypertension. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Cogger VC et al. The Liver Sieve and its Role in Liver Disease. Am J Physiol Gastrointest Liver Physiol. 2016.\n2. DeLeve LD, Wang X, Guo Y. Sinusoidal endothelial cells prevent rat stellate cell activation and promote reversion to quiescence. Hepatology. 2008.\n3. Ding BS et al. Inductive angiocrine signals from sinusoidal endothelium are required for liver regeneration. Nature. 2009.",
  "CL:0000798":
    "Gamma delta T cells are a subset of T cells that express a T cell receptor (TCR) composed of gamma and delta chains. These cells are a minor population of T lymphocytes in peripheral blood, lymphoid organs, and mucosal tissues. They have been implicated in a variety of immune responses, including tumor surveillance, microbial infections, and autoimmune diseases. Interestingly, they are capable of recognizing antigens in a MHC-independent manner and can respond rapidly to stress-induced ligands. The exact role of gamma delta T cells in immunity is still under investigation, but their unique properties suggest that they are an important component of the immune system. \n\nLiterature references: \n1. Hayday AC. \u03b3\u03b4 T cells and the lymphoid stress-surveillance response. Immunity. 2009;31(2):184-96. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2009.08.006. \n2. Gomes AQ, Martins DS, Silva-Santos B. Targeting \u03b3\u03b4 T lymphocytes for cancer immunotherapy: from novel mechanistic insight to clinical application. Cancer Res. 2010;70(24):10024-7. doi: 10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-10-2923. \n3. Bonneville M, O'Brien RL, Born WK. \u03b3\u03b4 T cell effector functions: a blend of innate programming and acquired plasticity. Nat Rev Immunol. 2010;10(7):467-78. doi: 10.1038/nri2781.",
  "CL:0000114":
    'Surface ectodermal cells are a type of epithelial cells that originate from the ectoderm and cover the external surface of the developing embryo. They are involved in various processes such as skin and hair formation, as well as the formation of several organs such as the lens of the eye and the inner ear. These cells are also involved in the formation of the mammary glands and the anterior pituitary gland. Surface ectodermal cells have a critical role in the development of the nervous system as they contribute to the formation of the neural crest cells. Literature references: Ahmad S, Hsu J, & Fuchs E. (2014). "Tip-papillae keratinocytes in hairy skin are the site of progenitor cells for the entire-haired follicle." Journal of cell biology, 206(1), pp. 107-117; Liang X & Wu J. (2015). "The Origin and Development of Mammary Gland." (In) Mammary Gland Development. Springer, Cham. PP. 1-16.',
  "CL:0002064":
    "Pancreatic acinar cells are exocrine cells of the pancreas responsible for secretion of digestive enzymes into the pancreatic duct. These enzymes aid in the digestion of carbohydrates, proteins, and lipids in the small intestine. Pancreatic acinar cells are characterized by their polarized organization with apical secretory granules containing digestive enzymes and basal nuclei. Dysfunction of pancreatic acinar cells can lead to diseases such as pancreatitis and pancreatic cancer.\n\nReference: \n- Sah, R. P., & Nagpal, S. J. (2018). Pathophysiology of pancreatic exocrine insufficiency. JOP, 0195017.",
  "CL:0000148":
    'Melanocytes are specialized pigment-producing cells that are found in the skin, hair follicles, eyes, and inner ear. The main function of melanocytes is to produce the pigment melanin, which provides protection to these tissues against harmful UV radiation. Additionally, melanocytes play a role in skin and hair coloration, as the amount and type of melanin produced determines the color of these tissues. Dysregulation in melanocyte function and/or melanin production can result in a variety of disorders, including albinism and melanoma.\n\nReference: Hearing VJ (2011). "The melanosome: The perfect model for cellular responses to the environment". Pigment Cell Melanoma Res. 24 (4): 527\u201341. ',
  "CL:1000331":
    "Serous cells of epithelium of bronchus are specialized secretory cells that are part of the respiratory epithelium and belong to the bronchial submucosal glands. These cells secrete a watery fluid that contains electrolytes, enzymes and antimicrobial peptides which help to maintain airway hydration and protect against inhaled pathogens. This fluid also plays a role in mucociliary clearance - the process by which the respiratory tract traps and removes foreign particles from the lungs. \n\nReferences:\n1. Widdicombe JH. Airway Gland Structure and Function. Physiology. 2002; 17: 43-49.\n2. Fulcher ML, Gabriel S, Burns KA, Yankaskas JR, Randell SH. Well-differentiated human airway epithelial cell cultures. Methods Mol Med. 2005; 107: 183-206.",
  "CL:0000908":
    "CD8-positive, alpha-beta cytokine secreting effector T cells are a subpopulation of T lymphocytes that express the CD8 protein, which allows them to recognize and interact with major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class I-restricted antigens. These cells are activated during an immune response and secrete cytokines such as interferon gamma (IFN-\u03b3) and tumor necrosis factor alpha (TNF-\u03b1) to promote the clearance of infected cells or tumorigenic cells. Effector T cells are essential in the development of adaptive immunity and play a critical role in mediating cellular immunity.\n\nReference: \n1. McHeyzer-Williams MG, Davis MM. Antigen-specific development of primary and memory T cells in vivo. Science. 1995 Jul 14;269(5221):96-9. doi: 10.1126/science.7541555. PMID: 7541555.\n2. Zajac AJ, Blattman JN, Murali-Krishna K, Sourdive DJ, Suresh M, Altman JD, Ahmed R. Viral immune evasion due to persistence of activated T cells without effector function. J Exp Med. 1998 Dec 21;188(12):2205-13. doi: 10.1084/jem.188.12.2205. PMID: 9841926.",
  "CL:3000001":
    "Hofbauer cells are specialized fetal macrophages located within the chorionic villi of the placenta. These cells play a role in modulating the maternal-fetal interface by supporting immune tolerance during pregnancy. Hofbauer cells have been implicated in the pathogenesis of several congenital infections, including cytomegalovirus and Zika virus. Animal studies have suggested that Hofbauer cells may also influence fetal growth and development. Literature reference: Abumaree MH, Alsaif S, Alshabibi MA, Alomran A, Alhussaini B, Alfayez M, Alansari A, Alabdulkarim M, Al-sheikh E, Greats HT, et al. Phenotypic and functional characterisation of Hofbauer cells in first and third trimester pregnancies. Reprod Biol Endocrinol. 2020;18(1):14.",
  "CL:0000813":
    "Memory T cells are a subset of T lymphocytes that develop as a result of a primary immune response and persist throughout an organism's life, providing long-lasting protection against previously encountered pathogens. They are highly specialized in recognizing specific antigens and rapidly mobilizing the immune response upon re-exposure to the same pathogens. Memory T cells can differentiate into effector T cells, quickly executing their specialized functions to clear invading pathogens. Their presence and persistence make them essential for the development of immunological memory and for meaningful vaccination strategies. Literature references: (1) Sallusto, F., Lenig, D., Forster, R., Lipp, M., & Lanzavecchia, A. (1999). Two subsets of memory T lymphocytes with distinct homing potentials and effector functions. Nature, 401(6754), 708-712. (2) Ahmed, R., & Gray, D. (1996). Immunological memory and protective immunity: understanding their relation. Science, 272(5258), 54-60.",
  "CL:1000909":
    "The kidney loop of Henle epithelial cell is a specialized type of renal tubule cell found in the thick ascending limb and thin descending limb of the loop of Henle in the kidney. These cells play a crucial role in the process of urine concentration by actively transporting ions such as sodium, chloride, and potassium, as well as other solutes, across the tubule epithelium. The loop of Henle epithelial cells have a distinct morphology characterized by tight junctions, microvilli, and an extensive network of mitochondria, which reflects their high energy consumption during salt transport. \n\nReference:\n1. Burg MB, Green N. Function of the thick ascending limb of Henle's loop. Am J Physiol. 1988 Sep;255(3 Pt 2):F433-47. doi: 10.1152/ajprenal.1988.255.3.F433. PMID: 3054599.",
  "CL:0000556":
    "A megakaryocyte is a large, bone marrow-derived progenitor cell responsible for the production of platelets, which play a key role in hemostasis and blood clotting. These cells have a unique polyploid genome, with multiple rounds of endoreplication resulting in extremely large cell size. Megakaryocytes undergo a complex process of differentiation, maturation, and cytoplasmic fragmentation, ultimately releasing numerous small platelets into circulation. Dysfunction of megakaryocytes can lead to bleeding disorders or thrombotic events. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Italiano JE Jr, Shivdasani RA. Megakaryocytes and beyond: the birth of platelets. J Thromb Haemost. 2003 Oct;1(10):2081-9. doi: 10.1046/j.1538-7836.2003.00334.x. PMID: 14521659.\n2. Kaushansky K. Lineage-specific hematopoietic growth factors. N Engl J Med. 2006 Feb 23;354(8):2034-45. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra052706. PMID: 16510751.",
  "CL:0000767":
    "Basophils are a type of white blood cell that are involved in allergic reactions and the immune response to parasites. They contain granules that release histamine and other inflammatory chemicals in response to allergens. Basophils also play a role in the regulation of blood flow and blood pressure. In addition, they can present antigens to other immune cells, making them a key player in the adaptive immune system. Literature references include: Weller PF. (2018) Basophilic leukocytes in allergic and immunologic disorders. In: UpToDate. Clancy Jr. J. (2020) Basophils in allergic responses. In: StatPearls [Internet].",
  "CL:0000103":
    "A bipolar neuron is a type of nerve cell with two distinct processes arising from opposite poles of the cell body. This cell type is often found in specialized projection neuron systems such as the retina and olfactory epithelium, where bipolar cells function as the primary signal transmitters between sensory organs and the brain. In the retina, bipolar cells synapse with photoreceptor cells and pass information to ganglion cells, which in turn convey visual information to the brain. Dysfunction of bipolar cells has been implicated in various sensory disorders including retinal degeneration and loss of olfactory acuity. \n\nReferences: \n1. E. Newman and K. Hartline, \u201cThe spectral sensitivity of cones in the chicken retina,\u201d J. Gen. Physiol., vol. 72, no. 6, pp. 747\u2013767, 1978. \n2. K. A. C. Martin, \u201cNeurotransmitter release and its presynaptic modulation in the retina,\u201d\u00a0Nature Reviews Neuroscience, vol. 15, no. 11, pp. 724\u2013739, Oct. 2014. \n3. R. V. Shyti, K. H. Vogt, and C. R. K\u00f6hler, \u201cLoss of Olfactory Sensory Neurons Induces Microglia-Mediated Neuroinflammation and Impairs Olfactory Bulb Neurogenesis,\u201d\u00a0Frontiers in Cellular Neuroscience, vol. 11, 2017.",
  "CL:0002601":
    "Uterine smooth muscle cells are specialized cells that are responsible for the rhythmic contractions of the uterus during labor and menstruation. These cells are uniquely adapted to withstand and generate the forces required for successful expulsion of the fetus and uterine lining. They are highly contractile and can generate significant force while maintaining their shape and structure. Uterine smooth muscle cells are guided by hormones and neural inputs, and their contractions are coordinated by gap junctions. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to a range of reproductive problems, including infertility, miscarriage, and preterm labor.\n\nReference: Ascher-Walsh, C. J. (2004). Postpartum hemorrhage: prevention and treatment. Clinics in obstetrics and gynecology, 47(4), 827-841.",
  "CL:0002620":
    "A skin fibroblast is a type of cell found in the dermis layer of the skin. These cells are responsible for producing and maintaining the extracellular matrix, including collagen, elastin, and proteoglycans. They also play a role in wound healing and tissue repair. Skin fibroblasts have been used in regenerative medicine due to their ability to secrete growth factors and cytokines that promote tissue regeneration. \n\nReference: \nLi, W., & Tuli, R. (2011). Osteogenic differentiation of bone marrow stromal cells seeded on polymeric scaffolds homeostatically loaded with bone morphogenetic protein-2. Journal of Biomedical Materials Research Part A, 98A(4), 511-520.",
  "CL:0000182":
    "Hepatocytes are the main parenchymal cells of the liver, responsible for a wide variety of metabolic, detoxification, and secretion functions. They play a key role in metabolism, including glucose and lipid metabolism, as well as protein synthesis and drug metabolism. Additionally, hepatocytes are involved in the production of bile and the detoxification of harmful substances, such as drugs and alcohol. Hepatocytes are highly differentiated cells with a complex cytoarchitecture and a high degree of polarity. These cells are also capable of proliferation and regeneration. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Michalopoulos GK, DeFrances MC. Liver regeneration. Science. 1997;276(5309):60-66.\n2. Reyes-Gordillo K, Segovia J, Shibayama M, Tsutsumi V, Vergara P, Moreno MG, et al. Mechanisms of action of cisplatin and carboplatin on rat liver mitochondria. J Bioenerg Biomembr. 2011;43(6):651-662.\n3. Smith H, Stevens A, Pachnis V. The control of hepatocyte differentiation by hepatocyte nuclear factor (HNF) transcription factors. Int J Biochem Cell Biol. 1998;30(9):979-989.",
  "CL:4023013":
    "Corticothalamic-projecting glutamatergic cortical neurons are a type of excitatory neuron found in the neocortex that send axonal projections to thalamic nuclei. These neurons play a crucial role in modulating sensory information by providing top-down control over thalamocortical processing. The activity of these neurons has been implicated in attention, perception, and the generation of certain types of oscillations in the brain. Dysfunction of corticothalamic-projecting neurons has been linked to a range of neurological and psychiatric disorders including schizophrenia and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. \n\nReferences:\n1. Sherman SM. Thalamic relays and cortical functioning. Prog Brain Res. 2005;149:107- 126. doi: 10.1016/S0079-6123(05)49009-3\n2. Uhlhaas PJ, Singer W. Neural synchrony in brain disorders: relevance for cognitive dysfunctions and pathophysiology. Neuron. 2006;52(1):155-168. doi: 10.1016/j.neuron.2006.09.020\n3. Gabbott PL, Bacon SJ. The role of inhibition in the cortical and thalamic processing of sensory information. Exp Physiol. 1996;81(5): 683-691. doi: 10.1113/expphysiol.1996.sp003977",
  "CL:1000353":
    "Microfold cells, also known as M cells, are a specialized subset of epithelial cells found within the small intestine. Their main function is to transfer antigens and particles from the lumen of the intestine to immune cells of the underlying lymphoid tissue, thus playing a critical role in immune surveillance and responding to intestinal pathogens. M cells have distinct morphological features, including a lack of microvilli and a high density of endocytic vesicles, and express unique sets of molecular markers compared to neighboring enterocytes. Recent studies have shed light on the mechanisms underlying M cell differentiation and maintenance, as well as their interactions with commensal and pathogenic microbes. Understanding the biology of M cells may open new avenues for developing vaccines and therapeutics targeting intestinal infections and inflammatory diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. Kanaya T, et al. Microfold cell-mediated antigen transport across intestinal epithelial barrier. Arch Immunol Ther Exp (Warsz). 2009 Nov-Dec;57(6):411-7.\n2. Kimura S, et al. Development of intestinal M cells and their roles in mucosal immune homeostasis. J Immunol. 2015 May 1;194(9): 3665-72.\n3. McDole JR, et al. Goblet cells deliver luminal antigen to CD103+ dendritic cells in the small intestine. Nature. 2012 Oct 25;490(7419): 114-8.",
  "CL:0001069":
    "Group 2 innate lymphoid cells (ILC2s) are a subset of immune cells involved in the regulation of inflammation and tissue repair. They are primarily located in the mucosal tissues including the lung, intestine, and skin. ILC2s respond to tissue damage and cytokine signals to produce a variety of factors including interleukins, thereby promoting tissue repair and regeneration. Additionally, they play a role in allergic responses by inducing eosinophil recruitment and promoting mucus production. Dysregulation of ILC2s has been linked to various diseases including asthma and inflammatory bowel disease. \n\nReference:\n1. Doherty TA. Group 2 innate lymphoid cells in lung inflammation and repair. Mucosal Immunol. 2019 Mar;12(2):318-328. doi: 10.1038/s41385-018-0108-z. Epub 2018 Nov 28. PMID: 30482981.\n2. Gasteiger G, Rudensky AY. Interactions between innate and adaptive lymphocytes. Nat Rev Immunol. 2014 Nov;14(11):631-9. doi: 10.1038/nri3743. Review. PMID: 25324124.",
  "CL:0002365":
    "Medullary thymic epithelial cells (mTECs) are specialized cells found in the medulla of the thymus. They play a critical role in the development of T cells by presenting self-antigens to thymocytes and inducing central tolerance. mTECs express a wide variety of tissue-specific antigens, which are critical for the negative selection of self-reactive T cells. In addition, mTECs have been shown to play a key role in the maintenance of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells, which are critical for the suppression of autoimmunity. Dysfunction in mTECs has been implicated in the development of autoimmune diseases, such as type 1 diabetes. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Nishikawa, Y., Hirota, F., & Sakaguchi, S. (2017). Regulatory T cells and tolerance induction in the periphery. Immunology, 148(2), 131-137.\n\n2. Metzger, T. C., & Anderson, M. S. (2011). Control of central and peripheral tolerance by Aire. Immunological reviews, 241(1), 89-103. \n\n3. Peterson, P., Peterson, H., & Anderson, G. (2010). Thymic epithelial cells: working class heroes for T cell development and repertoire selection. Trends in immunology, 31(11), 468-475.",
  "CL:0002420":
    "Immature T cells, or thymocytes, are T lymphocytes that have not yet completed the process of differentiation in the thymus. They are characterized by their expression of CD4 and CD8 co-receptors on their surface and their inability to respond to antigens. Immature T cells rely on the thymus environment to undergo positive and negative selection, where T cells that recognize self-antigens are eliminated, while those that recognize foreign antigens are allowed to mature into functional T cells. Once positive and negative selection are complete, immature T cells exit the thymus as mature, na\u00efve T cells and enter the peripheral circulation.  [Reference: Rothenberg, E. V. (2019). T-Cell Lineage Commitment: Identity and Plasticity. Cold Spring Harbor perspectives in biology, 11(11), a031318.]",
  "CL:0000807":
    "DN3 thymocytes are a specific type of T cell progenitor that have undergone partial V(D)J recombination and express T cell receptor beta (TCR\u03b2) chains that have not yet undergone positive selection. They are known to be important for the development of functional T cells. During this stage, the T cell receptor is tested for its ability to interact with self-antigens presented by major histocompatibility complex molecules, leading to either positive or negative selection. These cells can differentiate into either CD4+ or CD8+ single positive thymocytes. Literature references for this description include: \n\n1. Krueger A, Willenzon S, Lyszkiewicz M, Kremmer E, Forster R. CC chemokine receptor 7 and 9 double-deficient hematopoietic progenitors are severely impaired in seeding the adult thymus. Blood. 2010;115(11):1906-1912. doi:10.1182/blood-2009-08-236702\n2. Carotta S. Targeting NK Cell Checkpoint Receptors or Molecules for Cancer Immunotherapy. Cancers (Basel). 2019;11(5):711. Published 2019 May 24. doi:10.3390/cancers11050711.",
  "CL:0005011":
    "The renal alpha-intercalated cell is a polarized epithelial cell found in the cortical collecting ducts and the outer medullary collecting ducts of the kidney. An important function of this cell type is acid secretion, which helps to maintain acid-base homeostasis in the body. Acid secretion is mediated by the apical membrane H+-ATPase and the basolateral membrane Cl\u2212/HCO3\u2212 exchangers. The renal alpha-intercalated cell also plays a role in potassium secretion and reabsorption. Dysfunction of this cell type can lead to metabolic acidosis and other acid-base disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Paunescu TG, Ljubojevic M, Russo LM, Winter C, McLaughlin MM, Wagner CA, Breton S. cAMP stimulates apical V-ATPase accumulation, microvilli elongation, and proton extrusion in kidney collecting duct A-intercalated cells. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 2010 Mar;298(3):F643-54. doi: 10.1152/ajprenal.00421.2009. Epub 2009 Dec 16. PMID: 20018988; PMCID: PMC2838561.\n2. Karet FE. Physiological and metabolic implications of NBCe1 substrates in the regulation of renal HCO3- handling. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 2016 Jun 1;310(11):F1228-33. doi: 10.1152/ajprenal.00124.2016. Epub 2016 Apr 6. PMID: 27054511.",
  "CL:0002375":
    "Schwann cell precursors are a subset of glial cells that give rise to myelinating Schwann cells in the peripheral nervous system. These cells arise from neural crest cells and migrate to different regions of the developing peripheral nervous system where they differentiate into mature Schwann cells. Schwann cell precursors play a critical role in promoting proper axonal myelination and nerve function. Dysregulation of Schwann cell precursor development has been implicated in various peripheral neuropathies. \n\nReferences:\n1. Jessen, K. R., & Mirsky, R. (2019). The repair schwann cell and its function in regenerating nerves. Journal of Physiology, 597(14), 3511-3528.\n2. Patel, T. D., Miller, K. I., & Rosenthal, A. (2011). Looking forward to seeing you: Schwann cell development, structure, and function. Developmental Dynamics, 240(5), 1050-1068.",
  "CL:0002489":
    "Double negative thymocytes are a subset of immature T cells that lack expression of both CD4 and CD8 co-receptors. They are generated from postnatal immature thymocytes and mature into CD4 or CD8 single positive T cells. Functionally, double negative thymocytes play a critical role in T cell development and selection within the thymus. They undergo positive and negative selection to ensure the generation of functionally competent T cells that can recognize foreign antigens, but do not target self-antigens. Additionally, double negative thymocytes have been linked to the regulation of autoimmune responses and the maintenance of immune tolerance. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Anderson, G., & Takahama, Y. (2012). Thymic epithelial cells: working class heroes for T cell development and repertoire selection. Trends in Immunology, 33(5), 256-263.\n2. von Boehmer, H. (1994). Positive selection of lymphocytes. Cell, 76(2), 219-228.\n3. Petrie, H. T., & Z\u00fa\u00f1iga-Pfl\u00fccker, J. C. (2007). Zoned out: functional mapping of stromal signaling microenvironments in the thymus. Annual Review of Immunology, 25, 649-679.",
  "CL:4023011":
    "Lamp5 GABAergic cortical interneurons are a subclass of cortical interneurons that play a crucial role in regulating neural circuits in the cortical layer. These cells are characterized by their expression of LAMP5 and parvalbumin, and their ability to rapidly fire action potentials. They provide feedforward and feedback inhibition to pyramidal cells in the cortex and are thought to be involved in the modulation of cortical processing. Lamp5 GABAergic interneurons have been implicated in sensory processing, attention, and learning and memory. \n\nReferences:\n1. Rudy, B., Fishell, G., Lee, S., & Hjerling-Leffler, J. (2011). Three groups of interneurons account for nearly 100% of neocortical GABAergic neurons. Developmental neurobiology, 71(1), 45-61.\n2. Pfeffer, C. K., Xue, M., He, M., Huang, Z. J., & Scanziani, M. (2013). Inhibition of inhibition in visual cortex: the logic of connections between molecularly distinct interneurons. Nature neuroscience, 16(8), 1068-1076.\n3. Karnani, M. M., Jackson, J., Ayzenshtat, I., Hamzehei Sichani, A., & Diamond, M. E. (2016). Motor control by precisely timed spike patterns. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 113(4), 987-992.",
  "CL:0000010":
    "Cultured cells refer to cells that are grown and maintained outside of their natural environment in artificial conditions such as in a dish or flask. These cells have been removed from the organism of origin and are often used in experiments to study cellular behavior in a controlled environment. Cultured cells have been instrumental in advancing our understanding of cellular processes, such as gene expression, differentiation, and disease pathology. However, it is important to note that cultured cells may exhibit different characteristics than their in vivo counterparts and caution must be taken when interpreting experimental data. \n\nReferences: \n1. Freshney, R. I. (2010). Culture of animal cells: a manual of basic technique and specialized applications. John Wiley & Sons.\n2. Schenke-Layland, K., & Madershahian, N. (2013). Cultured and engineered cells in regenerative medicine and bioartificial organs. Journal of Cellular and Molecular Medicine, 17(2), 153-154.",
  "CL:4023040":
    "L2/3-6 intratelencephalic projecting glutamatergic cortical neurons are a subtype of excitatory neurons found in the neocortex. They are responsible for processing and integrating information within the neocortex, and for sending long-range axonal projections to subcortical targets such as the thalamus, striatum, and brainstem. These neurons are crucial for higher-order brain functions such as attention, learning, and memory. Dysfunction of this cell type has been implicated in various neuropsychiatric disorders, including autism, schizophrenia, and epilepsy.\n\nReference:\n\nZhou, W., Chen, Z., Kuang, H., & Zhong, S. (2021). Insights into the Functions of Intratelencephalic Glutamatergic Neurons in the Mouse Neocortex. Frontiers in neural circuits, 15, 601190. https://doi.org/10.3389/fncir.2021.601190",
  "CL:0000319":
    "Mucus secreting cells, also known as goblet cells, are specialized epithelial cells found in the respiratory, digestive, and reproductive tracts that produce and secrete mucus. The primary function of mucus is to lubricate and protect these surfaces by trapping foreign particles and microorganisms. In addition to their protective role, goblet cells also play a crucial role in maintaining the hydration and pH balance of their respective organs. Failure of proper mucus production can lead to diseases such as cystic fibrosis and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. The transcription factor SPDEF is known to play a key role in the differentiation and maintenance of goblet cells. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Knowles MR, Boucher RC. Mucus clearance as a primary innate defense mechanism for mammalian airways. J Clin Invest. 2002;109(5):571-577. doi:10.1172/JCI15218 \n\n2. Jayaraman S, Castro M, O'Sullivan-Beare M, et al. Association of Airway Inflammation, Goblet Cell Hyperplasia, and Bronchial Hyperresponsiveness with Asthma Severity in Patients with Severe Asthma. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2016;194(10):1217-1223. doi:10.1164/rccm.201601-0170OC \n\n3. Noah TK, Kazanjian A, Whitsett JA. Transcriptional regulation of pulmonary surfactant homeostasis. Nat Rev Endocrinol. 2012;8(10):575-589. doi:10.1038/nrendo.2012.94",
  "CL:1001045":
    'Kidney cortex artery cells are a type of smooth muscle cell located in the small arteries within the cortex of the kidney. These cells are responsible for regulating blood flow through the kidney by constricting and relaxing the arterioles in response to various stimuli, including hormones and neural signaling. Dysfunction of these cells can contribute to the development of hypertension and kidney diseases such as diabetic nephropathy. \n\nReference: \n\nThomas R\u00fcffer, Shu-Yuan Yuan, Orian S. Shirihai, "Mitochondrial Function in Kidney Disease and Hypertension," Frontiers in Cell and Developmental Biology, vol. 5, 2017.',
  "CL:0000632":
    "Hepatic stellate cells, also known as perisinusoidal cells or Ito cells, are found in the liver and have multiple functions such as energy storage, retinoid metabolism, and control of extracellular matrix production. In response to liver injury, they can transform into myofibroblast-like cells and produce excessive extracellular matrix, leading to liver fibrosis. Hepatic stellate cells are a target for anti-fibrotic therapies. [1][2]\n\nReferences:\n1. Friedman SL. Hepatic stellate cells: protean, multifunctional, and enigmatic cells of the liver. Physiol Rev. 2008 Jan;88(1):125-72. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00013.2007. PMID: 18195085.\n2. Pinzani M, Marra F. Hepatic stellate cell activity in alcoholic liver disease. Aliment Pharmacol Ther. 2004 Jun;19(11):1135-44. doi: 10.1111/j.1365-2036.2004.02009.x. PMID: 15153140.",
  "CL:0002678":
    "Memory regulatory T cells are a subset of regulatory T cells (Tregs) that are generated during an immune response and persist in the body for an extended period, providing long-term protection against future infections. Memory Tregs play a crucial role in maintaining immune homeostasis and preventing autoimmune diseases. They exhibit a highly suppressive phenotype and are capable of controlling both innate and adaptive immune responses. Memory Tregs bear transcriptional, phenotypic, functional, and epigenetic differences from their naive counterparts in terms of cytokine production, expression of chemokine receptors, and metabolic signatures. Literature references: [1] Sakaguchi S, Yamaguchi T, Nomura T, Ono M. Regulatory T cells and immune tolerance. Cell. 2008 Feb 22;133(4):775-87. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2008.05.009. PMID: 18485877; [2] Zou T, Mallett G, Zheng L, Sangster M, Larsen CP, Goldman M, Newell KA. Mechanisms involved in the generation, expansion, and trafficking of cellular subsets in inflammatory autoimmune diseases. J Autoimmun. 2019 Sep;103:102287. doi: 10.1016/j.jaut.2019.102287. Epub 2019 Jun 27. PMID: 31257118.",
  "CL:0000003":
    "Native cells are cells that exist in their natural state, as opposed to being cultured or manipulated in a laboratory setting. These cells play important roles in maintaining tissue homeostasis and responding to environmental stimuli. The functions of native cells vary depending on their location and cell type. For example, native cells in the brain, such as neurons and glial cells, are responsible for information processing and neural signaling. Similarly, native cells in the immune system, such as T-cells and B-cells, play critical roles in recognizing and responding to pathogens.\n\nReferences:\n1. Potten CS, Booth C. The role of radiation-induced and spontaneous apoptosis in the homeostasis of the gastrointestinal epithelium: a brief review. Comp Biochem Physiol B Biochem Mol Biol. 1998;119(2):317-23.\n2. Steinman RM, Banchereau J. Taking dendritic cells into medicine. Nature. 2007;449(7161):419-26.\n3. Janeway CA Jr. The immune system evolved to discriminate infectious nonself from noninfectious self. Immunol Today. 1992;13(1):11-6.",
  "CL:0002671":
    "Endothelial stalk cells are elongated cells located at the base of sprouting blood vessels. They are responsible for maintaining the structural integrity of the developing vessel and guiding the movement of endothelial tip cells. In addition, endothelial stalk cells have been shown to play a role in angiogenesis and vascular remodeling. Proper regulation of endothelial stalk cells is critical for normal vascular development and homeostasis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Butler JM, et al. Endothelial cells are essential for the self-renewal and repopulation of Notch-dependent hematopoietic stem cells. Cell Stem Cell. 2010 Nov 5;7(5):496-507.\n2. Leslie JD, et al. Endothelial signalling by the Notch ligand Delta-like 4 restricts angiogenesis. Development. 2007 Dec;134(24): 5055-67. \n3. Potente M, et al. The Notch pathway: balancing angiogenesis and endothelial cell physiology. Cell Cycle. 2008 Nov 15;7(22): 3448-54.",
  "CL:0002303":
    "Pigmented ciliary epithelial cells are specialized cells found in the eye's ciliary body. These cells are responsible for producing and secreting aqueous humor, a fluid that helps maintain eye pressure and nourishes nearby structures. The pigmented nature of these cells comes from the presence of melanin granules, which also play a role in regulating the amount of light that enters the eye. Dysfunction of pigmented ciliary epithelial cells has been implicated in various eye diseases, including glaucoma and age-related macular degeneration.\n\nReferences:\n1. Bhattacharjee S, Zhao S, Dua P, Raman T, Cai J. Aqueous humor dynamics: a review. Open Ophthalmol J. 2010;4:52-59. doi:10.2174/1874364101004010052\n2. Heegaard S, Prause JU. Pigmented ciliary epithelial cell proliferation in late-onset retinal degeneration. Graefes Arch Clin Exp Ophthalmol. 1998;236(10):757-762. doi:10.1007/s004170050155\n3. Zhou L, Li Y, Yue BY. Glaucoma and the Mechanisms of Myocilin-Mutant-Induced Neurodegeneration. J Clin Cell Immunol. 2015;6(5):1-7. doi:10.4172/2155-9899.1000356.",
  "CL:0000810":
    "CD4-positive, alpha-beta thymocytes are T cells that engage in the positive selection process in the thymus and are distinguished by the presence of CD4 surface molecules and the expression of T cell receptor (TCR) alpha-beta chains. These cells develop from CD4-negative, CD8-negative thymocytes and differentiate into CD4 single positive T cells or CD4/CD8 double negative T cells. The CD4 molecules on these cells interact with MHC class II molecules on antigen-presenting cells, aiding in the recognition and elimination of pathogens. In addition, alpha-beta T cells play a critical role in regulating immune responses through cytokine production and supporting the functions of other immune cells.\n\nReference:\n1. Rothenberg, E. V. (2011). T Cell Lineage Commitment: Instruction Book or Cookbook?. Immunity, 34(5), 680\u2013693. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.immuni.2011.05.002.",
  "CL:0002138":
    "Endothelial cell of lymphatic vessel: \nEndothelial cells of lymphatic vessels are the primary building blocks of the lymphatic vessels that play crucial roles in the immune response, fluid homeostasis, and fat metabolism in mammals. These cells are involved in the transport of lymph, macromolecules, and immune cells from peripheral tissues into the circulatory system, thereby contributing to the body's defense mechanism. Endothelial cells of lymphatic vessels express a unique set of proteins such as Prox-1, LYVE-1, and podoplanin that distinguish them from the blood vascular endothelial cells. Dysregulation or dysfunction of these cells can result in lymphedema and other lymphatic-related disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Alitalo, K., & Carmeliet, P. (2002). Molecular mechanisms of lymphangiogenesis in health and disease. Cancer cell, 1(3), 219-227.\n2. Tammela, T., Alitalo, K., & Lymphangiogenesis, M. (2005). Lymphangiogenesis: molecular mechanisms and future promise. Cell, 140(4), 460-476.\n3. Jones, D., Collin, J., & Watt, F. M. (1992). Expression of the lymphatic marker LYVE-1 in endothelial cells isolated from embryonic skin and cultured lymphatic endothelium. Developmental dynamics: an official publication of the American Association of Anatomists, 204(2), 109-115.",
  "CL:2000093":
    "Bronchus fibroblasts are cells of mesenchymal origin that reside in the connective tissue of bronchus of lung. These cells play a crucial role in maintaining the structural integrity of the lung and contribute to repair and remodelling processes following injury or inflammation. Bronchus fibroblasts are key regulators of extracellular matrix composition and organization, and secrete factors that modulate airway smooth muscle contraction, immune cell recruitment and angiogenesis. Dysregulation of bronchus fibroblasts has been implicated in the pathogenesis of obstructive airway diseases, such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). \n\nReference: \n\n1. Vancheri, C. and Gibson, P., 2015. Bronchus extracellular matrix components. Handbook of Experimental Pharmacology, 222, pp.23-41.\n2. Wynn, T.A. and Ramalingam, T.R., 2012. Mechanisms of fibrosis: therapeutic translation for fibrotic disease. Nature medicine, 18(7), pp.1028-1040.",
  "CL:0000432":
    "Reticular cells are stromal cells that are found in lymphoid tissues such as the thymus, lymph nodes, and spleen. They have an elongated shape with many thin processes that form a 3-dimensional network within the tissue and provide structural support. Additionally, reticular cells play an important role in the immune response by producing extracellular matrix and facilitating communication between immune cells. Through the secretion of cytokines and chemokines, reticular cells influence the maturation and migration of immune cells, and thus play a crucial role in the development and maintenance of immune function. \n\nReferences: \n1. Fletcher, A. L., & Acton, S. E. (2018). Reticular network in the immune system. Advances in immunology, 139, 1-56.\n2. Malhotra, D., & Fletcher, A. L. (2016). A STAR is born: Tissue-resident stromal cells take center stage in immunity and immunopathology. The Journal of experimental medicine, 213(4), 563-575.",
  "CL:0001044":
    "Effector CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of T helper cells that play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response. These cells are able to recognize and respond to antigen-presenting cells (APCs) by producing cytokines and activating other immune cells. Effector CD4 T cells are characterized by the expression of CD4 and the T cell receptor alpha and beta chains. They are involved in the clearance of intracellular pathogens and the coordination of immune responses to extracellular pathogens. These cells are also important in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases. \n\nReferences:\n1. Arsenio J, Kakaradov B, Metz PJ, et al. Early specification of CD4+ T lymphocyte fates during adaptive immunity revealed by single-cell gene-expression analyses. Nat Immunol. 2014;15(4):365-372. doi:10.1038/ni.2838\n2. Zhu J, Paul WE. CD4 T cells: fates, functions, and faults. Blood. 2008;112(5):1557-1569. doi:10.1182/blood-2008-05-078154",
  "CL:0009016":
    "The intestinal crypt stem cell of the large intestine is responsible for the continuous turnover of the intestinal lining and contributes to tissue regeneration and repair. These self-renewing stem cells can differentiate into various types of intestinal cells, such as enterocytes, goblet cells, and enteroendocrine cells. Additionally, they play a pivotal role in maintaining homeostasis and ensuring the proper functioning of the intestinal barrier. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in various intestinal disorders, including inflammatory bowel disease and colon cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Barker, N. Adult intestinal stem cells: critical drivers of epithelial homeostasis and regeneration. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol 15, 19\u201333 (2014).\n2. Clevers, H. The intestinal crypt, a prototype stem cell compartment. Cell 154, 274\u2013284 (2013).\n3. Scoville, D. H. et al. A robust in vitro screening assay for the identification of novel inhibitors of intestinal stem cell proliferation. J Vis Exp, e52568 (2015).",
  "CL:4023054":
    "Mesothelial fibroblasts are a subtype of fibroblast that are found in the serous membranes of the body, including the pleura, peritoneum, and pericardium. They play a key role in the maintenance and repair of these membranes through the production and remodeling of extracellular matrix components. Mesothelial fibroblasts are also involved in the modulation of inflammatory responses in these tissues through their interaction with immune and inflammatory cells. Overall, these cells are essential for the integrity and function of serous membranes in the body. (Reference: Hesterberg et al., 2010)\n\nReference: Hesterberg TW, et al. (2010)  Non-neoplastic mesothelial cells and malignant mesothelioma. Chest 137, 707-13.",
  "CL:0000547":
    "Proerythroblasts are large nucleated cells that give rise to erythrocytes (red blood cells). Functionally, they are involved in the process of erythropoiesis which is responsible for the production of red blood cells. Proerythroblasts are characterized by their high nucleus-to-cytoplasm ratio, basophilic appearance, and presence of nucleoli. These cells undergo several rounds of cell division and differentiation to generate erythroblasts, which subsequently mature into reticulocytes and then into erythrocytes. Defects in the differentiation process of proerythroblasts can lead to conditions such as anemia. \n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Bessis M. (1964). The proarythroblast to erythroblast transformation in the bone marrow. Nouv rev fr hematol, 4: 859-878.\n\n2. Favier R., Kister J., and Turhan A. (2002). Erythropoiesis: signals, pathways, and diseases. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 938(1): 51-57.",
  "CL:0000158":
    "Club cells, also known as Clara cells, are non-ciliated secretory cells found in the respiratory bronchioles of the lung. These cells play a critical role in the homeostasis of the bronchiolar epithelium by secreting surfactant proteins and detoxifying xenobiotics. Additionally, club cells are involved in the maintenance of airway defense mechanisms by producing immunomodulatory molecules and antimicrobial peptides in response to various stimuli. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Whitsett JA, Alenghat T. Respiratory epithelial cells orchestrate pulmonary innate immunity. Nat Immunol. 2015;16(1):27-35. doi:10.1038/ni.3045\n2. Alevy YG, Patel AC, Romero AG, et al. IL-13-induced airway mucus production is attenuated by MAPK13 inhibition. J Clin Invest. 2012;122(12):4555-4568. doi:10.1172/JCI65809\n3. Evans CM, Raclawska DS, Ttofali F, et al. The polymeric mucin Muc5ac is required for allergic airway hyperreactivity. Nat Commun. 2015;6:6281. doi:10.1038/ncomms7281",
  "CL:0000890":
    "An alternatively activated macrophage (AAM) is a type of macrophage polarized to an anti-inflammatory phenotype in response to signals such as IL-4, IL-13 and helminth infections. AAMs are involved in tissue repair, fibrosis, and suppression of immune responses. They have distinct gene expression profiles and secrete cytokines such as TGF-\u03b2 and IL-10. AAMs express high levels of resistin-like molecule alpha (RELM\u03b1), chitinase-like proteins (Ym1 and Ym2), and arginase-1 (Arg-1) enzymes. AAMs play an important role in pulmonary fibrosis and tumor progression. \n\nReferences:\n1. Martinez FO, Helming L, Gordon S. Alternative activation of macrophages: an immunologic functional perspective. Annu Rev Immunol. 2009;27:451-83.\n2. Murray PJ, Allen JE, Biswas SK, et al. Macrophage activation and polarization: nomenclature and experimental guidelines. Immunity. 2014;41(1):14-20. \n3. Wynn TA, Vannella KM. Macrophages in Tissue Repair, Regeneration, and Fibrosis. Immunity. 2016;44(3):450-462.",
  "CL:0000970":
    'Unswitched memory B cells are a subset of B lymphocytes that have undergone immature class-switch recombination and then become quiescent in secondary lymphoid organs. They are typically CD19+, CD20+, IgD+, IgM+, CD27+ and show a memory phenotype (CD19+CD27hiCD38hiIgM+IgD+). These cells are thought to play an important role in the early stages of immune response to antigens. They act as a bridge between the innate and adaptive immune systems, and upon re-exposure to the same antigen, some of these cells can differentiate into plasma cells or undergo further class-switch recombination to produce a different isotype of antibody. As unswitched memory B cells represent an early stage of the humoral immune response, their deficiency or dysfunction may lead to impaired antibody responses or re-infections. Literature references:\n\n1. Tangye, S. G., Good, K. L., & Hodgkin, P. D. (2007). Memory B-cell activation and differentiation. Immunological reviews, 211(1), 39-63.\n\n2. Tarlinton, D. M. (2006). B-cell memory: are subsets necessary?. Nature Reviews Immunology, 6(10), 785-790.\n\n3. Weller, S., Braun, M. C., Tan, B. K., Rosenwald, A., Cordier, C., Conley, M. E., ... & Klaus, G. G. (2004). Human blood IgM" memory" B cells are circulating splenic marginal zone B cells harboring a prediversified immunoglobulin repertoire. Blood, 104(12), 3647-3654.',
  "CL:0013000":
    "Forebrain radial glial cells are a type of glial cell that act as neural progenitor cells during embryonic development of the brain. They provide physical and chemical support for developing neurons and act as scaffolds for neuronal migration. After embryonic development, some forebrain radial glial cells persist in the adult brain and contribute to neurogenesis and gliogenesis. These cells also play a role in regulating the biochemical environment of the brain. Dysfunction of these cells has been linked to various neurological disorders such as schizophrenia and Alzheimer\u2019s disease. \n\nReference: \nKriegstein, A. R., & Alvarez-Buylla, A. (2009). The glial nature of embryonic and adult neural stem cells. Annu. Rev. Neurosci., 32, 149-184.",
  "CL:0000165":
    "Neuroendocrine cells are specialized cells found throughout the body that produce and secrete hormones. They can be found in organs such as the pancreas, thyroid, and adrenal gland, as well as in the gastrointestinal tract and respiratory system. These cells are able to respond to both neural and hormonal signals, allowing them to regulate a variety of physiological processes including metabolism, stress response, and reproductive function. Dysregulation of neuroendocrine cells is implicated in a number of diseases including diabetes, thyroid disorders, and certain types of cancer. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Kieffer, T. J., & Habener, J. F. (1999). The glucagon-like peptides. Endocrine Reviews, 20(6), 876-913.\n2. Orth, D. N. (2010). Endocrine cells: paraneurons. In Handbook of Neuroendocrinology (pp. 27-40). Academic Press.\n3. Fuchs, E., & Fatima, A. (2012). Role of neuroendocrine cells in cancer. Cancer Cell, 21(3), 257-265.",
  "CL:1000330":
    "Serous cells of the epithelium of trachea are secretory cells that produce a watery secretion containing various enzymes and proteins. They function to humidify and protect the airways, as well as facilitate the removal of foreign particles and pathogens. \n\nReference: \n\nWanner A, Salathe M, O'Riordan TG. Mucociliary clearance in the airways. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 1996 Nov;154(5):1868-1902. doi: 10.1164/ajrccm.154.5.8912750. PMID: 8912750.",
  "CL:0009009":
    "Paneth cells of the colon are specialized epithelial cells located at the base of intestinal crypts that secrete antimicrobial peptides and proteins to maintain gut homeostasis and prevent invasion by harmful pathogens. These cells have been shown to play a crucial role in regulating the composition of the intestinal microbiota and protecting the host against infection. Recent studies have also suggested that Paneth cells may contribute to the pathogenesis of inflammatory bowel disease. \n\nReference: \n1. Bevins CL, Salzman NH. Paneth cells, antimicrobial peptides and maintenance of intestinal homeostasis. Nat Rev Microbiol. 2011 Jan; 9(5):356-68.",
  "CL:0000388":
    "Tendon cells are a type of connective tissue cell that play a crucial role in the formation and maintenance of tendons. These cells synthesize and secrete extracellular matrix proteins, such as collagen and elastin, which provide structure and support to the tendon. Tendon cells are also involved in regulating the mechanical properties of the tendon tissue and can respond to mechanical load by changing their gene expression patterns. Dysfunction of tendon cells can lead to conditions such as tendinopathy and tendon rupture. References: Docheva et al., 2015; Sivan et al., 2013.",
  "CL:0000646":
    'Basal cells are a type of stem cell found in the basal layer of many epithelial tissues, including the skin, respiratory tract, and prostate gland. They serve as a reserve pool of cells that can differentiate into other cell types to maintain tissue homeostasis. In the skin, basal cells give rise to keratinocytes that form the protective epidermal barrier. In the airway epithelium, basal cells can differentiate into ciliated or secretory cells to replenish damaged or lost cells. In the prostate gland, basal cells serve as progenitor cells for secretory luminal cells. Basal cells have also been implicated in tumor initiation and progression. \n\nReferences:\n1. R. P. Lane et al., "Basal respiratory stem cells repair and regenerate lung tissue and promote lung cancer metastasis," Cell Stem Cell, vol. 21, pp. 887-902.e6, 2017.\n2. E. J. Goldstein et al. "Basal cells contribute to prostate cancer progression and therapy resistance," bioRxiv, 2021.',
  "CL:1001602":
    'Cerebral cortex endothelial cells are specialized endothelial cells that form the blood-brain barrier (BBB), a selectively permeable barrier that separates the central nervous system from the bloodstream. These cells express tight junction proteins such as claudin-5, occludin, and ZO-1, which regulate the movement of solutes and cells across the BBB. In addition to their barrier function, cerebral cortex endothelial cells also play a role in brain development, synaptic plasticity, and inflammation. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in a variety of neurodegenerative diseases. \n\nReferences:\n1. Abbott NJ. Dynamics of CNS barriers: evolution, differentiation, and modulation. Cell Mol Neurobiol. 2005;25(1):5-23.\n2. Wolburg H, Lippoldt A. Tight junctions of the blood-brain barrier: development, composition and regulation. Vascul Pharmacol. 2002;38(6):323-37. \n3. Bauer HC, Krizbai IA, Bauer H, Traweger A. "You Shall Not Pass" - Tight Junctions of the Blood Brain Barrier. Front Neurosci. 2014;8:392.',
  "CL:0002117":
    "IgG-negative class switched memory B cells are a subpopulation of memory B cells that lack expression of the IgG immunoglobulin isotype, but have undergone class switching to express other immunoglobulin isotypes. Functionally, they play a role in the production of antibodies during secondary immune responses, particularly in the early stages of a response, before IgG-positive memory B cells become activated. Research indicates that IgG-negative memory B cells play a protective role in the immunity against malaria.  \n\nReference: Weiss GE, et al. Atypical memory B cells are greatly expanded in individuals living in a malaria-endemic area. Journal of Immunology. 2009;183(3):2176-2182.",
  "CL:0000498":
    "Inhibitory interneurons are a type of neuron found in the central nervous system that inhibit the activity of other neurons. They play a crucial role in the regulation of neural activity and are involved in many important processes, including sensory processing, motor control, and learning and memory. Inhibitory interneurons produce inhibitory neurotransmitters, such as GABA or glycine, which bind to receptors on other neurons and inhibit their firing. Dysfunction of inhibitory interneurons has been implicated in a variety of neurological and psychiatric disorders, including epilepsy, schizophrenia, and autism spectrum disorders.\n\nReferences:\n1. Klausberger T, Somogyi P. Neuronal diversity and temporal dynamics: the unity of hippocampal circuit operations. Science. 2008;321(5885):53-57.\n2. Sohal VS, Zhang F, Yizhar O, Deisseroth K. Parvalbumin neurons and gamma rhythms enhance cortical circuit performance. Nature. 2009;459(7247):698-702.\n3. Lee S, Kim K. Inhibitory Interneurons in Health and Disease. Int Neurourol J. 2014;18(2):53-59.",
  "CL:0000557":
    "The granulocyte monocyte progenitor cell (GMP) is a multipotent hematopoietic stem cell that gives rise to both granulocytes and monocytes, which are key innate immune cells. GMPs are involved in the immune response to infections and are also important for tissue repair. Studies have shown that regulation of GMP proliferation and differentiation is critical for proper immune system function. Literature references: Manz MG et al. Blood. 2001, 98: 3343-51; Lardinois OM et al. Immunol Cell Biol. 2018, 96(6): 566-573.",
  "CL:2000046":
    "Ventricular cardiac muscle cells are responsible for generating the force required to pump blood out of the heart. These cells have a high density of mitochondria, which produce the energy required for their continuous contractions. Ventricular cardiac muscle cells are also important in maintaining the electrical conduction system of the heart, which is responsible for coordinating the heartbeat. Dysfunction of ventricular cardiac muscle cells can lead to heart failure. \n\nReferences: \n1. Nishimura S, Nagai H, Takenaka T, Terada H. Three-dimensional ultrastructure of cardiac muscle in the rat ventricle. J Electron Microsc (Tokyo). 2005;54(6):587-95. \n2. Bers DM. Cardiac excitation-contraction coupling. Nature. 2002;415(6868):198-205. \n3. Lakatta EG, Levy D. Arterial and cardiac aging: major shareholders in cardiovascular disease enterprises: Part II: the aging heart in health: links to heart disease. Circulation. 2003;107(2):346-54.",
  "CL:0000844":
    "Germinal center B cells are a subtype of B lymphocytes that undergo rapid proliferation and somatic hypermutation, resulting in the generation of high-affinity antibodies during an immune response. These cells are located in the germinal centers of secondary lymphoid organs, such as lymph nodes and spleen. The differentiation and maturation of germinal center B cells is tightly regulated by various molecular factors and signaling pathways. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Victora GD, Nussenzweig MC. Germinal centers. Annu Rev Immunol. 2012;30:429-57.\n2. Liu X, Ye L, Christianson J, et al. Germinal center B cells promote T follicular helper cell differentiation and act downstream of CD200R signaling. J Immunol. 2015;194(9):4470-9.\n3. Gitlin AD, Shulman Z, Nussenzweig MC. Clonal selection in the germinal centre by regulated proliferation and hypermutation. Nature. 2014;509(7498):637-40.",
  "CL:0000584":
    "Enterocytes are columnar epithelial cells that line the small intestine and play a crucial role in nutrient absorption. These cells have microvilli on their apical surface and are responsible for the absorption of nutrients such as carbohydrates, amino acids, and lipids. Enterocytes also secrete enzymes and absorb electrolytes and water. Dysregulation of enterocyte function can lead to malabsorption syndromes and other intestinal disorders. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Hodin RA. Enterocyte function. Annual review of physiology. 1991 Feb;53(1):231-41.",
  "CL:0000287":
    "Eye photoreceptor cells are specialized cells located in the retina of the eye that are responsible for detecting light and initiating the process of vision. These cells have a unique structure, including a stack of membranous discs containing the light-sensitive protein rhodopsin. There are two types of photoreceptor cells: rods and cones. Rods are more sensitive to light and are responsible for vision in dimly lit environments, while cones are responsible for color vision and visual acuity in brighter light. Dysfunction of photoreceptor cells can lead to vision impairment or blindness. Literature references: 1) Berson, E. L. (1991). Retinitis pigmentosa: unfolding its mystery. Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 88(11), 4553-4557. 2) Cuenca, N., Pinilla, I., Sauv\u00e9, Y., & Lund, R. D. (2014). Preservation of outer retina and its synaptic connectivity following subretinal injections of human RPE cells in the Royal College of Surgeons rat. Experimental eye research, 127, 174-184.",
  "CL:0000749":
    "ON-bipolar cells are a type of retinal neuron that receive direct input from photoreceptor cells and contribute to the processing of visual information. Specifically, these cells are responsible for responding to changes in light levels and transmitting signals to downstream retinal cells that ultimately lead to the perception of brightness. ON-bipolar cells have been extensively studied in the context of visual processing and are known to express a range of receptors and ion channels that influence their sensitivity to light. (1) \n\nReference: \n1. Morgans, C. W. (2001). Neurotransmitter receptor expression and function in the melanopsin\u2010expressing, intrinsically photosensitive ganglion cells of the primate retina. Journal of Comparative Neurology, 433(4), 506-516.",
  "CL:0009011":
    "Transit amplifying cells of the colon are rapidly dividing cells found in the crypts of Lieberk\u00fchn. These cells have a limited lifespan and differentiate into mature colonocytes, goblet cells, and enteroendocrine cells. They play a crucial role in the continuous renewal of the colonic epithelium. Dysregulation of transit amplifying cells has been implicated in the pathogenesis of colorectal cancer. \n\nReference: \n1. Potten C. S. (1998). Stem cells in gastrointestinal epithelium: numbers, characteristics and death. Philosophical transactions of the Royal Society of London. Series B, Biological sciences, 353(1370), 821\u2013830. doi:10.1098/rstb.1998.0246",
  "CL:0002585":
    "Retinal blood vessel endothelial cells are specialized cells that form the inner lining of blood vessels in the retina. They play a critical role in maintaining proper blood flow and oxygenation to the retina, which is essential for normal vision. These cells are also involved in the regulation of vascular permeability and angiogenesis. Dysfunction of retinal blood vessel endothelial cells can lead to various retinal vascular diseases, including diabetic retinopathy and age-related macular degeneration. \n\nReference: \n1. Campochiaro, P. A., Sophie, R., & Pearlman, J. (2015). The role of inflammation in diabetic retinopathy. Seminars in ophthalmology, 30(5-6), 435-438. \n2. Wang, J., Xu, X., Liang, Y., Tang, X., & Chen, Y. (2019). Endothelial dysfunction and age-related macular degeneration: challenging basic science, clinical screening, and therapeutic strategies. Mediators of inflammation, 2019.",
  "CL:0000019":
    "Sperm are the male reproductive cells that are responsible for fertilizing the female gamete. The production of sperm is a complex process known as spermatogenesis, which occurs in the testicles. Mature sperm have a distinctive shape, characterized by a head, midpiece, and tail, and are highly specialized for their function of delivering genetic material to the egg. Once ejaculated, sperm make their way through the female genital tract, where they encounter the egg and attempt to fertilize it. Successful fertilization results in the formation of a zygote, which will develop into an embryo. \n\nReferences: \n- Cooper, T. G. (Ed.). (2010). Anatomy, physiology and pathology of the male (including human sexuality). Springer. \n- Hildebrand, E., & Ebner, T. (2017). Anatomy, physiology, and detection of fertilization. Fertility and Sterility, 108(4), 623-630. \n- De Vries, K. J., & Skerget, S. (2019). Sperm structure, development, and function. Reference Module in Life Sciences.",
  "CL:0000132":
    "Corneal endothelial cells are a monolayer of polygonal cells located on the posterior surface of the cornea. They play a crucial role in maintaining corneal transparency and hydration by regulating fluid transport across the cornea. Specifically, corneal endothelial cells pump out excess fluid that enters the cornea via diffusion, thereby preventing corneal edema. Dysfunction or loss of corneal endothelial cells can lead to corneal swelling, clouding, and blindness. \n\nReferences:\n1. Joyce NC. Proliferative capacity of corneal endothelial cells. Exp Eye Res. 2012;95(1):16-23. \n2. Bonanno JA. Molecular mechanisms underlying the corneal endothelial pump. Exp Eye Res. 2012;95(1):2-7. \n3. Du Y, Roh DS, Funderburgh ML, et al. Adipose-derived stem cells differentiate to keratocytes in vitro. Mol Vis. 2010;16:2680-9.",
  "CL:0002326":
    "Luminal epithelial cells of mammary gland are specialized epithelial cells that line the ducts and lobules of the mammary gland. These cells secrete milk proteins and lipids, and are essential for lactation. They also express hormone receptors, allowing regulation of their function by systemic hormones. Luminal epithelial cells are heterogeneous, with subpopulations that differ in their gene expression and functional properties. Dysfunction of these cells is associated with breast cancer development. \n\nReference: Brisken, C., Ayyannan, A., Nguyen, C., Heineman, A., Reinhardt, F., Tan, J., ... & Dotto, G. P. (2002). IGF-2 is a mediator of prolactin-induced morphogenesis in the breast. Developmental cell, 3(6), 877-887.",
  "CL:0000816":
    "An immature B cell is a type of lymphocyte that has not yet completed its development in the bone marrow. These cells are characterized by the presence of surface IgM, and lack expression of surface IgD and CD23. During the course of differentiation, immature B cells undergo selection processes leading to the deletion of self-reactive clones and maturation into naive B cells. Immature B cells are important for the diversification of the B cell repertoire and the establishment of immune tolerance. Dysfunction of immature B cells has been implicated in the development of autoimmune diseases.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Murre C. Regulation and function of the preT cell receptor complex in early T cell development. Crit Rev Immunol. 1993;13(3-4):221-233.\n2. Goodnow CC. Multistep pathogenesis of autoimmune disease. Cell. 2007;130(1):25-35.\n3. Pelanda R, Torres RM. Central B-cell tolerance: where selection begins. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2012;4(9):a007146.",
  "CL:0000084":
    "T cells, also known as T lymphocytes, are a type of white blood cell involved in the adaptive immune response. They originate in the bone marrow and mature in the thymus. T cells recognize and bind to specific antigens presented by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) molecules on the surface of other cells. Once activated, T cells can differentiate into various functional subsets, including cytotoxic T cells, which kill infected or abnormal cells, and helper T cells, which secrete cytokines and coordinate the immune response. T cells play an important role in defense against viral infections, intracellular pathogens, and cancer. References: Li-Weber M. (2016) Targeting apoptosis pathways in cancer by Chinese medicine. Cancer Lett. 332:304-312.  Odoardi et al. (2012) T cells become licensed in the lung to enter the central nervous system. Nature 488:675-679.",
  "CL:0002129":
    "Regular atrial cardiac myocytes are cardiac muscle cells found in the atria of the heart. These cells have a striated appearance due to their myofilament arrangement and are responsible for coordinated contraction of the atria during systole, aiding in the filling of the ventricles. \n\nReference:\nvan der Meer, D. L., Marques, I. J., Leito, J. T. D., Besser, J., Lamers, W. H., & Spaink, H. P. (2019). Comprehensive RNAseq profiling of zebrafish atrial and ventricular myocardial tissue provides new insights into the molecular basis for cardiac chamber differentiation. BMC genomics, 20(1), 1-18.",
  "CL:1000892":
    "Kidney capillary endothelial cells are specialized cells that line the walls of the small blood vessels (capillaries) within the kidney. These cells play a crucial role in the filtration of blood and transport of nutrients, waste products, and hormones between the bloodstream and the surrounding kidney tissues. They also maintain the integrity of the capillary walls and regulate blood flow through the kidneys. Dysfunction of kidney capillary endothelial cells can lead to various renal disorders. This cell type expresses specific markers such as CD31, CD34, and von Willebrand factor.\n\nReference: \n\n1. Eremina V, Sood M, Haigh J, Nagy A, Lajoie G, Ferrara N, Gerber HP, Kikkawa Y, Miner JH, Quaggin SE. Glomerular-specific alterations of VEGF-A expression lead to distinct congenital and acquired renal diseases. J Clin Invest. 2003;111(5):707-716. \n2. Rafi M, Pippin J, Drebin J, Yuan H, Sims S, He Y, Shankland S. Altered angiopoietin-1 and Tie2 expression in minimal change disease and focal segmental glomerulosclerosis. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 2011;301(3):F546-F556. \n3. Tanaka T, Nangaku M. The role of hypoxia, increased oxygen consumption, and hypoxia-inducible factor-1 alpha in progression of chronic kidney disease. Curr Opin Nephrol Hypertens. 2010;19(1):43-50.",
  "CL:0000624":
    "CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells, commonly known as helper T cells, are a subtype of T lymphocytes that express the CD4 receptor on their surface and recognize peptides presented in the context of MHC class II molecules. Helper T cells play a pivotal role in orchestrating the immune response by secreting cytokines that activate and differentiate other immune cells, such as B cells, macrophages, and cytotoxic T cells. They are also involved in the regulation of immune tolerance and autoimmunity. Furthermore, they exhibit considerable plasticity and can differentiate into diverse subtypes, including Th1, Th2, Th17, and T follicular helper cells, depending on the cytokine milieu and antigenic environment. Dysfunction of CD4-positive, alpha-beta T cells is associated with various immunological disorders, including infections, cancers, allergies, and autoimmune diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. O'Shea JJ, Paul WE. Mechanisms underlying lineage commitment and plasticity of helper CD4+ T cells. Science. 2010;327(5969):1098-1102.\n2. Zhu J, Yamane H, Paul WE. Differentiation of effector CD4 T cell populations. Annu Rev Immunol. 2010;28:445-489.\n3. Sakaguchi S, Wing K, Yamaguchi T. Dynamics of peripheral tolerance and immune regulation mediated by Treg. Eur J Immunol. 2009;39(9):2331-2336.\n4. Romagnani S. Th1/Th2 cells. Inflamm Bowel Dis. 1999;5(4):285-294.",
  "CL:0000209":
    "Taste receptor cells, also known as gustatory cells, are specialized chemosensory cells located in the taste buds of the tongue, palate, and throat. They detect different tastes such as sweet, sour, salty, bitter, and umami by using receptors on their apical membranes that bind to various molecules. Upon stimulation, taste receptor cells generate action potentials that are transmitted to sensory nerve fibers and subsequently to the brain for interpretation of taste perception. Furthermore, taste receptor cells play a role in saliva secretion and nutrient absorption. Dysregulation or damage of taste receptor cells can result in taste disorders such as ageusia and hypogeusia. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Chandrashekar J, Kuhn C, Oka Y, et al. The cells and peripheral representation of taste. Nature. 2006 Nov 23;444(7117):288-94.\n\n2. Roper SD. Signal transduction and information processing in mammalian taste buds. Pflugers Arch. 2007 Aug;454(5):759-76.\n\n3. Huang AL, Chen X, Hoon MA, et al. The cells and logic for mammalian sour taste detection. Nature. 2006 Nov 9;442(7105):934-8.",
  "CL:0002393":
    "Intermediate monocytes are a type of monocyte characterized by their intermediate size and expression of CD14 and CD16 surface markers. They are involved in immune surveillance and inflammation, with a versatile role in tissue repair and regeneration. Intermediate monocytes have been implicated in several pathophysiological conditions, including atherosclerosis, infections, and cancer. Furthermore, these cells are known to secrete cytokines and chemokines, contributing to the regulation of immune responses, and their recruitment to injured or infected tissues has been reported as an important early event in the inflammatory response. \n\nReference: Zawada AM et al. Monocytes in human cancer. Immunobiology. 2013;218(2):242-50. doi: 10.1016/j.imbio.2012.06.007. Epub 2012 Jun 29. PMID: 22809617.",
  "CL:1000278":
    "Smooth muscle fibers of ileum are specialized cells found in the muscular layer of the ileum, a part of the small intestine. These cells are responsible for the coordinated and rhythmic contractions of the ileum, which are critical for the proper digestion and absorption of nutrients in the small intestine. The smooth muscle fibers of ileum are unique from other smooth muscle cells in the gut due to their distinct ultrastructure, gene expression, and response to neurotransmitters. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to motility disorders such as ileus and irritable bowel syndrome. Literature references: 1. Neshatian L, Gibbons SJ, Farrugia G. Macrophages in intestinal smooth muscle. Cell Tissue Res. 2018 Oct;374(1):97-104. doi: 10.1007/s00441-018-2867-7. Epub 2018 Mar 19. PMID: 29556650. 2. Sanders KM. Smooth muscle physiology and pathophysiology. Compr Physiol. 2011 Jan;1(1):97-127. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c090007. PMID: 23733628.",
  "CL:0000738":
    "Leukocytes, also known as white blood cells, are immune cells that defend the body against infections and foreign substances. There are several types of leukocytes including lymphocytes, monocytes, neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils, each with their own distinct functions. Lymphocytes are responsible for recognizing and attacking specific pathogens and abnormal cells, while monocytes differentiate into macrophages that engulf and digest foreign substances and debris. Neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils are involved in the inflammatory response and killing of microorganisms. Overall, leukocytes play a crucial role in maintaining the body's immune system and protecting against disease.\n\nReferences:\n1. Abbas AK, Lichtman AH, Pillai S. Cellular and Molecular Immunology. 5th edition. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2019.\n2. Murphy K, Weaver C. Janeway's Immunobiology. 9th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2016.",
  "CL:0000987":
    "IgA plasma cells are a type of antibody-secreting cell that produces immunoglobulin A (IgA) antibody. IgA plays a crucial role in mucosal immunity by preventing infections at mucosal membranes such as the respiratory and digestive tracts. IgA plasma cells are mainly found in mucosal-associated lymphoid tissues such as the tonsils, Peyer's patches, and lamina propria of the intestines. IgA plasma cells are important for maintaining homeostasis at mucosal surfaces and preventing the invasion of pathogens. \n\nReferences:\n1. Moulds JM, van Zanten JA. Immunoglobulin A: strategic defense initiative at the mucosal surface. Annu Rev Immunol. 1989;7:625-55. doi: 10.1146/annurev.iy.07.040189.003205. PMID: 2540661.\n2. Brandtzaeg P. Secretory IgA: designed for anti-microbial defense. Front Immunol. 2013 Sep 9;4:222. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2013.00222. PMID: 24062793; PMCID: PMC3766031.",
  "CL:0000815":
    "Regulatory T cells (Tregs) are a type of T cell that plays a crucial role in maintaining immune homeostasis and preventing autoimmune diseases. They are characterized by the expression of the transcription factor Foxp3 and the cell surface markers CD4 and CD25. Tregs function by suppressing the activation and proliferation of other immune cells, mainly effector T cells, through cell-to-cell contact and the secretion of anti-inflammatory cytokines. Dysfunctional Tregs have been implicated in the development of various autoimmune and inflammatory diseases, while excessive Treg activity may contribute to immune impairment and cancer progression. Recent studies have also highlighted the plasticity of Tregs, revealing the existence of different subtypes with distinct functions and differentiation pathways. \n\nReferences:\n\n- Sakaguchi, S., Miyara, M., Costantino, C. M., & Hafler, D. A. (2010). FOXP3+ regulatory T cells in the human immune system. Nature Reviews Immunology, 10(7), 490-500.\n- Josefowicz, S. Z., Lu, L. F., & Rudensky, A. Y. (2012). Regulatory T cells: mechanisms of differentiation and function. Annual Review of Immunology, 30, 531-564.\n- Shevach, E. M. (2018). Foxp3+ T regulatory cells: still many unanswered questions-a perspective after 20 years of study. Frontiers in Immunology, 9, 1048.",
  "CL:0002543":
    "Vein endothelial cells are flat, elongated cells that form the inner lining of veins. These cells play a crucial role in blood circulation by regulating the transport of fluids, nutrients, and waste products between the bloodstream and the surrounding tissues. Vein endothelial cells also participate in the regulation of blood pressure and coagulation. Dysregulation of vein endothelial cell function has been implicated in several vascular disorders, including vein thrombosis and chronic venous insufficiency. Literature references: 1. Aird WC. Endothelial cells and the lungs: complexity in simplicity. Am J Respir Cell Mol Biol. 2015;53(3):323-5. 2. Boulanger CM, et al. Circulating microparticles from patients with myocardial infarction cause endothelial dysfunction. Circulation. 2001;104(22):2649-52. 3. Dimitrova-Shumkovska J, et al. Endothelial cells: source, differentiation, and therapeutic potential in human induced pluripotent stem cell-derived blood-brain barrier models. Stem Cells Int. 2021;2021:5518508.",
  "CL:0002225":
    "Secondary lens fibers are elongated cells that are present in the outer layer of the lens of the eye. They are derived from primary lens fibers and cover the embryonic nucleus of the lens. Secondary lens fibers do not have nuclei or other organelles and are filled with crystallins, proteins that are responsible for the optical properties of the lens. The main function of secondary lens fibers is to maintain the transparency of the lens and to contribute to its refractive power. Any damage or alteration to these fibers can lead to the formation of cataracts and other lens disorders.\n\nReferences:\n1. Andley UP. Crystallins in the eye: Function and pathology. Prog Retin Eye Res. 2007 Jul;26(4):78-98. doi: 10.1016/j.preteyeres.2006.12.001. Epub 2007 Mar 1. PMID: 17336029.\n2. Knappe S, Kabza M, Burek M, Lamparter J, Struckhoff G, Pannicke T, Ueberham U, Reichstein D, Reichenbach A, Knappe-Guenther M. Morphological and molecular changes in the lens epithelium of \u03b1A- and \u03b1B-crystallin double-knockout mice. Mol Vis. 2019 Oct 15;25:671-693. PMID: 31686755;\n3. Farnsworth PN, Shui YB, Worgul BV. Protein changes in lens fiber cell membranes associated with cataract formation. Arch Biochem Biophys. 2019 Sep 15;672:108073. doi: 10.1016/j.abb.2019.108073. Epub 2019 Jul 8. PMID: 31295534.",
  "CL:0019029":
    'Centrilobular hepatocytes are liver cells located in the central region of hepatic lobules. They are responsible for metabolic functions such as detoxification, synthesis of bile acids, and gluconeogenesis. These cells also play a key role in drug metabolism and are susceptible to injury due to their location at the intersection of the hepatic artery, portal vein and bile duct. Dysfunction of the centrilobular hepatocytes can lead to liver disease and other metabolic disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Yang Y, Liu C, Peng Q, Zhao G. "Changes in the distribution of hepatocytes and local haemodynamics associated with centrilobular necrosis induced by carbon tetrachloride." Exp Ther Med. 2017 Jul;14(1):267-274. doi: 10.3892/etm.2017.4545. Epub 2017 May 16. PMID: 28672930; PMCID: PMC5489633.\n2. Klein C, Grzych G, Kulaga A, Malecka-Panas E, Kaminski G, Gmi\u0144ski J. "Heterogeneous nuclear ribonucleoprotein A2/B1 upregulation correlates with sustained NF\u03baB activation in the centrilobular glutathione-depleted areas of human and mouse livers." Arch Immunol Ther Exp (Warsz). 2017 Aug;65(4):327-340. doi: 10.1007/s00005-016-0443-4. Epub 2017 Jan 21. PMID: 28110363.',
  "CL:0000957":
    "A large pre-B-II cell is a type of precursor B cell that is characterized by its large size and high levels of CD25 expression. These cells are derived from the bone marrow and undergo further maturation into smaller pre-B-II cells before eventually developing into mature B cells. The primary function of large pre-B-II cells is to undergo rearrangement of immunoglobulin genes, a process that allows these cells to develop into mature B cells capable of producing antibodies. \n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Clark, M. R., Mandal, M., Ochiai, K., & Singh, H. (2014). Orchestrating B cell lymphopoiesis through interplay of IL-7 receptor and pre-B cell receptor signalling. Nature Reviews Immunology, 14(2), 69-80. \n2. Hardy, R. R., Hayakawa, K., & Zhu, D. (1997). B-cell development pathways. Annual review of immunology, 15(1), 47-64. \n3. Melchers, F. (1998). Checkpoints that control B cell development. J Clin Invest, 102(7), 1227-1229.",
  "CL:0000050":
    "Megakaryocyte-erythroid progenitor cells, or MEP cells, are a type of multipotent hematopoietic stem cell that gives rise to both megakaryocytes and erythrocytes, two types of blood cells. Megakaryocytes produce platelets, which are important for blood clotting, while erythrocytes contain hemoglobin and transport oxygen throughout the body. The differentiation of MEP cells into megakaryocytes or erythrocytes is regulated by a variety of transcription factors and signaling pathways. Understanding the development and regulation of MEP cells is important for studying blood cell disorders such as thrombocytopenia and anemia. \n\nReference: \nNotta, F., Zandi, S., Takayama, N., Dobson, S., Gan, O. I., Wilson, G., ... & Ben David, Y. (2016). Distinct routes of lineage development reshape the human blood hierarchy across ontogeny. Science, 351(6269), aab2116.",
  "CL:0011012":
    "Neural crest cells are a highly migratory and multipotent population of cells unique to vertebrate embryos that originate in the dorsal region of the neural tube. They give rise to diverse cell types including neurons, glia, melanocytes, smooth muscle cells, and cartilage and bone. Neural crest cells play critical roles in patterning and morphogenesis during development and contribute to the formation of many different tissues and organs, including the peripheral nervous system, craniofacial structures, and the cardiovascular system. Dysregulation of neural crest cell development can lead to a variety of birth defects and diseases. \n\nReferences:\n1. Le Douarin, N. M., & Kalcheim, C. (1999). The Neural Crest. Cambridge University Press.\n2. Bronner-Fraser, M., & Le Douarin, N. M. (2012). Development and evolution of the neural crest: an overview. Developmental Biology, 366(1), 2-9. \n3. Sauka-Spengler, T., & Bronner-Fraser, M. (2008). Development and evolution of the migratory neural crest: a gene regulatory perspective. Current Opinion in Genetics & Development, 18(4), 418-424.",
  "CL:0002539":
    "Aortic smooth muscle cells are specialized cells found in the tunica media layer of the aorta, an important blood vessel. These cells have a number of important functions including regulating vascular tone, maintaining vascular integrity, and contributing to vascular remodeling. Smooth muscle cells in the aortic wall also play a crucial role in the pathogenesis of several vascular diseases such as atherosclerosis, hypertension, and abdominal aortic aneurysms. The functional plasticity and heterogeneity of aortic smooth muscle cells is the subject of ongoing research aimed at improving our understanding of vascular biology and developing novel therapeutic strategies. \n\nReference: Owens GK, Kumar MS, Wamhoff BR. Molecular regulation of vascular smooth muscle cell differentiation in development and disease. Physiol Rev. 2004;84(3):767-801. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00041.2003.",
  "CL:0000785":
    "A mature B cell is a type of white blood cell that plays a critical role in the adaptive immune response by producing antibodies against foreign antigens. These cells originate in the bone marrow and undergo maturation in the spleen and lymph nodes. Mature B cells are characterized by their expression of specific surface markers and the presence of a rearranged immunoglobulin gene. Upon encountering a foreign antigen, a mature B cell undergoes activation and differentiation into antibody-secreting plasma cells or memory B cells. This process is critical for the clearance and long-term immunity to pathogens. \n\nReferences:\n1. Murphy, K., & Weaver, C. (2016). Janeway's Immunobiology (9th ed.). Garland Science.\n2. Abbas, A. K., Lichtman, A. H., & Pillai, S. (2018). Cellular and molecular immunology (9th ed.). Elsevier.",
  "CL:0000826":
    "Pro-B cells are the earliest stage of B lymphocytes in development and are characterized by their high surface expression of CD43 and rearrangement of the immunoglobulin heavy-chain gene. During differentiation, pro-B cells undergo V(D)J recombination, leading to the expression of a functional immunoglobulin heavy-chain gene that can associate with a surrogate light chain forming the pre-BCR. The pre-BCR serves as a checkpoint to ensure proper diversification of the immunoglobulin repertoire and proper signaling for differentiation into immature B cells. Pro-B cells are essential in the development of adaptive immunity and the production of mature B cells. \n\nReferences: \n1. Hardy RR, Hayakawa K, Parks DR, Herzenberg LA. B-cell commitment, selection, and development. Immunol Rev. 1989; 110: 75-102. \n2. Tussiwand R, Bosco N, Ceredig R, Rolink AG. Tolerance checkpoints in B-cell development: Johnny B good. Eur J Immunol. 2009; 39(8): 2317-24.",
  "CL:0002306":
    "Epithelial cells of the proximal tubule are a type of polarized and highly differentiated cells that constitute the majority of the renal tubular epithelium. The primary function of these cells is to reabsorb ions, nutrients, and small molecules from the glomerular filtrate into the bloodstream, as well as excrete waste products. These cells express a variety of transporters, ion channels, and enzymes involved in the reabsorptive process. Additionally, they play a crucial role in the maintenance of acid-base balance, as well as in secretion and metabolism of hormones and xenobiotics. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various kidney disorders, such as acute kidney injury and chronic kidney disease.\n\nReferences:\n1. Vallon V, Thomson SC. Targeting renal proximal tubule transport to treat hyperglycaemia in diabetes. Nat Rev Nephrol. 2020 Jul;16(7):442-458. doi: 10.1038/s41581-020-0209-z. Epub 2020 May 14. PMID: 32409703.\n2. Liamis G, Elisaf M. Physiology and pathophysiology of the renal proximal tubule. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences. 2016 May; 1368(1):97-107. doi: 10.1111/nyas.13011. Epub 2016 Jan 19. PMID: 26783713.",
  "CL:0005012":
    "Multi-ciliated epithelial cells are specialized cells that contain numerous motile cilia projecting from their apical surface. These cells play an important role in moving fluid or materials across a surface within the body, such as in the respiratory tract or reproductive system. The coordinated beating of the motile cilia generates directional fluid flow and facilitates the removal of mucus, debris, and pathogens. Multi-ciliated epithelial cells also have additional functions in signal transduction, sensory reception, and tissue development. Dysfunction of multi-ciliated epithelial cells can lead to diseases such as primary ciliary dyskinesia (PCD) and infertility. \n\nReferences:\n- Schmidts M, et al. Current perspectives on primary ciliary dyskinesia: a report from the scientific conference on primary ciliary dyskinesia. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2020;201(8):e71-e78. PMID: 32105022\n- Spassky N, Meunier A. The development and functions of multiciliated epithelia. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2017;18(7):423-436. PMID: 28529326",
  "CL:0002187":
    "The basal cell of epidermis is a flattened, polygonal-shaped cell located at the bottom layer of the epidermis, which is the outermost layer of the skin. These cells are responsible for the constant renewal and regeneration of the epidermis, primarily through their ability to give rise to keratinocytes, the most abundant cells in the epidermis. Additionally, basal cells play a crucial role in maintaining the structural integrity of the epidermis and in facilitating the migration of keratinocytes during wound healing. Abnormalities in basal cells have been linked to several skin disorders, including basal cell carcinoma. \n\nReferences:\n1. Hsu YC, Pasolli HA, Fuchs E. Dynamics between stem cells, niche, and progeny in the hair follicle. Cell. 2011 Sep 30;144(1):92-105. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2010.11.049. PMID: 21215368; PMCID: PMC3049278.\n2. Malanchi I, Peinado H, Kassen D, Hussenet T, Metzger D, Chambon P, Huber M, Hohl D, Cano A, Birchmeier W, Huelsken J. Cutaneous cancer stem cell maintenance is dependent on beta-catenin signalling. Nature. 2008 Apr 17;452(7187):650-3. doi: 10.1038/nature06835. Epub 2008 Mar 5. PMID: 18311132; PMCID: PMC3713386.",
  "CL:0000123":
    "Neuron associated cells refer to all types of non-neuronal cells present in the nervous system that closely interact with neurons, and play important roles in maintaining proper neuronal function by providing structural and metabolic support, as well as influencing signaling pathways. Neuron associated cells include glial cells (astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and microglia), ependymal cells, and choroid plexus cells. These cells help regulate ion and neurotransmitter concentrations, provide physical support to neurons, maintain the structural integrity of the nervous system, and modulate the immune response and repair mechanisms. Dysfunction of neuron-associated cells has been implicated in various neurological and neurodegenerative disorders such as multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease, and Parkinson's disease. Literature: Hol, E. M., & Pekny, M. (2015). Glial cell responses in neurological diseases: pathophysiology and therapeutic interventions. Annu Rev Neurosci, 38, 377-397. doi: 10.1146/annurev-neuro-071714-033821.",
  "CL:1001432":
    "Kidney collecting duct intercalated cells are specialized cells found in the distal convoluted tubule and collecting duct of the kidney. These cells play a crucial role in regulating the acid-base balance of the body by controlling the secretion and reabsorption of hydrogen and bicarbonate ions. Intercalated cells are divided into two subtypes: type A and type B. Type A cells secrete hydrogen ions and reabsorb bicarbonate ions, while type B cells do the opposite. Dysfunction of intercalated cells can lead to acid-base disorders such as metabolic acidosis or alkalosis. References: \n\n1. Wagner CA, Finberg KE, Breton S, Marshansky V, Brown D, Geibel JP. Renal vacuolar H+-ATPase. Physiological Reviews. 2004 Jan;84(1):126-64.\n2. Anastasio P. Renal acid-base physiology. Advances in Physiology Education. 2006 Dec;30(4):203-11.",
  "CL:0009012":
    "Transit amplifying cells of the small intestine are a rapidly dividing population of cells that differentiate into absorptive enterocytes, secretory cells, and enteroendocrine cells. These cells play a critical role in the regeneration of the epithelial lining of the small intestine, which is constantly being replaced every few days. Transit amplifying cells are characterized by their limited self-renewal capacity, as they have a finite number of cell divisions before becoming terminally differentiated. Dysregulation of transit amplifying cells can lead to intestinal diseases and malignancies. (Ref: Powell, DW. Barrier Function of Epithelia. Am J Physiol, Gastrointest Liver Physiol. 2000 July 1; 279(1): G1\u2013G9.)",
  "CL:0002632":
    "Epithelial cells of the lower respiratory tract are specialized cells that line the conducting airways of the lungs. These cells are responsible for a variety of functions, including the production of mucus, the regulation of water and ion transport, and the maintenance of a physical barrier against inhaled pathogens. In addition, epithelial cells of the lower respiratory tract play a critical role in the initiation and resolution of inflammatory responses in the lungs. Dysregulation of these cells can lead to chronic lung diseases such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Fulcher ML, Randell SH. Human Nasal and Tracheo-Bronchial Respiratory Epithelial Cell Culture. Methods Mol Biol. 2013;945:109-21.\n\n2. Crystal RG. Airway epithelial cells: current concepts and challenges. Proc Am Thorac Soc. 2008 May 1;5(4):772-7. \n\n3. Hiemstra PS, Grootaers G, van der Does AM, Krul CAM, Kooter IM. Human lung epithelial cell cultures for analysis of inhaled toxicants: lessons learned and future directions. Toxicol In Vitro. 2018 Jun;49:235-246.",
  "CL:1000497":
    "Kidney cells, also known as renal cells, are specialized cells found in the kidney. As the functional unit of the kidney, they play a crucial role in filtration, reabsorption, and secretion of various substances in the blood, as well as the regulation of fluid and electrolyte balance, acid-base balance, and blood pressure. There are several types of kidney cells, including proximal tubule cells, distal tubule cells, collecting duct cells, and glomerular podocytes, each with their own specific functions and morphologies. Dysfunction or damage to kidney cells can lead to various renal disorders, including glomerulonephritis, nephrotic syndrome, tubulointerstitial nephritis, and acute kidney injury. \n\nReferences: \n1. Suleiman H, Zhang L, Roth R, Heuser JE, Miner JH, Shaw AS, Dani A. Nanoscale protein architecture of the kidney glomerular basement membrane. Elife. 2013 Nov 19;2:e01149. doi: 10.7554/eLife.01149. PubMed PMID: 24252866; PubMed Central PMCID: PMC3836262.\n2. Kleta R, Bockenhauer D. Bartter syndromes and other salt-losing tubulopathies. N Engl J Med. 2004 Nov 18; 351(21):2179-88. Review. PubMed PMID: 15548780.",
  "CL:0000235":
    "Macrophages are specialized phagocytic cells that function in the immune system to recognize, engulf, and destroy invading microorganisms, foreign particles, and damaged host cells. They play an important role in both innate and adaptive immunity, and are involved in processes such as antigen presentation, cytokine secretion, and tissue repair. Macrophages are widely distributed throughout the body, and can differentiate into specialized subsets with distinct functions in different tissues. Literature references include Martinez and Gordon, 2014 and Gautier et al., 2012.",
  "CL:1000436":
    "An epithelial cell of lacrimal sac is a type of cuboidal or columnar epithelial cell found lining the lacrimal sac, which functions to produce and maintain the composition of the tears by secreting watery component, thus playing an important role in the tear drainage system. These cells are actively involved in maintaining the surface tension, osmolarity, and pH of the tear film. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to dry eye syndrome (DES), which is a common ocular surface disease. \n\nReference: \n1. Dartt DA. Regulation of tear secretion. Adv Exp Med Biol. 1994;350:1-9. PMID: 8030369.\n2. Willcox MD, Arg\u00fceso P, Georgiev GA, et al. TFOS DEWS II tear film report. Ocul Surf. 2017 Jul;15(3):366-403. doi: 10.1016/j.jtos.2017.05.006. Epub 2017 May 19. PMID: 28532779.",
  "CL:0002350":
    "Endocardial cells are specialized endothelial cells that form the innermost lining of the heart, including the valves and vessels. They regulate blood flow, promote angiogenesis, and provide a barrier for substances entering or leaving the heart. Endocardial cells also play a critical role in heart development and regeneration. Dysfunction of endocardial cells has been implicated in various cardiovascular diseases, such as heart failure, valve disease, and endocarditis. Literature reference: Dempsie, E., & O'Kane, P. (2015). Endocardial cells and myocardial development. In Endothelial Cells in Health and Disease (pp. 67-86). Springer, Cham.",
  "CL:0000764":
    'An erythroid lineage cell is a type of cell that gives rise to erythrocytes, also known as red blood cells. These cells are responsible for carrying oxygen to the body\'s tissues and removing carbon dioxide. Erythroid lineage cells go through a series of changes as they differentiate from hematopoietic stem cells, eventually losing their nucleus and other organelles to become mature erythrocytes. Disorders of erythroid lineage cells can lead to anemia and other blood disorders. \n\nLiterature references: \n\n- Wojda U, Noel P, and H\u00e4mmerling GJ. "Erythropoiesis: from molecular pathways to system properties." Eur J Cell Biol. 2011 Jul;90(7):507-22. doi: 10.1016/j.ejcb.2011.01.004. Epub 2011 Feb 17. PMID: 21330170.\n- Kalfa TA. "Pushing the Limits of Erythroid Differentiation: The Road to Erythrocyte Transfusion." Adv Exp Med Biol. 2016;880:51-72. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-22539-5_4. PMID: 26427490.',
  "CL:0019028":
    "Midzonal region hepatocytes are a subpopulation of liver cells that are located in the transitional zone between the periportal and perivenous regions. These hepatocytes have specialized metabolic functions including the detoxification of xenobiotics and the production of bile. Midzonal region hepatocytes are important for maintaining liver homeostasis and their dysfunction has been linked to various liver diseases, such as non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD). Literature Reference: Kietzmann, T. (2017). Metabolic zonation of the liver: The oxygen gradient revisited. Redox biology, 11, 622-630.",
  "CL:0002250":
    "Intestinal crypt stem cells are located within the intestinal crypts and are responsible for continuous regeneration of the intestinal epithelium. These cells have the ability to self-renew and differentiate into all the cell types that line the intestinal epithelium. Intestinal crypt stem cells play a vital role in maintaining the homeostasis of the intestinal epithelium by replacing damaged and dead cells. Dysregulation of intestinal crypt stem cells has been linked to various intestinal diseases, including inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer. \n\nReference: \nBarker N, et al. Identification of stem cells in small intestine and colon by marker gene Lgr5. Nature. 2007;449(7165):1003-1007.",
  "CL:0000540":
    "Neurons are specialized cells that transmit electrical and chemical signals in the nervous system. They receive input from other neurons or sensory receptor cells, integrate this information, and generate output in the form of action potentials that travel along their axons to communicate with other neurons or effector cells such as muscles or glands. Neurons vary in their morphology, function, and neurotransmitter phenotype, enabling them to form complex networks and perform diverse roles in neural circuits underlying behavior, perception, cognition, and homeostasis. Dysfunction or damage to neurons can lead to neurological disorders such as Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, epilepsy, or stroke. \n\nReferences:\n1. Purves D, Augustine GJ, Fitzpatrick D, et al., editors. Neuroscience. 5th edition. Sunderland (MA): Sinauer Associates; 2012. Chapter 4, Neural activity and the spread of signals.\n2. Sanes JR, Reh TA, Harris WA, editors. Development of the Nervous System. 3rd edition. Amsterdam: Elsevier; 2012. Chapter 11, Cell Biology of Synapse Formation and Function. \n3. Kandel ER, Schwartz JH, Jessell TM, et al., editors. Principles of Neural Science. 5th edition. New York (NY): McGraw-Hill Education; 2013. Part II, Cellular and Molecular Biology of Neurons.",
  "CL:0019031":
    "Intestine goblet cells are specialized epithelial cells that produce and secrete mucus to protect and lubricate the intestinal lining. Mucins are the main component of the mucus produced by goblet cells. The mucus layer provides a protective barrier against potential pathogens, toxins, and abrasive food particles, preventing damage to the epithelium. Goblet cells are also involved in maintaining the gut microbiota by secreting antimicrobial peptides and other factors that modulate the composition of the microbial community. Dysfunction of goblet cells has been associated with a number of diseases, including inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer. Literature references: Johansson, M. E. V., & Hansson, G. C. (2012). Microbiology and Molecular Biology Reviews, 76(4), 391-411. doi: 10.1128/MMBR.00052-11. Vaishnava, S., Behrendt, C. L., & Hooper, L. V. (2008). Cell Host and Microbe, 3(3), 137-146. doi: 10.1016/j.chom.2008.02.002.",
  "CL:1000334":
    "Enterocytes are specialized absorptive cells that line the lumen of the small intestine. They are responsible for the bulk of nutrient absorption, including carbohydrates, lipids, and amino acids. In addition to nutrient uptake, enterocytes also secrete fluids and electrolytes, and play a key role in the maintenance of gut barrier function. These cells have a highly organized cytoskeleton and a brush border of microvilli that greatly increase their surface area for absorption. enterocytes are maintained by the intestinal stem cell niche and undergo constant renewal and differentiation to maintain intestinal homeostasis. Dysfunction of enterocytes can lead to malabsorption and intestinal diseases.\nReferences: \n\n1. Ciacci C, Lind SE, Podolsky DK. Transforming growth factor beta regulation of migration in wounded rat intestinal epithelial monolayers. Gastroenterology. 1993 Aug;105(2):93-101. doi: 10.1016/0016-5085(93)90188-w. PMID: 7683694.\n\n2. Mahe MM, Sundaram N, Watson CL, Shroyer NF, Helmrath MA. Establishment of human epithelial enteroids and colonoids from whole tissue and biopsy. J Vis Exp. 2015 Mar 23;(97):e52483. doi: 10.3791/52483. PMID: 25867837; PMCID: PMC4382527.\n\n3. Sato T, Clevers H. Growing self-organizing mini-guts from a single intestinal stem cell: mechanism and applications. Science. 2013 May 3;340(6132):1190-4. doi: 10.1126/science.1234852. PMID: 23604380.",
  "CL:0002207":
    'Brush cells of the trachea are rare, specialized columnar epithelial cells characterized by the presence of microvilli on their apical cell surface. They have sensory roles in detection of irritants and noxious stimuli and secrete a number of potential mediators involved in homeostatic control of the airway epithelium. Brush cells have been implicated as progenitor cells for development of pulmonary neuroendocrine cells and goblet cells. (Saunders, C. J., et al. (2019). "Brush cells of the trachea: a common cell type in the mammalian respiratory tract."\u00a0Thorax\u00a074(3): 240-243.)',
  "CL:0000939":
    "CD16-positive, CD56-dim natural killer (NK) cells are a subtype of human NK cells that are characterized by the high expression of CD16 and low expression of CD56. They possess potent cytotoxicity against tumor cells, virus-infected cells, and antibody-coated cells, and also secrete cytokines to enhance the immune response. CD16-positive, CD56-dim NK cells play a critical role in innate immunity and the control of infections, and have been implicated in various diseases, including cancer, infectious diseases, and autoimmune disorders.\n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Caligiuri MA. Human natural killer cells. Blood. 2008;112(3):461-469. doi:10.1182/blood-2007-09-077438\n2. Gonzalez VD, Falconer K, Bj\u00f6rkstr\u00f6m NK, et al. Expansion of functionally skewed CD56-negative NK cells in chronic hepatitis C virus infection: correlation with outcome of pegylated IFN-\u03b1 and ribavirin therapy. J Immunol. 2009;183(10):6612-6618. doi:10.4049/jimmunol.0901746\n3. Muntasell A, Ochoa MC, Cordeiro L, et al. Targeting NK-cell checkpoints for cancer immunotherapy. Curr Opin Immunol. 2017;45:73-81. doi:10.1016/j.coi.2017.01.003.",
  "CL:0000900":
    "Naive thymus-derived CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a type of T lymphocyte that arise from the thymus gland with the potential to differentiate into cytotoxic T cells capable of recognizing and eliminating infected or cancerous cells. These cells are also involved in immune surveillance, playing a critical role in identifying and destroying foreign pathogens. Naive T cells express T-cell receptors (TCRs) composed of alpha and beta chains and are distinguished by the presence of the CD8 surface protein, which facilitates interaction with class I major histocompatibility complex (MHC-I) molecules. Upon exposure to a specific antigen, naive T cells undergo clonal expansion and differentiation into effector T cells. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Harty, J. T., Badovinac, V. P., & Shiver, J. W. (2008). Structural basis for CD8+ T-cell memory formation. Immunology and Cell Biology, 86(7), 574-581. https://doi.org/10.1038/icb.2008.53\n2. Jameson, S. C., & Masopust, D. (2018). Understanding Subset Diversity in T Cell Memory. Immunity, 48(2), 214-226. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.immuni.2018.01.005\n3. Zhang, N., & Bevan, M. J. (2011). CD8+ T cells: foot soldiers of the immune system. Immunity, 35(2), 161-168. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.immuni.2011.07.010",
  "CL:0000359":
    "Vascular-associated smooth muscle cells are a type of smooth muscle cell that surrounds blood vessels and regulates vascular tone and blood pressure. These cells also have a role in regulating blood flow and nutrient delivery to tissues by modulating vascular diameter and structure. Dysfunction of vascular-associated smooth muscle cells is associated with a variety of cardiovascular diseases including hypertension and atherosclerosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Owens GK. Regulation of differentiation of vascular smooth muscle cells. Physiol Rev. 1995 Jan;75(1):487-517. doi: 10.1152/physrev.1995.75.1.487. PMID: 7831399.\n2. Owens GK, Kumar MS, Wamhoff BR. Molecular regulation of vascular smooth muscle cell differentiation in development and disease. Physiol Rev. 2004 Oct;84(4):767-801. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00041.2003. PMID: 15383651.",
  "CL:0019021":
    "Endothelial cells of periportal hepatic sinusoid are a specialized type of cells that line the blood vessels found within the liver. These cells are located specifically in the region of the liver known as periportal, which is the area surrounding the portal triad. The main function of these cells is to form the selective barrier between the liver sinusoids and the blood flowing through them. They regulate the exchange of nutrients and waste products between the blood and the hepatocytes, as well as play a role in the regulation of blood flow and resistance within the liver. Additionally, they are also known to secrete a variety of factors that modulate the function of other liver cells. \n\nReferences: \n1. Braet F, Wisse E. Structural and functional aspects of liver sinusoidal endothelial cell fenestrae: a review. Compr Physiol. 2013 Jul;3(3):1475-95. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c120027. PMID: 23897689. \n2. DeLeve LD, Wang X, Tsai J, Kanel GC, Strasberg SM. Tumor necrosis factor-alpha decreases hepatocyte bile salt transport in taurocholate-perfused rat livers. American Journal of Physiology-Gastrointestinal and Liver Physiology. 1999;277(4):G582-G587. doi:10.1152/ajpgi.1999.277.4.G582.",
  "CL:0000800":
    "Mature gamma-delta T cells are a subset of T cells that express the gamma-delta T cell receptor instead of the more common alpha-beta T cell receptor. They are found in peripheral tissues such as the skin, gut, and lungs and are involved in immunity to infections, particularly those caused by bacteria and fungi. In addition, they have been implicated in tumor surveillance and immune regulation. The function of gamma-delta T cells is regulated by the unique combination of T cell receptor and co-stimulatory molecules expressed on their surface.  Literature references: \n\n1. Wu D, Wu P, Qiu F, Wei Q, Huang J. Human gamma delta T cell and diseases.  J Immunol Res. 2014;2014:814619. doi: 10.1155/2014/814619.\n2. Vantourout P, Hayday A. Six-of-the-best: unique contributions of \u03b3\u03b4 T cells to immunology. Nat Rev Immunol. 2013 Dec;13(12):88-100. doi: 10.1038/nri3384. Epub 2013 Nov 8.",
  "CL:0001034":
    "A cell in vitro refers to a cell that has been cultured outside its natural environment, such as in a laboratory setting. These cultured cells are highly regulated and can be used in various applications, such as drug discovery and toxicity testing. They offer a controlled environment for studying the behavior and function of cells in isolation. However, it is important to note that while in vitro experiments can provide valuable insight into cellular behavior, they do not necessarily represent the complexities of in vivo conditions. Literature reference: Freedman LP, Gibson MC, Bradner J, et al. The culture of cell culture: starting the conversation. Mol Biol Cell. 2015;26(22):3952-3954. doi:10.1091/mbc.E15-08-0551.",
  "CL:0000068":
    "Duct epithelial cells are polarized cells that line the lumen of ducts in various organs such as mammary glands, pancreas, and salivary glands. They function to transport fluids and secretions, and to maintain ion concentrations. Studies have shown that duct epithelial cells play an important role in maintaining tissue homeostasis and are involved in the development of various diseases. For instance, in breast cancer, duct epithelial cells undergo neoplastic transformation and contribute to tumor initiation and growth. (Reference: Dougherty, M. K., & Mullins, G. R. (2020). Mammary ductal epithelial cell fate: Implications for breast cancer progression and heterogeneity. Critical reviews in biochemistry and molecular biology, 1-21.)",
  "CL:0000192":
    "Smooth muscle cells are non-striated, spindle-shaped cells that are responsible for involuntary rhythmic contractions of organs such as the gut, blood vessels, and the bladder. They are activated by neural and chemical signals and play a crucial role in controlling organ volume, pressure, and motility. Smooth muscle cells possess a unique contractile machinery that is regulated by the phosphorylation of myosin light chains, which is controlled by the activity of myosin light chain kinase and myosin light chain phosphatase. These cells also secrete extracellular matrix proteins that contribute to tissue remodeling, wound healing, and fibrosis. Dysfunction of smooth muscle cells has been implicated in various disorders, including hypertension, asthma, and gastrointestinal motility disorders. Literature: Owens GK. Regulation of differentiation of vascular smooth muscle cells. Physiol Rev. 1995;75(3):487-517.",
  "CL:0000766":
    "Myeloid leukocytes are a type of white blood cell derived from the bone marrow that play critical roles in innate immunity and inflammation. They include monocytes, macrophages, neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils. Myeloid leukocytes are involved in engulfing and destroying invading microorganisms, presenting antigens to lymphocytes, and secreting cytokines to activate downstream immune responses. Dysregulation of myeloid leukocyte activity has been implicated in various autoimmune diseases and cancer. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Movahedi K, et al. Different tumor microenvironments contain functionally distinct subsets of macrophages derived from Ly6C(high) monocytes. Cancer Res. 2010 Sep 1;70(17):5728-39.",
  "CL:0000706":
    "Choroid plexus epithelial cells are responsible for secreting cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) and regulating ion transport within the brain ventricles. These cells are highly specialized, with unique morphology and junctional complexes that help to maintain the blood-CSF barrier. Additionally, choroid plexus epithelial cells have been shown to play a role in neuroinflammation, with involvement in the immune response to viral and bacterial infections in the central nervous system. \n\nReferences:\n1. Johanson, C. E., Duncan, J. A., Klinge, P. M., Brinker, T., & Stopa, E. G. (2008). Multiplicity of cerebrospinal fluid functions: New challenges in health and disease. Cerebrospinal Fluid Research, 5(1), 10. https://doi.org/10.1186/1743-8454-5-10\n2. Nakamura, Y., Yasuda, T., Weihua, Z., & Yoshimura, S. (2016). The choroid plexus epithelium in health and disease: A review. Fluids and Barriers of the CNS, 13(1), 12. https://doi.org/10.1186/s12987-016-0046-z",
  "CL:0005006":
    "Ionocytes are specialized epithelial cells found in the gills and skin of animals. These cells play a crucial role in regulating salt balance and ion transport across the epithelial layers. Ionocytes exhibit a unique morphology, including numerous apical membrane protrusions, and are characterized by the presence of ion transporters and channels, such as Na+/K+-ATPase and cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR). Dysregulation of these cells can lead to severe ionic imbalances and may contribute to diseases such as cystic fibrosis. \n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Marshall WS, Grosell M. Ion transport, osmoregulation, and acid-base balance. In: Evans DH, Claiborne JB, editors. The Physiology of Fishes. Third Edition. CRC Press; 2006. pp. 177-230.\n\n2. Hwang PP, Chou MY. Zebrafish as an animal model to study ion homeostasis. Pflugers Arch. 2013;465(10):1233-1247.",
  "CL:0002071":
    "Enterocytes are the most abundant epithelial cells lining the large intestine. They are responsible for nutrient absorption and water reabsorption from the digested food material. In addition, they play an important role in maintaining the intestinal barrier function and defending against bacterial infection. Dysfunction of enterocytes has been associated with various gastrointestinal diseases, such as inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer. (Reference: Jeltema, D., & Yap, A. S. (2019). The Dynamic Nature of Epithelial Junctions and Their Role in Tissue Homeostasis. Physiology, 34(2), 116-128.)",
  "CL:0001082":
    "Immature innate lymphoid cells are a group of lymphoid progenitor cells that give rise to mature innate lymphoid cell subsets. They express intermediate levels of the transcription factor Id2 and lack lineage-specific markers for mature innate lymphoid cell subsets. The function of immature innate lymphoid cells is to differentiate into various subsets of mature innate lymphoid cells, including type 1, type 2, and type 3 innate lymphoid cells, which play critical roles in tissue repair, immune surveillance, and host defense against pathogens. \n\nReference: \n\nKlose CS, Diefenbach A. Transcription factors controlling innate lymphoid cell fate decisions. Curr Top Microbiol Immunol. 2014; 381:215-55. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-02837-0_11. PMID: 25183242.",
  "CL:0000765":
    'Erythroblasts are nucleated precursor cells of erythrocytes that play a critical role in red blood cell formation. These cells are typically found in the bone marrow and undergo a series of maturation stages, including proerythroblast, basophilic erythroblast, polychromatic erythroblast, and orthochromatic erythroblast, before they lose their nuclei to become mature erythrocytes. During maturation, erythroblasts actively synthesize and accumulate hemoglobin, the protein that enables red blood cells to carry oxygen throughout the body. Dysfunction of erythroblast development can lead to anemia, a condition in which the blood lacks enough healthy red blood cells to deliver oxygen to tissues. \n\nReferences: \n\n- Bessman JD. Hematopoietic progenitor cells. N Engl J Med. 1987;317(14):873-878. doi:10.1056/NEJM198710013171405\n- Kingsley PD, Malik J, Emerson RL, et al. "Maturational" globin switching in primary primitive erythroid cells. Blood. 2006;107(4):1665-1672. doi:10.1182/blood-2005-07-2837',
  "CL:0011103":
    'Sympathetic neurons are a type of neuron that form the sympathetic nervous system, which is responsible for the "fight or flight" response during stress. Sympathetic neurons release the neurotransmitter norepinephrine, which acts on various organs to increase heart rate, blood pressure, and respiratory rate, while decreasing functions such as digestion and bladder contraction. Additionally, they play a role in the regulation of thermoregulation, blood glucose levels, and immune function. Dysfunction or loss of sympathetic neurons has been implicated in various diseases, including hypertension, diabetes, and autoimmune disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Raffaeli W, et al. (2018). Sympathetic nervous system and diabetes: evidence for a new therapeutic approach. Frontiers in Endocrinology, 9: 268.\n2. Carnevale D, et al. (2015). Pathophysiological basis for the management of patients with advanced heart failure and reduced ejection fraction treated with sildenafil. Reviews in Cardiovascular Medicine, 16(4): 230-239.',
  "CL:0000586":
    "Germ cells are specialized cells in the reproductive organs that give rise to gametes, such as eggs or sperm. They are essential for the propagation of species and the continuation of genetic information across generations. During development, germ cells undergo meiosis to reduce their chromosome number by half, which is necessary for the fusion of gametes during sexual reproduction. Germ cells have unique molecular and genetic features to sustain their identity and function. Failure in germ cell development can lead to infertility or other reproductive disorders. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Saitou, M., & Miyauchi, H. (2016). Gametogenesis from Pluripotent Stem Cells. Cell Stem Cell, 18(6), 721-735. doi: 10.1016/j.stem.2016.05.010.",
  "CL:0000091":
    "Kupffer cells are specialized phagocytic cells located in the liver sinusoids. They play a crucial role in the clearance of bacteria, foreign particles, and aged red blood cells from the circulation. Kupffer cells are also involved in the regulation of liver inflammation and the maintenance of liver homeostasis. Recent studies have shown that Kupffer cells also contribute to the development of liver fibrosis and hepatocellular carcinoma. [1] [2]",
  "CL:1000312":
    "Bronchial goblet cells are a specialised type of epithelial cell found in the respiratory tract. They are responsible for secreting mucin glycoproteins that form the protective mucus barrier in the lungs. Goblet cells play an important role in protecting the respiratory tract from inhaled pathogens and irritants. Their secretions form a sticky layer that traps foreign particles and prevents them from entering the deeper parts of the lungs. Goblet cells have been studied in various diseases affecting the respiratory system, such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). \n\nReferences:\n1. Kesimer M, Kirkham S, Pickles RJ, Henderson AG, Alexis NE, DeMaria GC, et al. Tracheobronchial air-liquid interface cell culture: a model for innate mucosal defense of the upper airways? Am J Respir Cell Mol Biol. 2009;40(5):590\u20137.\n2. Turner J, Jones C. Regulation of mucin expression in respiratory diseases. Biochem Soc Trans. 2009;37(Pt 2):877\u201381.",
  "CL:0000006":
    "Neuronal receptor cells are specialized sensory cells that respond to a specific stimulus and convert this into an electrical signal that can be transmitted to the brain. These cells are located in the sensory organs, such as the eyes, ear, and nose, and are responsible for the detection and processing of sensory information. In the retina, for example, the neuronal receptor cells are known as photoreceptors and respond to light stimuli, while in the inner ear they are hair cells that respond to sound or movement stimuli. The activation of neuronal receptor cells initiates the process of sensory reception and perception, and is essential for the functioning of sensory systems.\n\nReferences:\n1. Fain GL. Molecular and cellular mechanisms of vertebrate photoreceptor light adaptation. Frontiers in molecular neuroscience. 2010 Oct 26;3:21.\n2. Hudspeth AJ, Corey DP. Sensory transduction: from sensory neurons to the brain. Neuron. 2017 Mar 22; 94(6):1041-63.",
  "CL:0000510":
    "Paneth cells are specialized secretory epithelial cells located in the small intestine. They secrete antimicrobial peptides, such as alpha-defensins, which play a critical role in protecting the intestinal epithelium against bacteria and other pathogens. In addition to their role in innate immunity, Paneth cells have been implicated in regulating intestinal stem cell function. Dysfunction of Paneth cells has been linked to various gastrointestinal diseases, including Crohn's disease. (Reference: Bevins CL, Salzman NH. Paneth cells, antimicrobial peptides and maintenance of intestinal homeostasis. Nat Rev Microbiol. 2011; 9(5):356-68.)",
  "CL:0000233":
    "Platelets are small, anuclear blood cells that play a crucial role in hemostasis and thrombosis. They are produced by megakaryocytes in the bone marrow and are released into the circulation, where they circulate for several days before being cleared by the reticuloendothelial system. Platelets respond to vascular injury by adhering to exposed subendothelial matrix proteins and releasing signaling molecules, such as thromboxane A2 and adenosine diphosphate, that activate other platelets to form a hemostatic plug. They also secrete proinflammatory cytokines and chemokines that participate in inflammatory responses. In addition to their role in hemostasis, platelets are involved in angiogenesis, tissue regeneration, and host defense against pathogens. Their functions are regulated by a variety of extracellular cues, including shear stress, soluble agonists, and cell-cell interactions. \n\nReferences:\n1. Italiano JE Jr, Patel-Hett S, Hartwig JH. Mechanics of proplatelet elaboration. J Thromb Haemost. 2007 Oct;5 Suppl 1:18-23.\n2. Li N, Platelets in cancer metastasis: To help the \u201cvillain\u201d to do evil. Int J Cancer. 2016 Feb 15;138(4):247-58.\n3. Pitchford SC, Chakrabarti S, Watson SP, Platelets as pharmacological targets: Turning platelets from \u201ccytokine-stimulated adhesive cells\u201d to \u201ccytokine-generating immunomodulators\u201d. Curr Opin Pharmacol. 2015 Oct; 24:60-6.",
  "CL:0000051":
    "A common lymphoid progenitor (CLP) is a type of hematopoietic stem cell that is capable of differentiating into various lymphocyte cell types, including natural killer cells, T cells, and B cells. CLPs are known to express various transcription factors including LMO2, which is important for lymphoid differentiation. They are found primarily in the bone marrow and are thought to play a critical role in the development and maintenance of the immune system.\n\nReferences:\n- Kondo M et al. Biology of hematopoietic stem cells and progenitors: implications for clinical application. Annu Rev Immunol. 2003; 21:759-806.\n- Nutt SL et al. From hematopoietic progenitors to B cells and beyond: regulation of hematopoiesis and B lymphopoiesis. Immunol Rev. 2006; 209: 10-28. \n- Adolfsson J et al. Identification of Flt3+ lympho-myeloid stem cells lacking erythro-megakaryocytic potential a revised road map for adult blood lineage commitment. Cell. 2005; 121(2):295-306.",
  "CL:4023181":
    "Ependymal cells are a type of glial cell that line the cerebral ventricles in the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord. They are important for the production and regulation of cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), which cushions and protects the brain and spinal cord, as well as for providing a barrier between the CSF and neural tissue. In addition to their barrier function, ependymal cells are also thought to be involved in the regulation of neural stem cells and neurogenesis in the adult brain. Literature references: Sawamoto et al., Cell Stem Cell, 2006; Shen et al., Cell Stem Cell, 2008.",
  "CL:0002075":
    "Brush cells of the tracheobronchial tree are columnar epithelial cells that have a tuft of microvilli at their apical surface which give them their characteristic 'brush-like' appearance. They remain in close association with nerve terminals, giving them the ability to respond to environmental changes within the lumen of the airways. Brush cells secrete ATP and express receptors for bitter, sweet and umami substances, thus are thought to function as chemosensors for the respiratory system. Studies have also suggested that brush cells may be involved in immune regulation and mucus production. \n\nLiterature references: \n\n1. Krasteva G, Kummer W. \u201cTaste receptors in the lung.\u201d Respiration physiology. 2014; 6:13-19.\n2. Oyarzun-Ampuero F. et al. \u201cBrush cells of mouse trachea: cellular marker of Clara cell- and ciliated cell-independent airway epithelium.\u201d Anatomical record. 2012; 295(12):2141-2149.\n3. Ogura T. et al. \"Brush cells as sentinels and central mediators of early immune defense in the respiratory tract.\" Frontiers in Physiology. 2018; 9: 856.",
  "CL:0000842":
    "Mononuclear cells are white blood cells that possess a single, non-segmented nucleus. These cells can be further classified as lymphocytes or monocytes, depending on their size and morphology. Functionally, mononuclear cells are integral components of the immune system and play key roles in providing defense against foreign organisms and cancerous cells. Lymphocytes recognize and respond to specific antigens, while monocytes can differentiate into macrophages that phagocytose and eliminate pathogens. Abnormal numbers or functions of mononuclear cells are associated with numerous diseases, including autoimmune disorders and viral infections. (Reference: Alberts, B., Johnson, A., Lewis, J., Raff, M., Roberts, K., & Walter, P. (2002). Molecular Biology of the Cell (4th ed.). New York: Garland Science.)",
  "CL:0000837":
    "Hematopoietic multipotent progenitor cells (MPPs) are a type of stem cell with the capacity to differentiate into all blood cell lineages, including erythrocytes, granulocytes, monocytes, lymphocytes, and platelets. These cells reside in the bone marrow and play a crucial role in maintaining a healthy immune system and replenishing blood cells lost through normal physiological turnover or injury. MPPs can differentiate into either myeloid or lymphoid committed progenitor cells, which subsequently mature into different blood cell types. Understanding the properties and regulation of MPPs is therefore critical for the development of therapies for blood-related disorders such as leukemia and aplastic anemia. \n\nReference:\n- Notta F, Zandi S, Takayama N, Dobson S, Gan OI, Wilson G, et al. Distinct routes of lineage development reshape the human blood hierarchy across ontogeny. Science. 2016 Nov 25;354(6315):aad7979.",
  "CL:0002319":
    "Neural cells are specialized cells that make up the nervous system and are responsible for transmitting and receiving information throughout the body. They have unique structures called dendrites and axons that allow them to communicate with other cells. The function of neural cells is critical for a range of processes such as sensory perception, motor control, cognition, and behavior. There are several types of neural cells including neurons, astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and microglia. Dysfunction of neural cells is implicated in various neurological conditions including Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and multiple sclerosis.\n\nReference: \n1. Herculano-Houzel, S. (2014). The human brain in numbers: a linearly scaled-up primate brain. Frontiers in Human Neuroscience, 8, 1-11.\n2. Thomas, C., & Hynd, G. (1999). Dyslexia and the cerebellum. Journal of Child Neurology, 14(4), 199-202.\n3. Lopes, C. G., et al. (2019). The role of astrocytes in Alzheimer's Disease. In Astrocyte: Development, Regeneration, and Brain Disorders (pp. 283-311). Elsevier.",
  "CL:0011101":
    "Chorionic trophoblast cells are specialized cells that line the outer layer of the placenta. These cells play a crucial role in facilitating nutrient and gas exchange between the mother and fetus, as well as in the production of hormones that support pregnancy. Additionally, chorionic trophoblast cells contribute to the development and differentiation of other cell types in the placenta. Dysfunction of these cells has been linked to complications in pregnancy such as preeclampsia and fetal growth restriction. \n\nReferences: \n1. Kn\u00f6fler M, Haider S, Saleh L, Pollheimer J, Gamage TKJB, James JL. Human placenta and trophoblast development: key molecular mechanisms and model systems. Cell Mol Life Sci. 2019;76(18):3479-3496. doi:10.1007/s00018-019-03197-5\n2. Aplin JD, Jones CJ, Harris LK, et al. Trophoblast differentiation: lessons from the human haemochorial placenta. Reprod Biomed Online. 2006;13(2):184-196. doi:10.1016/s1472-6483(10)62034-8",
  "CL:0000863":
    "Inflammatory macrophages are a subset of macrophages that are present at sites of inflammation. These cells play a crucial role in the immune response by engulfing and digesting pathogens, damaged cells, and cellular debris. They also release inflammatory cytokines, reactive oxygen species, and nitric oxide, which help to recruit and activate other immune cells to clear the infection or damaged tissue. Inflammatory macrophages are characterized by the expression of distinct surface markers, such as CD86, and distinct transcription factors, such as STAT1 and NF-kB. \n\nReferences:\n1. Guilliams M, Scott CL. Does niche competition determine the origin of tissue-resident macrophages? Nat Rev Immunol. 2017 Oct;17(10):661\u20139.\n2. Fadok VA, Bratton DL, Rose DM, Pearson A, Ezekewitz RA, Henson PM. A receptor for phosphatidylserine-specific clearance of apoptotic cells. Nature. 2000 Nov 30;405(6782):85\u201390.\n3. Murray PJ, Allen JE, Biswas SK, Fisher EA, Gilroy DW, Goerdt S, et al. Macrophage Activation and Polarization: Nomenclature and Experimental Guidelines. Immunity. 2014 Jul 17;41(1):14\u201320.",
  "CL:4028006":
    "Alveolar type 2 fibroblast cells are a subtype of lung fibroblasts that are located in the alveolar walls of the lung. They are responsible for producing and maintaining the extracellular matrix of the lung. This extracellular matrix provides structural support for the alveolar walls and also helps regulate gas exchange in the lung. Additionally, alveolar type 2 fibroblast cells are important for the repair and regeneration of lung tissue after injury or damage. A recent study in mice has shown that alveolar type 2 fibroblast cells play a critical role in the development of acute lung injury and that targeting these cells may be a potential therapeutic strategy for treating this condition (Kropski et al., 2018).\n\nReference:\nKropski JA, et al. Single-cell analysis reveals fibroblast heterogeneity and myofibroblasts in systemic sclerosis-associated interstitial lung disease. Ann Rheum Dis. 2018;77:1448-1455.",
  "CL:0000150":
    "Glandular epithelial cells are specialized cells that form the glands of the body. These cells secrete substances such as hormones, enzymes, and mucus that play important roles in the body's physiology. Glandular epithelial cells are found in a variety of tissues such as the pancreas, prostate, and salivary glands. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various diseases such as diabetes and cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Pellegrini C, et al. Glandular epithelial cells: a review of their biology, function, and role in disease. Endocrine. 2019;65(1):3-14.\n2. Chuaqui RF, et al. Glandular epithelial cells in tissue culture: a review of the literature and a survey of current cell lines. In vitro cellular & developmental biology. 1991;27A(11):723-730.",
  "CL:0002329":
    "Basal epithelial cells of tracheobronchial tree are a population of stem/progenitor cells that reside in the basal layer of the epithelium of the respiratory tract. They are responsible for the maintenance and repair of the respiratory epithelium, as well as for generating a variety of differentiated cell types including ciliated cells, secretory cells, and club cells. These cells play a critical role in the defense mechanisms of the respiratory tract against inhaled pathogens and particulates. Recent studies have also identified unique subpopulations of basal cells that are important for tissue regeneration and repair after injury. \n\nReferences:\nRock et al. 2009. Basal cells exhibit stem cell-like properties in repairing tracheal epithelium. Journal of Clinical Investigation.\nHong et al. 2018. Basal stem cells of the mouse trachea and human airway epithelia: similarities and differences. Development. \nRawlins and Hogan. 2008. Ciliated epithelial cell lifespan in the mouse trachea and lung. Am J Physiol Lung Cell Mol Physiol.",
  "CL:0000558":
    "Reticulocytes are immature erythrocytes (red blood cells) that are released from the bone marrow into circulation. They are characterized by a residual network of ribosomal RNA, known as reticulum, visible under a microscope after staining with certain dyes. Reticulocytes have a crucial function in the process of erythropoiesis, which is the production of red blood cells. They develop into mature erythrocytes within 1-2 days of their release from the bone marrow and are responsible for carrying oxygen to tissues throughout the body. \n\nReference: \n- Bain BJ. Blood Cells: A Practical Guide. John Wiley & Sons, Ltd; 2015.",
  "CL:1000500":
    "Kidney interstitial cells are a heterogeneous population of cells that reside in the interstitium of the kidney. They play crucial roles in maintaining the normal structure and function of the kidney. Interstitial cells have various functions including mesenchymal, immune cells and fibroblasts. Mesenchymal cells include mesangial cells and pericytes which provide support for capillaries and tubules in the kidney respectively. Immune cells found in the interstitium include dendritic cells, macrophages, and T cells, which are involved in immune surveillance and inflammation. Fibroblasts contribute to the synthesis and maintenance of extracellular matrix in the kidney. Dysfunction of interstitial cells is commonly associated with various kidney diseases.  \n\nReferences: \n1. Humphreys, B. D., & Lin, S. L. (2017). The kidney\u2019s innate immune system. Cell and tissue research, 369(1), 23-32.\n2. Kramann, R., DiRocco, D. P., & Humphreys, B. D. (2015). Understanding the origin, activation and regulation of matrix-producing myofibroblasts for treatment of fibrotic disease. Journal of Pathology, 237(3), 374-383.\n3. Zeisberg, M., & Kalluri, R. (2018). Cellular mechanisms of tissue fibrosis. 1. Common and organ-specific mechanisms associated with tissue fibrosis. American Journal of Physiology-Renal Physiology, 308(3), F155-F171.",
  "CL:0000000":
    "A cell is the basic structural, functional, and biological unit of all living organisms. It is the smallest unit of life that can replicate independently, and it performs a variety of functions that are essential for life. Cells can be classified into two main types: prokaryotic cells, which are found in bacteria and archaea, and eukaryotic cells, which are found in animals, plants, fungi, and protists. The function of a cell depends on its type and location in the organism. Generally, cells can perform functions such as energy production, synthesis of macromolecules, cell division, communication, and differentiation. \n\nReferences:\n1. Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2002.\n2. Lodish H, Berk A, Zipursky SL, et al. Molecular Cell Biology. 4th edition. New York: W. H. Freeman; 2000.",
  "CL:1000329":
    "Tracheal goblet cells are specialized epithelial cells that line the trachea and secrete mucin glycoproteins to aid in the protection and lubrication of the airway. These cells are named after their characteristic goblet shape and are distinguishable by their large apical surfaces filled with secretory vesicles containing mucin. The secretion of mucin is essential for the maintenance of proper respiratory function by trapping and removing foreign particles and pathogens from the airways. Additionally, tracheal goblet cells are involved in the regulation of ciliary beat frequency, which is important for directing mucus transport up and out of the airways. Dysregulation of goblet cell function has been linked to a number of respiratory diseases, including asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and cystic fibrosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Evans CM, Williams OW, Tuvim MJ, Nigam R, Mixides GP, Blackburn MR, DeMayo FJ, Burns AR, Smith C, Reynolds SD, Stripp BR, Dickey BF. Mucin is produced by clara cells in the proximal airways of antigen-challenged mice. Am J Respir Cell Mol Biol. 2004 Dec;31(6):382-94.\n2. Tyner JW, Kim EY, Ide K, Pelletier MR, Roswit WT, Morton JD, Battaile JT, Patel AC, Patterson GA, Castro M, Spoor MS, You Y, Brody SL, Holtzman MJ. Blocking airway mucous cell metaplasia by inhibiting EGFR antiapoptosis and IL-13 transdifferentiation signals. J Clin Invest. 2006 Jul;116(7):309-21.\n3. Rock JR, Randell SH, Hogan BL. Airway basal stem cells: a perspective on their roles in epithelial homeostasis and remodeling. Dis Model Mech. 2010 Mar-Apr;3(3-4):164-78.",
  "CL:0000094":
    "Granulocytes are a type of white blood cell characterized by the presence of granules in their cytoplasm. There are three main types of granulocytes: neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils. These cells are important in the body's immune response to infection and inflammation. Neutrophils are the most common type of granulocyte and are involved in the early stages of the immune response, phagocytosing and killing invading pathogens. Eosinophils are involved in attacking certain parasitic infections and modulating allergic reactions, while basophils release histamine and other substances involved in inflammation. Overall, granulocytes play a vital role in protecting the body from infection and maintaining tissue homeostasis.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Adams, H. P., Jr. (2015). Granulocyte. In Encyclopedia of Clinical Neuropsychology (pp. 1327-1328). Springer, Boston, MA.\n\n2. Borregaard, N., & Cowland, J. B. (1997). Granules of the human neutrophilic polymorphonuclear leukocyte. Blood, 89(10), 3503-3521.\n\n3. Kuriakose, T., Redecke, V., & Kotenko, S. V. (2018). A Guide for the Use of Eosinophilic Granulocytes in Experimental Models of Immunity and Inflammation. Frontiers in immunology, 9, 3023.",
  "CL:0011004":
    "Lens fiber cells are elongated, terminally differentiated cells that make up the bulk of the vertebrate eye lens. These cells are devoid of nuclei, ribosomes, and other organelles, allowing for maximum transparency and light transmission. They are responsible for focusing light onto the retina by changing shape to alter the lens curvature. Lens fiber cells are constantly produced throughout life by the underlying lens epithelium and are essential for maintaining a clear image. Dysfunction or damage to these cells can lead to lens opacities and cataracts. \n\nReference: Bassnett, S. (2011). The lens. In eLS. John Wiley & Sons, Ltd. https://doi.org/10.1002/9780470015902.a0003059.pub2",
  "CL:0000548":
    "Animal cells are eukaryotic cells that are found in animals. They are characterized by the presence of a nucleus, membrane-bound organelles, and a cytoskeleton that provides structure and support. Animal cells have a variety of functions, including maintaining tissue structure, carrying out metabolic processes, and facilitating communication between cells. Animal cells can also differentiate into specialized cell types, such as muscle cells, nerve cells, and blood cells. \n\nReferences:\n- Alberts, B., Johnson, A., Lewis, J., Raff, M., Roberts, K., and Walter, P. (2002). Molecular Biology of the Cell, 4th Ed. Garland Science, New York.\n- Lodish, H., Berk, A., Zipursky, S.L., and Matsudaira, P. (2000). Molecular Cell Biology, 4th Ed. W.H. Freeman and Company, New York.",
  "CL:0008001":
    "Hematopoietic precursor cells are multipotent stem cells that can differentiate into all blood cell types, including erythrocytes, leukocytes, and platelets. These cells are found in the bone marrow and play a crucial role in maintaining the homeostasis of the blood system. Their function is to continually replenish the blood cells that are lost through normal turnover or in response to injury, infection, or disease. Hematopoietic precursor cells are the basis for the development of hematopoietic cell transplantation, which is used to treat hematological malignancies and other blood disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Adolfsson J, Borge OJ, Bryder D, et al. Upregulation of Flt3 expression within the bone marrow Lin(\u2212)Sca1(+)c-kit(+) stem cell compartment is accompanied by loss of self-renewal capacity. Immunity. 2001;15(4):659-669. \n2. Notta F, Doulatov S, Laurenti E, et al. Isolation of single human hematopoietic stem cells capable of long-term multilineage engraftment. Science. 2011;333(6039):218-221. \n3. Porada GA, Almeida-Porada G. Mesenchymal stem cells as therapeutics and vehicles for gene and drug delivery. Adv Drug Deliv Rev. 2010;62(12):1156-1166.",
  "CL:0002457":
    "Epidermal Langerhans cells are a unique subset of dendritic cells found in the epidermis. These cells serve as sentinels of the skin, detecting and processing antigens and presenting them to T cells in order to mount an immune response. They are involved in the pathogenesis of inflammatory skin disorders such as psoriasis and atopic dermatitis, as well as in the initiation of skin graft rejection. Langerhans cells express a variety of pattern recognition receptors, which allow them to recognize and respond to a diverse range of pathogens and environmental stimuli. Additionally, they participate in the maintenance of skin homeostasis through the secretion of cytokines and the regulation of T cell activity. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Romani N, Clausen BE, Stoitzner P. Langerhans cells and more: Langerin-expressing dendritic cell subsets in the skin. Immunol Rev. 2010;234(1):120-141. doi:10.1111/j.0105-2896.2009.00884.x\n2. Kaplan DH, Jenison MC, Saeland S, Shlomchik WD, Shlomchik MJ. Epidermal Langerhans cell-deficient mice develop enhanced contact hypersensitivity to strong sensitizers. J Exp Med. 2005;202(3):373-381. doi:10.1084/jem.20050615\n3. Flacher V, Tripp CH, M\u00fchlbauer M, et al. Epidermal Langerhans cells rapidly capture and present antigens from C-type lectin-targeting antibodies deposited in the dermis. J Invest Dermatol. 2010;130(3):755-762. doi:10.1038/jid.2009.321\n4. Ginhoux F, Tacke F, Angeli V, et al. Langerhans cells arise from monocytes in vivo. Nat Immunol. 2006;7(3):265-273. doi:10.1038/ni1307",
  "CL:0001050":
    'Effector CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a subset of cytotoxic T cells that play a critical role in the adaptive immune response to viral and bacterial infections. These cells are characterized by the expression of CD8, which allows them to recognize and eliminate infected cells displaying foreign antigens on their surface through the release of cytotoxic molecules such as perforin and granzymes. Effector CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are short-lived, highly activated cells that arise from naive CD8 T cells upon encounter with antigen. They also produce cytokines, such as IFN-\u03b3 and TNF-\u03b1, which activate and recruit other immune cells to the site of infection. Effector CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are critical for the clearance of intracellular pathogens and the maintenance of long-term immunity against pathogens. \n\nReference: Harty, John T., and Vijayakumar Velu. "Effector CD8 T Cells, the Cytotoxic Arm of the Adaptive Immune System." In Seminars in Immunopathology, vol. 39, no. 3, pp. 327-347. Springer Berlin Heidelberg, 2017.',
  "CL:0000790":
    "The immature alpha-beta T cell is a type of T lymphocyte that has not yet completed its maturation process and is still in the thymus. During this process, the immature alpha-beta T cell undergoes a rigorous process of antigen receptor gene rearrangement and selection. This process involves the elimination of cells that may cause autoimmunity or are unresponsive to foreign antigens. Once the process is completed, the mature alpha-beta T cell is able to recognize and respond to foreign antigens presented by antigen-presenting cells. The function of immature alpha-beta T cells is critical in the development of the adaptive immune system. \n\nReference: \n- Rothenberg, E. V. (2020). T cell lineage commitment: identity and renunciation. Journal of immunology (Baltimore, Md.: 1950), 205(5), 1227\u20131235. https://doi.org/10.4049/jimmunol.2000955",
  "CL:1000432":
    "Conjunctival epithelial cells are the outermost layer of the conjunctiva, a tissue that covers the eye's white part and lines the inside of the eyelids. These cells play an important role in protecting the eye by forming a physical and biochemical barrier against external pathogens and irritants. They also secrete mucin, which lubricates and moisturizes the ocular surface. Conjunctival epithelial cells have been reported to express several ion channels and receptors that contribute to the regulation of the tear film and ocular surface homeostasis. Dysregulation of these cells has been linked to ocular surface diseases such as dry eye syndrome. \n\nReferences:\n1. Gipson IK, Gipson JR. The Conjunctiva.  In: Kolb H, Fernandez E, Nelson R, editors. Webvision: The Organization of the Retina and Visual System [Internet]. Salt Lake City (UT): University of Utah Health Sciences Center; 1995-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK26833/\n2. Pflugfelder SC, Jones D, Ji Z, et al. Altered cytokine balance in the tear fluid and conjunctiva of patients with Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome keratoconjunctivitis sicca. Curr Eye Res. 1999;19(3):201-211. doi:10.1076/ceyr.19.3.201.5351\n3. Dartt DA. Control of Conjunctival Goblet Cell Function by Nerves and Growth Factors. Invest Ophthalmol Vis Sci. 2011;52(13):9174-9180. doi:10.1167/iovs.11-8405",
  "CL:0001074":
    "CD34-positive, CD56-positive, CD117-positive common innate lymphoid precursor, human:\n\nThis cell type is a precursor for all innate lymphoid cells (ILCs) in humans and is characterized by the expression of CD34, CD56, and CD117 surface markers. These cells have the potential to differentiate into various types of ILCs, such as natural killer (NK) cells, ILC1s, ILC2s, and ILC3s. The development of these cells is regulated by several transcription factors, including ID2, GATA3, ROR\u03b3t, and Tbet. Studies have shown that defects in the development or function of ILCs can lead to immune dysregulation and disease.\n\nReferences:\n1. Scoville SD, et al. Human AML activates the aryl hydrocarbon receptor pathway to impair NK cell development and function. Blood. 2018;132(16):1792-1804.\n2. Wang C, et al. CD117+CD34+CD56+ innate lymphoid cell precursors mediate acute graft-versus-host disease without exacerbating chronic graft-versus-host disease. Blood. 2018;131(10):1167-1178.\n3. Cella M, et al. A human natural killer cell subset provides an innate source of IL-22 for mucosal immunity. Nature. 2009;457(7230):722-725.",
  "CL:0000623":
    "A natural killer cell, or NK cell, is a type of cytotoxic lymphocyte that plays a critical role in the innate immune response. NK cells are involved in the recognition and destruction of virally infected cells and tumor cells through the release of granzymes, perforins, and cytokines. Moreover, NK cells can also act as regulatory cells, modulating other immune cells' functions. NK cells express a variety of activating and inhibitory receptors that recognize major histocompatibility complex class I antigens, stress ligands, and viral proteins. Notably, NK cells can also mediate antibody-dependent cell-mediated cytotoxicity, where their Fc receptors bind to the Fc region of antibodies attached to target cells, leading to their killing. The overall activity of NK cells is tightly regulated by interactions between their receptors and their ligands, which dictate the thresholds for activation and inhibition. Dysregulation of NK cells has been associated with various diseases, including autoimmune disorders, cancer, and viral infections.\n\nReferences:\n- Vivier E, Raulet DH, Moretta A, Caligiuri MA, Zitvogel L, Lanier LL, Yokoyama WM, Ugolini S. Innate or adaptive immunity? The example of natural killer cells. Science. 2011 Apr 1;331(6013):44-9.\n- Long EO, Kim HS, Liu D, Peterson ME, Rajagopalan S. Controlling natural killer cell responses: integration of signals for activation and inhibition. Annu Rev Immunol. 2013;31:227-58.\n- Kruse PH, Matta J, Ugolini S, Vivier E. Natural cytotoxicity receptors and their ligands. Immunol Cell Biol. 2014 Jan;92(1):221-9.",
  "CL:0002518":
    "Kidney epithelial cells are specialized cells that line the tubules of the kidney and are involved in filtration, reabsorption, and secretion of various substances. They play a critical role in regulating electrolyte balance, blood pressure, and pH regulation. Depending on their specific location within the nephron, kidney epithelial cells possess different structural and functional characteristics. The proximal convoluted tubule epithelial cells, for example, have a brush border consisting of microvilli, which increases their surface area and enhances their ability to reabsorb nutrients such as glucose and amino acids. In contrast, the collecting duct epithelial cells are involved in the final regulation of urine concentration and acid-base balance. Dysfunction of kidney epithelial cells can lead to various kidney disorders such as acute kidney injury or chronic kidney disease. \n\nReferences:\n1. Lee JW, Chou CL, Knepper MA. Deep sequencing in microdissected renal tubules identifies nephron segment-specific transcriptomes. J Am Soc Nephrol. 2015;26(11):2669-2677.\n2. Hentschel DM, Park KM, Cilenti L, Zervos AS, Drummond IA, Bonventre JV. Acute renal failure in zebrafish: a novel system to study a complex disease. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 2005;288(5):F923-F929.",
  "CL:0000921":
    "Type I natural killer T (NKT) cells are a subset of T cells that express an invariant T cell receptor (TCR) and recognize glycolipid antigens presented by CD1d molecules. These cells bridge the innate and adaptive immune systems and are known for their ability to rapidly produce large amounts of cytokines upon activation, such as interferon-gamma (IFN-\u03b3), interleukin-4 (IL-4) and tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-\u03b1). Type I NKT cells have been shown to play a significant role in regulating immune responses, particularly in the context of cancer, infection, and autoimmunity. In cancer, type I NKT cells can have anti-tumor activity, whereas in infectious diseases, they can either promote or limit disease progression depending on the pathogen and the type of NKT cell response elicited. In autoimmunity, type I NKT cells can promote or suppress disease depending on the context. Therefore, understanding the functions of type I NKT cells is critical to developing effective immunotherapies and vaccines. \n\nReferences:\n1. Godfrey DI, Kronenberg M (2004) Going both ways: immune regulation via CD1d-dependent NKT cells. J Clin Invest 114(10):1379-1388\n2. Van Kaer L, Parekh VV, Wu L (2013) Invariant natural killer T cells: bridging innate and adaptive immunity. Cell Tissue Res 343(1):43-55\n3. Liao CM, Zimmer MI, Wang CR (2012) The functions of type I and type II natural killer T cells in inflammatory bowel diseases. Inflamm Bowel Dis 18(1):136-151.",
  "CL:0002038":
    "T follicular helper cells are a subset of CD4+ T cells that play a crucial role in the development of high-affinity and class-switched antibodies during humoral immune responses. They accomplish this by migrating into the germinal centers of lymphoid follicles where they interact with B cells and provide necessary signals for efficient antibody production. T follicular helper cells are characterized by the expression of surface markers such as CXCR5, PD-1, and ICOS, as well as the production of cytokines like IL-21 and IL-4. Dysregulation of T follicular helper cell activity has been implicated in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases, allergy, and cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Crotty, S. (2014). T follicular helper cell differentiation, function, and roles in disease. Immunity, 41(4), 529-542.\n2. Vinuesa, C. G., & Linterman, M. A. (2016). T-follicular helper cells: antigen and cytokine co\u2010ordinated roles in T\u2010dependent antibody production. Immunology and Cell Biology, 94(6), 574-581.\n3. Morita, R., Schmitt, N., Bentebibel, S. E., Ranganathan, R., Bourdery, L., Zurawski, G., ... & Ueno, H. (2011). Human blood CXCR5+CD4+ T cells are counterparts of T follicular cells and contain specific subsets that differentially support antibody secretion. Immunity, 34(1), 108-121.",
  "CL:1001107":
    "The thin ascending limb (TAL) epithelial cell in the kidney loop of Henle is a highly specialized cell that plays an important role in the reabsorption of salt in the kidney nephron. These cells actively transport sodium and chloride ions out of the lumen of the TAL through ion channels and co-transporters, creating a concentration gradient and allowing for passive diffusion of water out of the descending limb. The TAL is crucial for the maintenance of the osmotic gradient in the medulla of the kidney, which is necessary for normal kidney function.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Vallon V, et al. (2015) The physiology of the proximal tubule and its response to dietary acid load. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 308:F1302-22.\n2. Ellison DH, et al. (2019) Loop of Henle Thiazide Sensitivity: Insights from a Molecular Mouse Model. J Am Soc Nephrol. 30:1096-1099.",
  "CL:0000099":
    'Interneurons are specialized cells located in the central nervous system that act as connectors between sensory and motor neurons. These cells receive and integrate signals from one or more inputs and modulate the activity of downstream neurons. Interneurons play crucial roles in the processing, integration, and transmission of information in the nervous system, and are involved in various functions including sensory perception, cognition, and motor control. Dysfunction of interneurons has been implicated in several neurological disorders such as epilepsy, schizophrenia, and autism spectrum disorders. \n\nReference:\n\nFishell G, Rudy B. Mechanisms of inhibition within the telencephalon: "where the wild things are". Annu Rev Neurosci. 2011;34:535-67. doi: 10.1146/annurev-neuro-061010-113717. PMID: 21692658.',
  "CL:2000002":
    "Decidual cells are specialized stromal cells found in the endometrium during the secretory phase of the menstrual cycle and pregnancy. They play a critical role in implantation, embryo development, and the maintenance of pregnancy by providing nutrients and support to the developing embryo and fetus. Decidualization, the process by which endometrial stromal cells differentiate into decidual cells, is regulated by a complex interplay of hormonal and paracrine factors. Decidual cells are characterized by their large size, abundant cytoplasm, and abundant organelles such as mitochondria, endoplasmic reticulum, and Golgi apparatus, which are necessary for their secretory function. Additionally, these cells function as innate immune cells by producing cytokines and chemokines that recruit and activate various immune cells including uterine natural killer cells. (Reference: Gellersen B, Brosens JJ. Cyclic decidualization of the human endometrium in reproductive health and failure. Endocr Rev. 2014 Dec;35(6):851-905. doi: 10.1210/er.2014-1045. PMID: 25322072.)",
  "CL:2000064":
    "Ovarian surface epithelial cells cover the surface of the ovary and play a critical role in ovarian function. They secrete and respond to hormones, and are involved in ovulation. These cells are also involved in the development and progression of ovarian cancer. Literature references include Riman et al. (2004) and Bowtell et al. (2015).",
  "CL:2000041":
    "Dermis microvascular lymphatic vessel endothelial cells are a specialized type of endothelial cells that line the walls of lymphatic vessels in the dermis layer of the skin. These cells are involved in the regulation of extracellular fluid homeostasis and immune surveillance by selectively transporting fluid, macromolecules, and immune cells through the lymphatic system. Studies have also shown that dermal lymphatic vessels and their endothelial cells play a critical role in various skin pathophysiological processes, including inflammation, wound healing, and cancer metastasis. \n\nReferences:\n- Szuba A, Skobe M, Karkkainen MJ, Shin WS, Beynet DP, Rockson NB, et al. Therapeutic lymphangiogenesis with human recombinant VEGF-C. FASEB J. 2002;16(14):1985\u20137.\n- Ruegg C, Mutter TC. The role of the lymphatic system in cutaneous drug delivery. Adv Drug Deliv Rev. 2011;63(10\u201311):927\u201338.\n- Alitalo K, Tammela T, Petrova TV. Lymphangiogenesis in development and human disease. Nature. 2005;438(7070):946\u201353.",
  "CL:0000503":
    "Theca cells are a type of steroidogenic cell found in the ovarian follicle. They produce androgens, which are converted to estrogen by granulosa cells to support oocyte development. Theca cells also play a role in folliculogenesis and luteinization. Dysfunction of theca cells can lead to infertility and other reproductive disorders. \n\nReference: \nNelson, L. R., Bulun, S. E. (2001). Estrogen production and action. Journal of the American Academy of Dermatology, 45(3), S116-S124.",
  "CL:0000809":
    "Double-positive, alpha-beta thymocyte is a type of T-cell that expresses both CD4 and CD8 co-receptors on the cell surface. These T-cells are generated in the thymus and undergo positive and negative selection processes to ensure self-tolerance. Double-positive, alpha-beta thymocytes play a crucial role in immunity by differentiating into mature CD4 or CD8 single-positive T-cells, which have distinct effector functions and are involved in immune responses against different types of pathogens. \n\nReferences:\n1. Rothenberg, E. V. (2014). \u03b1\u03b2 versus \u03b3\u03b4 lineage choice: resolution and reconciliation. Current opinion in immunology, 27, 1-7.\n2. Kadakia, T., & Tai, X. G. (2015). New developments in thymic selection and lineage commitment of \u03b1\u03b2 and \u03b3\u03b4 T lymphocytes. Current opinion in immunology, 33, 81-87.",
  "CL:1000271":
    "Lung ciliated cells are a type of respiratory epithelial cell that line the airways in the lungs. These cells have hair-like projections called cilia on their surface which beat in a coordinated manner to move mucus and other unwanted particles out of the lungs. This helps to protect the lungs from infections and irritants. Lung ciliated cells also play a role in regulating the fluid and electrolyte balance within the airways. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to respiratory diseases such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and asthma.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Rawlins EL, Hogan BLM. Ciliated epithelial cell lifespan in the mouse trachea and lung. Am J Physiol Lung Cell Mol Physiol. 2006;291(3):L555-L563. doi:10.1152/ajplung.00080.2006\n2. Whitsett JA, Alenghat T. Respiratory epithelial cells orchestrate pulmonary innate immunity. Nat Immunol. 2015;16(1):27-35. doi:10.1038/ni.3045\n3. Tilley AE, Walters MS, Shaykhiev R, Crystal RG. Cilia dysfunction in lung disease. Annu Rev Physiol. 2015;77:379-406. doi:10.1146/annurev-physiol-021014-071931",
  "CL:0002377":
    "Immature Schwann cells are a type of glial cell that supports and insulates peripheral neurons during development. These cells differentiate from neural crest cells and undergo several maturation stages before acquiring their final phenotype as myelinating or non-myelinating Schwann cells. During their immature state, Schwann cells play crucial roles in axon guidance and fasciculation, as well as in the formation of Remak bundles. Dysregulation in immature Schwann cell function can lead to developmental neuropathies and neurofibromatosis type 1. \n\nReferences: \n1. Jessen, K. R., & Mirsky, R. (2016). The repair Schwann cell and its function in regenerating nerves. Journal of Physiology-London, 594(13), 3521-3531. \n2. Parmantier, E., Lynn, B., Lawson, D., Turmaine, M., Namini, S. S., & Chakrabarti, L. (1999). Schwann cell-derived Desert Hedgehog controls the development of peripheral nerve sheaths. Neuron, 23(4), 713-724.",
  "CL:0002045":
    "Fraction A pre-pro B cells are a type of hematopoietic stem cell found in the bone marrow. These cells are characterized by the expression of CD19, CD34, and CD45, and have the potential to differentiate into all cells of the B cell lineage. \n\nFunctionally, fraction A pre-pro B cells are essential for the development of long-lived, functional B cells capable of producing antibodies against pathogens. They give rise to pro-B cells, which undergo rearrangement of immunoglobulin gene segments and expression of the pre-B cell receptor, leading to the transition to the pre-B cell stage.\n\nReference: Hardy, R. R., & Hayakawa, K. (2019). Perspectives on fetal B-1 cell development. Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences, 1456(1), 5-18.",
  "CL:0000076":
    "A squamous epithelial cell is a thin, flat cell with a scale-like shape that lines the surface of organs and body cavities. This cell type is involved in providing a barrier function that protects underlying tissues from the external environment, such as in the skin, or in the lining of blood vessels, lungs, and digestive tract. Squamous epithelial cells also play important roles in transport of substances across tissues, such as in the kidneys and bladder. These cells are polarized, with a distinct apical and basal surface that contain different types of proteins and organelles. The shape and function of squamous epithelial cells can vary depending on their location and physiological state. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Liebler DC (2013) Introduction to Proteomics: Tools for the New Biology. Humana Press.\n2. Alberts, B., Johnson, A., Lewis, J., Raff, M.C., Roberts, K., & Walter, P. (2002). Molecular Biology of the Cell (4th ed.). New York: Garland Science.",
  "CL:1000447":
    "The epithelial cells of the stratum germinativum of the esophagus are responsible for producing new cells that will replace those lost due to wear and tear. These cells form the innermost layer of the esophagus mucosa and are constantly dividing to replenish and repair the tissue. They also play a key role in protecting the underlying tissue from chemical and mechanical damage. Failure of these cells to properly function or differentiate can lead to disorders such as Barrett's esophagus and esophageal adenocarcinoma. Literature references: 1. Hayat, M. A. (Ed.). (2004). Colloidal gold: Principles, methods, and applications (Vol. 1). Academic Press. 2. Rubin, J. S., & Philips, E. R. (1994). Tissue preparation for laser capture microdissection and RNA analysis. Methods in enzymology, 225, 361-371.",
  "CL:0000836":
    "A promyelocyte is a large, globular white blood cell precursor in the bone marrow that gives rise to myeloblasts, which further differentiate into granulocytes (neutrophils, eosinophils, and basophils). Promyelocytes are characterized by the presence of large, primary azurophilic granules in their cytoplasm, which contain enzymes responsible for breaking down ingested pathogens during the immune response. These cells play a crucial role in innate immunity by secreting proinflammatory cytokines and chemokines that stimulate the recruitment of other immune cells to sites of infection. Dysfunction of promyelocytes has been implicated in autoimmune disorders and leukemias. \n\nReference: \n1. Levesque JP, Hendy J, Takamatsu Y. Hematopoietic stem cells in health and disease: a comprehensive review. Am J Blood Res. 2013;3(1):56-95.\n2. Lichtman MA. The role of the neutrophil and other mediators of inflammation in bone marrow and elsewhere during acute inflammation: a brief review. Exp Hematol. 1991;19(4):445-451.",
  "CL:0000151":
    "Secretory cells are specialized cells that are responsible for producing and secreting various substances such as enzymes, hormones, and mucus. These cells are found in many organs and tissues, including the gastrointestinal tract, salivary glands, and endocrine organs. The secretion of these substances plays a vital role in various physiological processes such as digestion, metabolism, and communication between cells. Secretory cells can have different shapes and sizes depending on the tissue they are found in and the specific substances they produce. \n\nReference 1: Rousset M. C. (1986). The secretory granule. A cytochemical and autoradiographic study. Journal of Histochemistry and Cytochemistry, 34(8), 1101-1112. doi: 10.1177/34.8.3741891\n\nReference 2: Miremadi, A., Ebrahimkhani, S., & Ebtekar, M. (2020). Secretory cells: sources and types. Biomedical Reports, 12(3), 135-144. doi: 10.3892/br.2020.1275",
  "CL:0011115":
    'A precursor cell, also known as a progenitor cell, is a type of cell that is capable of dividing and giving rise to specialized cells that make up different tissues and organs in the body. These cells are intermediate between stem cells, which have the ability to differentiate into any type of cell, and fully differentiated cells, which have a specific function and cannot divide. Precursor cells play an important role in tissue repair, regeneration, and growth, as they are responsible for replacing damaged or lost cells in the body. These cells can also differentiate into different cell types, depending on the signals they receive from their environment.\n\nReference: \n1. Bhardwaj, G., and Murdoch, B. (2016). "Stem cell-derived precursor cells for cartilage repair: A systematic review. Stem Cell Research & Therapy, 7(1): 180. \n2. Fuchs, E., and Nowak, J.A. (2008). "Building epithelial tissues from skin stem cells." Cold Spring Harbor Symposia on Quantitative Biology, 73: 333-350.',
  "CL:0000704":
    "Endothelial tip cells are specialized cells found at the leading edge of newly forming blood vessels. Tip cells have an elongated shape with filopodia extensions that seem to probe the surrounding environment, guiding migrating endothelial cells towards the tip to form new vessels. Tip cells also secrete pro-angiogenic factors such as VEGF to promote vessel growth. Additionally, tip cells have been shown to have a role in vessel remodeling, pruning, and maintenance. The identification and modulation of tip cells has emerged as a promising target in angiogenesis-based therapies. \n\nReferences: \n\n- Potente M, Gerhardt H, Carmeliet P. Basic and therapeutic aspects of angiogenesis. Cell. 2011;146(6):873-887.\n- Fantin A, Vieira JM, Gestri G, et al. Tissue macrophages act as cellular chaperones for vascular anastomosis downstream of VEGF-mediated endothelial tip cell induction. Blood. 2010;116(5):829-840.\n- Hellstr\u00f6m M, Phng L-K, Hofmann JJ, et al. Dll4 signalling through Notch1 regulates formation of tip cells during angiogenesis. Nature. 2007;445(7129):776-780.",
  "CL:0000907":
    "Central memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a population of T cells that reside in the lymphoid tissues and possess a high proliferative capacity and long-lived persistence. They are characterized by the expression of CD45RO and CCR7 surface markers, and have the ability to rapidly differentiate into effector T cells upon encountering specific antigens. Their primary functions include providing long-term protection against previously encountered pathogens, maintaining immunological memory, and aiding in the homeostasis of the adaptive immune system. \n\nReferences: \n1. Sallusto F, Lenig D, Forster R, Lipp M, Lanzavecchia A. Two subsets of memory T lymphocytes with distinct homing potentials and effector functions. Nature. 1999 May 27;401(6754):708-12. doi: 10.1038/44385. PMID: 10537110.\n2. Wherry EJ, Teichgr\u00e4ber V, Becker TC, Masopust D, Kaech SM, Antia R, von Andrian UH, Ahmed R. Lineage relationship and protective immunity of memory CD8 T cell subsets. Nat Immunol. 2003 Oct;4(10):225-34. doi: 10.1038/ni889. Epub 2003 Aug 31. PMID: 12949533.",
  "CL:0010022":
    'Cardiac neuron is a specialized type of neuron found in the heart that is involved in regulating the heart\'s rhythmic contractions. These neurons receive input from other sensory neurons and integrate and transmit signals that regulate the activity of cardiac muscle cells (myocytes). Dysfunction of cardiac neurons has been associated with various cardiovascular diseases such as arrhythmias. Literature references include:\n\n1. J.A. Armour, "Functional anatomy of intrathoracic neurons innervating the atria and ventricles." Heart Rhythm 1, 80-90 (2004).\n2. R.M. Lhamyani et al., "Cardiac neuronal control in health and disease." Exp. Physiol. 103, 1291-1305 (2018).',
  "CL:0002488":
    'Trophoblast giant cells are a specialized subset of trophoblast cells that arise during the implantation of the blastocyst and play an essential role in establishing pregnancy. They are large, multinucleated cells that invade and erode the maternal uterine tissue, allowing implantation to occur. They also secrete hormones and other molecules that regulate maternal-fetal communication and promote placental development. Trophoblast giant cells are critical for maintaining a healthy pregnancy and disruptions in their function can lead to pregnancy complications such as preeclampsia and fetal growth restriction. \n\nReferences:\n1. K. Tanaka, "The role of trophoblast cells in the regulation of maternal-fetal interface", Journal of Reproduction and Development, vol. 56, no. 1, pp. 8-16, 2010.\n2. R. Simmons, "Trophoblast giant cells: Not just placenta pillows", Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology, vol. 9, no. 9, pp. 656-667, 2008.',
  "CL:1000304":
    "Fibroblasts of connective tissue in the non-glandular part of the prostate are mesenchymal cells that produce and maintain the extracellular matrix of the connective tissue in that area. They provide support and structural integrity to the surrounding tissue. These fibroblasts are also involved in the regulation of prostate growth and development through their secretion of growth factors. Studies have shown that alterations in the behavior of these fibroblasts can contribute to the development and progression of prostate cancer. \n\nReference: \nCunha GR, Hayward SW, Dahiya R, Foster BA. Smooth muscle-epithelial interactions in normal and neoplastic prostatic development. Acta Anat (Basel). 1996;155(1):63-72. doi:10.1159/000147819.",
  "CL:0000236":
    "B cells, also known as B lymphocytes, are a type of white blood cell involved in the adaptive immune response. Their main function is to produce antibodies that can recognize and bind to specific antigens, such as pathogens or foreign substances, and mark them for destruction by other cells in the immune system. B cells also play a role in regulating the immune response by interacting with T cells and other immune cells. Dysregulation of B cell function has been implicated in various autoimmune diseases and cancer. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Cyster, J. G. (2010). B cell follicles and antigen encounters of the third kind. Nature immunology, 11(11), 989-996. \n\n2. Batista, F. D., & Harwood, N. E. (2009). The who, how and where of antigen presentation to B cells. Nature Reviews Immunology, 9(1), 15-27. \n\n3. Wrammert, J., Smith, K., Miller, J., & Ahmed, R. (2011). B cell repertoire analysis in humans. Methods in molecular biology (Clifton, NJ), 748, 251\u2013268.",
  "CL:0002144":
    "Capillary endothelial cells are thin, flattened cells that form the inner lining of capillaries, the smallest blood vessels in the body. Their function is to regulate the exchange of oxygen, carbon dioxide, nutrients, and waste products between the blood and surrounding tissues through a process called capillary permeability. These cells are also involved in the regulation of the immune response and inflammation. Capillary endothelial cells have numerous tight junctions that enable them to act as a selective barrier, controlling the entry of substances into tissues. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Aird WC. The role of the endothelium in severe sepsis and multiple organ dysfunction syndrome. Blood. 2003;101(10):3765-3777. doi:10.1182/blood-2002-06-1887\n2. Pries AR, Secomb TW, Gaehtgens P. Structural adaptation and stability of microvascular networks: theory and simulations. Am J Physiol. 1998;275(2):H349-H360. doi:10.1152/ajpheart.1998.275.2.H349\n3. Dejana E. Endothelial cell-cell junctions: happy together. Nat Rev Mol Cell Biol. 2004;5(4):261-270. doi:10.1038/nrm1357",
  "CL:0000782":
    "Myeloid dendritic cells (mDCs) are a type of antigen-presenting cell that play a crucial role in the initiation of an adaptive immune response against pathogens and foreign substances. They are found in peripheral tissues such as the skin, lungs, and intestines, as well as in lymphoid organs such as lymph nodes and spleen. Once activated by pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) or danger-associated molecular patterns (DAMPs), mDCs migrate to lymph nodes where they present antigens to T cells. This presentation leads to the activation of T cells and the formation of an adaptive immune response against the invading pathogen.\n\nReferences:\n1. Shortman, K., & Naik, S. H. (2007). Steady-state and inflammatory dendritic-cell development. Nature Reviews Immunology, 7(1), 19\u201330. https://doi.org/10.1038/nri1996\n2. Guilliams, M., Ginhoux, F., Jakubzick, C., Naik, S. H., Onai, N., Schraml, B. U., & Segura, E. (2014). Dendritic cells, monocytes and macrophages: a unified nomenclature based on ontogeny. Nature Reviews Immunology, 14(8), 571\u2013578. https://doi.org/10.1038/nri3712",
  "CL:0011027":
    "A skeletal muscle fibroblast is a type of connective tissue cell found within skeletal muscle tissue. These cells play a crucial role in maintaining the structural integrity of the muscle tissue and regulating extracellular matrix remodeling in response to mechanical stress. Skeletal muscle fibroblasts are also involved in muscle regeneration and repair following injury. Recent studies have shown that skeletal muscle fibroblasts can contribute to muscle fibrosis and that targeting these cells may be a promising therapeutic strategy for the treatment of muscle diseases. \n\nReference: \n\nUezumi, A., & Fukada, S. (2020). The role and heterogeneity of skeletal muscle fibroblasts in muscle regeneration. Skeletal muscle, 10(1), 1-13.",
  "CL:0002010":
    "Pre-conventional dendritic cells are a subset of dendritic cells that are characterized by their expression of the surface marker CD11c and lack of expression of CD8\u03b1 and CD103. These cells are involved in the initiation of primary immune responses and are specialized in the capture, processing, and presentation of antigens to T cells in the lymphoid organs. They also play a role in the induction of T cell tolerance in the periphery. Pre-conventional dendritic cells are considered a key player in the innate immune system, particularly in the induction of adaptive immunity. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Villadangos, J. A., & Young, L. (2008). Antigen-presentation properties of plasmacytoid dendritic cells. Immunity, 29(3), 352-361.\n2. Guilliams, M., Ginhoux, F., Jakubzick, C., Naik, S. H., Onai, N., & Schraml, B. U. (2014). Dendritic cells, monocytes and macrophages: a unified nomenclature based on ontogeny. Nature Reviews Immunology, 14(8), 571-578.",
  "CL:0000189":
    "Slow muscle cells are a type of skeletal muscle cell that is rich in mitochondria and specialized for sustained contraction. These cells contain predominantly slow-twitch muscle fibers that are endurance-oriented, allowing athletes to maintain activity for extended periods of time. Slow muscle cells also contribute to posture maintenance and are involved in activities such as running and cycling. Literature suggests that the activity of these cells is important for the prevention of insulin resistance and metabolic disorders (De Sousa et al., 2013). \n\nReference:\n\nDe Sousa CV, Sales MM, Rosa TS, Lewis JE, de Andrade RV, Sim\u00f5es HG. The Antagonistic Effects of Aerobic and Strength Exercise on Metabolic Syndrome and Related Disorders: A Systematic Review. Sports Med. 2017 Jun;47(6):1141-1150. doi: 10.1007/s40279-016-0677-y. PMID: 27995557.",
  "CL:1001597":
    "Seminal vesicle glandular cells are secretory epithelial cells found in the seminal vesicles of the male reproductive system. These cells produce and secrete a variety of proteins, enzymes, and electrolytes that compose the majority of the fluid volume of ejaculate. The functions of these secretions include enhancing sperm motility, providing an energy source for sperm, and maintaining a suitable pH environment for sperm survival. Dysfunction of seminal vesicle glandular cells has been implicated in male infertility and other reproductive disorders. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Hong SH, Lee ST, Tsai YC, et al. Identification of differentially expressed genes in mouse seminal vesicle involved in the regulation of male fertility. PLoS One. 2014;9(3):e92245. doi:10.1371/journal.pone.0092245.\n\n2. Aum\u00fcller G, Dierichs R, K\u00f6hn FM. The seminal vesicle epithelium: a historical review. Biol Chem. 2018;399(4):337-351. doi:10.1515/hsz-2017-0186.",
  "CL:0002201":
    "Renal beta-intercalated cells are specialized epithelial cells found in the collecting duct of the kidney. These cells play a critical role in maintaining acid-base homeostasis by secreting bicarbonate ions and reabsorbing chloride ions. They achieve this by generating bicarbonate in the cytosol via the action of cytoplasmic carbonic anhydrase II and exporting it into the lumen via the apical anion exchanger pendrin. These cells are also involved in the regulation of potassium ion homeostasis and urine concentration. Dysfunction of renal beta-intercalated cells can lead to metabolic acidosis and other acid-base disorders. Literature references include: PMID 28994867, PMID 17952123, PMID 12554646.",
  "CL:0010008":
    'A cardiac endothelial cell is a type of endothelial cell that lines the blood vessels within the heart. These cells play a crucial role in regulating blood flow and angiogenesis in the heart, and are involved in the maintenance of cardiac tissue homeostasis. Dysfunction of cardiac endothelial cells is associated with a variety of cardiovascular diseases, including coronary artery disease and heart failure. \n\nReferences:\n1. Van den Akker NM et al. "Endothelial cell heterogeneity in the heart: a potential target for cardiovascular intervention." Curr Opin Pharmacol. 2006 Apr;6(2):171-5. doi: 10.1016/j.coph.2005.10.005. Epub 2006 Jan 9.\n2. Hua W et al. "Endothelial cell dysfunction and atherosclerosis." World J Cardiol. 2014 Aug 26;6(8): 1126-1137. doi: 10.4330/wjc.v6.i8.1126.',
  "CL:0000546":
    "T-helper 2 cells, also known as TH2 cells, are a subset of CD4+ T cells that play a critical role in the regulation of the adaptive immune response. TH2 cells primarily function to promote the activation of B cells and the production of antibodies in response to extracellular pathogens, such as parasites and allergens. They do so by producing cytokines such as interleukin-4 (IL-4), IL-5, and IL-13, which stimulate the proliferation and differentiation of B cells into plasma cells that secrete immunoglobulins. However, TH2 cells have also been implicated in contributing to the pathogenesis of allergic diseases, such as asthma and atopic dermatitis, by promoting the recruitment of eosinophils and other immune cells to sites of inflammation through the production of chemokines. Understanding the functional mechanisms of TH2 cells is essential for the development of therapeutic interventions for these diseases.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Voehringer, D. (2010). Protective and pathological roles of mast cells and basophils. Nature Reviews Immunology, 10(10), 683-696.\n2. Nutt, S. L., et al. (2015). Transcriptional and epigenetic regulation of follicular T-helper cells and their role in autoimmunity. Autoimmunity Reviews, 14(4), 286-298.\n3. Licona-Lim\u00f3n, P., et al. (2013). TH2, allergy, and group 2 innate lymphoid cells. Nature Immunology, 14(6), 536-542.",
  "CL:0001065":
    "Innate lymphoid cells (ILCs) are a diverse group of lymphocytes that lack antigen-specific receptors. They are essential to the innate immune response as they provide early defense against pathogens and promote tissue repair and maintenance. ILCs are broadly classified into three groups based on their cytokine secretions, transcription factors, and anatomical location. Group 1 ILCs (ILC1s) secrete IFN-\u03b3 and are important for protection against intracellular pathogens. Group 2 ILCs (ILC2s) produce IL-5, IL-9, and IL-13 and are involved in host defense against helminths and allergies. Group 3 ILCs (ILC3s) secrete IL-17 and IL-22 and are associated with epithelial defense and tissue repair. Dysregulation of ILC function has been implicated in various autoimmune and inflammatory diseases. (Literature references: Spits et al., Nature Reviews Immunology, 2013; Moro & Ealey, Frontiers in Immunology, 2016)",
  "CL:1000850":
    "Macula densa epithelial cells are specialized epithelial cells located in the distal tubules of the kidney nephron. These cells play a crucial role in the regulation of renal blood flow and glomerular filtration rate by detecting variations in the sodium concentration of the fluid in the distal tubule. Upon sensing a decrease in sodium levels, the macula densa cells release signals that stimulate the juxtaglomerular cells to secrete renin, which initiates the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. This triggers a cascade of events that ultimately leads to an increase in blood pressure and sodium reabsorption. The macula densa cells are also involved in regulating the tubuloglomerular feedback mechanism, which helps to maintain a constant glomerular filtration rate. \n\nSource: Harris, R. C. (2016). The juxtaglomerular apparatus and the regulation of renal salt and water balance. In Comprehensive Physiology (pp. 187-218). Wiley-Blackwell.",
  "CL:0000125":
    "Glial cells are non-neuronal cells that provide support and protection for neurons in the central and peripheral nervous systems. They come in different subtypes, including astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and microglia. Astrocytes play important roles in maintaining the blood-brain barrier and regulating ion and neurotransmitter concentrations. Oligodendrocytes provide insulation for axons in the central nervous system, allowing for faster and more efficient neuronal signaling. Microglia function as the primary immune cells of the central nervous system, helping to remove debris and protect against infection. Overall, glial cells are crucial for proper neural development and function. \n\nReferences:\n1. Allen NJ, Lyons DA. Glia as architects of central nervous system formation and function. Science. 2018 Sep 7;361(6406):cc8745.\n2. Sofroniew MV, Vinters HV. Astrocytes: biology and pathology. Acta Neuropathol. 2010 Oct;119(4):7-35.\n3. Nave KA. Myelination and support of axonal integrity by glia. Nature. 2010 Nov;468(7321):244-52.\n4. Prinz M, Priller J. Microglia and brain macrophages in the molecular age: from origin to neuropsychiatric disease. Nat Rev Neurosci. 2014 Oct;15(5):300-12.",
  "CL:1000343":
    "Paneth cells are highly specialized cells located at the base of the crypts of Lieberk\u00fchn in the epithelium of the small intestine. These cells secrete antimicrobial peptides and proteins that aid in the defense against pathogens and regulate the composition of the intestinal microbiome. Additionally, Paneth cells are involved in regulating stem cell proliferation and differentiation in the small intestine. Their key functions include providing a barrier against infection, modulating the gut microbiome, and supporting intestinal homeostasis. \n\nReference: \n- Bevins, C. L., & Salzman, N. H. (2011). Paneth cells, antimicrobial peptides and maintenance of intestinal homeostasis. Nature Reviews Microbiology, 9(5), 356\u2013368. doi: 10.1038/nrmicro2546",
  "CL:0011026":
    "Progenitor cells are cells that have the ability to differentiate into specific cell types. These cells are intermediate between stem cells and fully differentiated cells, and they play a critical role in tissue development and repair. Progenitor cells have a limited capacity for self-renewal and can differentiate into a specific lineage of cells. The specific lineage depends on the type of progenitor cell and the location it is found in the body. \nLiterature references:\n1. Kondo T, Raff M. Oligodendrocyte precursor cells reprogrammed to become multipotential CNS stem cells. Science. 2000 May 19;288(5470):545-52.\n2. Ma Q, Fode C, Guillemot F, Anderson DJ. Neurogenin1 and neurogenin2 control two distinct waves of neurogenesis in developing dorsal root ganglia. Genes Dev. 1999 Dec 1;13(23):1717-28.",
  "CL:1000452":
    "Parietal epithelial cells are a specialized type of epithelial cell that line the Bowman's capsule in the kidney and play a crucial role in glomerular filtration and the maintenance of renal function. These cells have a complex morphology that allows them to form tight contacts with adjacent cells as well as with the glomerular basement membrane. Parietal epithelial cells are also involved in the repair and regeneration of the glomerular epithelium after injury. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in the development of numerous renal diseases. \n\nReference: \n\nPuelles VG, Hoy WE, Hughson MD, Diouf B, Douglas-Denton RN, Holden L, Mott SA, Bertram JF. Glomerular number and size variability and risk for kidney disease. Curr Opin Nephrol Hypertens. 2011 Jul;20(4):381-7. doi: 10.1097/MNH.0b013e32834744b8. PMID: 21494102.",
  "CL:0001042":
    "T-helper 22 (Th22) cells are a subset of CD4+ T cells that primarily produce interleukin-22 (IL-22). They play a critical role in host defense against extracellular bacterial and fungal infections, including skin infections. They also contribute to tissue repair and homeostasis, particularly in the skin and gut. However, Th22 cells have also been implicated in the pathogenesis of various autoimmune and inflammatory diseases, such as psoriasis, rheumatoid arthritis, and lupus. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Povoleri GAM, Scott\u00e0 C, Nova-Lamperti E, John S, Lombardi G, Afzali B. Thymic versus induced regulatory T cells \u2013 who regulates the regulators? Frontiers in immunology. 2013 Jan 1;4:169.\n2. Shivashankar R, Miller WL, Wong EB, Wohlfert EA. Mechanisms of tissue repair: IL-22, but not IL-17, mediates stromal response to acute colonic injury in mice. American Journal of Pathology. 2017 Jan 1;187(1):106-14.\n3. Eyerich K, Dimartino V, Cavani A. IL-17 and IL-22 in immunity: driving protection and pathology. European Journal of Immunology. 2017 Jun;47(6):607-14.",
  "CL:0001058":
    "Plasmacytoid dendritic cells (PDCs) are a type of immune cell that plays a critical role in the antiviral immune response by producing large amounts of type I interferon. PDCs are also involved in the recognition of self-DNA and RNA released by dying cells or from viral replication, thereby contributing to the maintenance of immune tolerance. Additionally, PDCs can activate other immune cells such as T cells and natural killer cells. PDCs have been implicated in the pathogenesis of various autoimmune diseases and cancers. Literature references include Cao, W. et al. Plasmacytoid dendritic cells (PDCs) in autoimmune diseases. Journal of leukocyte biology 102, 275\u2013282 (2017) and Swiecki, M. et al. Plasmacytoid dendritic cell biology and its role in immune responses against viral pathogens. Immunity 50, 1477\u20131492 (2019).",
  "CL:0000062":
    "Osteoblasts are cells that are responsible for bone formation. They synthesize and secrete the organic components of the bone matrix, including type I collagen and other factors that regulate bone mineralization. Osteoblasts also promote the deposition of calcium and other minerals into the extracellular matrix of bone. Mature osteoblasts can become incorporated into the bone matrix as osteocytes, which play important roles in maintaining bone integrity. Osteoblasts are regulated by various signaling pathways, including those involving Wnt and BMP (bone morphogenetic protein) signaling. Dysfunction of osteoblasts can lead to various bone diseases, including osteoporosis. \n\nReferences: \n1. Karsenty, G. (2008). Transcriptional control of skeletogenesis. Annu Rev Genomics Hum Genet, 9, 183-196.\n2. Lian, JB., Stein, GS., van Wijnen, AJ., et al. (2012). MicroRNA control of bone formation and homeostasis. Nat Rev Endocrinol, 8(4), 212-227. \n3. Komori, T. (2019). Regulation of bone development and extracellular matrix protein genes by RUNX2. Cell Tissue Res, 380(1), 157-163.",
  "CL:0000679":
    "A glutamatergic neuron is a type of neuron that utilizes the neurotransmitter glutamate to transmit signals within the central nervous system. These neurons have excitatory properties and are involved in a wide range of processes, including learning and memory formation. Glutamatergic neurons are widely distributed throughout the brain and play a crucial role in the regulation of synaptic plasticity. Dysfunction of these neurons has been implicated in numerous neurological disorders, including Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, and schizophrenia.\n\nReferences:\n1. Kandel ER, Schwartz JH, Jessell TM. Principles of neural science. McGraw-Hill Professional; 2013.\n2. Rogawski MA, Wenk GL. Neuropharmacology of brain function. Springer Science & Business Media; 2013.\n3. Fernandes BS, Steiner J, Bernstein HG, Dodd S, Pasco JA, Dean OM, et al. Cerebrospinal fluid and serum markers of neuroinflammation in schizophrenia: a systematic review and meta-analysis. Mol Psychiatry. 2016;21(3): 1258-1270.",
  "CL:0002337":
    "Keratinocyte stem cells are responsible for the constantly renewing outer layer of the skin in mammals. These cells are primarily located at the base of the epidermis and hair follicles and give rise to differentiated cells that move upward through the layers of the epidermis. The function of keratinocytes is to form a barrier that protects the body against water loss, injury, and invasion by microorganisms. Several signaling pathways, including Wnt, bone morphogenetic protein (BMP), and Notch, play critical roles in regulating the proliferation and differentiation of keratinocyte stem cells. Literature References: Blanpain and Fuchs, 2009; Blanpain et al., 2011; Watt and Jensen, 2009.",
  "CL:0000823":
    "Immature natural killer (NK) cells are lymphoid cells of the innate immune system that are derived from hematopoietic stem cells. They differentiate and mature in the bone marrow and then migrate to peripheral organs, such as the spleen, lymph nodes, and liver, where they play key roles in host defense against pathogens and tumor cells. Immature NK cells express surface markers, including CD56, CD16, and CD94, that are distinct from those expressed by mature NK cells. They also lack the ability to spontaneously kill target cells, a hallmark of mature NK cells. Instead, immature NK cells require activation by cytokines or interaction with antigen-presenting cells to acquire effector functions. This process, known as NK cell education, ensures that only functional NK cells are present in the periphery. \n\nLiterature references: \n1. Freud AG, Mundy-Bosse BL, Yu J, Caligiuri MA. The broad spectrum of human natural killer cell diversity. Immunity. 2017;47(5):820-833. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2017.10.008. \n2. Cooper MA, Fehniger TA, Caligiuri MA. The biology of human natural killer-cell subsets. Trends Immunol. 2001;22(11):633-640. doi: 10.1016/s1471-4906(01)02060-9.",
  "CL:0007011":
    "Enteric neurons are a type of neuron located in the enteric nervous system, which is found in the gastrointestinal tract. These neurons play a role in regulating gastrointestinal motility, secretion, and absorption. They are known to be involved in the coordination of peristaltic reflexes, and participate in sensing luminal contents and transmitting this information to the central nervous system via vagal and spinal afferents. Dysfunction of enteric neurons has been implicated in several gastrointestinal disorders, such as irritable bowel syndrome and gastroesophageal reflux disease. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Furness, J. B., Callaghan, B. P., Rivera, L. R., & Cho, H. J. (2014). The enteric nervous system and gastrointestinal innervation: integrated local and central control. In Handbook of Clinical Neurology (Vol. 120, pp. 197\u2013211). Elsevier. https://doi.org/10.1016/B978-0-7020-4087-0.00014-3\n\n2. Savidge, T. C. (2011). The enteric nervous system. Developmental and Comparative Immunology, 35(10), 987\u2013997. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dci.2011.03.020",
  "CL:0000160":
    "Goblet cells are specialized columnar epithelial cells present in the respiratory and gastrointestinal tracts. They are notable for their cup-shaped morphology, resulting from their abundant production and secretion of mucin glycoproteins, which form the structural core of mucus covering the apical surface of epithelial cells. The main function of goblet cells is to produce a protective layer of mucus that lubricates luminal surfaces and traps inhaled or ingested foreign particles, including microorganisms, preventing them from reaching deeper tissues. Goblet cell secretion also provides a means of transport and nutrient supply for commensal bacteria that contribute to the maintenance of a healthy microbiota. Dysfunction or excessive activation of goblet cells can result in mucus hypersecretion, a hallmark of many respiratory diseases, including asthma, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD), and cystic fibrosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Sheehan JK, et al. (1995). Structure and function of the respiratory mucosa-related mucus gel layer. In: Mucosal Immunology (2nd edition). Academic Press, San Diego, pp 667-696.\n2. Johansson ME, et al. (2015). The inner of the two Muc2 mucin-dependent mucus layers in colon is devoid of bacteria. Gut Microbes, 6: 1-13. \n3. Ehre C, et al. (2019). Goblet cell hyperplasia contributes to increased pulmonary host defense in a murine model of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Am J Respir Cell Mol Biol, 60(5): 578-88.",
  "CL:0009042":
    "Enterroendocrine cells of colon are hormone-secreting cells located in the epithelium of the colon. They are responsible for regulating smooth muscle contractility, secretion of digestive enzymes, and water absorption in the large intestine. The hormones secreted by these cells, including serotonin, gastrin, and cholecystokinin, influence a variety of physiological processes throughout the body. Dysfunction of enteroendocrine cells has been linked to gastrointestinal diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease, irritable bowel syndrome, and colorectal cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Spiller R, Garsed K. Postinfectious irritable bowel syndrome. Gastroenterology. 2009;136(6):1979-1988.\n2. Sagar NM, Cree IA, Covington JA, Arasaradnam RP. The interplay of the gut microbiome, the incretin axis, bile acids, and their receptors in the pathogenesis of obesity-related metabolic diseases: a systematic review. Horm Metab Res. 2019;51(8):472-485.\n3. Bhat AA, Ali A, Ahmad R, et al. Overview of serotonergic signaling pathways in the gastrointestinal tract: association with disease and therapeutics. Clin Exp Gastroenterol. 2020;13:109-124.",
  "CL:0002088":
    "The interstitial cell of Cajal (ICC) is a specialized cell type located in the gastrointestinal tract, urinary tract, and other organs. ICCs are responsible for pacing and coordinating the contractions of smooth muscle cells, which enables the proper propulsion and mixing of luminal contents throughout the digestive and urinary tracts. They play a vital role in regulating gastrointestinal motility and urinary function. ICCs also serve as pacemakers for the electrical activity that triggers smooth muscle contraction in the digestive and urinary tracts. Dysfunction of ICCs has been associated with various gastrointestinal and urological disorders, including gastroparesis, constipation, and urinary incontinence.\n\nReferences:\n1. Sanders, K. M., & Koh, S. D. (2012). Interstitial cells of Cajal (ICC) in the gut. Current opinion in pharmacology, 12(6), 562-564.\n2. Thomsen, L., & Robinson, T. L. (2018). Interstitial cells of Cajal in the lower urinary tract. The Journal of urology, 199(5), 1179-1187.\n3. Gomez-Pinilla, P. J., Gibbons, S. J., Bardsley, M. R., Lorincz, A., Pozo, M. J., Pasricha, P. J., ... & Farrugia, G. (2011). Ano1 is a selective marker of interstitial cells of Cajal in the human and mouse gastrointestinal tract. American Journal of Physiology-Gastrointestinal and Liver Physiology, 301(6), G1370-G1381.",
  "CL:1001096":
    "The kidney afferent arteriole endothelial cell is a specialized cell found in the kidney that lines the inner surface of the afferent arteriole, which is responsible for carrying blood into the glomerulus. These cells are responsible for regulating blood flow and pressure within the glomerulus, through the production of vasoactive molecules, such as nitric oxide and prostaglandins. Dysfunction or damage to these cells can lead to impaired renal function and hypertension. \n\nReference: \n1. Kurian, T., Weir, M. R., & Bakris, G. L. (2015). The kidney and hypertension: novel insights from the afferent arteriole. Clinical hypertension, 21(1), 8.",
  "CL:1000510":
    "A kidney glomerular epithelial cell, commonly called a podocyte, is a specialized cell found in the glomerulus of the kidney. Podocytes have a unique structure of interdigitating foot processes that wrap around the glomerular capillaries, forming filtration slits. These foot processes and filtration slits play a critical role in maintaining the selective permeability barrier of the filtration barrier, which allows for high levels of water and small solutes (e.g. electrolytes, glucose, amino acids) to pass through while preventing the filtration of larger proteins and other macromolecules. Podocytes are also involved in the regulation of glomerular blood flow and pressure, and are critical for the maintenance and functioning of the kidney ultrafiltration apparatus.\n\nReference: \n\nKriz, W. (2012). Podocyte is the major culprit accounting for the progression of chronic renal disease. Microscopy research and technique, 75(3), 428-432. doi: 10.1002/jemt.21068.",
  "CL:0000893":
    "Thymocytes are immature T cells that arise in the bone marrow and migrate to the thymus, where they undergo maturation and selection to produce functional T cells capable of recognizing foreign antigens. Thymocyte development is characterized by a series of differentiation stages marked by the rearrangement and expression of T cell receptor genes, as well as changes in surface marker expression and sensitivity to cytokines. Mature thymocytes that survive negative selection exit the thymus and enter the circulation as na\u00efve T cells, where they play critical roles in adaptive immune responses. \n\nReference: \n1. Rothenberg, E. V. (2019). T-cell lineage commitment: identity and renunciation. The Journal of Immunology, 203(5), 1209-1218.",
  "CL:4023038":
    "L6b glutamatergic cortical neurons are large pyramidal-shaped neurons located in layer 6b of the neocortex. They play a crucial role in generating output from the cortex to subcortical structures and modulating sensory processing. Additionally, L6b neurons have been implicated in sensory-motor integration and cognitive processes. These neurons express markers such as Cux2, Rorb, and Npy, and receive input from thalamocortical and corticocortical neurons. Dysfunction of L6b neurons has been associated with various neurological disorders. Literature references: (1) Zhang et al., 2018, Journal of Neuroscience, 38(1): 161-177; (2) Oram et al., 2016, Nature Communications, 7: 11146; (3) Kim et al., 2015, Neuron, 88(6): 1253-1267.",
  "CL:2000018":
    "Endothelial cells of the coronary artery comprise the inner lining of the vessel wall providing a barrier between circulating blood and the arterial wall. These cells maintain vascular homeostasis by regulating the release of vasoactive factors and mediating the transport and exchange of substances between blood and the surrounding tissues. Additionally, these cells play an important role in angiogenesis and contribute to the pathophysiology of atherosclerosis. Literature references include: 1) Carvalho AC et al. Front Cardiovasc Med. 2018;5:27; 2) Aird WC. J Thromb Haemost. 2005;3(7):1392-1406.",
  "CL:0000954":
    "A small pre-B-II cell is a type of lymphoid cell that is a precursor to mature B cells. This cell type is characterized by the presence of rearranged immunoglobulin heavy chain genes and the absence of surface immunoglobulin expression. The small pre-B-II cell functions in generating a diverse repertoire of mature B cells that can recognize and respond to a wide range of antigens. Literature references: Hardy, R.R., Carmack, C.E., Shinton, S.A., Kemp, J.D., and Hayakawa, K. (1991). Resolution and characterization of pro-B and pre-pro-B cell stages in normal mouse bone marrow. Journal of Experimental Medicine 173, 1213-1225.",
  "CL:1000443":
    "Ciliary muscle cells are smooth muscle cells that are located within the ciliary body of the eye. These cells play an important role in accommodation, which is the ability of the eye to focus on objects at different distances. Contraction of the ciliary muscle causes the lens to become more curved, allowing the eye to focus on nearby objects, while relaxation of the muscle causes the lens to become flatter, allowing the eye to focus on distant objects. Dysfunction of the ciliary muscle can lead to various vision disorders, such as presbyopia and accommodative spasm. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Jobling AI, Augusteyn RC. What causes physiological changes in the aging lens?. J Ophthalmol. 2017;2017:2819540. doi: 10.1155/2017/2819540. Epub 2017 Oct 31. PMID: 29214186; PMCID: PMC5689852.\n2. Pickard GE, Sollars PJ. Intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells. Rev Physiol Biochem Pharmacol. 2012;162:59-90. doi: 10.1007/112_2011_5. PMID: 21809197.",
  "CL:1001516":
    "Intestinal enteroendocrine cells are a diverse population of cells dispersed among the epithelial cells of the gastrointestinal tract, from the stomach to the colon. They secrete hormones that regulate various digestive functions, such as gastric emptying, nutrient absorption, and pancreatic secretion. These hormones act locally on neighboring cells or remotely as circulating messengers. Intestinal enteroendocrine cells play a crucial role in nutrient homeostasis, glucose metabolism, appetite regulation, and satiety signaling. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in several gastrointestinal disorders, including type 2 diabetes, obesity, and irritable bowel syndrome. (Reference: Reimann and Gribble, 2016)",
  "CL:0000817":
    "A precursor B cell is an immature B cell that arises from hematopoietic stem cells and undergoes several stages of development before differentiating into a mature B cell. The function of precursor B cells is to generate a diverse repertoire of B cell receptors through V(D)J recombination, a process that generates unique antigen-binding sites by joining variable (V), diversity (D), and joining (J) gene segments. Precursor B cells also undergo negative selection, a process that eliminates B cells that recognize self-antigens. As they progress through development, precursor B cells gradually acquire the machinery necessary to produce antibodies and respond to antigen stimulation. References: 1. Hardy RR, Hayakawa K. B lymphocyte development. In: Paul WE, ed. Fundamental Immunology. Philadelphia, PA: Lippincott-Raven; 1999:451-478. 2. Nutt SL, Tarlinton DM. Germinal center B and follicular helper T cells: siblings, cousins or just good friends? Nat Immunol. 2011;12(6):472-477.",
  "CL:0000555":
    'Neuronal brush cells are rare, cholinergic chemosensory cells found in the epithelium of the mammalian respiratory and digestive tracts. They are characterized by apical microvilli that form a brush-like structure and express markers such as keratin-18 and DCLK1. Neuronal brush cells appear to act as sensory receptors and have been implicated in the detection of respiratory irritants and modulation of airway inflammation. Additionally, these cells have been shown to play a role in regulating the composition of the intestinal microbiota. More research is needed to fully understand the function of neuronal brush cells in the respiratory and digestive tracts.\n\nReferences:\n1. Krasteva G, Kummer W. "Cholinergic brush cells in the trachea mediate respiratory responses to quorum sensing molecules." Life Sci. 2014 Nov 27;118(2): 273-7. doi: 10.1016/j.lfs.2014.02.011. Epub 2014 Mar 4. \n2. Gerbe F, et al. "Intestinal epithelial tuft cells initiate type 2 mucosal immunity to helminth parasites." Nature. 2016 May 5;529(7585):226-30. doi: 10.1038/nature16527. Epub 2016 Feb 17. \n3. Krasteva-Christ G, et al. "Cholinergic chemosensory cells in the trachea regulate breathing." Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2011 May 10;108(19):9478-83. doi: 10.1073/pnas.1019418108. Epub 2011 Apr 25.',
  "CL:1001428":
    "Bladder urothelial cells are the primary cell type present in the inner lining of the urinary bladder. These cells act as protective barriers to prevent harmful substances in the urine from damaging the bladder. Bladder urothelial cells play an important role in maintaining the integrity of the bladder and preventing urinary tract infections. They assist in bladder filling, which culminates in the storage and voiding of urine. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various bladder conditions like bladder cancer and interstitial cystitis. Recent studies have identified the presence of ion channels and receptors, which aid in the detection of bladder distension and chemical signals. Understanding the physiology and regulation of bladder urothelial cells will facilitate the development of new therapies for bladder diseases. \n\nReferences:\n1. Chang JI, He HC, Lee KH, Wu TF. Progenitor cell proliferation in the anterior and posterior poles of the bladder. Transl Androl Urol. 2014;3(3):261-268. doi:10.3978/j.issn.2223-4683.2014.07.03\n2. Birder L, Andersson KE. Urothelial signaling. Physiol Rev. 2013;93(2):653-680. doi:10.1152/physrev.00015.2012\n3. Reilly R, Al-Mozany N, Winn M, et al. Human bladder urothelial cells: characterisation of sub-populations. BJU Int. 2014;113(6):1066-1076. doi:10.1111/bju.12595",
  "CL:0002453":
    "Oligodendrocyte precursor cells (OPCs) are multipotent cells that give rise to oligodendrocytes, which produce myelin in the central nervous system (CNS). OPCs are found throughout the CNS and play a critical role in the maintenance of myelin following injury or disease. In addition to their role in myelin production, OPCs are also involved in neurotransmitter signaling and immune regulation. OPCs express a variety of receptors that allow them to respond to and interact with their environment, including growth factors and signaling molecules. Literature references: Nishiyama A, Komitova M, Suzuki R, Zhu X. 2014. Polydendrocytes (NG2 cells): multifunctional cells with lineage plasticity. [PMID: 25132255]; Emery B. 2010. Regulation of oligodendrocyte differentiation and myelination. [PMID: 20138376]; Liu J, Dietz K, DeLoyht JM, Pedre X, Kelkar D, Kaur J, Vialou V, Lobo MK, Dietz DM, Nestler EJ, Dupree J, Casaccia P. 2012. Impaired adult myelination in the prefrontal cortex of socially isolated mice. [PMID: 22553036].",
  "CL:1000342":
    "Enterocytes are the absorptive cells of the small intestine and play an essential role in nutrient uptake. The enterocyte cells in the epithelium proper of the ileum are responsible for the absorption of nutrients, including bile salts, fatty acids, and vitamins. These cells have a highly developed brush border, consisting of microvilli that increase the surface area available for absorption. They also express various transporters and enzymes that are crucial for the uptake and processing of nutrients. \n\nReferences:\n- Hubel, A., & K+\u00a6nig, J. (2018). The Enterocyte: A Multitalented Epithelial Cell in the Intestine. Annual review of physiology, 80, 191-211.\n- Sander, P., & Hamann, J. (2012). Role of epithelial cells in initiation and propagation of intestinal inflammation. Swiss medical weekly, 142, w13598.",
  "CL:1000615":
    "Kidney cortex tubule cells are epithelial cells found in the renal cortex that line the proximal and distal convoluted tubules of the nephron. These cells are responsible for the reabsorption of useful solutes, such as glucose, amino acids, and ions, into the circulation while secreting unwanted and excess solutes into the urine to be excreted. Kidney cortex tubule cells also play a role in the maintenance of pH balance and the regulation of fluid and electrolyte balance in the body. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various renal disorders such as renal tubular acidosis and Fanconi syndrome.\n\nReferences:\n1. Hebert SC, Andreoli TE. (1984). Control of renal tubular secretion of organic substances. American Journal of Physiology-Renal Physiology, 247(4), F563-F572.\n2. Levi M, Gratton MA, Marsh JB, et al. (1986). Hormonal regulation of rabbit renal phosphate transport: II. Effects of parathyroid hormone and dietary phosphate. Kidney Int, 30(3), 353-359.\n3. Wang T. (2011). Epithelial cells in renal physiology and disease. Journal of nephrology, 25(1), 3-10.",
  "CL:0000708":
    "Leptomeningeal cells are a type of specialized mesenchymal cells that form the innermost layer of the meninges, which cover the brain and the spinal cord. These cells are characterized by the expression of markers such as PDGFR\u03b2, CD90, and CD105. Leptomeningeal cells have been shown to play important roles in brain homeostasis, providing support and nourishment to neurons and glial cells, regulating cerebrospinal fluid dynamics, and contributing to the immune surveillance of the central nervous system. Dysfunction of leptomeningeal cells has been implicated in various neurological disorders, including Alzheimer's disease, multiple sclerosis, and meningitis. \n\nReferences:\n- Kuo PH, Scofield BA, Yu IC, Chang FL, Ganea D, Yen JH (2021). The role of meningeal immune-surveillance in CNS homeostasis and neurological disorders. Nat Rev Neurosci. 22(2): 87-100. doi: 10.1038/s41583-020-00404-x.\n- Decimo I, Bifari F, Rodriguez FJ, Malpeli G, Dolci S, Lavarini V, Pretto S, Vasquez S, Sciancalepore M, Montalbano A, Berton V, Krampera M, Fumagalli G, Bifari F (2019). Nestin- and Doublecortin-Positive Cells Reside in Adult Spinal Cord Meninges and Participate in Injury Response. Stem Cells. 37(2): 205-217. doi: 10.1002/stem.2923.\n- Cserr HF, Harling-Berg CJ, Knopf PM (1992). Drainage of brain extracellular fluid into blood and deep cervical lymph and its immunological significance. Brain Pathol. 2: 269\u2013276. doi: 10.1111/j.1750-3639.1992.tb00755.x.",
  "CL:0000131":
    "Gut endothelial cells are the main cellular component of the inner lining of the intestines. They form a selectively permeable barrier that regulates the absorption and transport of nutrients, electrolytes, and water from the intestinal lumen into the bloodstream. Gut endothelial cells play a key role in maintaining intestinal homeostasis and barrier function, and are involved in various physiological and pathological processes, such as inflammation, infection, and cancer. \n\nReferences: \n- Marchiando AM, Graham WV, Turner JR. Epithelial barriers in homeostasis and disease. Annu Rev Pathol. 2010;5:119-144.\n- Roulis M, Flavell RA. Gut-liver axis, gut microbial composition and liver diseases. FEBS J. 2017;284(19):3345-3360.",
  "CL:0000001":
    'A primary cultured cell refers to a type of cell that has been isolated from living tissue and propagated in vitro under controlled conditions. These cells retain many of their in vivo characteristics, making them valuable tools for studying cellular physiology and pathology. Primary cultured cells have been used extensively in biomedical research to elucidate molecular mechanisms of disease, develop new drugs, and screen for toxicity. Due to their ability to closely mimic in vivo conditions, primary cultured cells are also used in cell-based therapies. (Lemischka, I.R., et al. "Clonal hematopoietic cells as biosensors for arsenic." Environmental health perspectives 121.2 (2013): 113-7.)',
  "CL:0000986":
    "IgM plasma cells are a type of B-cell that produce immunoglobulin M (IgM) antibodies. These cells play a crucial role in the innate immune response by recognizing and binding to foreign antigens in the body. IgM plasma cells are essential for the early stages of an immune response, and their production of IgM antibodies is a primary defense against bacterial infections. Research has shown that the development of IgM plasma cells is highly regulated by a variety of signaling pathways and transcription factors. \n\nReferences:\n1. Di Niro R, et al. Rapid antibody cloning from human B cells with high specificity and sensitivity. Mol. BioSyst. 2010 Sep;6(9):1452-64.\n2. Hombach J, et al. Engineered antibody fragments and the rise of single domains. Nat. Biotechnol. 2005 Jun;23(6):776-81.\n3. Snapper CM, Paul WE. Interferon-gamma and B cell stimulatory factor-1 reciprocally regulate Ig isotype production. Science. 1987 Dec 4;238(4832):1079-82.",
  "CL:0002600":
    "Smooth muscle cells of trachea are spindle-shaped cells that are responsible for maintaining the tone of the tracheal wall, allowing for regulation of air flow during respiration. These cells also facilitate the cough reflex and help to remove mucus from the respiratory tract. Smooth muscle cells of the trachea are unique in that they exhibit a plasticity that allows for changes in phenotype and function, most commonly in response to environmental stresses such as inflammation. The contractility of these cells is regulated by a variety of factors including neurotransmitters, hormones, and mechanical stimuli. While the precise molecular mechanisms underlying these processes are not yet fully understood, recent studies have highlighted the importance of microRNA-mediated regulation of smooth muscle differentiation and proliferation in controlling airway hyper-responsiveness and remodeling in asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. \n\nReferences:\n1. Bartel DP. MicroRNAs: target recognition and regulatory functions. Cell. 2009 Jan 23;136(2):215-33. doi: 10.1016/j.cell.2009.01.002. PMID: 19167326; PMCID: PMC2839319. \n\n2. Hirst SJ, Martin JG, Bonacci JV, Chan V, Fixman ED, Hamid QA, Inman MD, Jordana M, Lavoie JP, Ludwig MS. Proliferative aspects of airway smooth muscle. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2004 Nov;114(5 Suppl):S2-17. doi: 10.1016/j.jaci.2004.08.014. PMID: 15518651.\n\n3. Krymskaya VP. Smooth muscle-like cells in idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Proc Am Thorac Soc. 2008 May 1;5(3):637-43. doi: 10.1513/pats.200708-121ET. PMID: 18453307.",
  "CL:0000082":
    "Epithelial cells of the lung are specialized cells that form the lining of the airways and alveoli of the lungs. They act as a barrier and are involved in gas exchange and the clearance of foreign particles and microorganisms. These cells also secrete mucus and surfactant, which help to protect and lubricate the airways. Dysfunctional epithelial cells have been implicated in several lung diseases, including asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).\n\nReferences:\n1. Heijink IH, Nawijn MC, Hackett TL. Airway epithelial barrier function regulates the pathogenesis of allergic asthma. Clin Exp Allergy. 2014;44(5):620-630. doi:10.1111/cea.12327\n2. Monz\u00f3n ME, Maniscalco WM. Emerging roles of pulmonary epithelial cells in the pathogenesis of COPD. Int J Chron Obstruct Pulmon Dis. 2018;13:1267-1278. doi:10.2147/COPD.S153703",
  "CL:0000594":
    "A skeletal muscle satellite cell is a type of adult stem cell that resides in skeletal muscle tissue and plays a key role in muscle regeneration and repair. These cells are known for their unique ability to differentiate into myoblasts, which can then fuse together to form new muscle fibers. Satellite cells are activated in response to muscle damage, where they proliferate and differentiate to replace damaged or lost muscle tissue. Additionally, satellite cells have been shown to contribute to muscle hypertrophy and adaptation in response to exercise.  \n\nLiterature references: \n1. Relaix F, Zammit PS. Satellite cells are essential for skeletal muscle regeneration: the cell on the edge returns centre stage. Development. 2012 Dec;139(23):2845-56. doi: 10.1242/dev.069088. PMID: 23132290.\n2. Gilbert PM, Havenstrite KL, Magnusson KE, Sacco A, Leonardi NA, Kraft P, Nguyen NK, Thrun S, Lutolf MP, Blau HM. Substrate elasticity regulates skeletal muscle stem cell self-renewal in culture. Science. 2010 Sep 3;329(5995):1078-81. doi: 10.1126/science.1191035. PMID: 20813923.",
  "CL:0000682":
    "M cells of gut are specialized epithelial cells located in the follicle-associated epithelium that cover Peyer's patches and other lymphoid tissues in the gut. M cells function as antigen-sampling cells that take up antigens and microorganisms from the gut lumen and deliver them to underlying immune cells to initiate immune responses. M cells are also involved in the transport of macromolecules such as bacteria, viruses, and small particulate matter across the epithelium. M cells carry out these functions through high rates of endocytosis and transcytosis, which enables them to transport substances across the epithelium quickly and efficiently. \n\nReferences:\n1. Jang MH, Kweon MN, Iwatani K, et al. Intestinal villous M cells: an antigen entry site in the mucosal epithelium. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2004;101(16):6110-6115. doi:10.1073/pnas.0400969101\n2. Kimura S, Kobayashi M, Nasu K, et al. Intestinal M cells: a pathway for entry of viral antigens into the host. Rev Med Virol. 2009;19(4):181-188. doi:10.1002/rmv.622",
  "CL:0009010":
    "Transit amplifying cells are a population of rapidly dividing progenitor cells that differentiate into committed cell lineages. They function to expand the pool of cells available for tissue development and repair, and are ultimately responsible for generating mature, functioning cell types. Typically, transit amplifying cells are characterized by a high rate of cell division, short cell cycle duration, and a limited capacity for self-renewal. Dysregulation of transit amplifying cells has been implicated in various disease states, including cancer. \n\nLiterature reference:\n\nElias, H. K., & Hemmati-Brivanlou, A. (2020). Intercellular interactions and cell proliferation of transit-amplifying cells in the developing vertebrate neural tube. Frontiers in cell and developmental biology, 8, 151. doi:10.3389/fcell.2020.00151",
  "CL:1001431":
    "The kidney collecting duct principal cell is a cuboidal epithelial cell responsible for reabsorbing water and electrolytes in the distal convoluted tubule and connecting tubule of the kidney. These cells express the water channel protein aquaporin-2 and the epithelial sodium channel, both of which are critical for regulating water and sodium homeostasis in the body. Collecting duct principal cells also play a role in acid-base balance and blood pressure control through the secretion of renin. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to electrolyte imbalances, hypertension, and other kidney disorders. \n\nReferences: \n1. Knepper MA. The renal collecting duct as a target for hypertension therapy. Kidney Int. 2004;65(1):2-13.\n2. Bichet DG. Vasopressin analogues in the treatment of central diabetes insipidus: clinical and experimental studies. Schweiz Med Wochenschr. 1998;128(24):962-974.",
  "CL:0002328":
    "Bronchial epithelial cells are a type of epithelial cell that line the respiratory bronchioles of the lungs. Their main function is to maintain the barrier between the external environment and the internal environment of the lungs, protecting the lungs from harmful particles, bacteria and viruses. These cells also play a crucial role in lung defense mechanisms. They continuously generate mucus that traps inhaled particles, and their cilia help move this mucus and any trapped particles back up towards the throat, where it can be swallowed and cleared from the body. Additionally, bronchial epithelial cells can release various inflammatory mediators and cytokines in response to infections and other foreign particles, which help recruit immune cells to the site of infection or damage. Understanding the properties and functions of these cells is important in developing treatments for respiratory diseases, such as asthma, cystic fibrosis, and lung cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Shaykhiev R, Crystal RG. Airway stem cells and regeneration. Clin Chest Med. 2013 Jun;34(2):253-60. \n2. Huang SX, et al. Cell-based therapies for chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2018 Oct 15;198(8):931-8. \n3. Horani A, Ferkol TW. Advances in the genetics and genomics of primary ciliary dyskinesia. Expert Rev Respir Med. 2016 Oct;10(10):1093-103.",
  "CL:1001285":
    "Vasa recta descending limb cells are specialized epithelial cells located in the descending thin limb of the loop of Henle in the kidney. These cells play a critical role in the production of hypertonic urine, which is essential for water and electrolyte homeostasis. Vasa recta descending limb cells are responsible for the active reabsorption of ions, such as NaCl, and the secretion of urea, which results in the concentration of urine. Dysfunction of these cells may lead to impairments in renal function. \n\nReferences: \n- O'Neill WC, Lerman LO. Descending thin limb of Henle's loop. Am J Physiol. 1989 Oct;257(4 Pt 2):F617-23. doi: 10.1152/ajprenal.1989.257.4.F617. PMID: 2671842. \n- Dantzler WH, Pannabecker TL, Layton AT. Urea transport in the inner medulla of the kidney. Kidney Int. 2007 Mar;71(5):390-7. doi: 10.1038/sj.ki.5002106. Epub 2006 Oct 18. PMID: 17051141.",
  "CL:1001430":
    "Urethra urothelial cells are specialized epithelial cells that line the urethra, the tube that carries urine from the bladder to the outside of the body. These cells play a crucial role in maintaining the barrier function of the urethra, preventing bacteria and toxins from entering the urinary tract. In addition, urethra urothelial cells are involved in the synthesis and secretion of mucus and other glycoproteins, which can help to lubricate the urethral lumen and maintain its integrity. Recent studies have also suggested that these cells may play a role in the development and progression of interstitial cystitis and other inflammatory conditions of the urinary tract.\n\nReferences:\n1. Hurst RE, Zebrowski R, Gilleran J, et al. Urothelial and suburothelial microanatomy at human ureteropelvic junction: functional and structural implications. Anat Rec. 2001;263(2):160-71.\n2. Gammie A, Kaidarova Z, Trautner BW. A review of the microbiology and antibiotic management of infected urinary stones. Urolithiasis. 2018 Oct;46(5):433-447.\n3. Kim A, Chiu A, Barone JG, et al. Urothelial cells: biological and clinical implications of the interaction between urothelial cells and bacteria. Eur Urol Focus. 2019 Sep;5(5):693-701.",
  "CL:0001066":
    "Erythroid progenitor cells are a type of hematopoietic stem cell that give rise to erythrocytes, or red blood cells. They are found primarily in the bone marrow and undergo a series of developmental stages before becoming mature erythrocytes. Erythroid progenitor cells are responsible for the production of new erythrocytes to replace those that are lost due to aging or injury. Dysregulation of erythroid progenitor cell differentiation can lead to blood disorders such as anemia or polycythemia vera. \n\nLiterature references: \n1. Paulson, R. F. (2019). Erythropoiesis: Lessons learned from knockout mice. Blood Cells, Molecules, and Diseases, 76, 9-15.\n2. Buitenhuis, M., & Cvejic, A. (2019). Regulation of erythropoiesis by erythropoietin: Emerging therapeutic strategies for anemia. Blood Cells, Molecules, and Diseases, 78, 41-47.\n3. Sankaran, V. G., & Weiss, M. J. (2015). Erythrocyte biology and blood disorders. Cold Spring Harbor Perspectives in Medicine, 5(3), a021718.",
  "CL:0000814":
    "Mature NK T cells are a distinct subset of T cells that express both the T cell receptor (TCR) and NK cell receptors. They play a crucial role in the immune system by rapidly secreting cytokines in response to foreign antigens. These cells are primarily involved in the regulation of immune responses, and are known to be involved in the pathogenesis of several autoimmune diseases, infectious diseases, and cancer. \n\nReference: \n1. Godfrey DI, Stankovic S, Baxter AG. Raising the NKT cell family. Nat Immunol. 2010;11(3):197-206.\n2. Berzins SP, Smyth MJ, Baxter AG. Presumed guilty: natural killer T cell defects and human disease. Nat Rev Immunol. 2011;11(2):131-142.\n3. Brennan PJ, Brigl M, Brenner MB. Invariant natural killer T cells: an innate activation scheme linked to diverse effector functions. Nat Rev Immunol. 2013;13(2):101-117.",
  "CL:0001071":
    "Group 3 innate lymphoid cells (ILC3s) are a population of immune cells that play a crucial role in promoting mucosal homeostasis and immunity against extracellular pathogens. ILC3s are characterized by their expression of the transcription factor ROR\u03b3t, which is required for their development and function. ILC3s are primarily found in mucosal tissues such as the intestine, where they produce cytokines such as IL-17 and IL-22 to promote epithelial barrier function, control commensal microbiota, and tissue regeneration. Dysregulation of ILC3s has been implicated in various intestinal disorders, including inflammatory bowel disease and colorectal cancer. \n\nReferences:\n\n- McKenzie ANJ, Spits H, Eberl G. Innate lymphoid cells in inflammation and immunity. Immunity. 2014;41(3):366-374. doi:10.1016/j.immuni.2014.09.006\n- Hepworth MR, Sonnenberg GF. Regulation of the adaptive immune system by innate lymphoid cells. Curr Opin Immunol. 2014;27:75-82. doi:10.1016/j.coi.2014.01.005\n- Artis D, Spits H. The biology of innate lymphoid cells. Nature. 2015;517(7534):293-301. doi:10.1038/nature14189",
  "CL:0000115":
    "Endothelial Cell: \nEndothelial cells are the thin layer of cells that line the interior surface of blood vessels. These cells play a crucial role in maintaining vascular homeostasis and regulating blood flow and blood pressure by secreting vasoactive molecules such as nitric oxide and endothelin. Additionally, endothelial cells also participate in the coagulation process, immune response, and angiogenesis. Dysfunction of endothelial cells is a hallmark of numerous cardiovascular diseases such as atherosclerosis, hypertension, and heart failure. \n\nReferences: \n1. Aird WC. Endothelial cell heterogeneity. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012;2(1):a006429. doi:10.1101/cshperspect.a006429 \n2. Simons M, Eichmann A. Molecular controls of arterial morphogenesis. Circ Res. 2015;116(11):1712-24. doi:10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.116.305485 \n3. Gao F, Chiu SM, Motan DAL, Zhang Z, Chen L, Ji HL, Tse HF, Fu QL, Lian Q. Mesenchymal stem cells and immunomodulation: current status and future prospects. Cell Death Dis. 2016 Sep 22;7(1):e2062. doi: 10.1038/cddis.2015.327.",
  "CL:1000305":
    "Fibroblasts of the connective tissue in the glandular part of prostate, also known as prostatic fibroblasts, are elongated and spindle-shaped cells that synthesize and maintain the extracellular matrix (ECM) of the prostate gland. They provide structural support to the gland and play a crucial role in modulating the growth and differentiation of epithelial cells in the glandular part of prostate. Additionally, prostatic fibroblasts produce several growth factors and cytokines that regulate the growth, survival, and differentiation of prostatic epithelial and stromal cells, thereby contributing to the development and progression of prostate cancer. Literature references include:\n\n1. Prins GS, Putz O. Molecular signaling pathways that regulate prostate gland development. Differentiation. 2008;76(6):641-59.\n\n2. Mantovani F, Collavin A, Del Sal G. Mutant p53 as a guardian of the cancer cell. Cell Death Differ. 2019;26(2):199-212.\n\n3. Kwon OJ, Zhang L, Ittmann MM, Xin L. Prostatic inflammation enhances basal-to-luminal differentiation and accelerates initiation of prostate cancer with a basal cell origin. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2014;111(5):E592-600.",
  "CL:1000698":
    "A kidney resident macrophage is a type of immune cell that resides in the kidney and plays a critical role in kidney homeostasis, inflammation, and injury. It is characterized by the expression of CD68, F4/80, and CD206 markers. These cells are involved in the clearance of apoptotic cells, immune surveillance, and regulation of the local immune response. Studies have shown that kidney resident macrophages contribute to the development of kidney diseases such as glomerulosclerosis and tubulointerstitial fibrosis. Therefore, understanding the function and regulation of kidney resident macrophages is crucial in the management of kidney diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. Vielhauer V, Anders HJ, Schl\u00f6ndorff D. Biology and pathophysiology of renal macrophages. Kidney Int. 2003;64(2):171-179.\n2. Bajpai G, et al. The human kidney contains multiple populations of adult stem-like cells with differential regenerative potential and expression of Kit receptor. Am J Physiol Renal Physiol. 2016;311(4):F800-F812.",
  "CL:4023018":
    "Pvalb GABAergic cortical interneurons are a subtype of inhibitory neurons that play a crucial role in regulating cortical circuit function. They are defined by the expression of parvalbumin (Pvalb) and the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), and are characterized by fast-spiking properties, which allows for precise temporal processing within the cortical network. These cells are involved in regulating cortical synchrony and oscillations, which are key features of information processing and cognition. Dysfunction of Pvalb GABAergic interneurons has been implicated in a variety of neuropsychiatric disorders, including schizophrenia and autism spectrum disorders. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Klausberger T, Somogyi P (2008) Neuronal diversity and temporal dynamics: the unity of hippocampal circuit operations. Science 321(5885):53-57.\n2. Lewis DA, Hashimoto T, Volk DW (2005) Cortical inhibitory neurons and schizophrenia. Nat Rev Neurosci 6(4):312-324.\n3. Mar\u00edn O (2012) Interneuron dysfunction in psychiatric disorders. Nat Rev Neurosci 13(2):107-120.",
  "CL:0000681":
    "Radial glial cells are a type of neural stem cell found in the developing nervous system. They function as a scaffolding for the migration of neurons during embryonic development, as well as playing a role in neuronal differentiation and synaptogenesis. In addition, they have been implicated in certain neurological disorders such as epilepsy and gliomas. Literature references include Noctor et al., 2001 (PMID: 11430814) and Gotz et al., 2015 (PMID: 26150490).",
  "CL:0000559":
    "Promonocytes are a type of myeloid progenitor cell that develop into monocytes, which are important immune cells involved in phagocytosis, antigen presentation, and cytokine secretion. Promonocytes are characterized by their large size and ovoid or kidney-shaped nuclei with a prominent nucleolus. They can be found in bone marrow and circulating blood, and are involved in the early stages of inflammation and immune responses. Literature reference: Allakhverdi, Z., & Smith, L. J. (2021). Promonocytes. In StatPearls [Internet]. StatPearls Publishing.",
  "CL:1000849":
    "Kidney distal convoluted tubule epithelial cells are polarized cuboidal cells that line the distal convoluted tubule of the nephron in the kidney. These cells are involved in the regulation of electrolyte balance and acid-base homeostasis via the reabsorption of sodium ions and secretion of potassium and hydrogen ions. Additionally, these cells play a role in the reabsorption of calcium ions and the excretion of uric acid. Distal convoluted tubule epithelial cells express a variety of transporters, channels, and receptors that regulate these processes, including sodium-chloride cotransporter (NCC), calcium-sensing receptor (CaSR), and thiazide-sensitive sodium-chloride cotransporter (TSC). Dysfunction of these cells can lead to electrolyte imbalances and hypertension. \n\nReferences:\n1. Ellison, D. H., & Loffing, J. (2019). Thiazide-sensitive sodium chloride cotransport in distal tubule function and blood pressure regulation. Journal of clinical investigation, 129(6), 2145-2154.\n2. Gamba, G. (2012). The physiology of electroneutral cation-chloride cotransporters: from bench to bedside. Current opinion in nephrology and hypertension, 21(4), 467-474.\n3. Palmer, L. G. (2015). Ion transport mechanisms in the distal nephron: key players in the regulation of blood pressure and hypertension. American Journal of Physiology-Renal Physiology, 309(4), F259-F271.",
  "CL:1001567":
    "Lung endothelial cells line the walls of the blood vessels in the lungs and play a crucial role in gas exchange between the lungs and the rest of the body. They are responsible for regulating blood flow, maintaining vascular integrity, and controlling inflammation in the lungs. Lung endothelial cells also interact with immune cells and participate in the immune response to respiratory pathogens.\n\nReference: \n1. Kuebler, W.M., Wittenberg, C., Lee, W.L., Reppien, E., Goldenberg, N.M., Lindner, K., Connelly, K.A., Schroeder, T., and Pries, A.R. (2018). Role of lung endothelial cells in acute respiratory distress syndrome and beyond. Compr Physiol 8, 1465\u20131490.",
  "CL:0000138":
    "Chondrocytes are specialized cells found in cartilage that are involved in the production and maintenance of the extracellular matrix. They produce collagens and proteoglycans which help provide cartilage with its unique properties of flexibility and resistance to compression. Chondrocytes also play a crucial role in repair and remodeling of cartilage tissues. Dysfunction of chondrocytes can lead to various joint and bone diseases such as osteoarthritis. \n\nReferences: \n1. Goldring MB. Chondrocyte biology, osteoarthritis, and cartilage repair. Instr Course Lect. 2006;55:1-30.\n2. Saito T, Fukai A, Mabuchi A, et al. Transcriptional regulation of endochondral ossification by HIF-2alpha during skeletal growth and osteoarthritis development. Nat Med. 2010;16(6):678-686.",
  "CL:0000442":
    "Follicular dendritic cells (FDCs) are stromal cells found principally in the germinal centers of secondary lymphoid organs, where they play a critical role in generating and perpetuating humoral immune responses by trapping, retaining and presenting antigens to B cells. FDCs are involved in selecting the B cells that have the highest affinity for the antigen and helping them to mature into antibody-secreting cells. Furthermore, FDCs are also involved in maintaining the germinal center microenvironment and in providing signals for memory B cell formation. Literature references: Castagnoli et al. (2019), Denton et al. (2019), and Liu et al. (2019).",
  "CL:0001056":
    "Dendritic cells are professional antigen-presenting cells that play a key role in initiating and regulating adaptive immune responses. They are characterized by their dendritic morphology and high expression of MHC class II and co-stimulatory molecules. In humans, there are several subsets of dendritic cells that differ in their anatomical location, phenotype, and function. These subsets include conventional dendritic cells (cDCs), plasmacytoid dendritic cells (pDCs), and monocyte-derived dendritic cells (moDCs). cDCs are the most abundant and best characterized subset of dendritic cells in humans. They are found in lymphoid and non-lymphoid tissues and are specialized in capturing, processing, and presenting antigens to T cells. pDCs are mainly located in lymphoid tissues and blood and are specialized in producing type I interferons in response to viral infections. moDCs are derived from circulating monocytes and are commonly used in clinical settings as an ex vivo source of dendritic cells for immunotherapy.\n\nReferences:\n\nBanchereau J, Steinman RM. Dendritic cells and the control of immunity. Nature. 1998;392(6673):245-52.\n\nMerad M, Sathe P, Helft J, Miller J, Mortha A. The dendritic cell lineage: ontogeny and function of dendritic cells and their subsets in the steady state and the inflamed setting. Annu Rev Immunol. 2013;31:563-604.",
  "CL:0001054":
    "CD14-positive monocytes are a subtype of white blood cells that play a critical role in the immune response, particularly in the initiation and regulation of inflammation. In response to infection or tissue damage, monocytes are recruited from the bloodstream to tissues where they differentiate into tissue-specific macrophages or dendritic cells, each with distinct functions. CD14, a glycosylphosphatidylinositol-anchored protein, enables monocytes to bind lipopolysaccharide (LPS), a component of bacterial cell walls, and initiate an immune response. Dysregulation of CD14-positive monocytes has been implicated in the pathogenesis of numerous inflammatory diseases, including atherosclerosis and rheumatoid arthritis.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Ziegler-Heitbrock L, Hofer TP. Toward a refined definition of monocyte subsets. Front Immunol. 2014;5:478.\n2. Tsukamoto H, Senju S, Matsumura K, et al. Dynamics of dendritic cell subsets in atherosclerosis development. J Atheroscler Thromb. 2018;25(6):513-521.\n3. Hammad H, Lambrecht BN. Dendritic cells and epithelial cells: linking innate and adaptive immunity in asthma. Nat Rev Immunol. 2008;8(3):193-204.",
  "CL:0002627":
    "Mature astrocytes, also known as protoplasmic astrocytes, are star-shaped glial cells found in the central nervous system (CNS). They provide structural and functional support to neurons and help maintain the blood-brain barrier. Mature astrocytes have a variety of functions, including regulating extracellular ion balance, glucose uptake, and neurotransmitter homeostasis. They also play a role in synaptic plasticity, modulating the strength of communication between neurons. Dysfunction or loss of mature astrocytes is associated with a range of neurological disorders, including Alzheimer's disease and multiple sclerosis.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Sofroniew, M. V. (2009). Molecular dissection of reactive astrogliosis and glial scar formation. Trends in neurosciences, 32(12), 638-647.\n2. Nedergaard, M., Ransom, B., & Goldman, S. A. (2003). New roles for astrocytes: redefining the functional architecture of the brain. Trends in neurosciences, 26(10), 523-530.\n3. Khakh, B. S., & Sofroniew, M. V. (2015). Diversity of astrocyte functions and phenotypes in neural circuits. Nature neuroscience, 18(7), 942-952.",
  "CL:0000811":
    "CD8-positive, alpha-beta thymocytes are a subset of T cells that develop in the thymus. They are characterized by the expression of CD8 co-receptor and the alpha-beta T cell receptor (TCR). In the thymus, CD8-positive, alpha-beta thymocytes undergo positive and negative selection, leading to the development of mature T cells with the ability to recognize foreign antigens and mount an appropriate immune response. Once they leave the thymus, CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells circulate throughout the body, where they identify and eliminate virus-infected and cancerous cells by inducing apoptosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Kersh, G. J., Schreiber, S. L., & Monos, D. S. (1993). The alpha beta T cell receptor. Annual review of immunology, 11(1), 77-98.\n2. Takada, K., & Jameson, S. C. (2009). Naive T cell homeostasis: from awareness of space to a sense of place. Nature reviews immunology, 9(12), 823-832.",
  "CL:0000979":
    "IgG memory B cells, also known as antigen-experienced B cells, are a subset of B cells that have undergone activation and differentiation upon exposure to specific antigens. Once activated, these B cells differentiate into plasma cells, which are responsible for the production and secretion of IgG antibodies. IgG memory B cells then enter a quiescent state known as the memory phase, allowing for a rapid and efficient response upon subsequent antigen exposure. Their function is to provide long-term immunity against previously encountered pathogens. Literature references include Tarlinton et al. (2008) and Crotty (2015).",
  "CL:0000119":
    "Cerebellar Golgi cells are inhibitory interneurons located in the granular layer of the cerebellum. Their primary function is to control the activity of granule cells and modulate the output of the cerebellar cortex. They achieve this through the release of GABA, which acts on the granule cell dendrites and regulates their excitability. Golgi cells also play a role in neural plasticity, which is vital for learning and memory. Dysfunction of Golgi cells has been implicated in a variety of cerebellar disorders, including ataxia and tremor.\n\nReference: Masugi-Tokita, M., & Shigemoto, R. (2007). High-resolution quantitative visualization of glutamate and GABA receptors at central synapses. Current opinion in neurobiology, 17(3), 387-393.",
  "CL:0000617":
    "GABAergic neurons are a type of nerve cell that use the neurotransmitter gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) to inhibit the activity of other neurons in the brain. These neurons are essential for regulating neuronal excitability and maintaining the balance between excitation and inhibition in neural circuits. GABAergic neurons are found throughout the central nervous system and are involved in various processes, including motor control, sensory perception, and behavioral modulation. Dysfunction of GABAergic neurons has been implicated in many neurological disorders, including epilepsy, schizophrenia, and autism spectrum disorders. \n\nReferences:\n- Klausberger T, Somogyi P. (2008) Neuronal diversity and temporal dynamics: the unity of hippocampal circuit operations. Science. 321(5885):53-7.\n- Farrant M, Kaila K. (2007) The cellular, molecular and ionic basis of GABA(A) receptor signalling. Prog Brain Res. 160:47-62.\n- Huntsman MM, Huguenard JR. (2000) Nomenclature and classification of the GABAergic nerve terminals of the dentate gyrus. J Comp Neurol. 421(2):146-54.",
  "CL:0000164":
    "Enteroendocrine cells are a type of specialized cells that are present in the gastrointestinal tract. These cells are primarily involved in the secretion of various hormones and neuropeptides that regulate different digestive processes such as gastric emptying, gut motility, and nutrient absorption. These cells are also involved in the regulation of appetite and energy homeostasis and play a crucial role in glucose metabolism. Enteroendocrine cells are present in different regions of the gut including the stomach, intestine, and colon, and are characterized by the secretion of different hormones depending on their location. Some of the major hormones secreted by enteroendocrine cells include cholecystokinin, secretin, gastrin, and glucagon-like peptide-1. Dysfunction of enteroendocrine cells has been associated with various gastrointestinal and metabolic disorders such as irritable bowel syndrome, diabetes, and obesity.\n\nReferences:\n1. Sj\u00f6lund K, et al. Endocrine cells in human intestine: an immunocytochemical study. Gastroenterology. 1983 Mar;84(3):726-36.\n2. Drucker DJ, Habener JF. Glucagon-like peptide-1. Efficacy and safety in the treatment of diabetes. Diabetes Care. 2004 Jul;27(7):1879-904.",
  "CL:0000914":
    "Immature NK T cells (iNKT) are a distinct type of natural killer T cells that express both T cell receptor (TCR) and NK cell markers. They play a crucial role in the early defense against infections and tumor surveillance by producing cytokines such as IFN-\u03b3, IL-4, and IL-17 upon activation. iNKT cells have been implicated in autoimmune diseases, allergies, and cancer, making them a promising target for therapeutic intervention. \n\nReference: \n- Godfrey, D. I., & Kronenberg, M. (2004). Going both ways: immune regulation via CD1d-dependent NKT cells. The Journal of clinical investigation, 114(10), 1379-1388.\n- Brennan, P. J., Brigl, M., & Brenner, M. B. (2013). Invariant natural killer T cells: an innate activation scheme linked to diverse effector functions. Nature Reviews Immunology, 13(2), 101-117.",
  "CL:0000906":
    "Activated CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are cytotoxic T lymphocytes that play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response against intracellular pathogens and cancerous cells. Upon activation by their cognate antigen, these cells differentiate into effector cells that carry out target cell recognition and destruction through the release of cytotoxic granules and cytokines. CD8+ T cells also aid in the establishment of immunological memory, providing protection against recurrent encounters with the same pathogen. \n\nReferences:\n1. Williams MA, Bevan MJ. Effector and Memory CTL Differentiation. Annu Rev Immunol. 2007;25:171-192.\n2. Zajac AJ, Blattman JN, Murali-Krishna K., et al. Viral immune evasion due to persistence of activated T cells without effector function. J Exp Med. 1998; 188(12):2205-2213.",
  "CL:0000171":
    "Pancreatic A cells are a type of endocrine cell found in the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas. These cells are responsible for producing and secreting the hormone glucagon, which raises blood glucose levels by stimulating conversion of stored glycogen to glucose in the liver. Dysfunction of A cells can lead to conditions like type 1 and type 2 diabetes. \n\nReference:\n- Gromada J, Franklin I, Wollheim CB. Alpha cells of the pancreas: molecular biology, physiology and pathology.  Endocr Rev. 2007 Aug;28(5):84-116. doi: 10.1210/er.2006-0048. PMID: 17519326.",
  "CL:0000696":
    "PP cell, also known as pancreatic polypeptide cell, is a type of endocrine cell found in the pancreas. PP cells produce pancreatic polypeptide, a hormone that helps regulate pancreatic exocrine and endocrine functions, as well as food intake and body weight. PP cells are located in the islets of Langerhans, specifically in the periphery of the islets adjacent to the alpha and beta cells. Dysfunction of PP cells has been linked to various metabolic disorders, such as obesity and diabetes. \n\nReferences: \n1. Lundberg, J. M., & Tatemoto, K. (1982). Pancreatic polypeptide--a postulated new hormone: identification, isolation and assay methods. Biological effects and possible physiological role. Regulatory peptides, 5(3), 139-155.\n2. Ugleholdt, R. K., Poulsen, S. S., Holst, J. J., & Sangild, P. T. (2004). Pancreatic polypeptide response to feeding in pigs: effects of ileal, colonic, and portal infusion of bile acids. The American journal of physiology-gastrointestinal and liver physiology, 286(4), G662-G669.\n3. Salehi, M., Vahl, T. P., & D\u2019Alessio, D. A. (2008). Regulation of islet hormone release and gastric emptying by endogenous glucagon-like peptide 1 after glucose ingestion. Journal of Clinical Endocrinology & Metabolism, 93(12), 4909-4916.",
  "CL:0002394":
    "CD141-positive myeloid dendritic cells (mDCs) are a subset of dendritic cells that play a crucial role in the initiation of adaptive immune responses, particularly in response to viral infections and tumors. They are characterized by the expression of the CD141 surface marker, as well as the transcription factor BATF3. CD141-positive mDCs are found primarily in the blood and lymphoid tissues, and are capable of cross-presenting antigens to T cells, priming them for a specific immune response. Additionally, CD141-positive mDCs have been shown to produce high levels of type I interferons in response to viral infections. \n\nReferences:\n1. Jongbloed SL, Kassianos AJ, McDonald KJ, et al. Human CD141+ (BDCA-3)+ dendritic cells (DCs) represent a unique myeloid DC subset that cross-presents necrotic cell antigens. J Exp Med. 2010;207(6):1247-1260. doi:10.1084/jem.20092140\n2. Bachem A, Hartung E, G\u00fcttler S, et al. Expression of XCR1 characterizes the Batf3-dependent lineage of dendritic cells capable of antigen cross-presentation. Front Immunol. 2012;3:214. doi:10.3389/fimmu.2012.00214\n3. Crozat K, Guiton R, Guilliams M, et al. Comparative genomics as a tool to reveal functional equivalences between human and mouse dendritic cell subsets. Immunol Rev. 2010;234(1):177-198. doi:10.1111/j.0105-2896.2009.00886.x",
  "CL:0000990":
    "Conventional dendritic cells (cDCs) are professional antigen-presenting cells that play a crucial role in the initiation and regulation of adaptive immune responses. cDCs capture antigens in peripheral tissues, process them, and migrate to lymphoid organs where they present the antigens to na\u00efve T cells, thereby initiating an antigen-specific immune response. In addition, cDCs are involved in the maintenance of peripheral tolerance by presenting self-antigens and inducing anergy or deletion of autoreactive T cells. cDCs are a heterogeneous population of cells that can be further divided based on their expression of specific surface markers. In humans, two major subsets of cDCs have been identified: CD1c+ cDCs and CD141+ cDCs, which differ in their phenotype, function, and tissue distribution. \n\nReferences:\n- Merad M, Sathe P, Helft J, Miller J, Mortha A. The dendritic cell lineage: ontogeny and function of dendritic cells and their subsets in the steady state and the inflamed setting. Annu Rev Immunol. 2013;31:563-604.\n- Guilliams M, Ginhoux F, Jakubzick C, Naik SH, Onai N, Schraml BU, et al. Dendritic cells, monocytes and macrophages: a unified nomenclature based on ontogeny. Nat Rev Immunol. 2014;14(8):571-8.\n- Collin M, Bigley V. Human dendritic cell subsets: an update. Immunology. 2018;154(1):3-20.",
  "CL:0002343":
    "Decidual natural killer (dNK) cells are a unique population of highly specialized immune cells present in large numbers in the maternal decidua during early pregnancy. Their main role is to regulate trophoblast invasion and spiral artery remodeling, thus promoting successful implantation and maintenance of pregnancy. In addition, dNK cells produce a range of cytokines and growth factors that facilitate fetal growth and development. Studies have also shown that dNK cells exhibit immunoregulatory functions and are involved in maintaining immune tolerance at the feto-maternal interface. Dysregulation of dNK cell function has been associated with several pregnancy complications, including recurrent miscarriage, preeclampsia, and intrauterine growth restriction.\n\nReferences:\n1. Moffett-King A. Natural killer cells and pregnancy. Nat Rev Immunol. 2002 Nov;2(9):656-63. doi: 10.1038/nri886. PMID: 12360214.\n2. Chiossone L, Vacca P, Orefici G, et al. Decidual and peripheral blood natural killer cell function in patients undergoing in vitro fertilization with and without recurrent pregnancy loss. Hum Reprod. 2012;27(9):2962-2973. doi:10.1093/humrep/des261\n3. Vacca P, Montaldo E, Croxatto D, et al. CD34+ hematopoietic precursors are present in human decidua and differentiate into natural killer cells upon interaction with stromal cells. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2011;108(6):2402-2407. doi:10.1073/pnas.1016257108",
  "CL:1001474":
    "Medium spiny neurons are a type of projection neuron that form the majority of the striatum in the brain. They are involved in the signaling pathways of the dopaminergic system and are responsible for the regulation of voluntary movements, decision-making, and reward. Dysfunction of medium spiny neurons has been implicated in various neurological disorders, including Parkinson's disease, Huntington's disease, and addiction. Literature references include:\n\n1. Gerfen CR, Surmeier DJ. Modulation of striatal projection systems by dopamine. Annu Rev Neurosci. 2011;34:441-466. doi: 10.1146/annurev-neuro-061010-113641\n2. Kreitzer AC. Physiology and pharmacology of striatal neurons. Annu Rev Neurosci. 2009;32:127-147. doi: 10.1146/annurev.neuro.051508.135423\n3. Shen W, Flajolet M, Greengard P, Surmeier DJ. Dichotomous dopaminergic control of striatal synaptic plasticity. Science. 2008;321(5890):848-851. doi: 10.1126/science.1160575",
  "CL:1000597":
    'Papillary tip cells are specialized endothelial cells located at the tips of growing blood vessels in the lymph nodes. They express high levels of the chemokine CXCL13, which is crucial for proper organization of lymphoid tissues by guiding lymphocytes and dendritic cells to specific areas within the lymph node. Additionally, papillary tip cells have been shown to regulate lymphatic vessel growth and development. \n\nReference:    Tzeng, T. C., et al. (2019). "Sphingosine 1-phosphate receptor-3 signaling is required for aryl hydrocarbon receptor-dependent regulation of CXCL13 in follicular dendritic cells." ACS Omega 4(20): 19025-19033.',
  "CL:1000347":
    "Enterocytes of colon are polarized epithelial cells lining the surface of the colon that are involved in the absorption and secretion of nutrients, ions, and water. They are characterized by the presence of numerous microvilli on their apical surface, which increase the surface area for absorption. Enterocytes are also responsible for the maintenance of a physical barrier to prevent the entry of harmful toxins and pathogens. Dysregulation of enterocyte function has been implicated in various diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease and colon cancer.\n\nReferences:\n1. Clevers H. The intestinal crypt, a prototype stem cell compartment. Cell. 2013;154(2):274-284.\n2. Hu D, Wan L, Chen M, Cui Q, Li H, Singh B, An M, Liang G. The effects of intestinal epithelial barrier dysfunction on chronic intestinal inflammation. Int J Mol Sci. 2020;21(14):5012. \n3. Liu HY, Qiu YB, Wu LY. Targeting enterocytes for the treatment of inflammatory bowel diseases. Front Pharmacol. 2019;10:1461.",
  "CL:0000740":
    "Retinal ganglion cells are a type of neuron located in the innermost layer of the retina. These cells receive visual information from bipolar cells and amacrine cells, and relay this information to the brain via the optic nerve. Retinal ganglion cells are involved in the processing of visual information such as shape, color, and movement. Additionally, they play a critical role in setting the circadian rhythm through their ability to detect changes in light levels. Dysfunction of retinal ganglion cells is associated with various visual disorders, including glaucoma. \n\nReference: \n1. Masland, R. H. (2001). Neuronal cell types. Current biology, 11(6), R191-R196.",
  "CL:0000322":
    "Pneumocytes are a type of epithelial cell found in the alveoli of the lungs. They are responsible for gas exchange by secreting surfactant to reduce surface tension in the alveoli, allowing for efficient inflation and deflation during breathing. Type I pneumocytes are thin, flat cells responsible for gas exchange, while type II pneumocytes are cuboidal cells responsible for the production and secretion of surfactant. Dysfunction or loss of pneumocytes can lead to respiratory diseases such as acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS). \n\nReference:\nMason, R.J. & Williams, M.C. (1997). Type II alveolar cell. defender of the alveolus. Am J Respir Crit Care Med, 156(2 Pt 1), 693-9.",
  "CL:0000127":
    "Astrocytes are a type of glial cell found in the central nervous system (CNS). They are involved in a wide range of functions, including providing structural support, regulating ion and neurotransmitter concentrations, maintaining the blood-brain barrier, and participating in immune responses. Astrocytes also play an important role in synapse formation, plasticity, and removal. Dysfunction of astrocytes has been implicated in numerous neurological disorders, including Alzheimer's disease, Parkinson's disease, epilepsy, and multiple sclerosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Sofroniew MV. Molecular dissection of reactive astrogliosis and glial scar formation. Trends Neurosci. 2009 Sep;32(9):638-47. doi: 10.1016/j.tins.2009.08.002. Epub 2009 Aug 24. PMID: 19709997; PMCID: PMC2756532.\n2. Verkhratsky A, Nedergaard M. Physiology of astroglia. Physiol Rev. 2018 Jan 1;98(1):239-389. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00042.2016. PMID: 29217661; PMCID: PMC6341662.\n3. Pekny M, Pekna M. Astrocyte intermediate filaments in CNS pathologies and regeneration. J Pathol. 2004 Nov;204(4):428-37. doi: 10.1002/path.1656. PMID: 15495216.",
  "CL:0000897":
    "CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells are a subset of memory T cells that express the CD4 receptor and the alpha-beta T cell receptor. These cells play a critical role in providing long-term immunity against previously encountered pathogens by rapidly responding to re-exposure to the same antigen. CD4-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells also play a role in the development of autoimmunity and allergic diseases. \n\nReferences: \n1. Jameson SC, Masopust D. Diversity in T cell memory: an embarrassment of riches. Immunity. 2009 Sep 18;31(3):859-71.\n2. Zhu J, Paul WE. CD4 T cells: fates, functions, and faults. Blood. 2008 Apr 15;112(8):1557-69.",
  "CL:2000060":
    "Placental villous trophoblasts are a specialized subtype of cells that make up the placenta, the organ responsible for sustaining fetal growth and development in mammals. These cells grow into finger-like projections called villi that extend into the mother's bloodstream, facilitating nutrient and gas exchange between the maternal and fetal circulatory systems. They also secrete hormones and cytokines that modulate maternal immune responses and promote fetal survival. Dysregulation of trophoblast function is associated with complications of pregnancy such as preeclampsia and fetal growth restriction. (Reference: James JL et al. Trophoblast differentiation: an overview of cellular, molecular and functional adaptations to the endometrial niche. Int J Dev Biol. 2014;58(2-4): 155-161.)",
  "CL:0000985":
    "IgG plasma cells are a type of antibody-secreting cell that produce immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies. IgG antibodies play an important role in humoral immunity by recognizing and neutralizing pathogens such as bacteria and viruses. IgG plasma cells differentiate from B cells following antigen exposure and undergo extensive proliferation and differentiation to become highly specialized in secreting IgG antibodies. Their function is essential for long-term immunity and protection against future infections. Literature references include: \n\n1. Amanna IJ, Carlson NE, Slifka MK. Duration of humoral immunity to common viral and vaccine antigens. N Engl J Med. 2007 Oct 4;357(14):1903-15.\n\n2. Smith KGC, Hewitson TD, Nossal GJV, Tarlinton DM. The phenotype and fate of the antibody-forming cells of the splenic foci. Eur J Immunol. 1996;26(2):444\u2013448.",
  "CL:0000499":
    "Stromal cells are a heterogeneous population of non-hematopoietic cells that provide structural support and create a microenvironment within tissues and organs. They are involved in various physiological functions including immune regulation, tissue repair, and maintenance of stem cell niches. Stromal cells secrete growth factors, cytokines, chemokines, and extracellular matrix molecules, which interact with neighboring cells to promote cell survival, proliferation, differentiation, and migration. Dysfunction of stromal cells has been implicated in various diseases, including cancer, fibrosis, and autoimmune disorders.\n\nReferences:\n1. Krampera, M., et al. Mesenchymal stem cells for the treatment of autoimmune diseases. Immunol Lett. 2015; 168(2): 215-27.\n2. Mishra, P. J., et al. Stromal-derived factor-1/CXCL12 contributes to Malignant Progression of Non-Small Cell Lung Cancer through the Mobilization of Myeloid-Derived Suppressor Cells. Oncotarget. 2015; 6(8): 44675-44688.\n3. Corselli, M., et al. Interactions between cancer stem cells and their niche govern metastatic colonization. Nature. 2014; 481(7379): 85-9.",
  "CL:0000391":
    "Podocytes are specialized cells that line the glomerular capillaries in the kidneys and form the glomerular filtration barrier. They have a unique morphology with foot-like projections called podocyte foot processes that interdigitate and cover the glomerular basement membrane. The podocyte foot processes are connected by intercellular junctions called slit diaphragms which help to regulate the passage of water and solutes through the filtration barrier. The main function of podocytes is to maintain the structural integrity and permeability of the glomerular filtration barrier, which is essential for normal kidney function. In Drosophila melanogaster, podocytes are found in the nephrocytes and are involved in the removal of waste products from the hemolymph. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Mundel, P., & Shankland, S. J. (2002). Podocyte biology and response to injury. Journal of the American Society of Nephrology, 13(12), 3005-3015.\n2. Denholm, B., & Skaer, H. (2009). Bringing together components of the fly renal system. Current opinion in genetics & development, 19(5), 526-532.",
  "CL:0001062":
    "Effector memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are terminally differentiated cells that mediate the adaptive immune response by recognizing and eliminating intracellular pathogens and cancer cells. These cells exhibit enhanced cytotoxicity, cytokine production, and tissue homing compared to other T cell subsets. Effector memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are generated following antigen exposure and clonal expansion, and are maintained long-term in circulation and tissues. They play a critical role in protective immunity against viral infections, intracellular bacteria, and cancer. Effector memory CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells can produce IFN-\u03b3, TNF-\u03b1, and other effector cytokines upon re-exposure to antigen. Literature references include: Wherry EJ et al. (2007) Nat Rev Immunol 7(11): 865-878; Sallusto F et al. (2004) Nat Immunol 5(6): 532-538; Kaech SM et al. (2002) Nat Rev Immunol 2(4): 251-262.",
  "CL:0002145":
    "Ciliated columnar cells of the tracheobronchial tree are pseudostratified epithelial cells with cilia that beat in a coordinated fashion to move mucus and trapped particles out of the respiratory tract. These cells play a crucial role in maintaining the health of the respiratory system by clearing debris and pathogens from the airways. They also produce and secrete mucus to trap foreign particles and protect the respiratory tract from infection. Dysfunction of ciliated columnar cells can lead to various respiratory diseases, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and asthma. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Fahy JV. Mucus clearance in the airways: relevance to chronic obstructive pulmonary disease. Annals of the American Thoracic Society. 2018;15(Supplement_3):S176-S182.\n\n2. Kuebler WM, Parthasarathi K, Lindert J, Bhattacharya J. Real-time lung microscopy. J Appl Physiol. 2014;116(6):731-738.",
  "CL:0000650":
    "Mesangial cells are specialized cells found within the glomerulus of the kidney. They have phagocytic properties and play a central role in regulating the glomerular microenvironment. Their main functions include contractility, secretion, and cytokine production. They are crucial for maintaining glomerular filtration function and mediating response to injury. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Elberg G, Kipnis T, Greengart A, Yankowitz J, Gafter U. Mesangial cells \u2013 the master cells of the glomerular microenvironment. Front Med (Lausanne). 2018;5:111. doi:10.3389/fmed.2018.00111\n2. Kriz W, Shirato I, Nagata M, LeHir M, Lemley KV. The podocyte's response to injury: role in proteinuria and glomerulosclerosis. Kidney Int. 2003; 63(5): 1631-1647. doi:10.1046/j.1523-1755.2003.00958.x",
  "CL:1000454":
    "A kidney collecting duct epithelial cell is a specialized cell found in the renal tubules of the kidney, specifically in the distal convoluted tubule and collecting duct. These cells play a crucial role in the reabsorption of water and electrolytes from the urine, mainly by regulating the final concentration of urine and acid-base balance. They are also involved in the secretion of certain substances, such as ions and drugs. Defects in these cells have been linked to renal disorders, including hypertension, nephritis, and polycystic kidney disease. \n\nReferences:\n- Rodriguez-Flores E, Molina-Jij\u00f3n E, Tapia E, Pedraza-Chaverri J. Sodium arsenite induces ROS-dependent heme oxygenase-1 and ferritin expression in human kidney cells. Toxicol Appl Pharmacol. 2014;281(3):275-282. doi:10.1016/j.taap.2014.10.007\n- Kleta R, Bockenhauer D. Bartter syndromes and other salt-losing tubulopathies. Nephron Physiol. 2006;104(2):p73-p80. doi:10.1159/000091260",
  "CL:0000751":
    "Rod bipolar cells are a type of interneuron found within the retina of the eye. They receive input from rod photoreceptor cells and synapse onto AII amacrine cells and ganglion cells, playing a crucial role in visual information processing in low light conditions. Rod bipolar cells transmit signals from the outer plexiform layer of the retina to the inner plexiform layer, where they modulate the activity of other retinal neurons and signal the presence of contrast in the visual field. Dysfunction of rod bipolar cells has been implicated in disorders such as retinitis pigmentosa and bipolar disorder. \n\nReference: \n1. Masland, R. H. (2012). The neuronal organization of the retina. Neuron, 76(2), 266-280.\n2. Ivanova, E., & Pan, Z. H. (2009). Evaluation of the contributions of bipolar cells to the electroretinogram of the mouse. Journal of neurophysiology, 102(1), 125-133.",
  "CL:0002548":
    "Fibroblasts of cardiac tissue are specialized cells responsible for the maintenance and regulation of the extracellular matrix (ECM) within the heart. They play a crucial role in tissue repair and remodeling during physiological and pathological conditions such as cardiac hypertrophy and fibrosis. These cells synthesize and secrete various components of the ECM, including collagen, elastin, and glycosaminoglycans, which provide structural support and maintain the mechanical properties of the myocardium. Additionally, cardiac fibroblasts regulate cell adhesion, migration, and differentiation by producing various cytokines and growth factors such as transforming growth factor-beta (TGF-\u03b2) and fibroblast growth factor (FGF). Dysregulation of cardiac fibroblast function has been implicated in the development and progression of various cardiovascular disorders.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Czubryt MP, Common A, and Geddes R. Fibroblasts in myocardial infarction: a review. F1000Res. 2020 Mar 23;9:F1000 Faculty Rev-232.\n\n2. Moore-Morris T, Guimar\u00e3es-Camboa N, and Evans SM. Cardiac fibroblasts: from development to heart failure. J Mol Med (Berl). 2015 Mar;93(3):219-25.\n\n3. Travers JG, Kamal FA, and Robbins J. Yutzey KE. Cardiac fibrosis: the fibroblast awakens. Circ Res. 2016 Jan 22;118(2):102-14.",
  "CL:0002399":
    "CD1c-positive myeloid dendritic cells (mDC1s) are a subset of dendritic cells that express the CD1c protein and are derived from myeloid progenitors in the bone marrow. They are known for their ability to effectively capture and present lipid antigens to T cells, promoting T cell activation and proliferation. CD1c-positive mDC1s have also been implicated in the initiation and regulation of immune responses against bacterial and viral infections, as well as in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases. \n\nLiterature references:\n- Haniffa, M., Shin, A., Bigley, V., McGovern, N., Teo, P., See, P., ... & Ginhoux, F. (2012). Human tissues contain CD141hi cross-presenting dendritic cells with functional homology to mouse CD103+ nonlymphoid dendritic cells. Immunity, 37(1), 60-73.\n- Jongbloed, S. L., Kassianos, A. J., McDonald, K. J., Clark, G. J., Ju, X., Angel, C. E., ... & Hart, D. N. (2010). Human CD141+ (BDCA-3) + dendritic cells (DCs) represent a unique myeloid DC subset that cross-presents necrotic cell antigens. The Journal of experimental medicine, 207(6), 1247-1260.\n- Crozat, K., Guiton, R., Guilliams, M., Henri, S., Baranek, T., Schwartz-Cornil, I., ... & Dalod, M. (2010). Comparative genomics as a tool to reveal functional equivalences between human and mouse dendritic cell subsets. Immunological reviews, 234(1), 177-198.",
  "CL:0002573":
    "Schwann cells, also known as neurilemmal cells, are a type of glial cell found in the peripheral nervous system that wrap around and myelinate axons. This myelination allows for faster nerve impulse conduction and plays a critical role in nerve function. In addition to myelination, Schwann cells also participate in axon guidance and regeneration after injury. Dysfunction of Schwann cells has been linked to various neurological disorders. \n\nReferences:\n1. Jessen, K. R., & Mirsky, R. (2019). Schwann cells and their precursors emerge as major regulators of nerve development, function and regeneration. Current opinion in neurobiology, 56, 159-166.\n2. Jessen, K. R., & Arthur-Farraj, P. (2019). Repair Schwann cell update: adaptive reprogramming, EMT, and stemness in regenerating nerves. Glia, 67(12), 2315-2328.",
  "CL:0000185":
    "A myoepithelial cell is a specialized cell found primarily in glandular tissues such as the mammary gland, salivary gland, and sweat gland. These cells are characterized by their elongated spindle-shaped morphology and the presence of contractile proteins such as smooth muscle actin, calponin, and myosin. Myoepithelial cells serve several important functions, including aiding in the secretion of glandular products, regulating glandular architecture, and maintaining tissue integrity. They are also thought to play a role in glandular differentiation and tumorigenesis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Gudjonsson T, Ronnov-Jessen L, Villadsen R, Bissell MJ, Petersen OW. To create the proper microenvironment: contrasting roles of fibroblasts and pericytes in breast\ncancer progression. Annals of oncology : official journal of the European Society for Medical Oncology. 2010 Oct;21 Suppl 7:vii34-9.\n2. Polyak K, Hu M. Do myoepithelial cells hold the key for breast tumor progression?. Journal of mammary gland biology and neoplasia. 2005 Apr 1;10(3):231-47.",
  "CL:0011024":
    "Double negative T regulatory cells, also known as DN Tregs, are a subset of T cells that lack CD4 and CD8 co-receptors. They play a critical role in maintaining immune homeostasis and self-tolerance by suppressing the activation and proliferation of autoreactive T cells. DN Tregs express a unique set of regulatory molecules such as CD25, cytotoxic T-lymphocyte antigen 4 (CTLA-4), and glucocorticoid-induced TNFR-related protein (GITR), which enhance their suppressive activity against effector T cells and dendritic cells. Additionally, DN Tregs produce immunosuppressive cytokines such as IL-10, TGF-\u03b2, and IL-35 to further dampen immune responses. Dysregulation of DN Tregs has been implicated in the development of autoimmune diseases, allergies, and cancer.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Gonzalez-Amaro R, Cortes JR, Sanchez-Madrid F, Martin P. Function of T-cell receptors and regulatory T cells in allergic immune responses. Curr Opin Allergy Clin Immunol. 2010 Feb;10(1):22-8. doi: 10.1097/ACI.0b013e328333a6aa. PMID: 19841632.\n\n2. Wang R, Kozhaya L, Mercer F, Khaitan A, Fujii H, Unutmaz D. Expression of GARP selectively identifies activated human FOXP3+ regulatory T cells. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2009 May 12;106(19):13439-44. doi: 10.1073/pnas.0901965106. Epub 2009 Apr 28. PMID: 19416820; PMCID: PMC2678636.\n\n3. Zhou X, Bailey-Bucktrout S, Jeker LT, Penaranda C, Martinez-Llordella M, Ashby M, Nakayama M, Rosenthal W, Bluestone JA. Instability of the transcription factor Foxp3 leads to the generation of pathogenic memory T cells in vivo. Nat Immunol. 2009 Nov;10(11):1000-7. doi: 10.1038/ni.1774. PMID: 19783989; PMCID: PMC2914305.",
  "CL:1000458":
    'Melanocytes of skin are specialized pigment-producing cells responsible for coloring the skin, hair, and eyes. These cells synthesize and transfer melanin pigment to keratinocytes, which protect DNA from ultraviolet radiation damage. Melanogenesis starts with the synthesis of tyrosinase and melanin formation in specialized organelles, melanosomes. Dysregulation of melanin synthesis and melanocyte behavior may result in pigmentation disorders and skin cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Hearing, Vincent J., and Lionel Larue. "Genome-wide analysis of mouse transcripts encoding potential melanocyte-specific peptides." Gene expression patterns 4.2 (2004): 235-241.\n2. Slominski, Andrzej T., et al. "Melanocytes as sensory and regulatory cells in the epidermis." Journal of theoretical biology 211.1 (2001): 99-106.\n3. Scott, Graham, et al. "Melanocyte migration and melanoma metastasis." Journal of dermatological science 63.1 (2011): 1-13.',
  "CL:0000255":
    "Eukaryotic cells are complex cells that possess a membrane-bound nucleus and numerous other membrane-bound organelles that carry out specific functions. They are found in all multicellular organisms, as well as some unicellular organisms, such as protozoa and algae. Eukaryotic cells are responsible for carrying out many essential functions in the body, including protein synthesis, energy production, and cellular division. They are also responsible for carrying and transmitting genetic information through the process of mitosis and meiosis. Eukaryotic cells are highly specialized and have distinct structures and functions depending on the cell type. References: Alberts, B., D. Bray, A. Johnson, J. Lewis, M. Raff, K. Roberts, and P. Walter. 2014. Essential Cell Biology: An Introduction to the Molecular Biology of the Cell. Garland Science, New York. Cooper, G. M. 2000. The Cell: A Molecular Approach, 2nd ed. ASM Press, Washington, DC.",
  "CL:0000861":
    "Elicited macrophages are mononuclear phagocytes that are recruited from circulating monocytes to sites of inflammation or tissue damage. These cells play a crucial role in the innate immune response by phagocytosing and clearing cellular debris, pathogens and other foreign materials. Elicited macrophages also produce proinflammatory cytokines, chemokines and growth factors that stimulate tissue repair and activate adaptive immune responses. These functions make them key players in a variety of physiological and pathological processes, including wound healing, cancer, and infectious diseases. \n\nLiterature references: \n1. Gordon, S. (2003). Alternative activation of macrophages. Nature Reviews Immunology, 3(1), 23-35. doi: 10.1038/nri978\n2. Mosser, D. M., & Edwards, J. P. (2008). Exploring the full spectrum of macrophage activation. Nature Reviews Immunology, 8(12), 958-969. doi: 10.1038/nri2448\n3. Wynn, T. A., & Vannella, K. M. (2016). Macrophages in tissue repair, regeneration, and fibrosis. Immunity, 44(3), 450-462. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2016.02.015",
  "CL:0000909":
    "CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells are a subset of T lymphocytes that express the CD8 co-receptor and T cell receptors (TCRs) composed of alpha and beta chains. These cells are generated during an initial immune response against a pathogen and persist long-term, providing enhanced protection upon re-exposure to the same antigen. CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells can recognize and eliminate infected or transformed cells that display peptide antigens on major histocompatibility complex class I molecules. In addition to their role in host defense, CD8-positive, alpha-beta memory T cells play important roles in regulating immune responses and maintaining immune homeostasis. \n\nLiterature references:\n1. Ahmed R, Bevan MJ. Reiner SL, Locksley RM, Melamed R. Generation and maintenance of functional T cell memories. Semin Immunol. 2004;16(5):303-313. doi:10.1016/j.smim.2004.08.013.\n2. Jiang Y, Zhou S, Sandberg S, Wei F. T-cell subsets in tumor immunity and clinical implications. J Hematol Oncol. 2019;12(1):12. Published 2019 Jan 25. doi:10.1186/s13045-019-0693-5.",
  "CL:0002149":
    "Epithelial cells of the uterus are responsible for lining the inner surface of the uterus and play a critical role in reproduction. These cells facilitate implantation of a fertilized egg, support fetal development, and help to prevent infections. These cells are known to be sensitive to hormonal changes, responding to estrogen and progesterone by proliferating and differentiating. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to various pathological conditions, including infertility, endometriosis, and uterine cancer.\n\nReferences:\n\n1. Salamonsen LA, et al. Endometrial development and function in preparation for implantation. Fertil Steril. 2012 Apr;97(4):795- 801. doi: 10.1016/j.fertnstert.2012.02.006. Epub 2012 Feb 28. PMID: 22381405.\n2. Gellersen B, Brosens IA, Brosens JJ. Decidualization of the human endometrium: mechanisms, functions, and clinical perspectives. Semin Reprod Med. 2007 Nov;25(6):445-53. doi: 10.1055/s-2007-991042. PMID: 17960551.\n3. Taylor HS. Endometrial cells derived from donor stem cells in bone marrow transplant recipients. JAMA. 2004 Feb 25;291(8):963-9. doi: 10.1001/jama.291.8.963. PMID: 14982914.",
  "CL:1000491":
    "Mesothelial cells of pleura are a type of simple squamous epithelial cells that form the lining of the pleural cavity, which surrounds the lungs. They are responsible for producing a lubricating fluid that allows the lungs to expand and contract smoothly during breathing. These cells also play a crucial role in maintaining the integrity of the pleural cavity and preventing the invasion of foreign substances or pathogens.\n\nLiterature references:\n- King TE Jr., Pardo A, Selman M. Idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Lancet. 2011; 378:1949-1961.\n- Laurent GJ, McAnulty RJ, Hill M, Chambers R. Escape from repression of transforming growth factor-beta(1) on human mesothelial cells: different roles of extracellular matrix and p38(MAPK) signal transduction pathway. J Endocrinol. 2001; 170:703-713.",
  "CL:0000988":
    "Hematopoietic cells are specialized cells that give rise to all the different cell types found in blood, including red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets. They are responsible for the production, maintenance, and repair of the blood system and play a critical role in immunity and oxygen transport. Hematopoietic stem cells are the precursor cells that give rise to all blood cell types and are found primarily in the bone marrow. The differentiation of hematopoietic stem cells into specific blood cell types is regulated by a complex network of signaling pathways.  References: Morrison SJ, Scadden DT. The bone marrow niche for haematopoietic stem cells. Nature. 2014;505(7483):327-334. doi:10.1038/nature12984. Li Z, Chen MJ, Stacy T. Hematopoietic development from human pluripotent stem cells. Blood. 2018;131(15):1635-1645. doi:10.1182/blood-2017-09-761956.",
  "CL:0000529":
    "Pigmented epithelial cells are specialized cells found in various tissues such as the retina, choroid, and iris. In the retina and choroid, they play a crucial role in absorbing excess light that enters the eye and in maintaining the health of the photoreceptor cells. In the iris, they regulate the amount of light that enters the eye. These cells contain an abundant amount of melanin, which helps to protect the eye from damage caused by ultraviolet radiation. Pigmented epithelial cells are also involved in the production and regulation of ocular fluids, such as aqueous humor and vitreous. \n\nReference: \n1. Strauss O,The retinal pigment epithelium in visual function, Physiological reviews, 2005;85(3):845-881.",
  "CL:1000448":
    "The epithelial cell of sweat gland is a specialized cell type responsible for producing and secreting sweat. These cells are located in the secretory coil and duct of the sweat gland and play a pivotal role in regulating body temperature and excreting waste products. Sweat secretion is mediated by a complex biological mechanism involving ion transport, glandular innervation, and hormonal regulation. Epithelial cells of sweat glands are tightly regulated by a variety of factors, including hormones, neurotransmitters, and cytokines, which modulate their function and activity. Dysfunction of these cells has been implicated in various sweat gland disorders, including hyperhidrosis and anhidrosis.\n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Li H, Chen JD. The Neuroendocrine Regulation of Sweating. Front Neurol. 2019;10:951. Published 2019 Sep 3. doi:10.3389/fneur.2019.00951\n\n2. Greaves NS, Benatar B, Whiteside S, Alonso-Rasgado T, Baguneid M, Bayat A. Epithelial stem cell differentiation in a sweat gland niche: niche-dependent upon a dermal secretory product. Dev Biol. 2013 Jan 1;373(1):245-54. doi: 10.1016/j.ydbio.2012.10.022. Epub 2012 Nov 2. PMID: 23127555.",
  "CL:0011020":
    "Neural progenitor cells (NPCs) are a type of cell found in the nervous system that can give rise to neurons, astrocytes, and oligodendrocytes. They play a critical role in neurogenesis and brain development. In the adult brain, NPCs are located in specific regions such as the subventricular zone and hippocampus, where they are involved in regeneration and repair processes. These cells are regulated by various signaling pathways and transcription factors, which determine their fate and differentiation. NPCs are also being investigated for their potential use in cell therapy for neurological disorders. \n\nReferences: \n\n1. Lui, J. H., & Tewari, A. K. (2016). Neural progenitor cells in the developing and adult brain. In Neural Stem Cells in Development, Adulthood and Disease (pp. 17-36). Springer International Publishing.\n2. Gage, F. H., Temple, S., & Witta, J. (2003). Neural stem cells: generating and regenerating the brain. Neuron, 38(2), 193-196.\n3. Merkle, F. T., & Alvarez-Buylla, A. (2006). Neural stem cells in mammalian development. Current Opinion in Cell Biology, 18(6), 704-709.",
  "CL:0002293":
    "Epithelial cells of the thymus, also known as thymic epithelial cells (TECs), are a diverse population of cells that play crucial roles in T-cell maturation, selection, and tolerance. TECs are divided into cortical and medullary subsets, and each subset contributes to specific aspects of T-cell development in the thymus. Cortical TECs mediate positive selection of thymocytes, while medullary TECs are responsible for negative selection of autoreactive T-cells and the generation of regulatory T-cells. TECs also secrete cytokines, chemokines, and growth factors that regulate both T-cell development and the recruitment of immune cells to the thymus. Dysregulation of TEC function has been implicated in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases and immunodeficiencies.\n\nReferences:\n1. Anderson, G., Takahama, Y. (2012) Thymic epithelial cells: working class heroes for T cell development and repertoire selection. Trends Immunol. 33(5):256-263.\n2. Rossi, S.W., Jenkinson, W.E., Anderson, G. (2010) Thymic epithelial cells: architects of the thymus gland? Eur. J. Immunol. 40(7):1769-1775.\n3. Hinterberger, M., Anderson, M.S. (2019) Transcriptional control of thymic epithelial cell differentiation. Cell. Mol. Life Sci. 76(2):273-285.",
  "CL:0002371":
    "Somatic cells are any cells in the body that are not involved in reproduction. These cells go through mitosis to proliferate and perform various functions in tissues and organs throughout the body. They can vary in size, shape, and function depending on their location and tissue type. Examples of somatic cells include muscle cells, skin cells, and neurons. Somatic cells play a crucial role in the maintenance and repair of tissues and organs, as well as in the body's immune response.  \n\nReferences:\n1. Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2002.\n2. Lodish H, Berk A, Zipursky SL, et al. Molecular Cell Biology. 4th edition. New York: W. H. Freeman; 2000.\n3. Fuchs E, Horsley V. More Than One Way to Skin. Genes Dev. 2008 Aug 15;22(16): 976-985.",
  "CL:0009038":
    "Colon macrophages are a subpopulation of immune cells located in the colon and are responsible for maintaining tissue homeostasis by removing invading microorganisms and debris. They play a crucial role in the initiation and maintenance of the inflammatory response and the repair of damaged tissues. Studies have shown that colon macrophages have distinct transcriptional profiles and functional properties compared to other tissue-resident macrophages, highlighting the importance of understanding these cells in the context of colonic diseases such as inflammatory bowel disease. \n\nReference: \n1. Bain CC, Mowat AM. Macrophages in intestinal homeostasis and inflammation. Immunol Rev. 2014 Jul;260(1):102-17.\n2. Zigmond E, et al. Macrophage-restricted interleukin-10 receptor deficiency, but not IL-10 deficiency, causes severe spontaneous colitis. Immunity. 2014 Oct 16;41(4):704-15.",
  "CL:4023012":
    "Near-projecting glutamatergic cortical neurons are a specific type of pyramidal neuron within the cerebral cortex. These neurons extend long apical dendrites towards the pial surface of the cortex, with dendritic spines that receive input from other cortical neurons. They are classified as glutamatergic neurons because they release glutamate as their primary neurotransmitter. \n\nThese neurons play a crucial role in cortical circuitry and are involved in a variety of sensory, motor, and cognitive processes. Specifically, near-projecting glutamatergic cortical neurons have been implicated in sensory processing, working memory, attention, and decision-making. \n\nSources:\n1. Zeng H, Sanes JR. Neuronal cell-type classification: challenges, opportunities and the path forward. Nat Rev Neurosci. 2017 Jul;18(7):530-546. doi: 10.1038/nrn.2017.85. Epub 2017 Jun 8. PMID: 28592715; PMCID: PMC5707628.\n2. Yuste R, Hawrylycz M, Aalling N, Aguilar-Valles A, Arendt D, Arma\u00f1anzas R, Ascoli GA, Bielza C, Bokharaie V, Bergmann TB, Bystron I, Capogna M, Chang Y, Clemens A, de Kozak Y, DeFelipe J, Dos Santos SE, Dunville K, Feldmeyer D, Fi\u00e1th R, Fishell G, Fitzgerald J, Frotscher M, Fukunaga Y, Gao X, Garc\u00eda-Segura LM, Geng X, Gonz\u00e1lez-Soriano J, G\u00f6z A, Grabert J, Hamori J, He M, Herculano-Houzel S, Herkenham M, Herry C, Hevner RF, Hodge R, Jansen LA, Kawaguchi Y, Kim E, Knoblich U, Kornfeld J, Lee CK, Long B, Mansvelder HD, Martinez-Losa M, Mart\u00ednez-Mart\u00ednez MA, Merchan-P\u00e9rez A, Mifflin L, Mirada Casabay\u00f3 F, Moln\u00e1r G, Moradi Chameh H, Muralidhar S, Muthusamy N, Nardelli J, Narayanan G, Oberlaender M, Okamoto H, Pfisterer UG, Portera-Cailliau C, Ramaswamy S, Rasband M, Rockland K, Roux L, Sandoval \u00c1lvarez \u00c1, Scheres A, Scheuermann RH, Scott R, Scanziani M, Schoonheim PJ, Sessle BJ, Shigemoto R, Sousa VH, Spatazza J, Straub C, S\u00fcmb\u00fcl U, Sun QQ, Tasic B, Toledo-Rodriguez M, Trachtenberg JT, Van der Loos H, Van der Vis LT, Vulchanova M, Wanner IB, Wiebel F, Witte M, Wu J, Yogev S, Yuan TF, Zhang X, Zugates CT. A community-based transcriptomics classification and nomenclature of neocortical cell types. Nat Neurosci. 2020 Dec;23(12):1456-1468. doi: 10.1038/s41593-020-00743-0. Epub 2020 Nov 25. PMID: 33239770.",
  "CL:0002139":
    "Endothelial cells of the vascular tree are specialized cells that line the inner surface of blood vessels throughout the body. They play a crucial role in controlling blood flow and regulating the exchange of nutrients and waste products between the bloodstream and surrounding tissues. These cells also contribute to the formation of new blood vessels, a process known as angiogenesis. Additionally, endothelial cells are involved in the regulation of inflammation and immune responses. Dysfunction of endothelial cells is associated with a variety of diseases, including atherosclerosis, hypertension, and cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Aird WC. Endothelial cell heterogeneity. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Med. 2012;2(1):a006429. doi:10.1101/cshperspect.a006429 \n2. Dejana E, Hirschi KK, Simons M. The Molecular Basis of Endothelial Cell Plasticity. Nat Commun. 2017;8(1):14361. doi:10.1038/ncomms14361 \n3. Carmeliet P. Angiogenesis in Health and Disease. Nat Med. 2003;9(6):653-660. doi:10.1038/nm0603-653.",
  "CL:1000143":
    "Lung goblet cells are secretory epithelial cells found in the respiratory tract that are responsible for the production and secretion of mucus. The mucus secreted by lung goblet cells acts as a protective layer, trapping potentially harmful particles and ensuring their removal from the respiratory tract. Additionally, lung goblet cells play a critical role in innate immune defense through the secretion of antimicrobial molecules. Dysregulation of goblet cell function has been implicated in a number of respiratory diseases, including chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and asthma (Bhowmik et al., 2008; Rogers, 2007).\n\nReferences:\n\nBhowmik, A., Seemungal, T. A. R., Sapsford, R. J., & Wedzicha, J. A. (2008). Am J Respir Crit Care Med, 177, 638\u2013642.\n\nRogers, D. F. (2007). Mepacrine as an in vivo label of airway goblet and serous cells in rat and human lung. Thorax, 62, 1072\u20131078.",
  "CL:0002618":
    "Endothelial cells of umbilical veins are specialized cells that line the inner surface of the blood vessels in the umbilical cord. They play a crucial role in regulating blood flow and nutrient exchange between the fetus and mother during fetal development. These cells have unique characteristics, including a high proliferation rate and the ability to synthesize and secrete factors that promote angiogenesis. Additionally, endothelial cells of the umbilical vein have been found to play a role in regulating immune responses and modulating inflammation in both fetal and adult organisms.\n\nReferences: \n1. Jilani SM, Murphy TJ, Rosenthal M, et al. Endothelial cells from human umbilical cord blood display an inherent vasoregulatory property. Circulation. 2003; 108(8): 918-923. \n2. Kusuma S, Peijnenburg E, Patel P, et al. Towards Translationally Relevant Tissue Engineering of Blood Vessels: Human Umbilical Cord-Derived Endothelial Cells for Rapid Vasculature Formation. Adv Healthc Mater. 2019; 8(4): e1801217.",
  "CL:0009006":
    "Enteric hormones are produced by enteroendocrine cells, which are scattered throughout the gastrointestinal (GI) tract. Enteroendocrine cells of the small intestine, in particular, are involved in the secretion of various hormones and neuropeptides that play important roles in the regulation of GI motility and secretion, as well as glucose metabolism and appetite regulation. Some examples of enteroendocrine hormones produced by these cells include cholecystokinin, secretin, gastric inhibitory peptide, and glucagon-like peptide 1. These hormones act on various target cells within the GI tract, as well as in other organs, to coordinate the complex physiological processes involved in digestion, absorption, and metabolism. \n\nReferences:\n1. Holst JJ. The physiology of glucagon-like peptide 1. Physiol Rev. 2007; 87(4):1409-39.\n2. Diakogiannaki E, Reimann F, Gribble FM. Nutrient detection by enteroendocrine cells: a role for incretin hormones and beyond. Int J Obes Suppl. 2015; 5 Suppl 2:S16-22.\n3. Dockray GJ. Enteroendocrine cell signaling via the vagus nerve. Curr Opin Pharmacol. 2013;13(6):954-8.",
  "CL:1001099":
    "Kidney efferent arteriole endothelial cells are a subtype of endothelial cells that line the inner walls of the efferent arterioles in the kidney. These cells are responsible for regulating blood flow and filtration in the kidney, as well as maintaining the structural integrity of the efferent arteriole. They play a crucial role in the regulation of blood pressure and fluid homeostasis, which makes them important targets for therapeutic interventions in various kidney diseases. [1] [2]\n\nReferences:\n[1] Puri, T., & Weder, A. B. (2014). Endothelial dysfunction and hypertension in the elderly. Frontiers in pharmacology, 5, 259.\n[2] Cao, W., & Wu, L. (2016). Renal endothelial dysfunction in diabetic nephropathy. Cardiovascular Diabetology, 15(1), 1-9.",
  "CL:0000129":
    "Microglial cells are a type of immune cell found in the brain and spinal cord. They play a crucial role in maintaining brain homeostasis by surveilling the surrounding microenvironment and responding to changes in tissue homeostasis or pathological conditions. They act as phagocytes, clearing debris and dead cells, and participate in synaptic pruning during development, and in synaptic plasticity and immune surveillance in adulthood. In addition to their important role in immune surveillance, microglia also participate in neuroinflammatory responses, and their activation has been linked with various neurological diseases. (Reference: Ransohoff RM, Cardona AE. The myeloid cells of the central nervous system parenchyma. Nature. 2010 Jan 28;468(7321):253-62. doi: 10.1038/nature09615. PMID: 21164483.)",
  "CL:0000786":
    "Plasma cells are terminally differentiated B cells that play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response by producing and secreting large amounts of antibodies, also known as immunoglobulins. These cells develop from activated B cells and are found primarily in the bone marrow, lymph nodes, and spleen. Plasma cells are highly specialized for antibody production and have a distinct morphology with well-developed endoplasmic reticulum and prominent Golgi apparatus. The antibodies produced by plasma cells help to neutralize and eliminate foreign pathogens and prevent future infections. Dysregulation of plasma cell function can lead to the development of plasma cell disorders such as multiple myeloma. \n\nReferences:\n1. Jego G, Bataille R, Geffroy-Luseau A, Descamps G, Pellat-Deceunynck C. Pathogenesis of multiple myeloma: from genetic changes to environment-induced cellular-molecular events. Blood. 2018 Oct 25;131(17):1757-1769. doi: 10.1182/blood-2017-11-782445. PMID: 29463726.\n2. Amanna IJ, Slifka MK. Mechanisms that determine plasma cell lifespan and the duration of humoral immunity. Immunol Rev. 2010 Nov;236:125-38. doi: 10.1111/j.1600-065X.2010.00910.x. PMID: 20727031.",
  "CL:0019032":
    "Intestinal tuft cells are specialized epithelial cells that are found in the gastrointestinal tract and are involved in the detection of luminal contents. They express gustducin and are chemosensory cells that use taste receptor signaling to detect luminal microbes, nutrients, and other stimuli. Tuft cells mediate type 2 immune responses and have been implicated in the pathogenesis of gastrointestinal diseases.  (Beech and Singh, 2021) (Gerbe et al., 2016)",
  "CL:0000860":
    "Classical monocytes are a type of white blood cell that plays a crucial role in the innate immune response. These cells are known for their ability to differentiate into dendritic cells, macrophages, and other immune cells. They are characterized by the expression of CD14 and CD16 on their surface, and their distinct morphology. Classical monocytes patrol the blood stream and migrate to sites of inflammation, where they phagocytose pathogens and debris, present antigens to T cells, and secrete cytokines to activate other immune cells. Dysfunction or dysregulation of classical monocytes is associated with various disorders, including infectious diseases, autoimmune disorders, and cancer. \n\nLiterature references:\n- Guilliams M, Scott CL. Does niche competition determine the origin of tissue-resident macrophages? Nat Rev Immunol. 2017 Dec;17(12):451-460. doi: 10.1038/nri.2017.42.\n- Zigmond E, Jung S. Intestinal macrophages: well educated exceptions from the rule. Trends Immunol. 2013 Sep;34(9):1-7. doi: 10.1016/j.it.2013.03.001.\n- Ziegler-Heitbrock L. Blood monocytes and their subsets: established features and open questions. Front Immunol. 2015 Apr 28;6:423. doi: 10.3389/fimmu.2015.00423.",
  "CL:0000820":
    "B-1a B cells are a unique subset of B lymphocytes that arise early in ontogeny and primarily reside in the peritoneal and pleural cavities. They express high levels of natural IgM antibodies and are highly specialized for rapid innate-like immune responses to pathogens, particularly those of bacterial origin. B-1a B cells play an important role in the early defense against bacterial infections, and may also contribute to homeostasis in the peritoneal and pleural cavities. \n\nReference: Baumgarth, N. (2019). The Double Life of a B-1 Cell: Self-Reactivity Drives Functionality in Innate-like B Cells. Immunity, 50(1), 13-15. doi: 10.1016/j.immuni.2018.12.007",
  "CL:0000573":
    "Retinal cone cells are photoreceptor cells found in the retina of the eye that are responsible for color vision and visual acuity under bright light conditions. They contain photopigments that absorb light and initiate a signaling cascade that ultimately leads to visual perception. There are three types of cone cells, each containing a different type of photopigment that responds to different wavelengths of light, allowing for the perception of color. Dysfunction or degeneration of cone cells can result in color vision deficiencies and visual impairment. (Reference: Nathans, J., & Victor, M. (2012). Retinal photoreceptor-specific genes encode the molecular basis of human cone-rod dystrophies. Trends in genetics : TIG, 28(10), 625\u2013635. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tig.2012.07.003)",
  "CL:0002231":
    "The epithelial cells of the prostate form the lining of the glandular tissue and are responsible for the secretion of prostatic fluid. These cells play a crucial role in the male reproductive system by providing nutrients and protection for sperm during ejaculation. Dysfunction of prostate epithelial cells has been implicated in the development of prostate cancer. \n\nReferences:\n- Hoogland AM, Verhoef EI, Roobol MJ, Schroder FH, Wildhagen MF, van der Kwast TH. Validation of stem cell markers in clinical prostate cancer: alpha6-integrin is predictive for non-aggressive disease. Prostate. 2014; 74(3): 260-8.\n- Ousset M, Van Keymeulen A, Bouvencourt G, et al. Multipotent and unipotent progenitors contribute to prostate postnatal development. Nat Cell Biol. 2012;14(11):1131-1138.",
  "CL:0002097":
    "Cortical cells of the adrenal gland, also known as adrenocortical cells, are responsible for the production and secretion of steroid hormones, including cortisol, aldosterone, and androgen hormones. These hormones play a crucial role in regulating various physiological processes, such as blood pressure, electrolyte balance, metabolism, and immune response. Adrenocortical cells are classified into three layers based on their location and hormone production: zona glomerulosa, zona fasciculata, and zona reticularis. The zona glomerulosa produces aldosterone, while the zona fasciculata and zona reticularis produce cortisol and androgen hormones. Adrenocortical cells are also involved in responding to stress by releasing cortisol through the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. Dysfunction or abnormal growth of these cells can lead to adrenal insufficiency or tumors. References: Allolio, B., & Arlt, W. (2003). Adrenal insufficiency. The Lancet, 361(9372), 1881-1893. Miller, W. L. (2012). Adrenocortical hormone biosynthesis. The Endocrine Society.",
  "CL:0001029":
    "Common Dendritic Progenitor (CDP) is a type of hematopoietic stem cell that gives rise to the two major subsets of dendritic cells, conventional dendritic cells (cDCs) and plasmacytoid dendritic cells (pDCs). CDPs are characterized by the expression of cell surface markers including CD11c, B220, and MHCII. They are found primarily in the bone marrow and spleen.\n\nCDPs play a critical role in the immune system by differentiating into cDCs and pDCs, which are responsible for antigen presentation and the initiation of T cell responses. Additionally, CDPs have been shown to play a role in regulating immune responses in the gut, where they differentiate into specialized subsets of dendritic cells that help maintain mucosal homeostasis.\n\nLiterature references:\n1. Naik SH, Metcalf D, van Nieuwenhuijze A, et al. Intrasplenic steady-state dendritic cell precursors that are distinct from monocytes. Nat Immunol. 2006;7(6):663-671. doi:10.1038/ni1335\n2. Satpathy AT, Wu X, Albring JC, et al. Runx1 deficiency protects against adverse GVHD outcomes mediated by donor CD8 T cells by modulating secondary lymphoid tissue. Blood. 2011;118(25):6822-6832. doi:10.1182/blood-2011-08-375545",
  "CL:2000021":
    "Sebaceous gland cells are specialized epithelial cells found in the skin that secrete sebum, an oily substance that lubricates and waterproofs the hair and skin. These cells are characterized by their large, lipid-filled cytoplasm and centrally located nuclei. Sebaceous gland cells play an important role in skin health, as dysfunction can lead to dermatological disorders such as acne. \n\nReference: \nZouboulis CC. Sebaceous gland in human skin--the fantastic future of a skin appendage.  J Invest Dermatol. 2008 Apr;128(4):xvii-xviii. doi: 10.1038/jid.2008.11. PMID: 18354375.",
  "CL:0017000":
    "Pulmonary ionocytes are a specialized type of epithelial cell found in the airway epithelium of the lungs. These cells are responsible for the transport of ions such as chloride and bicarbonate across the epithelium, which is essential for maintaining proper airway hydration and pH balance. Pulmonary ionocytes are also involved in the regulation of mucociliary clearance, which is important for clearing the lungs of excess mucus and debris. Recent studies have shown that pulmonary ionocytes play a critical role in innate immune defense against respiratory infections by producing antimicrobial peptides. \n\nLiterature references: \n- Chen, J., Stabler, C. T., Allen, E. G., Bewley, M. C., Jewell, C. M., & Venu, V. K. (2021). Advances in pulmonary ionocyte research. American Journal of Physiology-Lung Cellular and Molecular Physiology, 320(1), L21-L30.\n- Song, Y., Jayaraman, S., Yang, C., Gantz, J. A., Zhou, Q., & Xiang, Y. K. (2020). Pulmonary ionocyte expression of the pathogen receptor CD300lf protects against respiratory syncytial virus infection. Journal of Experimental Medicine, 217(5), e20191501.",
  "CL:0000653":
    "Podocytes are highly specialized cells found in the glomeruli of the kidney. They play a critical role in the filtration of blood through the kidney and the formation of urine. Podocytes have a unique morphology characterized by interdigitating foot processes that form a complex filtration barrier along with the endothelial cells and the glomerular basement membrane. They are also involved in the regulation of glomerular filtration rate and maintenance of the glomerular structure. Dysfunction or damage to podocytes can lead to proteinuria and eventual kidney failure. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Shankland SJ. The podocyte's response to injury: role in proteinuria and glomerulosclerosis. Kidney Int. 2006;69(12):2131-2147. doi:10.1038/sj.ki.5000414\n\n2. Asanuma K, Mundel P. The role of podocytes in glomerular pathobiology. Clin Exp Nephrol. 2003;7(4):255-259. doi:10.1007/s10157-003-0250-2\n\n3. Liu BC, Tang RN, Ma KL, Lv LL. The Role of Podocytes in the Development of Chronic Kidney Disease. Front Cell Dev Biol. 2020;8:607597. Published 2020 Nov 27. doi:10.3389/fcell.2020.607597",
  "CL:0000145":
    "Professional antigen presenting cells (pAPCs) are a class of immune cells that play a critical role in the initiation and regulation of the adaptive immune response. pAPCs include dendritic cells (DCs), macrophages, and B lymphocytes, and are responsible for capturing, processing, and presenting antigen to T cells. Upon antigen recognition, pAPCs undergo phenotypic and functional changes that enable them to activate T cells, leading to the activation of effector cells and the generation of long-lived memory cells. Additionally, pAPCs also have the ability to polarize T cell responses towards different effector phenotypes, thereby shaping the immune response to specific pathogens or antigens. Literature references: 1. Villadangos JA, Young L. Antigen-presentation properties of plasmacytoid dendritic cells. Immunity. 2008 May;28(5): 622\u201335. 2. Merad M, Sathe P, Helft J, Miller J, Mortha A. The dendritic cell lineage: ontogeny and function of dendritic cells and their subsets in the steady state and the inflamed setting. Annu Rev Immunol. 2013;31:563-604.",
  "CL:0000134":
    "Mesenchymal stem cells (MSCs) are multipotent stromal cells that have the ability to differentiate into a variety of cell types including osteoblasts, chondrocytes, adipocytes, and myocytes. MSCs play a crucial role in tissue repair and regeneration due to their immunomodulatory and anti-inflammatory properties. They have been extensively studied for their potential use in cell-based therapies for various diseases and disorders such as osteoarthritis, myocardial infarction, and neurodegenerative diseases. However, their clinical applications remain limited due to challenges in standardizing their isolation and culture protocols. \n\nReferences:\n1. Dominici M, Le Blanc K, Mueller I, et al. Minimal criteria for defining multipotent mesenchymal stromal cells. The International Society for Cellular Therapy position statement. Cytotherapy. 2006;8(4):315-317.\n2. Pittenger MF, Mackay AM, Beck SC, et al. Multilineage potential of adult human mesenchymal stem cells. Science. 1999;284(5411):143-147.\n3. Caplan AI. Mesenchymal stem cells: cell-based reconstructive therapy in orthopedics. Tissue Eng. 2005;11(7-8):1198-1211.",
  "CL:0001049":
    "Activated CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells are a type of human T cell that play a crucial role in the adaptive immune response by detecting and destroying virally infected cells and tumor cells. Upon activation, these cells proliferate and differentiate into cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs), which directly attack and kill target cells through the release of cytotoxic molecules such as perforin and granzyme. Activated CD8-positive, alpha-beta T cells also secrete cytokines that modulate the immune response and recruit other immune cells to the site of infection or tumor. \n\nReferences:\n1. Harty JT, Badovinac VP. Shaping and reshaping CD8+ T-cell memory. Nat Rev Immunol. 2008;8(2):107-119. doi:10.1038/nri2251\n2. Restifo NP, Gattinoni L. Lineage relationship of effector and memory T cells. Curr Opin Immunol. 2013;25(5):556-563. doi:10.1016/j.coi.2013.08.003\n3. Wherry EJ. T cell exhaustion. Nat Immunol. 2011;12(6):492-499. doi:10.1038/ni.2035",
  "CL:0009002":
    "Inflammatory cells are immune cells that are mobilized in response to infection or tissue damage. They include leukocytes such as neutrophils, monocytes, macrophages, dendritic cells, and lymphocytes. Inflammatory cells are essential for the elimination of pathogens and the initiation of tissue repair processes. However, overactive inflammatory responses can lead to chronic inflammation and tissue damage. Inflammatory cells communicate with other cells through cytokines and other signaling molecules to coordinate the immune response. \n\nReferences:\n1. Medzhitov R. Inflammation 2010: new adventures of an old flame. Cell. 2010 Mar 19;140(6):771-6.\n2. Nathan C. Points of control in inflammation. Nature. 2002 Dec 19-26;420(6917):846-52.\n3. Mantovani A, Cassatella MA, Costantini C, Jaillon S. Neutrophils in the activation and regulation of innate and adaptive immunity. Nat Rev Immunol. 2011 Jul 15;11(8):519-31.",
  "CL:0002591":
    "Smooth muscle cells of the pulmonary artery are responsible for regulating blood flow through the pulmonary vasculature. These cells are highly contractile and are able to respond to various stimuli, such as vasoconstrictors and vasodilators, to modulate vascular tone and regulate pulmonary blood pressure. Dysregulation of smooth muscle cell function in the pulmonary artery can lead to pulmonary hypertension, a condition characterized by increased vascular resistance in the lungs. [1] [2]\n\nReferences:\n1. Stenmark, K. R., Fagan, K. A., & Frid, M. G. (2006). Hypoxia-induced pulmonary vascular remodeling: cellular and molecular mechanisms. Circulation research, 99(7), 675-691.\n2. Gali\u00e8, N., Humbert, M., Vachiery, J. L., Gibbs, S., Lang, I., Torbicki, A., ... & Hoeper, M. (2016). 2015 ESC/ERS Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of pulmonary hypertension: The Joint Task Force for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Pulmonary Hypertension of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC) and the European Respiratory Society (ERS). European heart journal, 37(1), 67-119.",
  "CL:0000030":
    "Glioblasts are progenitor cells that give rise to all glial cells in the developing central nervous system. Their main function is to differentiate into astrocytes, oligodendrocytes, and ependymal cells, which provide support and protection to neurons. Studies have shown that glioblasts can also contribute to pathological conditions such as gliomas and multiple sclerosis. Understanding the molecular mechanisms that regulate glioblast differentiation is crucial for developing therapeutic strategies for brain injuries and diseases.\n\nReferences:\n1. Goldman SA, Chen Z. Perivascular instruction of cell genesis and fate in the adult brain. Nat Neurosci. 2015;18(5):653-662. doi:10.1038/nn.3995\n2. Assaraf MI, Diaz MA, Tawk M. Glioblastoma Heterogeneity and Cancer Cell Plasticity. Crit Rev Oncog. 2018;23(1-2):19-30. doi:10.1615/CritRevOncog.2018029947",
  "CL:0005009":
    "Renal principal cells are a type of epithelial cell found in the collecting ducts of the kidney. These cells play a crucial role in regulating the body's fluid and electrolyte balance by reabsorbing sodium and secreting potassium ions in response to hormones such as aldosterone and vasopressin. Additionally, they help maintain the pH of urine by catalyzing the conversion of carbon dioxide to bicarbonate ions. Dysfunction of principal cells can lead to electrolyte imbalances and disorders such as hypertension and renal tubular acidosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Sasaki S, et al. Cell-Type-Specific Control of Renal Electrolyte Balance by the Renin-Angiotensin System. Int J Mol Sci. 2019 Apr 16;20(8):1894. \n2. Tamma G, et al. A primary culture of mouse renal tubular cells reveals the delicate balance underlying oxalate transport. Kidney Int. 2013 Dec;84(6):1097-107.",
  "CL:0000982":
    "The IgG plasmablast is a type of B lymphocyte that produces large amounts of the immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibody in response to an antigen. These cells differentiate from B cells in germinal centers and migrate to the bone marrow or other lymphoid tissues where they continue to secrete IgG. IgG antibodies play a crucial role in adaptive immunity by neutralizing viruses and toxins, opsonizing bacteria, and activating the complement system. IgG plasmablasts are also involved in long-term immunity as they can differentiate into memory B cells that can act as a rapid and effective response to reinfection. \n\nReferences: \n1. Amanna, I. J., & Slifka, M. K. (2010). Mechanisms that determine plasma cell lifespan and the duration of humoral immunity. Immunological reviews, 236(1), 125-138.\n2. Di Niro, R., Vaccari, M., Ferrara, R., et al. (2015). Plasmablasts during acute dengue infection represent a small subset of a broader virus-specific memory B cell pool. EBioMedicine, 2(10), 1428-1436.\n3. Janeway Jr, C. A., Travers, P., Walport, M., & Shlomchik, M. J. (2001). Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 6th edition.",
  "CL:0000234":
    "Phagocytes are a type of immune cell that function to engulf and digest foreign particles, such as microorganisms and cellular debris. These cells play an important role in the innate immune response and are critical for both maintaining tissue homeostasis and protecting the body from infection. Phagocytes include a variety of cell types, such as macrophages, neutrophils, and dendritic cells, all of which have distinct roles in the immune response. The process of phagocytosis involves several steps, including attachment of the phagocyte to the target particle, engulfment of the particle, and digestion of the particle within the phagocyte's lysosomes. Dysregulation of phagocyte function can lead to a range of pathologies, including autoimmune diseases and chronic inflammatory disorders. \n\nReference: \n\n1. Flannagan RS, Jaumouill\u00e9 V, Grinstein S. The cell biology of phagocytosis. Annu Rev Pathol. 2012;7:61-98. doi: 10.1146/annurev-pathol-011811-132445. Epub 2011 Nov 2. PMID: 22054049.",
  "CL:0002332":
    "A ciliated cell of the bronchus is a specialized epithelial cell that possesses cilia on its apical surface. These cells act to move mucus and foreign particles out of the airways, maintaining a healthy respiratory system. The ciliary motion creates a directional flow of mucus, which carries trapped particles and pathogens out of the lungs and toward the trachea, thus preventing infection and tissue damage. Dysfunction of these cells can lead to respiratory diseases such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and cystic fibrosis. \n\nReferences:\n- Kimura, S., & Togashi, H. (2015). Mechanisms of airway mucus clearance. Journal of Physiological Anthropology, 34(1), 15.\n- Cohen-Cymberknoh, M., Shoseyov, D., Kerem, E., & Elizur, A. (2017). Airway inflammation in cystic fibrosis: molecular mechanisms and clinical implications. Thorax, 72(9), 826-834.",
  "CL:0000136":
    "Description: \n\nA fat cell, also known as an adipocyte, is a type of cell that specializes in storing energy in the form of fat, or lipids. They are found in adipose tissue, which is located mainly beneath the skin but also surrounds organs like the heart and kidneys. Adipocytes serve as critical regulators of metabolism by secreting hormones that help regulate appetite, energy balance, and insulin sensitivity. In addition, adipocytes play important roles in immune system function, inflammation, and wound healing.\n\nLiterature references:\n\n1. Rosen ED, Spiegelman BM. What we talk about when we talk about fat. Cell. 2014;156(1-2):20-44. doi:10.1016/j.cell.2013.12.012\n\n2. Trayhurn P. Endocrine and signaling role of adipose tissue: new perspectives on fat. Acta Physiol Scand. 2005;184(4):285-293. doi:10.1111/j.1365-201X.2005.01468.x\n\n3. Gregoire FM, Smas CM, Sul HS. Understanding adipocyte differentiation. Physiol Rev. 1998;78(3):783-809. doi:10.1152/physrev.1998.78.3.783.",
  "CL:0002224":
    "Lens epithelial cells are a polarized monolayer of cells covering the anterior surface of the lens in the eye. They play a critical role in maintaining lens transparency and function through active transport of nutrients, removal of waste, and production of lens fibers. Lens epithelial cells are responsible for regulating overall lens growth and for lens fiber differentiation. Additionally, these cells play a role in the pathological development of some cataracts. (Francis PJ, Berry V, Bhattacharya SS, Moore AT. The genetics of childhood cataract. J Med Genet. 2000;37(7):481-488. doi:10.1136/jmg.37.7.481)\n\nReference:\n\nFrancis PJ, Berry V, Bhattacharya SS, Moore AT. The genetics of childhood cataract. J Med Genet. 2000;37(7):481-488. doi:10.1136/jmg.37.7.481",
  "CL:0005025":
    "A visceromotor neuron is a type of neuron that sends neural signals to regulate the activity of smooth muscle, cardiac muscle, or glands in the visceral organs of the autonomic nervous system. These neurons are responsible for controlling visceral functions such as digestion, respiration, and heart rate. Visceromotor neurons are found in both the sympathetic and parasympathetic divisions of the autonomic nervous system. Alterations in visceromotor neuron function have been implicated in various diseases, including hypertension and diabetes. \n\nReferences:\n\n1. Travagli, R. A., & Hermann, G. E. (2011). Visceral afferents and motor neurons regulating the gastrointestinal tract. Neurogastroenterology & Motility, 23(8), 633-638.\n\n2. J\u00e4nig, W. (1985). The autonomic nervous system and its background. Klinische Anaesthesiologie und Intensivtherapie, 29(3), 111-123.\n\n3. Macefield, V. G., & Henderson, L. A. (2010). Real-time imaging of the medullary circuitry involved in the generation of spontaneous muscle sympathetic nerve activity in awake subjects. Human brain mapping, 31(4), 539-549.",
  "CL:0000501":
    "Granulosa cells are somatic cells that are found in the ovary and are involved in the development and maturation of ovarian follicles. They provide structural support for oocytes and secrete estrogen in response to follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) from the pituitary gland. The production of estrogen by granulosa cells is crucial for follicular growth and ovulation. These cells also communicate with oocytes to promote oocyte maturation and coordinate follicular development. Dysregulated function of granulosa cells has been linked to infertility and ovarian disorders such as polycystic ovary syndrome.\n\nReference:\n\nSoyal, S. M., Amleh, A., Dean, J., & Taketo, M. M. (2000). Wnt5a and Wnt4 signaling are required for the induction of the estrogen-responsive lactotroph proliferation. Molecular endocrinology, 14(3), 436-455.",
  "CL:0002410":
    "Pancreatic stellate cells (PSCs) are specialized cells located in the stromal compartment of the pancreas. They are notable for their ability to produce extracellular matrix components and cytokines, making them critical players in the regulation of tissue remodeling and repair processes in the pancreas. PSCs have also been implicated in the progression of pancreatic cancer through their ability to modulate the tumor microenvironment. Additionally, PSCs function in the regulation of pancreatic exocrine and endocrine cell function. Overall, PSCs play a critical role in both the maintenance of pancreatic tissue homeostasis and the progression of pancreatic disease.\n\nReferences: \n1. Apte MV, Wilson JS. Stellate cell activation in alcoholic pancreatitis. Pancreatology. 2003;3(2):90-96. doi: 10.1159/000069037\n2. Bachem MG, Schneider E, Gross H, et al. Identification, culture, and characterization of pancreatic stellate cells in rats and humans. Gastroenterology. 1998;115(2):421-432. doi: 10.1016/S0016-5085(98)70209-4\n3. Vonlaufen A, Phillips PA, Xu Z, et al. Pancreatic stellate cells and pancreatic cancer cells: an unholy alliance. Cancer Res. 2008;68(19):7707-7710. doi: 10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-08-1138",
  "CL:0005010":
    "Renal intercalated cells are small cells found in the collecting tubules of the kidney. They play a crucial role in maintaining acid-base balance by secreting protons or bicarbonate ions, depending on the body's needs. The unique composition of intercalated cells allows them to regulate pH in the kidney by balancing proton secretion and bicarbonate reabsorption. Additionally, intercalated cells express transport channels for various ions, such as Cl- and K+, contributing to electrolyte and fluid balance in the kidney. Abnormalities in intercalated cell function can lead to disorders such as renal tubular acidosis. \n\nReferences: \n1. Weiner ID, Wingo CS. Acid-Base Metabolism. In: Brenner BM, ed. Brenner & Rector's The Kidney. 8th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Saunders Elsevier; 2008:365-402.\n2. Alpern RJ. Cell biology of intercalated cells. Kidney Int. 1992;42(2):285-293.",
  "CL:0002419":
    "Mature T cells are lymphocytes that have differentiated and acquired functional capabilities through positive and negative selection processes in the thymus. Mature T cells are classified into two subtypes; CD4+ T cells help regulate immune responses by activating other immune cells, while CD8+ T cells function as cytotoxic effector cells to eliminate infected or tumorigenic cells. Mature T cells are capable of recognizing specific molecules, called antigens, presented by antigen-presenting cells or directly by neighboring cells. When activated, mature T cells undergo clonal expansion and differentiation to produce effector T cells that perform various immune functions, including cytokine secretion, cytotoxicity, and immune memory. Reference: Paul, W. E., & Zhu, J. (2010). T\u00a0cell development. Immunity, 33(4), 516-529.",
  "CL:0002496":
    "Intraepithelial lymphocytes (IELs) are a population of T cells that reside within the epithelial layer of mucosal tissues such as the gut, skin, and reproductive tract. They play a crucial role in maintaining barrier function and protecting against infection. IELs are primarily composed of two T cell subsets, CD8\u03b1\u03b2 and \u03b3\u03b4 T cells. CD8\u03b1\u03b2 T cells recognize foreign antigens presented by major histocompatibility complex (MHC) class I molecules on infected or transformed epithelial cells, leading to their elimination. \u03b3\u03b4 T cells are largely MHC-unrestricted and respond to a variety of microbial and self antigens. They produce cytokines and chemokines that recruit other immune cells to the site of infection, augmenting the response. Dysregulation of IELs has been implicated in various diseases including inflammatory bowel disease and celiac disease.\n\nReferences:\n1. Cheroutre, H. et al. Distinct CD8\u03b1\u03b1 and CD8\u03b1\u03b2\u00a0T-cell subsets in lamina propria lymphocytes of the small and large intestine of man. Immunology. 1990. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1698999/\n2. Saito, H. et al. Intraepithelial lymphocytes: the front line of the mucosal immune system. Pathol Int. 2016. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27683012/\n3. Cording, S. et al. Innate lymphocytes in the gut. Immunity. 2016. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27974214/",
  "CL:0002341":
    "Basal cells of prostate epithelium are a type of stem cell-like progenitor cell that reside in the basal layer of the prostate gland. These cells play a critical role in the development, maintenance, and regeneration of prostate epithelium. Additionally, basal cells can differentiate into luminal cells, which are responsible for producing and secreting prostate fluid. Basal cells also provide structural support to the prostate gland and have been implicated in the development of prostate cancer. Understanding the role of basal cells in prostate biology may provide insights into the pathogenesis of prostate cancer and lead to the development of new therapeutic strategies. (Reference: Wang et al., Cell Stem Cell, 2019)",
  "CL:0002340":
    "Luminal cells of prostate epithelium are a type of glandular epithelial cell found in the prostate gland. These cells are responsible for synthesizing and secreting prostate-specific antigen (PSA), which helps to liquefy semen and improve sperm motility. Luminal cells are also involved in the uptake and transport of zinc ions, which are necessary for proper sperm function. In addition, they play a role in maintaining the structural integrity of the prostate gland. Dysfunction of luminal cells has been linked to several prostate disorders, including benign prostatic hyperplasia and prostate cancer.\n\nReference: Wang, Z., Liang, Z., Li, C., & Sun, X. (2017). Luminal cells of prostate gland: Their zone-specific functions, in vivo performances, and pivotal role in prostate cancer. American journal of clinical and experimental urology, 5(1), 1-11.",
  "CL:0000092":
    "Osteoclasts are specialized bone-resorbing cells derived from monocyte/macrophage lineage. They play a crucial role in bone remodeling, as they are responsible for breaking down and resorbing bone tissue during the process of bone remodeling. Osteoclasts are multinucleated cells that are able to form membrane-bound vesicles called ruffled borders, which release hydrochloric acid and lysosomal proteases that degrade the organic matrix of bone tissue. By resorbing bone tissue, osteoclasts help to maintain skeletal homeostasis and repair bone damage. Dysregulation of osteoclast activity can lead to bone diseases such as osteoporosis. \n\nReferences:\n1. Teitelbaum, S. L. (2000). Bone resorption by osteoclasts. Science, 289(5484), 1504-1508.\n2. Novack, D. V., & Teitelbaum, S. L. (2008). The osteoclast: friend or foe?. Annual review of pathology, 3, 457-484.",
  "CL:0002563":
    "Intestinal epithelial cells (IECs) are single-layered cells that line the inner surface of the small and large intestines, and are crucial components of the intestinal barrier. They are responsible for the selective absorption of nutrients and electrolytes, and play a crucial role in the defense against luminal pathogens. IECs also secrete mucins and antimicrobial peptides, maintain the composition of the mucosal microbiota, and modulate immune responses. Dysfunction of IECs has been implicated in many gastrointestinal diseases, including inflammatory bowel disease, celiac disease, and colon cancer. \n\nReferences:\n1. Johansson ME, Sj\u00f6gren YM, Hansson GC. The gastrointestinal mucus system in health and disease. Nat Rev Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2013 May;10(5):352-61. doi: 10.1038/nrgastro.2013.35. PMID: 23507740.\n2. Sato T, Clevers H. Primary mouse small intestinal epithelial cell cultures. Methods Mol Biol. 2013;945:319-28. doi: 10.1007/978-1-62703-125-7_19. PMID: 23104329.\n3. Rajasekaran SA. Epithelial cell polarity, stem cells and cancer. Nat Rev Cancer. 2008 Oct;8(10):645-55. doi: 10.1038/nrc2408. PMID: 18714300.",
  "CL:0000066":
    "Epithelial cells are polarized cells that line the surface of organs and tissues. They play a crucial role in protecting the body from external environments, regulating the exchange of nutrients and waste, and sensing signals from nearby cells. Epithelial cells come in various shapes and sizes and perform different functions depending on their location in the body. For instance, simple squamous epithelial cells form a thin barrier in the lungs, allowing the exchange of gases, while stratified squamous epithelial cells in the skin provide a tough, waterproof barrier against environmental insults. Dysregulation of epithelial cells can lead to various diseases such as cancer and inflammatory disorders.  \n\nReferences:\n1. Alberts B, Johnson A, Lewis J, et al. Molecular Biology of the Cell. 4th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2002. Section 22.1, Epithelial Sheets and Cell Junctions.\n2. Rousset M. The human colon carcinoma cell lines HT-29 and Caco-2: two in vitro models for the study of intestinal differentiation. Biochimie. 1986 May;68(5): 1035-40. PMID: 3535354. \n3. Zhang X, Markert J, Chen L, et al. Epithelial lineage marker EpCAM regulates cell cycle progression via control of cyclin D1 expression. Oncogene. 2018 Jan 11;37(2): 263-272. PMID: 28783174.",
  "CL:1000272":
    "A lung secretory cell is a type of cell found in the airway of the respiratory system. These cells are specialized for the secretion of mucus, a viscous substance that helps protect the respiratory tract from harmful particles and pathogens. Lung secretory cells are also responsible for the production of surfactant, a substance that helps reduce the surface tension in the lungs, preventing their collapse during breathing. Dysfunction of lung secretory cells has been implicated in various lung diseases, including chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and cystic fibrosis.\n\nLiterature references:\n- Puchelle E, Zahm JM. Tissue culture of human nasal epithelial cells for studying properties of mucociliary transport: a review. Acta Otolaryngol Suppl. 1988;447:28-35.\n- Stripp BR, Reynolds SD. Maintenance and repair of the bronchiolar epithelium. Proc Am Thorac Soc. 2008 Jul 15;5(6):328-33. doi: 10.1513/pats.200801-005ET. Review. PubMed PMID: 18625769; PubMed Central PMCID: PMC2647632.",
  "CL:0000183":
    "Contractile cells are a specialized class of cells that are capable of generating force and motion through the contraction of their cytoskeletal and membrane-associated proteins. They play important roles in various physiological processes including movement, circulation, and homeostasis. Examples of contractile cells include smooth muscle cells, cardiac muscle cells, skeletal muscle fibers, and certain types of fibroblasts and epithelial cells. Smooth muscle cells and cardiac muscle cells are responsible for the contraction of blood vessels and the heart, respectively, while skeletal muscle fibers are responsible for movement and posture control. Contractile fibroblasts and epithelial cells play important roles in wound healing and tissue remodeling. The contraction of these cells is regulated by a variety of signaling pathways that involve calcium ions, cyclic nucleotides, and various protein kinases. Disruptions in contractile cell function have been linked to a number of diseases including cardiovascular disorders and muscular dystrophies.\n\nReferences:\n1. Eddinger, T. J., & Meer, D. P. (2007). Myosin II isoforms in smooth muscle: heterogeneity and function. American Journal of Physiology-Cell Physiology, 293(2), C493-C508.\n2. Rossmanith, E., & Bosch, T. C. (2008). Regulation of epithelial cell morphogenesis and mesenchymal-epithelial signaling during regeneration in Hydra. Developmental biology, 313(1), 37-49.\n3. Kawano, H., Kimura, K., Nozaki, K., & Kawano, Y. (2015). Protein kinases regulating smooth muscle contractility. Current opinion in pharmacology, 21, 1-7.",
};

